{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"sourceId":"aristotleEthics","displayName":"Aristotle — Ethics & Politics","type":"quotes","language":"English","edition":"Ross & Welldon Translations, 1890s-1920s","primaryCategory":"Philosophy & Thought","subcategory":"Ancient Greek","audienceTags":["philosophy","ethics"],"sortPriority":42,"itemCount":1739,"supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true,"browseOrder":"sequence","groupingLevels":["work","book"],"groupingLabels":["Work","Book"],"dataPath":"Data/Collections/Aristotle_Ethics.json","version":"1.0"},"data":[{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-1","text":"The form of the thinking which enters into conduct is that which\r terminates in the production of a rule which declares some means to the\r end of life. The process presupposes _(a)_ a clear and just\r apprehension of the nature of that end—such as the _Ethics_ itself\r endeavours to supply; _(b)_ a correct perception of the conditions of\r action, _(a)_ at least is impossible except to a man whose character\r has been duly formed by discipline; it arises only in a man who has\r acquired moral virtue. For such action and feeling as forms bad\r character, blinds the eye of the soul and corrupts the mo","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":0},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-2","text":"Aristotle is not an intuitionist, but he recognises the implication in\r conduct of a direct and immediate apprehension both of the end and of\r the character of his circumstances under which it is from moment to\r moment realised. The directness of such apprehension makes it analogous\r to sensation or sense-perception; but it is on his view in the end due\r to the existence or activity in man of that power in him which is the\r highest thing in his nature, and akin to or identical with the divine\r nature—mind, or intelligence. It is this which reveals to us what is\r best for us—the ideal of a happ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-3","text":"The next book (Book VII.), is concerned partly with moral conditions,\r in which the agent seems to rise above the level of moral virtue or\r fall below that of moral vice, but partly and more largely with\r conditions in which the agent occupies a middle position between the\r two. Aristotle’s attention is here directed chiefly towards the\r phenomena of “Incontinence,” weakness of will or imperfect\r self-control. This condition was to the Greeks a matter of only too\r frequent experience, but it appeared to them peculiarly difficult to\r understand. How can a man know what is good or best for him, ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":2},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-4","text":"Books VIII. and IX. (on Friendship) are almost an interruption of the\r argument. The subject-matter of them was a favourite topic of ancient\r writers, and the treatment is smoother and more orderly than elsewhere\r in the _Ethics_. The argument is clear, and may be left without comment\r to the readers. These books contain a necessary and attractive\r complement to the somewhat dry account of Greek morality in the\r preceding books, and there are in them profound reflections on what may\r be called the metaphysics of friendship or love.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":3},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-5","text":"At the beginning of Book X. we return to the topic of Pleasure, which\r is now regarded from a different point of view. In Book VII. the\r antagonists were those who over-emphasised the irrationality or badness\r of Pleasure: here it is rather those who so exaggerate its value as to\r confuse or identify it with the good or Happiness. But there is offered\r us in this section much more than criticism of the errors of others.\r Answers are given both to the psychological question, “What is\r Pleasure?” and to the ethical question, “What is its value?” Pleasure,\r we are told, is the natural concomitant","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":4},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-6","text":"Pleasure is, therefore, a necessary element in the best life, but it is\r not the whole of it nor the principal ingredient. The value of a life\r depends upon the nature and worth of the activity which it involves;\r given the maximum of full free action, the maximum of pleasure\r necessary follows. But on what sort of life is such activity possible?\r This leads us back to the question, What is happiness? In what life can\r man find the fullest satisfaction for his desires? To this question\r Aristotle gives an answer which cannot but surprise us after what has\r preceded. True Happiness, great satis","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":5},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-7","text":"But it must not be forgotten that Aristotle conceives of this life as\r one of intense activity or energising: it is just this which gives it\r its supremacy. In spite of the almost religious fervour with which he\r speaks of it (“the most orthodox of his disciples” paraphrases his\r meaning by describing its content as “the service and vision of God”),\r it is clear that he identified it with the life of the philosopher, as\r he understood it, a life of ceaseless intellectual activity in which at\r least at times all the distractions and disturbances inseparable from\r practical life seemed to disapp","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":6},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-8","text":"The nobility of this ideal cannot be questioned; the conception of the\r end of man or a life lived for truth—of a life blissfully absorbed in\r the vision of truth—is a lofty and inspiring one. But we cannot resist\r certain criticisms upon its presentation by Aristotle: (1) the relation\r of it to the lower ideal of practice is left somewhat obscure; (2) it\r is described in such a way as renders its realisation possible only to\r a gifted few, and under exceptional circumstances; (3) it seems in\r various ways, as regards its content, to be unnecessarily and\r unjustifiably limited. But it must be ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":7},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-9","text":"The Moral Ideal to those who have most deeply reflected on it leads to\r the thought of an Ideal beyond and above it, which alone gives it\r meaning, but which seems to escape from definite conception by man. The\r richness and variety of this Ideal ceaselessly invite, but as\r ceaselessly defy, our attempts to imprison it in a definite formula or\r portray it in detailed imagination. Yet the thought of it is and\r remains inexpungable from our minds.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":8},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-10","text":"This conception of the best life is not forgotten in the _Politics_ The\r end of life in the state is itself well-living and well-doing—a life\r which helps to produce the best life The great agency in the production\r of such life is the State operating through Law, which is Reason backed\r by Force. For its greatest efficiency there is required the development\r of a science of legislation. The main drift of what he says here is\r that the most desirable thing would be that the best reason of the\r community should be embodied in its laws. But so far as that is not\r possible, it still is true that ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":9},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-11","text":"On looking back it will be seen that the discussion of the central\r topic of the nature and formation of character has expanded into a\r Philosophy of Human Conduct, merging at its beginning and end into\r metaphysics The result is a Moral Philosophy set against a background\r of Political Theory and general Philosophy. The most characteristic\r features of this Moral Philosophy are due to the fact of its\r essentially teleological view of human life and action: (1) Every human\r activity, but especially every human practical activity, is directed\r towards a simple End discoverable by reflection, an","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":10},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-12","text":"This view has the great advantage of exhibiting morality as essentially\r reasonable, but the accompanying disadvantage of lowering it into a\r somewhat prosaic and unideal Prudentialism, nor is it saved from this\r by the tacking on to it, by a sort of after-thought, of the second and\r higher Ideal—an addition which ruins the coherence of the account\r without really transmuting its substance The source of our\r dissatisfaction with the whole theory lies deeper than in its tendency\r to identify the end with the maximum of enjoyment or satisfaction, or\r to regard the goodness or badness of acts and","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":11},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-13","text":"But this does not mean that Moral Philosophy has not still much to\r learn from Aristotle’s _Ethics_. The work still remains one of the best\r introductions to a study of its important subject-matter, it spreads\r before us a view of the relevant facts, it reduces them to manageable\r compass and order, it raises some of the central problems, and makes\r acute and valuable suggestions towards their solution. Above all, it\r perpetually incites to renewed and independent reflection upon them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":12},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-14","text":"First edition of works (with omission of Rhetorica, Poetica, and second\r book of Economica), 5 vols by Aldus Manutius, Venice, 1495 8, re\r impression supervised by Erasmus and with certain corrections by\r Grynaeus (including Rhetorica and Poetica), 1531, 1539, revised 1550,\r later editions were followed by that of Immanuel Bekker and Brandis\r (Greek and Latin), 5 vols. The 5th vol contains the Index by Bomtz,\r 1831-70, Didot edition (Greek and Latin), 5 vols 1848 74","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":13},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-15","text":"ENGLISH TRANSLATIONS Edited by T Taylor, with Porphyry’s Introduction,\r 9 vols, 1812, under editorship of J A Smith and W D Ross, II vols,\r 1908-31, Loeb editions Ethica, Rhetorica, Poetica, Physica, Politica,\r Metaphysica, 1926-33","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":14},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-16","text":"Later editions of separate works _De Anima_ Torstrik, 1862,\r Trendelenburg, 2nd edition, 1877, with English translation, L Wallace,\r 1882, Biehl, 1884, 1896, with English, R D Hicks, 1907 _Ethica_ J S\r Brewer (Nicomachean), 1836, W E Jelf, 1856, J F T Rogers, 1865, A\r Grant, 1857 8, 1866, 1874, 1885, E Moore, 1871, 1878, 4th edition,\r 1890, Ramsauer (Nicomachean), 1878, Susemihl, 1878, 1880, revised by O\r Apelt, 1903, A Grant, 1885, I Bywater (Nicomachean), 1890, J Burnet,\r 1900","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":15},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-17","text":"_Poetica_ Vahlen, 1867, 1874, with Notes by E Moore, 1875, with English\r translation by E R Wharton, 1883, 1885, Uberweg, 1870, 1875, with\r German translation, Susemihl, 1874, Schmidt, 1875, Christ, 1878, I\r Bywater, 1898, T G Tucker, 1899","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":16},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-18","text":"_De Republica Athenientium_ Text and facsimile of Papyrus, F G Kenyon,\r 1891, 3rd edition, 1892, Kaibel and Wilamowitz-Moellendorf, 1891, 3rd\r edition, 1898, Van Herwerden and Leeuwen (from Kenyon’s text), 1891,\r Blass, 1892, 1895, 1898, 1903, J E Sandys, 1893","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":17},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-19","text":"_Politica_ Susemihl, 1872, with German, 1878, 3rd edition, 1882,\r Susemihl and Hicks, 1894, etc, O Immisch, 1909","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":18},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-20","text":"_Rhetorica_ Stahr, 1862, Sprengel (with Latin text), 1867, Cope and\r Sandys, 1877, Roemer, 1885, 1898","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":19},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-21","text":"ENGLISH TRANSLATIONS OF ONE OR MORE WORKS De Anima (with Parva\r Naturalia), by W A Hammond, 1902 Ethica Of Morals to Nicomachus, by E\r Pargiter, 1745, with Politica by J Gillies, 1797, 1804, 1813, with\r Rhetorica and Poetica, by T Taylor, 1818, and later editions\r Nicomachean Ethics, 1819, mainly from text of Bekker by D P Chase,\r 1847, revised 1861, and later editions, with an introductory essay by G\r H Lewes (Camelot Classics) 1890, re-edited by J M Mitchell (New\r Universal Library), 1906, 1910, by R W Browne (Bohn’s Classical\r Library), 1848, etc, by R Williams, 1869, 1876, by W M Hatch and","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":20},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-1-22","text":"LIFE, ETC J W Blakesley, 1839, A Crichton (Jardine’s Naturalist’s\r Library), 1843, JS Blackie, Four Phases of Morals, Socrates, Aristotle,\r etc, 1871, G Grote, Aristotle, edited by A Bain and G C Robertson,\r 1872, 1880, E Wallace, Outlines of the Philosophy of Aristotle, 1875,\r 1880, A Grant (Ancient Classics for English readers), 1877, T Davidson,\r Aristotle and Ancient Educational Ideals (Great Educators), 1892, F\r Sewall, Swedenborg and Aristotle, 1895, W A Heidel, The Necessary and\r the Contingent of the Aristotelian System (University of Chicago\r Contributions to Philosophy), 1896, F W Ba","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":21},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-1","text":"Every art, and every science reduced to a teachable form, and in like\r manner every action and moral choice, aims, it is thought, at some\r good: for which reason a common and by no means a bad description of\r the Chief Good is, “that which all things aim at.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":22},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-2","text":"Now there plainly is a difference in the Ends proposed: for in some\r cases they are acts of working, and in others certain works or tangible\r results beyond and beside the acts of working: and where there are\r certain Ends beyond and beside the actions, the works are in their\r nature better than the acts of working. Again, since actions and arts\r and sciences are many, the Ends likewise come to be many: of the\r healing art, for instance, health; of the ship-building art, a vessel;\r of the military art, victory; and of domestic management, wealth; are\r respectively the Ends.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":23},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-3","text":"And whatever of such actions, arts, or sciences range under some one\r faculty (as under that of horsemanship the art of making bridles, and\r all that are connected with the manufacture of horse-furniture in\r general; this itself again, and every action connected with war, under\r the military art; and in the same way others under others), in all\r such, the Ends of the master-arts are more choice-worthy than those\r ranging under them, because it is with a view to the former that the\r latter are pursued.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":24},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-4","text":"(And in this comparison it makes no difference whether the acts of\r working are themselves the Ends of the actions, or something further\r beside them, as is the case in the arts and sciences we have been just\r speaking of.)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":25},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-5","text":"Since then of all things which may be done there is some one End which\r we desire for its own sake, and with a view to which we desire\r everything else; and since we do not choose in all instances with a\r further End in view (for then men would go on without limit, and so the\r desire would be unsatisfied and fruitless), this plainly must be the\r Chief Good, _i.e._ the best thing of all.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":26},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-6","text":"Surely then, even with reference to actual life and conduct, the\r knowledge of it must have great weight; and like archers, with a mark\r in view, we shall be more likely to hit upon what is right: and if so,\r we ought to try to describe, in outline at least, what it is and of\r which of the sciences and faculties it is the End.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":27},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-7","text":"Now one would naturally suppose it to be the End of that which is most\r commanding and most inclusive: and to this description, πολιτικὴ[1]\r plainly answers: for this it is that determines which of the sciences\r should be in the communities, and which kind individuals are to learn,\r and what degree of proficiency is to be required. Again; we see also\r ranging under this the most highly esteemed faculties, such as the art\r military, and that of domestic management, and Rhetoric. Well then,\r since this uses all the other practical sciences, and moreover lays\r down rules as to what men are to do,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":28},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-8","text":"Such then are the objects proposed by our treatise, which is of the\r nature of πολιτικὴ: and I conceive I shall have spoken on them\r satisfactorily, if they be made as distinctly clear as the nature of\r the subject-matter will admit: for exactness must not be looked for in\r all discussions alike, any more than in all works of handicraft. Now\r the notions of nobleness and justice, with the examination of which\r πολιτικὴ is concerned, admit of variation and error to such a degree,\r that they are supposed by some to exist conventionally only, and not in\r the nature of things: but then, again, the","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":29},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-9","text":"We must be content then, in speaking of such things and from such data,\r to set forth the truth roughly and in outline; in other words, since we\r are speaking of general matter and from general data, to draw also\r conclusions merely general. And in the same spirit should each person\r receive what we say: for the man of education will seek exactness so\r far in each subject as the nature of the thing admits, it being plainly\r much the same absurdity to put up with a mathematician who tries to\r persuade instead of proving, and to demand strict demonstrative\r reasoning of a Rhetorician.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":30},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-10","text":"Now each man judges well what he knows, and of these things he is a\r good judge: on each particular matter then he is a good judge who has\r been instructed in _it_, and in a general way the man of general mental\r cultivation.[2]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":31},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-11","text":"Hence the young man is not a fit student of Moral Philosophy, for he\r has no experience in the actions of life, while all that is said\r presupposes and is concerned with these: and in the next place, since\r he is apt to follow the impulses of his passions, he will hear as\r though he heard not, and to no profit, the end in view being practice\r and not mere knowledge.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":32},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-12","text":"And I draw no distinction between young in years, and youthful in\r temper and disposition: the defect to which I allude being no direct\r result of the time, but of living at the beck and call of passion, and\r following each object as it rises.[3] For to them that are such the\r knowledge comes to be unprofitable, as to those of imperfect\r self-control: but, to those who form their desires and act in\r accordance with reason, to have knowledge on these points must be very\r profitable.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":33},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-13","text":"Let thus much suffice by way of preface on these three points, the\r student, the spirit in which our observations should be received, and\r the object which we propose.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":34},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-14","text":"And now, resuming the statement with which we commenced, since all\r knowledge and moral choice grasps at good of some kind or another, what\r good is that which we say πολιτικὴ aims at? or, in other words, what is\r the highest of all the goods which are the objects of action?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":35},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-15","text":"So far as name goes, there is a pretty general agreement: for HAPPINESS\r both the multitude and the refined few call it, and “living well” and\r “doing well” they conceive to be the same with “being happy;” but about\r the Nature of this Happiness, men dispute, and the multitude do not in\r their account of it agree with the wise. For some say it is some one of\r those things which are palpable and apparent, as pleasure or wealth or\r honour; in fact, some one thing, some another; nay, oftentimes the same\r man gives a different account of it; for when ill, he calls it health;\r when poor, wealth: an","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":36},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-16","text":"Now to sift all the opinions would be perhaps rather a fruitless task;\r so it shall suffice to sift those which are most generally current, or\r are thought to have some reason in them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":37},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-17","text":"And here we must not forget the difference between reasoning from\r principles, and reasoning to principles: for with good cause did Plato\r too doubt about this, and enquire whether the right road is from\r principles or to principles, just as in the racecourse from the judges\r to the further end, or _vice versâ_.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":38},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-18","text":"Of course, we must begin with what is known; but then this is of two\r kinds, what we _do_ know, and what we _may_ know:[5] perhaps then as\r individuals we must begin with what we _do_ know. Hence the necessity\r that he should have been well trained in habits, who is to study, with\r any tolerable chance of profit, the principles of nobleness and justice\r and moral philosophy generally. For a principle is a matter of fact,\r and if the fact is sufficiently clear to a man there will be no need in\r addition of the reason for the fact. And he that has been thus trained\r either has principles already","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":39},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-19","text":"He is best of all who of himself conceiveth all things;\r Good again is he too who can adopt a good suggestion;\r But whoso neither of himself conceiveth nor hearing from another\r Layeth it to heart;—he is a useless man.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":40},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-20","text":"Now of the Chief Good (_i.e._ of Happiness) men seem to form their\r notions from the different modes of life, as we might naturally expect:\r the many and most low conceive it to be pleasure, and hence they are\r content with the life of sensual enjoyment. For there are three lines\r of life which stand out prominently to view: that just mentioned, and\r the life in society, and, thirdly, the life of contemplation.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":41},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-21","text":"Now the many are plainly quite slavish, choosing a life like that of\r brute animals: yet they obtain some consideration, because many of the\r great share the tastes of Sardanapalus. The refined and active again\r conceive it to be honour: for this may be said to be the end of the\r life in society: yet it is plainly too superficial for the object of\r our search, because it is thought to rest with those who pay rather\r than with him who receives it, whereas the Chief Good we feel\r instinctively must be something which is our own, and not easily to be\r taken from us.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":42},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-22","text":"And besides, men seem to pursue honour, that they may believe\r themselves to be good:[6] for instance, they seek to be honoured by the\r wise, and by those among whom they are known, and for virtue: clearly\r then, in the opinion at least of these men, virtue is higher than\r honour. In truth, one would be much more inclined to think this to be\r the end of the life in society; yet this itself is plainly not\r sufficiently final: for it is conceived possible, that a man possessed\r of virtue might sleep or be inactive all through his life, or, as a\r third case, suffer the greatest evils and misfortu","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":43},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-23","text":"And for these let thus much suffice, for they have been treated of at\r sufficient length in my Encyclia.[8]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":44},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-24","text":"A third line of life is that of contemplation, concerning which we\r shall make our examination in the following pages.[9]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":45},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-25","text":"As for the life of money-making, it is one of constraint, and wealth\r manifestly is not the good we are seeking, because it is for use, that\r is, for the sake of something further: and hence one would rather\r conceive the forementioned ends to be the right ones, for men rest\r content with them for their own sakes. Yet, clearly, they are not the\r objects of our search either, though many words have been wasted on\r them.[10] So much then for these.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":46},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-26","text":"Again, the notion of one Universal Good (the same, that is, in all\r things), it is better perhaps we should examine, and discuss the\r meaning of it, though such an enquiry is unpleasant, because they are\r friends of ours who have introduced these εἴδη.[11] Still perhaps it\r may appear better, nay to be our duty where the safety of the truth is\r concerned, to upset if need be even our own theories, specially as we\r are lovers of wisdom: for since both are dear to us, we are bound to\r prefer the truth. Now they who invented this doctrine of εἴδη, did not\r apply it to those things in which they s","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":47},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-27","text":"In the next place, since good is predicated in as many ways as there\r are modes of existence [for it is predicated in the category of\r Substance, as God, Intellect—and in that of Quality, as The Virtues—and\r in that of Quantity, as The Mean—and in that of Relation, as The\r Useful—and in that of Time, as Opportunity—and in that of Place, as\r Abode; and other such like things], it manifestly cannot be something\r common and universal and one in all: else it would not have been\r predicated in all the categories, but in one only.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":48},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-28","text":"Thirdly, since those things which range under one ἰδέα are also under\r the cognisance of one science, there would have been, on their theory,\r only one science taking cognisance of all goods collectively: but in\r fact there are many even for those which range under one category: for\r instance, of Opportunity or Seasonableness (which I have before\r mentioned as being in the category of Time), the science is, in war,\r generalship; in disease, medical science; and of the Mean (which I\r quoted before as being in the category of Quantity), in food, the\r medical science; and in labour or exercise, t","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":49},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-29","text":"No. The Pythagoreans do seem to give a more credible account of the\r matter, who place “One” among the goods in their double list of goods\r and bads:[12] which philosophers, in fact, Speusippus[13] seems to have\r followed.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":50},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-30","text":"But of these matters let us speak at some other time. Now there is\r plainly a loophole to object to what has been advanced, on the plea\r that the theory I have attacked is not by its advocates applied to all\r good: but those goods only are spoken of as being under one ἰδέα, which\r are pursued, and with which men rest content simply for their own\r sakes: whereas those things which have a tendency to produce or\r preserve them in any way, or to hinder their contraries, are called\r good because of these other goods, and after another fashion. It is\r manifest then that the goods may be so called in","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":51},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-31","text":"Very well then, let us separate the independent goods from the\r instrumental, and see whether they are spoken of as under one ἰδέα.\r But the question next arises, what kind of goods are we to call\r independent? All such as are pursued even when separated from other\r goods, as, for instance, being wise, seeing, and certain pleasures and\r honours (for these, though we do pursue them with some further end in\r view, one would still place among the independent goods)? or does it\r come in fact to this, that we can call nothing independent good except\r the ἰδέα, and so the concrete of it will be noug","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":52},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-32","text":"If, on the other hand, these are independent goods, then we shall\r require that the account of the goodness be the same clearly in all,\r just as that of the whiteness is in snow and white lead. But how stands\r the fact? Why of honour and wisdom and pleasure the accounts are\r distinct and different in so far as they are good. The Chief Good then\r is not something common, and after one ἰδέα.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":53},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-33","text":"But then, how does the name come to be common (for it is not seemingly\r a case of fortuitous equivocation)? Are different individual things\r called good by virtue of being from one source, or all conducing to one\r end, or rather by way of analogy, for that intellect is to the soul as\r sight to the body, and so on? However, perhaps we ought to leave these\r questions now, for an accurate investigation of them is more properly\r the business of a different philosophy. And likewise respecting the\r ἰδέα: for even if there is some one good predicated in common of all\r things that are good, or separab","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":54},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-34","text":"It may readily occur to any one, that it would be better to attain a\r knowledge of it with a view to such concrete goods as are attainable\r and practical, because, with this as a kind of model in our hands, we\r shall the better know what things are good for us individually, and\r when we know them, we shall attain them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":55},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-35","text":"Some plausibility, it is true, this argument possesses, but it is\r contradicted by the facts of the Arts and Sciences; for all these,\r though aiming at some good, and seeking that which is deficient, yet\r pretermit the knowledge of it: now it is not exactly probable that all\r artisans without exception should be ignorant of so great a help as\r this would be, and not even look after it; neither is it easy to see\r wherein a weaver or a carpenter will be profited in respect of his\r craft by knowing the very-good, or how a man will be the more apt to\r effect cures or to command an army for having ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":56},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-36","text":"And now let us revert to the Good of which we are in search: what can\r it be? for manifestly it is different in different actions and arts:\r for it is different in the healing art and in the art military, and\r similarly in the rest. What then is the Chief Good in each? Is it not\r “that for the sake of which the other things are done?” and this in the\r healing art is health, and in the art military victory, and in that of\r house-building a house, and in any other thing something else; in\r short, in every action and moral choice the End, because in all cases\r men do everything else with a view t","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":57},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-37","text":"Thus our discussion after some traversing about has come to the same\r point which we reached before. And this we must try yet more to clear\r up.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":58},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-38","text":"Now since the ends are plainly many, and of these we choose some with a\r view to others (wealth, for instance, musical instruments, and, in\r general, all instruments), it is clear that all are not final: but the\r Chief Good is manifestly something final; and so, if there is some one\r only which is final, this must be the object of our search: but if\r several, then the most final of them will be it.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":59},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-39","text":"Now that which is an object of pursuit in itself we call more final\r than that which is so with a view to something else; that again which\r is never an object of choice with a view to something else than those\r which are so both in themselves and with a view to this ulterior\r object: and so by the term “absolutely final,” we denote that which is\r an object of choice always in itself, and never with a view to any\r other.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":60},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-40","text":"And of this nature Happiness is mostly thought to be, for this we\r choose always for its own sake, and never with a view to anything\r further: whereas honour, pleasure, intellect, in fact every excellence\r we choose for their own sakes, it is true (because we would choose each\r of these even if no result were to follow), but we choose them also\r with a view to happiness, conceiving that through their instrumentality\r we shall be happy: but no man chooses happiness with a view to them,\r nor in fact with a view to any other thing whatsoever.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":61},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-41","text":"The same result[15] is seen to follow also from the notion of\r self-sufficiency, a quality thought to belong to the final good. Now by\r sufficient for Self, we mean not for a single individual living a\r solitary life, but for his parents also and children and wife, and, in\r general, friends and countrymen; for man is by nature adapted to a\r social existence. But of these, of course, some limit must be fixed:\r for if one extends it to parents and descendants and friends’ friends,\r there is no end to it. This point, however, must be left for future\r investigation: for the present we define that ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":62},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-42","text":"So then Happiness is manifestly something final and self-sufficient,\r being the end of all things which are and may be done.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":63},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-43","text":"But, it may be, to call Happiness the Chief Good is a mere truism, and\r what is wanted is some clearer account of its real nature. Now this\r object may be easily attained, when we have discovered what is the work\r of man; for as in the case of flute-player, statuary, or artisan of any\r kind, or, more generally, all who have any work or course of action,\r their Chief Good and Excellence is thought to reside in their work, so\r it would seem to be with man, if there is any work belonging to him.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":64},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-44","text":"Are we then to suppose, that while carpenter and cobbler have certain\r works and courses of action, Man as Man has none, but is left by Nature\r without a work? or would not one rather hold, that as eye, hand, and\r foot, and generally each of his members, has manifestly some special\r work; so too the whole Man, as distinct from all these, has some work\r of his own?[18]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":65},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-45","text":"What then can this be? not mere life, because that plainly is shared\r with him even by vegetables, and we want what is peculiar to him. We\r must separate off then the life of mere nourishment and growth, and\r next will come the life of sensation: but this again manifestly is\r common to horses, oxen, and every animal. There remains then a kind of\r life of the Rational Nature apt to act: and of this Nature there are\r two parts denominated Rational, the one as being obedient to Reason,\r the other as having and exerting it. Again, as this life is also spoken\r of in two ways,[19] we must take that ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":66},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-46","text":"And we must add, ἐν βίῳ τελείῳ;[20] for as it is not one swallow or one\r fine day that makes a spring, so it is not one day or a short time that\r makes a man blessed and happy.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":67},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-47","text":"Let this then be taken for a rough sketch of the Chief Good: since it\r is probably the right way to give first the outline, and fill it in\r afterwards. And it would seem that any man may improve and connect what\r is good in the sketch, and that time is a good discoverer and\r co-operator in such matters: it is thus in fact that all improvements\r in the various arts have been brought about, for any man may fill up a\r deficiency.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":68},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-48","text":"You must remember also what has been already stated, and not seek for\r exactness in all matters alike, but in each according to the\r subject-matter, and so far as properly belongs to the system. The\r carpenter and geometrician, for instance, enquire into the right line\r in different fashion: the former so far as he wants it for his work,\r the latter enquires into its nature and properties, because he is\r concerned with the truth.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":69},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-49","text":"So then should one do in other matters, that the incidental matters may\r not exceed the direct ones.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":70},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-50","text":"And again, you must not demand the reason either in all things\r alike,[21] because in some it is sufficient that the fact has been well\r demonstrated, which is the case with first principles; and the fact is\r the first step, _i.e._ starting-point or principle.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":71},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-51","text":"And of these first principles some are obtained by induction, some by\r perception,[22] some by a course of habituation, others in other\r different ways. And we must try to trace up each in their own nature,\r and take pains to secure their being well defined, because they have\r great influence on what follows: it is thought, I mean, that the\r starting-point or principle is more than half the whole matter, and\r that many of the points of enquiry come simultaneously into view\r thereby.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":72},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-52","text":"We must now enquire concerning Happiness, not only from our conclusion\r and the data on which our reasoning proceeds, but likewise from what is\r commonly said about it: because with what is true all things which\r really are are in harmony, but with that which is false the true very\r soon jars.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":73},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-53","text":"Now there is a common division of goods into three classes; one being\r called external, the other two those of the soul and body respectively,\r and those belonging to the soul we call most properly and specially\r good. Well, in our definition we assume that the actions and workings\r of the soul constitute Happiness, and these of course belong to the\r soul. And so our account is a good one, at least according to this\r opinion, which is of ancient date, and accepted by those who profess\r philosophy. Rightly too are certain actions and workings said to be the\r end, for thus it is brought into the","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":74},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-54","text":"And further, the points required in Happiness are found in combination\r in our account of it.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":75},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-55","text":"For some think it is virtue, others practical wisdom, others a kind of\r scientific philosophy; others that it is these, or else some one of\r them, in combination with pleasure, or at least not independently of\r it; while others again take in external prosperity.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":76},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-56","text":"Of these opinions, some rest on the authority of numbers or antiquity,\r others on that of few, and those men of note: and it is not likely that\r either of these classes should be wrong in all points, but be right at\r least in some one, or even in most.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":77},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-57","text":"Now with those who assert it to be Virtue (Excellence), or some kind of\r Virtue, our account agrees: for working in the way of Excellence surely\r belongs to Excellence.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":78},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-58","text":"And there is perhaps no unimportant difference between conceiving of\r the Chief Good as in possession or as in use, in other words, as a mere\r state or as a working. For the state or habit[23] may possibly exist in\r a subject without effecting any good, as, for instance, in him who is\r asleep, or in any other way inactive; but the working cannot so, for it\r will of necessity act, and act well. And as at the Olympic games it is\r not the finest and strongest men who are crowned, but they who enter\r the lists, for out of these the prize-men are selected; so too in life,\r of the honourable and the","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":79},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-59","text":"Their life too is in itself pleasant: for the feeling of pleasure is a\r mental sensation, and that is to each pleasant of which he is said to\r be fond: a horse, for instance, to him who is fond of horses, and a\r sight to him who is fond of sights: and so in like manner just acts to\r him who is fond of justice, and more generally the things in accordance\r with virtue to him who is fond of virtue. Now in the case of the\r multitude of men the things which they individually esteem pleasant\r clash, because they are not such by nature, whereas to the lovers of\r nobleness those things are pleasant wh","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":80},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-60","text":"So then their life has no need of pleasure as a kind of additional\r appendage, but involves pleasure in itself. For, besides what I have\r just mentioned, a man is not a good man at all who feels no pleasure in\r noble actions,[25] just as no one would call that man just who does not\r feel pleasure in acting justly, or liberal who does not in liberal\r actions, and similarly in the case of the other virtues which might be\r enumerated: and if this be so, then the actions in accordance with\r virtue must be in themselves pleasurable. Then again they are certainly\r good and noble, and each of these i","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":81},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-61","text":"Thus then Happiness is most excellent, most noble, and most pleasant,\r and these attributes are not separated as in the well-known Delian\r inscription—","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":82},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-62","text":"“Most noble is that which is most just, but best is health;\r And naturally most pleasant is the obtaining one’s desires.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":83},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-63","text":"For all these co-exist in the best acts of working: and we say that\r Happiness is these, or one, that is, the best of them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":84},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-64","text":"Still[26] it is quite plain that it does require the addition of\r external goods, as we have said: because without appliances it is\r impossible, or at all events not easy, to do noble actions: for\r friends, money, and political influence are in a manner instruments\r whereby many things are done: some things there are again a deficiency\r in which mars blessedness; good birth, for instance, or fine offspring,\r or even personal beauty: for he is not at all capable of Happiness who\r is very ugly, or is ill-born, or solitary and childless; and still less\r perhaps supposing him to have very bad chil","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":85},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-65","text":"And hence too a question is raised, whether it is a thing that can be\r learned, or acquired by habituation or discipline of some other kind,\r or whether it comes in the way of divine dispensation, or even in the\r way of chance.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":86},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-66","text":"Now to be sure, if anything else is a gift of the Gods to men, it is\r probable that Happiness is a gift of theirs too, and specially because\r of all human goods it is the highest. But this, it may be, is a\r question belonging more properly to an investigation different from\r ours:[27] and it is quite clear, that on the supposition of its not\r being sent from the Gods direct, but coming to us by reason of virtue\r and learning of a certain kind, or discipline, it is yet one of the\r most Godlike things; because the prize and End of virtue is manifestly\r somewhat most excellent, nay divine and ble","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":87},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-67","text":"It will also on this supposition be widely participated, for it may\r through learning and diligence of a certain kind exist in all who have\r not been maimed[28] for virtue.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":88},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-68","text":"And if it is better we should be happy thus than as a result of chance,\r this is in itself an argument that the case is so; because those things\r which are in the way of nature, and in like manner of art, and of every\r cause, and specially the best cause, are by nature in the best way\r possible: to leave them to chance what is greatest and most noble would\r be very much out of harmony with all these facts.[29]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":89},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-69","text":"The question may be determined also by a reference to our definition of\r Happiness, that it is a working of the soul in the way of excellence or\r virtue of a certain kind: and of the other goods, some we must have to\r begin with, and those which are co-operative and useful are given by\r nature as instruments.[30]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":90},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-70","text":"These considerations will harmonise also with what we said at the\r commencement: for we assumed the End of πολιτικὴ to be most excellent:\r now this bestows most care on making the members of the community of a\r certain character; good that is and apt to do what is honourable.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":91},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-71","text":"With good reason then neither ox nor horse nor any other brute animal\r do we call happy, for none of them can partake in such working: and for\r this same reason a child is not happy either, because by reason of his\r tender age he cannot yet perform such actions: if the term is applied,\r it is by way of anticipation.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":92},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-72","text":"For to constitute Happiness, there must be, as we have said, complete\r virtue and a complete life: for many changes and chances of all kinds\r arise during a life, and he who is most prosperous may become involved\r in great misfortunes in his old age, as in the heroic poems the tale is\r told of Priam: but the man who has experienced such fortune and died in\r wretchedness, no man calls happy.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":93},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-73","text":"Are we then to call no man happy while he lives, and, as Solon would\r have us, look to the end? And again, if we are to maintain this\r position, is a man then happy when he is dead? or is not this a\r complete absurdity, specially in us who say Happiness is a working of a\r certain kind?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":94},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-74","text":"If on the other hand we do not assert that the dead man is happy, and\r Solon does not mean this, but only that one would then be safe in\r pronouncing a man happy, as being thenceforward out of the reach of\r evils and misfortunes, this too admits of some dispute, since it is\r thought that the dead has somewhat both of good and evil (if, as we\r must allow, a man may have when alive but not aware of the\r circumstances), as honour and dishonour, and good and bad fortune of\r children and descendants generally.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":95},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-75","text":"Nor is this view again without its difficulties: for, after a man has\r lived in blessedness to old age and died accordingly, many changes may\r befall him in right of his descendants; some of them may be good and\r obtain positions in life accordant to their merits, others again quite\r the contrary: it is plain too that the descendants may at different\r intervals or grades stand in all manner of relations to the\r ancestors.[31] Absurd indeed would be the position that even the dead\r man is to change about with them and become at one time happy and at\r another miserable. Absurd however it is on t","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":96},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-76","text":"But we must revert to the point first raised,[32] since the present\r question will be easily determined from that.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":97},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-77","text":"If then we are to look to the end and then pronounce the man blessed,\r not as being so but as having been so at some previous time, surely it\r is absurd that when he _is_ happy the truth is not to be asserted of\r him, because we are unwilling to pronounce the living happy by reason\r of their liability to changes, and because, whereas we have conceived\r of happiness as something stable and no way easily changeable, the fact\r is that good and bad fortune are constantly circling about the same\r people: for it is quite plain, that if we are to depend upon the\r fortunes of men, we shall often have ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":98},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-78","text":"Is not this the solution? that to make our sentence dependent on the\r changes of fortune, is no way right: for not in them stands the well,\r or the ill, but though human life needs these as accessories (which we\r have allowed already), the workings in the way of virtue are what\r determine Happiness, and the contrary the contrary.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":99},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-79","text":"And, by the way, the question which has been here discussed, testifies\r incidentally to the truth of our account of Happiness.[33] For to\r nothing does a stability of human results attach so much as it does to\r the workings in the way of virtue, since these are held to be more\r abiding even than the sciences: and of these last again[34] the most\r precious are the most abiding, because the blessed live in them most\r and most continuously, which seems to be the reason why they are not\r forgotten. So then this stability which is sought will be in the happy\r man, and he will be such through life, ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":100},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-80","text":"And whereas the incidents of chance are many, and differ in greatness\r and smallness, the small pieces of good or ill fortune evidently do not\r affect the balance of life, but the great and numerous, if happening\r for good, will make life more blessed (for it is their nature to\r contribute to ornament, and the using of them comes to be noble and\r excellent), but if for ill, they bruise as it were and maim the\r blessedness: for they bring in positive pain, and hinder many acts of\r working. But still, even in these, nobleness shines through when a man\r bears contentedly many and great mischances","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":101},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-81","text":"And if, as we have said, the acts of working are what determine the\r character of the life, no one of the blessed can ever become wretched,\r because he will never do those things which are hateful and mean. For\r the man who is truly good and sensible bears all fortunes, we presume,\r becomingly, and always does what is noblest under the circumstances,\r just as a good general employs to the best advantage the force he has\r with him; or a good shoemaker makes the handsomest shoe he can out of\r the leather which has been given him; and all other good artisans\r likewise. And if this be so, wretched","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":102},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-82","text":"Nor, in truth, is he shifting and easily changeable, for on the one\r hand from his happiness he will not be shaken easily nor by ordinary\r mischances, but, if at all, by those which are great and numerous; and,\r on the other, after such mischances he cannot regain his happiness in a\r little time; but, if at all, in a long and complete period, during\r which he has made himself master of great and noble things.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":103},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-83","text":"Why then should we not call happy the man who works in the way of\r perfect virtue, and is furnished with external goods sufficient for\r acting his part in the drama of life:[35] and this during no ordinary\r period but such as constitutes a complete life as we have been\r describing it.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":104},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-84","text":"Or we must add, that not only is he to live so, but his death must be\r in keeping with such life, since the future is dark to us, and\r Happiness we assume to be in every way an end and complete. And, if\r this be so, we shall call them among the living blessed who have and\r will have the things specified, but blessed _as Men_.[36]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":105},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-85","text":"Now that the fortunes of their descendants, and friends generally,\r contribute nothing towards forming the condition of the dead, is\r plainly a very heartless notion, and contrary to the current opinions.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":106},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-86","text":"But since things which befall are many, and differ in all kinds of\r ways, and some touch more nearly, others less, to go into minute\r particular distinctions would evidently be a long and endless task: and\r so it may suffice to speak generally and in outline.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":107},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-87","text":"If then, as of the misfortunes which happen to one’s self, some have a\r certain weight and turn the balance of life, while others are, so to\r speak, lighter; so it is likewise with those which befall all our\r friends alike; if further, whether they whom each suffering befalls be\r alive or dead makes much more difference than in a tragedy the\r presupposing or actual perpetration of the various crimes and horrors,\r we must take into our account this difference also, and still more\r perhaps the doubt concerning the dead whether they really partake of\r any good or evil; it seems to result from all","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":108},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-88","text":"It is plain then that the good or ill fortunes of their friends do\r affect the dead somewhat: but in such kind and degree as neither to\r make the happy unhappy nor produce any other such effect.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":109},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-89","text":"Having determined these points, let us examine with respect to\r Happiness, whether it belongs to the class of things praiseworthy or\r things precious; for to that of faculties[38] it evidently does not.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":110},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-90","text":"Now it is plain that everything which is a subject of praise is praised\r for being of a certain kind and bearing a certain relation to something\r else: for instance, the just, and the valiant, and generally the good\r man, and virtue itself, we praise because of the actions and the\r results: and the strong man, and the quick runner, and so forth, we\r praise for being of a certain nature and bearing a certain relation to\r something good and excellent (and this is illustrated by attempts to\r praise the gods; for they are presented in a ludicrous aspect[39] by\r being referred to our standard, and ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":111},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-91","text":"Eudoxus[40] too is thought to have advanced a sound argument in support\r of the claim of pleasure to the highest prize: for the fact that,\r though it is one of the good things, it is not praised, he took for an\r indication of its superiority to those which are subjects of praise: a\r superiority he attributed also to a god and the Chief Good, on the\r ground that they form the standard to which everything besides is\r referred. For praise applies to virtue, because it makes men apt to do\r what is noble; but encomia to definite works of body or mind.[41]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":112},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-92","text":"However, it is perhaps more suitable to a regular treatise on encomia\r to pursue this topic with exactness: it is enough for our purpose that\r from what has been said it is evident that Happiness belongs to the\r class of things precious and final. And it seems to be so also because\r of its being a starting-point; which it is, in that with a view to it\r we all do everything else that is done; now the starting-point and\r cause of good things we assume to be something precious and divine.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":113},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-93","text":"Moreover, since Happiness is a kind of working of the soul in the way\r of perfect Excellence, we must enquire concerning Excellence: for so\r probably shall we have a clearer view concerning Happiness; and again,\r he who is really a statesman is generally thought to have spent most\r pains on this, for he wishes to make the citizens good and obedient to\r the laws. (For examples of this class we have the lawgivers of the\r Cretans and Lacedæmonians and whatever other such there have been.)\r But if this investigation belongs properly to πολιτικὴ, then clearly\r the enquiry will be in accordance with","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":114},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-94","text":"Well, we are to enquire concerning Excellence, _i.e._ Human Excellence\r of course, because it was the Chief Good of Man and the Happiness of\r Man that we were enquiring of just now.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":115},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-95","text":"And by Human Excellence we mean not that of man’s body but that of his\r soul; for we call Happiness a working of the Soul.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":116},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-96","text":"And if this is so, it is plain that some knowledge of the nature of the\r Soul is necessary for the statesman, just as for the oculist a\r knowledge of the whole body, and the more so in proportion as πολιτικὴ\r is more precious and higher than the healing art: and in fact\r physicians of the higher class do busy themselves much with the\r knowledge of the body.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":117},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-97","text":"So then the statesman is to consider the nature of the Soul: but he\r must do so with these objects in view, and so far only as may suffice\r for the objects of his special enquiry: for to carry his speculations\r to a greater exactness is perhaps a task more laborious than falls\r within his province.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":118},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-98","text":"In fact, the few statements made on the subject in my popular treatises\r are quite enough, and accordingly we will adopt them here: as, that the\r Soul consists of two parts, the Irrational and the Rational (as to\r whether these are actually divided, as are the parts of the body, and\r everything that is capable of division; or are only metaphysically\r speaking two, being by nature inseparable, as are convex and concave\r circumferences, matters not in respect of our present purpose). And of\r the Irrational, the one part seems common to other objects, and in fact\r vegetative; I mean the cause of ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":119},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-99","text":"Now the Excellence of this manifestly is not peculiar to the human\r species but common to others: for this part and this faculty is thought\r to work most in time of sleep, and the good and bad man are least\r distinguishable while asleep; whence it is a common saying that during\r one half of life there is no difference between the happy and the\r wretched; and this accords with our anticipations, for sleep is an\r inactivity of the soul, in so far as it is denominated good or bad,\r except that in some wise some of its movements find their way through\r the veil and so the good come to have better ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":120},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-100","text":"And there seems to be another Irrational Nature of the Soul, which yet\r in a way partakes of Reason. For in the man who controls his appetites,\r and in him who resolves to do so and fails, we praise the Reason or\r Rational part of the Soul, because it exhorts aright and to the best\r course: but clearly there is in them, beside the Reason, some other\r natural principle which fights with and strains against the Reason.\r (For in plain terms, just as paralysed limbs of the body when their\r owners would move them to the right are borne aside in a contrary\r direction to the left, so is it in the cas","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":121},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-101","text":"But of Reason this too does evidently partake, as we have said: for\r instance, in the man of self-control it obeys Reason: and perhaps in\r the man of perfected self-mastery,[43] or the brave man, it is yet\r more obedient; in them it agrees entirely with the Reason.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":122},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-102","text":"So then the Irrational is plainly twofold: the one part, the merely\r vegetative, has no share of Reason, but that of desire, or appetition\r generally, does partake of it in a sense, in so far as it is obedient\r to it and capable of submitting to its rule. (So too in common phrase\r we say we have λόγος of our father or friends, and this in a different\r sense from that in which we say we have λόγος of mathematics.)[44]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":123},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-103","text":"Now that the Irrational is in some way persuaded by the Reason,\r admonition, and every act of rebuke and exhortation indicate. If then\r we are to say that this also has Reason, then the Rational, as well as\r the Irrational, will be twofold, the one supremely and in itself, the\r other paying it a kind of filial regard.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":124},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-2-104","text":"The Excellence of Man then is divided in accordance with this\r difference: we make two classes, calling the one Intellectual, and the\r other Moral; pure science, intelligence, and practical\r wisdom—Intellectual: liberality, and perfected self-mastery—Moral: in\r speaking of a man’s Moral character, we do not say he is a scientific\r or intelligent but a meek man, or one of perfected self-mastery: and we\r praise the man of science in right of his mental state;[45] and of\r these such as are praiseworthy we call Excellences.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":125},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-1","text":"Well: human Excellence is of two kinds, Intellectual and Moral:[1] now\r the Intellectual springs originally, and is increased subsequently,\r from teaching (for the most part that is[2]), and needs therefore\r experience and time; whereas the Moral comes from custom, and so the\r Greek term denoting it is but a slight deflection from the term\r denoting custom in that language.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":126},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-2","text":"From this fact it is plain that not one of the Moral Virtues comes to\r be in us merely by nature: because of such things as exist by nature,\r none can be changed by custom: a stone, for instance, by nature\r gravitating downwards, could never by custom be brought to ascend, not\r even if one were to try and accustom it by throwing it up ten thousand\r times; nor could file again be brought to descend, nor in fact could\r anything whose nature is in one way be brought by custom to be in\r another. The Virtues then come to be in us neither by nature, nor in\r despite of nature,[3] but we are furnished","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":127},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-3","text":"Again, in whatever cases we get things by nature, we get the faculties\r first and perform the acts of working afterwards; an illustration of\r which is afforded by the case of our bodily senses, for it was not from\r having often seen or heard that we got these senses, but just the\r reverse: we had them and so exercised them, but did not have them\r because we had exercised them. But the Virtues we get by first\r performing single acts of working, which, again, is the case of other\r things, as the arts for instance; for what we have to make when we have\r learned how, these we learn how to make by ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":128},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-4","text":"And to the truth of this testimony is borne by what takes place in\r communities: because the law-givers make the individual members good\r men by habituation, and this is the intention certainly of every\r law-giver, and all who do not effect it well fail of their intent; and\r herein consists the difference between a good Constitution and a bad.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":129},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-5","text":"Again, every Virtue is either produced or destroyed from and by the\r very same circumstances: art too in like manner; I mean it is by\r playing the harp that both the good and the bad harp-players are\r formed: and similarly builders and all the rest; by building well men\r will become good builders; by doing it badly bad ones: in fact, if this\r had not been so, there would have been no need of instructors, but all\r men would have been at once good or bad in their several arts without\r them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":130},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-6","text":"So too then is it with the Virtues: for by acting in the various\r relations in which we are thrown with our fellow men, we come to be,\r some just, some unjust: and by acting in dangerous positions and being\r habituated to feel fear or confidence, we come to be, some brave,\r others cowards.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":131},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-7","text":"Similarly is it also with respect to the occasions of lust and anger:\r for some men come to be perfected in self-mastery and mild, others\r destitute of all self-control and passionate; the one class by behaving\r in one way under them, the other by behaving in another. Or, in one\r word, the habits are produced from the acts of working like to them:\r and so what we have to do is to give a certain character to these\r particular acts, because the habits formed correspond to the\r differences of these.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":132},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-8","text":"So then, whether we are accustomed this way or that straight from\r childhood, makes not a small but an important difference, or rather I\r would say it makes all the difference.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":133},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-9","text":"Since then the object of the present treatise is not mere speculation,\r as it is of some others (for we are enquiring not merely that we may\r know what virtue is but that we may become virtuous, else it would have\r been useless), we must consider as to the particular actions how we are\r to do them, because, as we have just said, the quality of the habits\r that shall be formed depends on these.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":134},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-10","text":"Now, that we are to act in accordance with Right Reason is a general\r maxim, and may for the present be taken for granted: we will speak of\r it hereafter, and say both what Right Reason is, and what are its\r relations to the other virtues.[4]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":135},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-11","text":"But let this point be first thoroughly understood between us, that all\r which can be said on moral action must be said in outline, as it were,\r and not exactly: for as we remarked at the commencement, such reasoning\r only must be required as the nature of the subject-matter admits of,\r and matters of moral action and expediency have no fixedness any more\r than matters of health. And if the subject in its general maxims is\r such, still less in its application to particular cases is exactness\r attainable:[5] because these fall not under any art or system of rules,\r but it must be left in each in","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":136},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-12","text":"First then this must be noted, that it is the nature of such things to\r be spoiled by defect and excess; as we see in the case of health and\r strength (since for the illustration of things which cannot be seen we\r must use those that can), for excessive training impairs the strength\r as well as deficient: meat and drink, in like manner, in too great or\r too small quantities, impair the health: while in due proportion they\r cause, increase, and preserve it.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":137},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-13","text":"Thus it is therefore with the habits of perfected Self-Mastery and\r Courage and the rest of the Virtues: for the man who flies from and\r fears all things, and never stands up against anything, comes to be a\r coward; and he who fears nothing, but goes at everything, comes to be\r rash. In like manner too, he that tastes of every pleasure and abstains\r from none comes to lose all self-control; while he who avoids all, as\r do the dull and clownish, comes as it were to lose his faculties of\r perception: that is to say, the habits of perfected Self-Mastery and\r Courage are spoiled by the excess and ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":138},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-14","text":"Furthermore, not only do the origination, growth, and marring of the\r habits come from and by the same circumstances, but also the acts of\r working after the habits are formed will be exercised on the same: for\r so it is also with those other things which are more directly matters\r of sight, strength for instance: for this comes by taking plenty of\r food and doing plenty of work, and the man who has attained strength is\r best able to do these: and so it is with the Virtues, for not only do\r we by abstaining from pleasures come to be perfected in Self-Mastery,\r but when we have come to be so we","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":139},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-15","text":"And for a test of the formation of the habits we must take the pleasure\r or pain which succeeds the acts; for he is perfected in Self-Mastery\r who not only abstains from the bodily pleasures but is glad to do so;\r whereas he who abstains but is sorry to do it has not Self-Mastery: he\r again is brave who stands up against danger, either with positive\r pleasure or at least without any pain; whereas he who does it with pain\r is not brave.[6]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":140},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-16","text":"For Moral Virtue has for its object-matter pleasures and pains, because\r by reason of pleasure we do what is bad, and by reason of pain decline\r doing what is right (for which cause, as Plato observes, men should\r have been trained straight from their childhood to receive pleasure and\r pain from proper objects, for this is the right education). Again:\r since Virtues have to do with actions and feelings, and on every\r feeling and every action pleasure and pain follow, here again is\r another proof that Virtue has for its object-matter pleasure and pain.\r The same is shown also by the fact that p","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":141},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-17","text":"The following considerations may also serve to set this in a clear\r light. There are principally three things moving us to choice and three\r to avoidance, the honourable, the expedient, the pleasant; and their\r three contraries, the dishonourable, the hurtful, and the painful: now\r the good man is apt to go right, and the bad man wrong, with respect to\r all these of course, but most specially with respect to pleasure:\r because not only is this common to him with all animals but also it is\r a concomitant of all those things which move to choice, since both the\r honourable and the expedient give","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":142},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-18","text":"Again, it grows up with us all from infancy, and so it is a hard matter\r to remove from ourselves this feeling, engrained as it is into our very\r life.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":143},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-19","text":"Again, we adopt pleasure and pain (some of us more, and some less) as\r the measure even of actions: for this cause then our whole business\r must be with them, since to receive right or wrong impressions of\r pleasure and pain is a thing of no little importance in respect of the\r actions. Once more; it is harder, as Heraclitus says, to fight against\r pleasure than against anger: now it is about that which is more than\r commonly difficult that art comes into being, and virtue too, because\r in that which is difficult the good is of a higher order: and so for\r this reason too both virtue and moral ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":144},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-20","text":"Let us then be understood to have stated, that Virtue has for its\r object-matter pleasures and pains, and that it is either increased or\r marred by the same circumstances (differently used) by which it is\r originally generated, and that it exerts itself on the same\r circumstances out of which it was generated.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":145},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-21","text":"Now I can conceive a person perplexed as to the meaning of our\r statement, that men must do just actions to become just, and those of\r self-mastery to acquire the habit of self-mastery; “for,” he would say,\r “if men are doing the actions they have the respective virtues already,\r just as men are grammarians or musicians when they do the actions of\r either art.” May we not reply by saying that it is not so even in the\r case of the arts referred to: because a man may produce something\r grammatical either by chance or the suggestion of another; but then\r only will he be a grammarian when he not o","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":146},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-22","text":"Again, the cases of the arts and the virtues are not parallel: because\r those things which are produced by the arts have their excellence in\r themselves, and it is sufficient therefore that these when produced\r should be in a certain state: but those which are produced in the way\r of the virtues, are, strictly speaking, actions of a certain kind (say\r of Justice or perfected Self-Mastery), not merely if in themselves they\r are in a certain state but if also he who does them does them being\r himself in a certain state, first if knowing what he is doing, next if\r with deliberate preference, and ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":147},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-23","text":"The facts,[8] it is true, are called by the names of these habits when\r they are such as the just or perfectly self-mastering man would do; but\r he is not in possession of the virtues who merely does these facts, but\r he who also so does them as the just and self-mastering do them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":148},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-24","text":"We are right then in saying, that these virtues are formed in a man by\r his doing the actions; but no one, if he should leave them undone,\r would be even in the way to become a good man. Yet people in general do\r not perform these actions, but taking refuge in talk they flatter\r themselves they are philosophising, and that they will so be good men:\r acting in truth very like those sick people who listen to the doctor\r with great attention but do nothing that he tells them: just as these\r then cannot be well bodily under such a course of treatment, so neither\r can those be mentally by such phil","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":149},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-25","text":"Next, we must examine what Virtue is.[9] Well, since the things which\r come to be in the mind are, in all, of three kinds, Feelings,\r Capacities, States, Virtue of course must belong to one of the three\r classes.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":150},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-26","text":"By Feelings, I mean such as lust, anger, fear, confidence, envy, joy,\r friendship, hatred, longing, emulation, compassion, in short all such\r as are followed by pleasure or pain: by Capacities, those in right of\r which we are said to be capable of these feelings; as by virtue of\r which we are able to have been made angry, or grieved, or to have\r compassionated; by States, those in right of which we are in a certain\r relation good or bad to the aforementioned feelings; to having been\r made angry, for instance, we are in a wrong relation if in our anger we\r were too violent or too slack, but if ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":151},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-27","text":"Now Feelings neither the virtues nor vices are, because in right of the\r Feelings we are not denominated either good or bad, but in right of the\r virtues and vices we are.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":152},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-28","text":"Again, in right of the Feelings we are neither praised nor blamed,[10]\r (for a man is not commended for being afraid or being angry, nor blamed\r for being angry merely but for being so in a particular way), but in\r right of the virtues and vices we are.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":153},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-29","text":"Again, both anger and fear we feel without moral choice, whereas the\r virtues are acts of moral choice, or at least certainly not independent\r of it.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":154},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-30","text":"Moreover, in right of the Feelings we are said to be moved, but in\r right of the virtues and vices not to be moved, but disposed, in a\r certain way.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":155},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-31","text":"And for these same reasons they are not Capacities, for we are not\r called good or bad merely because we are able to feel, nor are we\r praised or blamed.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":156},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-32","text":"And again, Capacities we have by nature, but we do not come to be good\r or bad by nature, as we have said before.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":157},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-33","text":"Since then the virtues are neither Feelings nor Capacities, it remains\r that they must be States.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":158},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-34","text":"Now what the genus of Virtue is has been said; but we must not merely\r speak of it thus, that it is a state but say also what kind of a state\r it is.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":159},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-35","text":"We must observe then that all excellence makes that whereof it is the\r excellence both to be itself in a good state and to perform its work\r well. The excellence of the eye, for instance, makes both the eye good\r and its work also: for by the excellence of the eye we see well. So too\r the excellence of the horse makes a horse good, and good in speed, and\r in carrying his rider, and standing up against the enemy. If then this\r is universally the case, the excellence of Man, i.e. Virtue, must be a\r state whereby Man comes to be good and whereby he will perform well his\r proper work. Now how this","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":160},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-36","text":"In all quantity then, whether continuous or discrete,[11] one may take\r the greater part, the less, or the exactly equal, and these either with\r reference to the thing itself, or relatively to us: and the exactly\r equal is a mean between excess and defect. Now by the mean of the\r thing, _i.e._ absolute mean, I denote that which is equidistant from\r either extreme (which of course is one and the same to all), and by the\r mean relatively to ourselves, that which is neither too much nor too\r little for the particular individual. This of course is not one nor the\r same to all: for instance, suppos","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":161},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-37","text":"But the mean relatively to ourselves must not be so found ; for it does\r not follow, supposing ten minæ[13] is too large a quantity to eat and\r two too small, that the trainer will order his man six; because for the\r person who is to take it this also may be too much or too little: for\r Milo it would be too little, but for a man just commencing his athletic\r exercises too much: similarly too of the exercises themselves, as\r running or wrestling.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":162},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-38","text":"So then it seems every one possessed of skill avoids excess and defect,\r but seeks for and chooses the mean, not the absolute but the relative.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":163},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-39","text":"Now if all skill thus accomplishes well its work by keeping an eye on\r the mean, and bringing the works to this point (whence it is common\r enough to say of such works as are in a good state, “one cannot add to\r or take ought from them,” under the notion of excess or defect\r destroying goodness but the mean state preserving it), and good\r artisans, as we say, work with their eye on this, and excellence, like\r nature, is more exact and better than any art in the world, it must\r have an aptitude to aim at the mean.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":164},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-40","text":"It is moral excellence, _i.e._ Virtue, of course which I mean, because\r this it is which is concerned with feelings and actions, and in these\r there can be excess and defect and the mean: it is possible, for\r instance, to feel the emotions of fear, confidence, lust, anger,\r compassion, and pleasure and pain generally, too much or too little,\r and in either case wrongly; but to feel them when we ought, on what\r occasions, towards whom, why, and as, we should do, is the mean, or in\r other words the best state, and this is the property of Virtue.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":165},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-41","text":"In like manner too with respect to the actions, there may be excess and\r defect and the mean. Now Virtue is concerned with feelings and actions,\r in which the excess is wrong and the defect is blamed but the mean is\r praised and goes right; and both these circumstances belong to Virtue.\r Virtue then is in a sense a mean state, since it certainly has an\r aptitude for aiming at the mean.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":166},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-42","text":"Again, one may go wrong in many different ways (because, as the\r Pythagoreans expressed it, evil is of the class of the infinite, good\r of the finite), but right only in one; and so the former is easy, the\r latter difficult; easy to miss the mark, but hard to hit it: and for\r these reasons, therefore, both the excess and defect belong to Vice,\r and the mean state to Virtue; for, as the poet has it,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":167},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-43","text":"Virtue then is “a state apt to exercise deliberate choice, being in the\r relative mean, determined by reason, and[14] as the man of practical\r wisdom would determine.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":168},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-44","text":"It is a middle state between too faulty ones, in the way of excess on\r one side and of defect on the other: and it is so moreover, because the\r faulty states on one side fall short of, and those on the other exceed,\r what is right, both in the case of the feelings and the actions; but\r Virtue finds, and when found adopts, the mean.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":169},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-45","text":"And so, viewing it in respect of its essence and definition, Virtue is\r a mean state; but in reference to the chief good and to excellence it\r is the highest state possible.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":170},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-46","text":"But it must not be supposed that every action or every feeling is\r capable of subsisting in this mean state, because some there are which\r are so named as immediately to convey the notion of badness, as\r malevolence, shamelessness, envy; or, to instance in actions, adultery,\r theft, homicide; for all these and suchlike are blamed because they are\r in themselves bad, not the having too much or too little of them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":171},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-47","text":"In these then you never can go right, but must always be wrong: nor in\r such does the right or wrong depend on the selection of a proper\r person, time, or manner (take adultery for instance), but simply doing\r any one soever of those things is being wrong.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":172},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-48","text":"You might as well require that there should be determined a mean state,\r an excess and a defect in respect of acting unjustly, being cowardly,\r or giving up all control of the passions: for at this rate there will\r be of excess and defect a mean state; of excess, excess; and of defect,\r defect.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":173},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-49","text":"But just as of perfected self-mastery and courage there is no excess\r and defect, because the mean is in one point of view the highest\r possible state, so neither of those faulty states can you have a mean\r state, excess, or defect, but howsoever done they are wrong: you\r cannot, in short, have of excess and defect a mean state, nor of a mean\r state excess and defect.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":174},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-50","text":"It is not enough, however, to state this in general terms, we must also\r apply it to particular instances, because in treatises on moral conduct\r general statements have an air of vagueness, but those which go into\r detail one of greater reality: for the actions after all must be in\r detail, and the general statements, to be worth anything, must hold\r good here.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":175},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-51","text":"The Mean state is Courage: men may exceed, of course, either in absence\r of fear or in positive confidence: the former has no name (which is a\r common case), the latter is called rash: again, the man who has too\r much fear and too little confidence is called a coward.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":176},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-52","text":"II. In respect of pleasures and pains (but not all, and perhaps fewer\r pains than pleasures):","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":177},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-53","text":"The Mean state here is perfected Self-Mastery, the defect total absence\r of Self-control. As for defect in respect of pleasure, there are really\r no people who are chargeable with it, so, of course, there is really no\r name for such characters, but, as they are conceivable, we will give\r them one and call them insensible.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":178},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-54","text":"The mean state is Liberality, the excess Prodigality, the defect\r Stinginess: here each of the extremes involves really an excess and\r defect contrary to each other: I mean, the prodigal gives out too much\r and takes in too little, while the stingy man takes in too much and\r gives out too little. (It must be understood that we are now giving\r merely an outline and summary, intentionally: and we will, in a later\r part of the treatise, draw out the distinctions with greater\r exactness.)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":179},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-55","text":"There are other dispositions besides these just mentioned; a mean state\r called Munificence (for the munificent man differs from the liberal,\r the former having necessarily to do with great wealth, the latter with\r but small); the excess called by the names either of Want of taste or\r Vulgar Profusion, and the defect Paltriness (these also differ from the\r extremes connected with liberality, and the manner of their difference\r shall also be spoken of later).","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":180},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-56","text":"The mean state Greatness of Soul, the excess which may be called\r χαυνότης,[17] and the defect Littleness of Soul.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":181},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-57","text":"Now there is a state bearing the same relation to Greatness of Soul as\r we said just now Liberality does to Munificence, with the difference\r that is of being about a small amount of the same thing: this state\r having reference to small honour, as Greatness of Soul to great honour;\r a man may, of course, grasp at honour either more than he should or\r less; now he that exceeds in his grasping at it is called ambitious, he\r that falls short unambitious, he that is just as he should be has no\r proper name: nor in fact have the states, except that the disposition\r of the ambitious man is called am","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":182},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-58","text":"Here too there is excess, defect, and a mean state; but since they may\r be said to have really no proper names, as we call the virtuous\r character Meek, we will call the mean state Meekness, and of the\r extremes, let the man who is excessive be denominated Passionate, and\r the faulty state Passionateness, and him who is deficient Angerless,\r and the defect Angerlessness.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":183},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-59","text":"There are also three other mean states, having some mutual resemblance,\r but still with differences; they are alike in that they all have for\r their object-matter intercourse of words and deeds, and they differ in\r that one has respect to truth herein, the other two to what is\r pleasant; and this in two ways, the one in relaxation and amusement,\r the other in all things which occur in daily life. We must say a word\r or two about these also, that we may the better see that in all matters\r the mean is praiseworthy, while the extremes are neither right nor\r worthy of praise but of blame.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":184},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-60","text":"Now of these, it is true, the majority have really no proper names, but\r still we must try, as in the other cases, to coin some for them for the\r sake of clearness and intelligibleness.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":185},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-61","text":"The man who is in the mean state we will call Truthful, and his state\r  Truthfulness, and as to the disguise of truth, if it be on the side of\r  exaggeration, Braggadocia, and him that has it a Braggadocio; if on\r  that of diminution, Reserve and Reserved shall be the terms.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":186},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-62","text":"The mean state shall be called Easy-pleasantry, and the character\r accordingly a man of Easy-pleasantry; the excess Buffoonery, and the\r man a Buffoon; the man deficient herein a Clown, and his state\r Clownishness.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":187},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-63","text":"He that is as he should be may be called Friendly, and his mean state\r Friendliness: he that exceeds, if it be without any interested motive,\r somewhat too Complaisant, if with such motive, a Flatterer: he that is\r deficient and in all instances unpleasant, Quarrelsome and Cross.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":188},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-64","text":"There are mean states likewise in feelings and matters concerning them.\r Shamefacedness, for instance, is no virtue, still a man is praised for\r being shamefaced: for in these too the one is denominated the man in\r the mean state, the other in the excess; the Dumbfoundered, for\r instance, who is overwhelmed with shame on all and any occasions: the\r man who is in the defect, _i.e._ who has no shame at all in his\r composition, is called Shameless: but the right character Shamefaced.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":189},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-65","text":"Indignation against successful vice,[19] again, is a state in the mean\r between Envy and Malevolence: they all three have respect to pleasure\r and pain produced by what happens to one’s neighbour: for the man who\r has this right feeling is annoyed at undeserved success of others,\r while the envious man goes beyond him and is annoyed at all success of\r others, and the malevolent falls so far short of feeling annoyance that\r he even rejoices [at misfortune of others].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":190},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-66","text":"But for the discussion of these also there will be another opportunity,\r as of Justice too, because the term is used in more senses than one. So\r after this we will go accurately into each and say how they are mean\r states: and in like manner also with respect to the Intellectual\r Excellences.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":191},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-67","text":"Now as there are three states in each case, two faulty either in the\r way of excess or defect, and one right, which is the mean state, of\r course all are in a way opposed to one another; the extremes, for\r instance, not only to the mean but also to one another, and the mean to\r the extremes: for just as the half is greater if compared with the less\r portion, and less if compared with the greater, so the mean states,\r compared with the defects, exceed, whether in feelings or actions, and\r _vice versa_. The brave man, for instance, shows as rash when compared\r with the coward, and cowardly when ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":192},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-68","text":"And so the extreme characters push away, so to speak, towards each\r other the man in the mean state; the brave man is called a rash man by\r the coward, and a coward by the rash man, and in the other cases\r accordingly. And there being this mutual opposition, the contrariety\r between the extremes is greater than between either and the mean,\r because they are further from one another than from the mean, just as\r the greater or less portion differ more from each other than either\r from the exact half.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":193},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-69","text":"Again, in some cases an extreme will bear a resemblance to the mean;\r rashness, for instance, to courage, and prodigality to liberality; but\r between the extremes there is the greatest dissimilarity. Now things\r which are furthest from one another[20] are defined to be contrary, and\r so the further off the more contrary will they be.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":194},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-70","text":"Further: of the extremes in some cases the excess, and in others the\r defect, is most opposed to the mean: to courage, for instance, not\r rashness which is the excess, but cowardice which is the defect;\r whereas to perfected self-mastery not insensibility which is the defect\r but absence of all self-control which is the excess.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":195},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-71","text":"And for this there are two reasons to be given; one from the nature of\r the thing itself, because from the one extreme being nearer and more\r like the mean, we do not put this against it, but the other; as, for\r instance, since rashness is thought to be nearer to courage than\r cowardice is, and to resemble it more, we put cowardice against courage\r rather than rashness, because those things which are further from the\r mean are thought to be more contrary to it. This then is one reason\r arising from the thing itself; there is another arising from our own\r constitution and make: for in each man’","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":196},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-72","text":"These things then to which the bias is, we call more contrary, and so\r total want of self-control (the excess) is more contrary than the\r defect is to perfected self-mastery.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":197},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-73","text":"Now that Moral Virtue is a mean state, and how it is so, and that it\r lies between two faulty states, one in the way of excess and another in\r the way of defect, and that it is so because it has an aptitude to aim\r at the mean both in feelings and actions, all this has been set forth\r fully and sufficiently.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":198},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-74","text":"And so it is hard to be good: for surely hard it is in each instance to\r find the mean, just as to find the mean point or centre of a circle is\r not what any man can do, but only he who knows how: just so to be\r angry, to give money, and be expensive, is what any man can do, and\r easy: but to do these to the right person, in due proportion, at the\r right time, with a right object, and in the right manner, this is not\r as before what any man can do, nor is it easy; and for this cause\r goodness is rare, and praiseworthy, and noble.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":199},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-75","text":"Therefore he who aims at the mean should make it his first care to keep\r away from that extreme which is more contrary than the other to the\r mean; just as Calypso in Homer advises Ulysses,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":200},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-76","text":"because of the two extremes the one is always more, and the other less,\r erroneous; and, therefore, since to hit exactly on the mean is\r difficult, one must take the least of the evils as the safest plan;[21]\r and this a man will be doing, if he follows this method.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":201},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-77","text":"We ought also to take into consideration our own natural bias; which\r varies in each man’s case, and will be ascertained from the pleasure\r and pain arising in us. Furthermore, we should force ourselves off in\r the contrary direction, because we shall find ourselves in the mean\r after we have removed ourselves far from the wrong side, exactly as men\r do in straightening bent timber.[22]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":202},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-78","text":"But in all cases we must guard most carefully against what is pleasant,\r and pleasure itself, because we are not impartial judges of it.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":203},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-79","text":"We ought to feel in fact towards pleasure as did the old counsellors\r towards Helen, and in all cases pronounce a similar sentence; for so by\r sending it away from us, we shall err the less.[23]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":204},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-80","text":"Well, to speak very briefly, these are the precautions by adopting\r which we shall be best able to attain the mean.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":205},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-81","text":"Still, perhaps, after all it is a matter of difficulty, and specially\r in the particular instances: it is not easy, for instance, to determine\r exactly in what manner, with what persons, for what causes, and for\r what length of time, one ought to feel anger: for we ourselves\r sometimes praise those who are defective in this feeling, and we call\r them meek; at another, we term the hot-tempered manly and spirited.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":206},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-82","text":"Then, again, he who makes a small deflection from what is right, be it\r on the side of too much or too little, is not blamed, only he who makes\r a considerable one; for he cannot escape observation. But to what point\r or degree a man must err in order to incur blame, it is not easy to\r determine exactly in words: nor in fact any of those points which are\r matter of perception by the Moral Sense: such questions are matters of\r detail, and the decision of them rests with the Moral Sense.[24]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":207},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-3-83","text":"At all events thus much is plain, that the mean state is in all things\r praiseworthy, and that practically we must deflect sometimes towards\r excess sometimes towards defect, because this will be the easiest\r method of hitting on the mean, that is, on what is right.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":208},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-1","text":"Now since Virtue is concerned with the regulation of feelings and\r actions, and praise and blame arise upon such as are voluntary, while\r for the involuntary allowance is made, and sometimes compassion is\r excited, it is perhaps a necessary task for those who are investigating\r the nature of Virtue to draw out the distinction between what is\r voluntary and what involuntary; and it is certainly useful for\r legislators, with respect to the assigning of honours and punishments.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":209},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-2","text":"Involuntary actions then are thought to be of two kinds, being done\r either on compulsion, or by reason of ignorance. An action is, properly\r speaking, compulsory, when the origination is external to the agent,\r being such that in it the agent (perhaps we may more properly say the\r patient) contributes nothing; as if a wind were to convey you anywhere,\r or men having power over your person.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":210},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-3","text":"But when actions are done, either from fear of greater evils, or from\r some honourable motive, as, for instance, if you were ordered to commit\r some base act by a despot who had your parents or children in his\r power, and they were to be saved upon your compliance or die upon your\r refusal, in such cases there is room for a question whether the actions\r are voluntary or involuntary.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":211},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-4","text":"A similar question arises with respect to cases of throwing goods\r overboard in a storm: abstractedly no man throws away his property\r willingly, but with a view to his own and his shipmates’ safety any one\r would who had any sense.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":212},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-5","text":"The truth is, such actions are of a mixed kind, but are most like\r voluntary actions; for they are choice-worthy at the time when they are\r being done, and the end or object of the action must be taken with\r reference to the actual occasion. Further, we must denominate an action\r voluntary or involuntary at the time of doing it: now in the given case\r the man acts voluntarily, because the originating of the motion of his\r limbs in such actions rests with himself; and where the origination is\r in himself it rests with himself to do or not to do.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":213},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-6","text":"Such actions then are voluntary, though in the abstract perhaps\r involuntary because no one would choose any of such things in and by\r itself.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":214},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-7","text":"But for such actions men sometimes are even praised, as when they\r endure any disgrace or pain to secure great and honourable equivalents;\r if _vice versâ_, then they are blamed, because it shows a base mind to\r endure things very disgraceful for no honourable object, or for a\r trifling one.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":215},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-8","text":"For some again no praise is given, but allowance is made; as where a\r man does what he should not by reason of such things as overstrain the\r powers of human nature, or pass the limits of human endurance.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":216},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-9","text":"Some acts perhaps there are for which compulsion cannot be pleaded, but\r a man should rather suffer the worst and die; how absurd, for instance,\r are the pleas of compulsion with which Alcmaeon in Euripides’ play\r excuses his matricide!","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":217},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-10","text":"But it is difficult sometimes to decide what kind of thing should be\r chosen instead of what, or what endured in preference to what, and much\r moreso to abide by one’s decisions: for in general the alternatives are\r painful, and the actions required are base, and so praise or blame is\r awarded according as persons have been compelled or no.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":218},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-11","text":"What kind of actions then are to be called compulsory? may we say,\r simply and abstractedly whenever the cause is external and the agent\r contributes nothing; and that where the acts are in themselves such as\r one would not wish but choice-worthy at the present time and in\r preference to such and such things, and where the origination rests\r with the agent, the actions are in themselves involuntary but at the\r given time and in preference to such and such things voluntary; and\r they are more like voluntary than involuntary, because the actions\r consist of little details, and these are voluntar","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":219},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-12","text":"But what kind of things one ought to choose instead of what, it is not\r easy to settle, for there are many differences in particular instances.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":220},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-13","text":"But suppose a person should say, things pleasant and honourable exert a\r compulsive force (for that they are external and do compel); at that\r rate every action is on compulsion, because these are universal motives\r of action.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":221},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-14","text":"Again, they who act on compulsion and against their will do so with\r pain; but they who act by reason of what is pleasant or honourable act\r with pleasure.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":222},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-15","text":"It is truly absurd for a man to attribute his actions to external\r things instead of to his own capacity for being easily caught by\r them;[1] or, again, to ascribe the honourable to himself, and the base\r ones to pleasure.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":223},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-16","text":"So then that seems to be compulsory “whose origination is from without,\r the party compelled contributing nothing.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":224},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-17","text":"Now every action of which ignorance is the cause is not-voluntary, but\r that only is involuntary which is attended with pain and remorse; for\r clearly the man who has done anything by reason of ignorance, but is\r not annoyed at his own action, cannot be said to have done it _with_\r his will because he did not know he was doing it, nor again _against_\r his will because he is not sorry for it.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":225},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-18","text":"So then of the class “acting by reason of ignorance,” he who feels\r regret afterwards is thought to be an involuntary agent, and him that\r has no such feeling, since he certainly is different from the other, we\r will call a not-voluntary agent; for as there is a real difference it\r is better to have a proper name.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":226},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-19","text":"Again, there seems to be a difference between acting _because of_\r ignorance and acting _with_ ignorance: for instance, we do not usually\r assign ignorance as the cause of the actions of the drunken or angry\r man, but either the drunkenness or the anger, yet they act not\r knowingly but with ignorance.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":227},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-20","text":"Again, every bad man is ignorant what he ought to do and what to leave\r undone, and by reason of such error men become unjust and wholly evil.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":228},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-21","text":"Again, we do not usually apply the term involuntary when a man is\r ignorant of his own true interest;[2] because ignorance which affects\r moral choice[3] constitutes depravity but not involuntariness: nor does\r any ignorance of principle (because for this men are blamed) but\r ignorance in particular details, wherein consists the action and\r wherewith it is concerned, for in these there is both compassion and\r allowance, because he who acts in ignorance of any of them acts in a\r proper sense involuntarily.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":229},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-22","text":"It may be as well, therefore, to define these particular details; what\r they are, and how many; viz. who acts, what he is doing, with respect\r to what or in what, sometimes with what, as with what instrument, and\r with what result;[4] as that of preservation, for instance, and how, as\r whether softly or violently.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":230},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-23","text":"All these particulars, in one and the same case, no man in his senses\r could be ignorant of; plainly not of the agent, being himself. But what\r he is doing a man may be ignorant, as men in speaking say a thing\r escaped them unawares; or as Aeschylus did with respect to the\r Mysteries, that he was not aware that it was unlawful to speak of them;\r or as in the case of that catapult accident the other day the man said\r he discharged it merely to display its operation. Or a person might\r suppose a son to be an enemy, as Merope did; or that the spear really\r pointed was rounded off; or that the sto","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":231},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-24","text":"Now since ignorance is possible in respect to all these details in\r which the action consists, he that acted in ignorance of any of them is\r thought to have acted involuntarily, and he most so who was in\r ignorance as regards the most important, which are thought to be those\r in which the action consists, and the result.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":232},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-25","text":"Further, not only must the ignorance be of this kind, to constitute an\r action involuntary, but it must be also understood that the action is\r followed by pain and regret.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":233},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-26","text":"Now since all involuntary action is either upon compulsion or by reason\r of ignorance, Voluntary Action would seem to be “that whose origination\r is in the agent, he being aware of the particular details in which the\r action consists.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":234},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-27","text":"For, it may be, men are not justified by calling those actions\r involuntary, which are done by reason of Anger or Lust.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":235},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-28","text":"Because, in the first place, if this be so no other animal but man, and\r not even children, can be said to act voluntarily. Next, is it meant\r that we never act voluntarily when we act from Lust or Anger, or that\r we act voluntarily in doing what is right and involuntarily in doing\r what is discreditable? The latter supposition is absurd, since the\r cause is one and the same. Then as to the former, it is a strange thing\r to maintain actions to be involuntary which we are bound to grasp at:\r now there are occasions on which anger is a duty,[5] and there are\r things which we are bound to lust af","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":236},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-29","text":"Again, whereas actions strictly involuntary are thought to be attended\r with pain, those which are done to gratify lust are thought to be\r pleasant.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":237},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-30","text":"Again: how does the involuntariness make any difference[7] between\r wrong actions done from deliberate calculation, and those done by\r reason of anger? for both ought to be avoided, and the irrational\r feelings are thought to be just as natural to man as reason, and so of\r course must be such actions of the individual as are done from Anger\r and Lust. It is absurd then to class these actions among the\r involuntary.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":238},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-31","text":"Having thus drawn out the distinction between voluntary and involuntary\r action our next step is to examine into the nature of Moral Choice,\r because this seems most intimately connected with Virtue and to be a\r more decisive test of moral character than a man’s acts are.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":239},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-32","text":"Now Moral Choice is plainly voluntary, but the two are not\r co-extensive, voluntary being the more comprehensive term; for first,\r children and all other animals share in voluntary action but not in\r Moral Choice; and next, sudden actions we call voluntary but do not\r ascribe them to Moral Choice.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":240},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-33","text":"Nor do they appear to be right who say it is lust or anger, or wish, or\r opinion of a certain kind; because, in the first place, Moral Choice is\r not shared by the irrational animals while Lust and Anger are. Next;\r the man who fails of self-control acts from Lust but not from Moral\r Choice; the man of self-control, on the contrary, from Moral Choice,\r not from Lust. Again: whereas Lust is frequently opposed to Moral\r Choice, Lust is not to Lust.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":241},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-34","text":"Lastly: the object-matter of Lust is the pleasant and the painful, but\r of Moral Choice neither the one nor the other. Still less can it be\r Anger, because actions done from Anger are thought generally to be\r least of all consequent on Moral Choice.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":242},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-35","text":"Nor is it Wish either, though appearing closely connected with it;\r because, in the first place, Moral Choice has not for its objects\r impossibilities, and if a man were to say he chose them he would be\r thought to be a fool; but Wish may have impossible things for its\r objects, immortality for instance.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":243},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-36","text":"Wish again may be exercised on things in the accomplishment of which\r one’s self could have nothing to do, as the success of any particular\r actor or athlete; but no man chooses things of this nature, only such\r as he believes he may himself be instrumental in procuring.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":244},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-37","text":"Further: Wish has for its object the End rather, but Moral Choice the\r means to the End; for instance, we wish to be healthy but we choose the\r means which will make us so; or happiness again we wish for, and\r commonly say so, but to say we choose is not an appropriate term,\r because, in short, the province of Moral Choice seems to be those\r things which are in our own power.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":245},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-38","text":"Neither can it be Opinion; for Opinion is thought to be unlimited in\r its range of objects, and to be exercised as well upon things eternal\r and impossible as on those which are in our own power: again, Opinion\r is logically divided into true and false, not into good and bad as\r Moral Choice is.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":246},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-39","text":"However, nobody perhaps maintains its identity with Opinion simply; but\r it is not the same with opinion of any kind,[8] because by choosing good\r and bad things we are constituted of a certain character, but by having\r opinions on them we are not.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":247},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-40","text":"Again, we choose to take or avoid, and so on, but we opine what a thing\r is, or for what it is serviceable, or how; but we do not opine to take\r or avoid.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":248},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-41","text":"Further, Moral Choice is commended rather for having a right object\r than for being judicious, but Opinion for being formed in accordance\r with truth.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":249},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-42","text":"Again, we choose such things as we pretty well know to be good, but we\r form opinions respecting such as we do not know at all.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":250},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-43","text":"And it is not thought that choosing and opining best always go\r together, but that some opine the better course and yet by reason of\r viciousness choose not the things which they should.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":251},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-44","text":"It may be urged, that Opinion always precedes or accompanies Moral\r Choice; be it so, this makes no difference, for this is not the point\r in question, but whether Moral Choice is the same as Opinion of a\r certain kind.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":252},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-45","text":"Since then it is none of the aforementioned things, what is it, or how\r is it characterised? Voluntary it plainly is, but not all voluntary\r action is an object of Moral Choice. May we not say then, it is “that\r voluntary which has passed through a stage of previous deliberation?”\r because Moral Choice is attended with reasoning and intellectual\r process. The etymology of its Greek name seems to give a hint of it,\r being when analysed “chosen in preference to somewhat else.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":253},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-46","text":"Well then; do men deliberate about everything, and is anything soever\r the object of Deliberation, or are there some matters with respect to\r which there is none? (It may be as well perhaps to say, that by “object\r of Deliberation” is meant such matter as a sensible man would\r deliberate upon, not what any fool or madman might.)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":254},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-47","text":"Well: about eternal things no one deliberates; as, for instance, the\r universe, or the incommensurability of the diameter and side of a\r square.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":255},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-48","text":"Nor again about things which are in motion but which always happen in\r the same way either necessarily, or naturally, or from some other\r cause, as the solstices or the sunrise.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":256},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-49","text":"Nor about those which are variable, as drought and rains; nor\r fortuitous matters, as finding of treasure.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":257},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-50","text":"Nor in fact even about all human affairs; no Lacedæmonian, for\r instance, deliberates as to the best course for the Scythian government\r to adopt; because in such cases we have no power over the result.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":258},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-51","text":"But we do deliberate respecting such practical matters as are in our\r own power (which are what are left after all our exclusions).","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":259},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-52","text":"I have adopted this division because causes seem to be divisible into\r nature, necessity, chance, and moreover intellect, and all human\r powers.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":260},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-53","text":"And as man in general deliberates about what man in general can effect,\r so individuals do about such practical things as can be effected\r through their own instrumentality.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":261},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-54","text":"Again, we do not deliberate respecting such arts or sciences as are\r exact and independent: as, for instance, about written characters,\r because we have no doubt how they should be formed; but we do\r deliberate on all buch things as are usually done through our own\r instrumentality, but not invariably in the same way; as, for instance,\r about matters connected with the healing art, or with money-making;\r and, again, more about piloting ships than gymnastic exercises, because\r the former has been less exactly determined, and so forth; and more\r about arts than sciences, because we more frequent","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":262},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-55","text":"So then Deliberation takes place in such matters as are under general\r laws, but still uncertain how in any given case they will issue, _i.e._\r in which there is some indefiniteness; and for great matters we\r associate coadjutors in counsel, distrusting our ability to settle them\r alone.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":263},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-56","text":"Further, we deliberate not about Ends, but Means to Ends. No physician,\r for instance, deliberates whether he will cure, nor orator whether he\r will persuade, nor statesman whether he will produce a good\r constitution, nor in fact any man in any other function about his\r particular End; but having set before them a certain End they look how\r and through what means it may be accomplished: if there is a choice of\r means, they examine further which are easiest and most creditable; or,\r if there is but one means of accomplishing the object, then how it may\r be through this, this again through what","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":264},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-57","text":"And by possible I mean what may be done through our own instrumentality\r (of course what may be done through our friends is through our own\r instrumentality in a certain sense, because the origination in such\r cases rests with us). And the object of search is sometimes the\r necessary instruments, sometimes the method of using them; and\r similarly in the rest sometimes through what, and sometimes how or\r through what.[9]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":265},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-58","text":"So it seems, as has been said, that Man is the originator of his\r actions; and Deliberation has for its object whatever may be done\r through one’s own instrumentality, and the actions are with a view to\r other things; and so it is, not the End, but the Means to Ends on which\r Deliberation is employed.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":266},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-59","text":"Nor, again, is it employed on matters of detail, as whether the\r substance before me is bread, or has been properly cooked; for these\r come under the province of sense, and if a man is to be always\r deliberating, he may go on _ad infinitum_.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":267},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-60","text":"Further, exactly the same matter is the object both of Deliberation and\r Moral Choice; but that which is the object of Moral Choice is\r thenceforward separated off and definite,[10] because by object of\r Moral Choice is denoted that which after Deliberation has been\r preferred to something else: for each man leaves off searching how he\r shall do a thing when he has brought the origination up to himself,\r _i.e_. to the governing principle in himself,[11] because it is this\r which makes the choice. A good illustration of this is furnished by the\r old regal constitutions which Homer drew from, in","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":268},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-61","text":"Now since that which is the object of Moral Choice is something in our\r own power, which is the object of deliberation and the grasping of the\r Will, Moral Choice must be “a grasping after something in our own power\r consequent upon Deliberation:” because after having deliberated we\r decide, and then grasp by our Will in accordance with the result of our\r deliberation.[12]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":269},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-62","text":"Let this be accepted as a sketch of the nature and object of Moral\r Choice, that object being “Means to Ends.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":270},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-63","text":"That Wish has for its object-matter the End, has been already stated;\r but there are two opinions respecting it; some thinking that its object\r is real good, others whatever impresses the mind with a notion of good.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":271},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-64","text":"Now those who maintain that the object of Wish is real good are beset\r by this difficulty, that what is wished for by him who chooses wrongly\r is not really an object of Wish (because, on their theory, if it is an\r object of wish, it must be good, but it is, in the case supposed,\r evil). Those who maintain, on the contrary, that that which impresses\r the mind with a notion of good is properly the object of Wish, have to\r meet this difficulty, that there is nothing naturally an object of Wish\r but to each individual whatever seems good to him; now different people\r have different notions, and i","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":272},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-65","text":"But, if these opinions do not satisfy us, may we not say that,\r abstractedly and as a matter of objective truth, the really good is the\r object of Wish, but to each individual whatever impresses his mind with\r the notion of good.[13] And so to the good man that is an object of\r Wish which is really and truly so, but to the bad man anything may be;\r just as physically those things are wholesome to the healthy which are\r really so, but other things to the sick. And so too of bitter and\r sweet, and hot and heavy, and so on. For the good man judges in every\r instance correctly, and in every instan","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":273},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-66","text":"For there are fair and pleasant things peculiar to, and so varying\r with, each state; and perhaps the most distinguishing characteristic of\r the good man is his seeing the truth in every instance, he being, in\r fact, the rule and measure of these matters.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":274},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-67","text":"The multitude of men seem to be deceived by reason of pleasure, because\r though it is not really a good it impresses their minds with the notion\r of goodness, so they choose what is pleasant as good and avoid pain as\r an evil.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":275},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-68","text":"Now since the End is the object of Wish, and the means to the End of\r Deliberation and Moral Choice, the actions regarding these matters must\r be in the way of Moral Choice, _i.e._ voluntary: but the acts of\r working out the virtues are such actions, and therefore Virtue is in\r our power.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":276},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-69","text":"And so too is Vice: because wherever it is in our power to do it is\r also in our power to forbear doing, and _vice versâ_: therefore if the\r doing (being in a given case creditable) is in our power, so too is the\r forbearing (which is in the same case discreditable), and _vice versâ_.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":277},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-70","text":"But if it is in our power to do and to forbear doing what is creditable\r or the contrary, and these respectively constitute the being good or\r bad, then the being good or vicious characters is in our power.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":278},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-71","text":"As for the well-known saying, “No man voluntarily is wicked or\r involuntarily happy,” it is partly true, partly false; for no man is\r happy against his will, of course, but wickedness is voluntary. Or must\r we dispute the statements lately made, and not say that Man is the\r originator or generator of his actions as much as of his children?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":279},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-72","text":"But if this is matter of plain manifest fact, and we cannot refer our\r actions to any other originations beside those in our own power, those\r things must be in our own power, and so voluntary, the originations of\r which are in ourselves.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":280},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-73","text":"Moreover, testimony seems to be borne to these positions both privately\r by individuals, and by law-givers too, in that they chastise and punish\r those who do wrong (unless they do so on compulsion, or by reason of\r ignorance which is not self-caused), while they honour those who act\r rightly, under the notion of being likely to encourage the latter and\r restrain the former. But such things as are not in our own power,\r _i.e._ not voluntary, no one thinks of encouraging us to do, knowing it\r to be of no avail for one to have been persuaded not to be hot (for\r instance), or feel pain, or be hun","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":281},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-74","text":"And what makes the case stronger is this: that they chastise for the\r very fact of ignorance, when it is thought to be self-caused; to the\r drunken, for instance, penalties are double, because the origination in\r such case lies in a man’s own self: for he might have helped getting\r drunk, and this is the cause of his ignorance.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":282},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-75","text":"Again, those also who are ignorant of legal regulations which they are\r bound to know, and which are not hard to know, they chastise; and\r similarly in all other cases where neglect is thought to be the cause\r of the ignorance, under the notion that it was in their power to\r prevent their ignorance, because they might have paid attention.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":283},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-76","text":"But perhaps a man is of such a character that he cannot attend to such\r things: still men are themselves the causes of having become such\r characters by living carelessly, and also of being unjust or destitute\r of self-control, the former by doing evil actions, the latter by\r spending their time in drinking and such-like; because the particular\r acts of working form corresponding characters, as is shown by those who\r are practising for any contest or particular course of action, for such\r men persevere in the acts of working.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":284},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-77","text":"As for the plea, that a man did not know that habits are produced from\r separate acts of working, we reply, such ignorance is a mark of\r excessive stupidity.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":285},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-78","text":"Furthermore, it is wholly irrelevant to say that the man who acts\r unjustly or dissolutely does not _wish_ to attain the habits of these\r vices: for if a man wittingly does those things whereby he must become\r unjust he is to all intents and purposes unjust voluntarily; but he\r cannot with a wish cease to be unjust and become just. For, to take the\r analogous case, the sick man cannot with a wish be well again, yet in a\r supposable case he is voluntarily ill because he has produced his\r sickness by living intemperately and disregarding his physicians. There\r was a time then when he might have ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":286},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-79","text":"And not only are mental diseases voluntary, but the bodily are so in\r some men, whom we accordingly blame: for such as are naturally deformed\r no one blames, only such as are so by reason of want of exercise, and\r neglect: and so too of weakness and maiming: no one would think of\r upbraiding, but would rather compassionate, a man who is blind by\r nature, or from disease, or from an accident; but every one would blame\r him who was so from excess of wine, or any other kind of intemperance.\r It seems, then, that in respect of bodily diseases, those which depend\r on ourselves are censured, those w","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":287},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-80","text":"But suppose a man to say, “that (by our own admission) all men aim at\r that which conveys to their minds an impression of good, and that men\r have no control over this impression, but that the End impresses each\r with a notion correspondent to his own individual character; that to be\r sure if each man is in a way the cause of his own moral state, so he\r will be also of the kind of impression he receives: whereas, if this is\r not so, no one is the cause to himself of doing evil actions, but he\r does them by reason of ignorance of the true End, supposing that\r through their means he will secure ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":288},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-81","text":"If all this be true, how will Virtue be a whit more voluntary than\r Vice? Alike to the good man and the bad, the End gives its impression\r and is fixed by nature or howsoever you like to say, and they act so\r and so, referring everything else to this End.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":289},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-82","text":"Whether then we suppose that the End impresses each man’s mind with\r certain notions not merely by nature, but that there is somewhat also\r dependent on himself; or that the End is given by nature, and yet\r Virtue is voluntary because the good man does all the rest voluntarily,\r Vice must be equally so; because his own agency equally attaches to the\r bad man in the actions, even if not in the selection of the End.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":290},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-83","text":"If then, as is commonly said, the Virtues are voluntary (because we at\r least cooperate[15] in producing our moral states, and we assume the\r End to be of a certain kind according as we are ourselves of certain\r characters), the Vices must be voluntary also, because the cases are\r exactly similar.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":291},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-84","text":"Well now, we have stated generally respecting the Moral Virtues, the\r genus (in outline), that they are mean states, and that they are\r habits, and how they are formed, and that they are of themselves\r calculated to act upon the circumstances out of which they were formed,\r and that they are in our own power and voluntary, and are to be done so\r as right Reason may direct.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":292},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-85","text":"But the particular actions and the habits are not voluntary in the same\r sense; for of the actions we are masters from beginning to end\r (supposing of course a knowledge of the particular details), but only\r of the origination of the habits, the addition by small particular\r accessions not being cognisiable (as is the case with sicknesses):\r still they are voluntary because it rested with us to use our\r circumstances this way or that.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":293},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-86","text":"Here we will resume the particular discussion of the Moral Virtues, and\r say what they are, what is their object-matter, and how they stand\r respectively related to it: of course their number will be thereby\r shown.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":294},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-87","text":"First, then, of Courage. Now that it is a mean state, in respect of\r fear and boldness, has been already said: further, the objects of our\r fears are obviously things fearful or, in a general way of statement,\r evils; which accounts for the common definition of fear, viz.\r “expectation of evil.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":295},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-88","text":"Of course we fear evils of all kinds: disgrace, for instance, poverty,\r disease, desolateness, death; but not all these seem to be the\r object-matter of the Brave man, because there are things which to fear\r is right and noble, and not to fear is base; disgrace, for example,\r since he who fears this is a good man and has a sense of honour, and he\r who does not fear it is shameless (though there are those who call him\r Brave by analogy, because he somewhat resembles the Brave man who\r agrees with him in being free from fear); but poverty, perhaps, or\r disease, and in fact whatever does not proc","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":296},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-89","text":"Yet we do apply the term[16] in right of the similarity of the cases;\r for there are men who, though timid in the dangers of war, are liberal\r men and are stout enough to face loss of wealth.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":297},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-90","text":"And, again, a man is not a coward for fearing insult to his wife or\r children, or envy, or any such thing; nor is he a Brave man for being\r bold when going to be scourged.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":298},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-91","text":"What kind of fearful things then do constitute the object-matter of the\r Brave man? first of all, must they not be the greatest, since no man is\r more apt to withstand what is dreadful. Now the object of the greatest\r dread is death, because it is the end of all things, and the dead man\r is thought to be capable neither of good nor evil. Still it would seem\r that the Brave man has not for his object-matter even death in every\r circumstance; on the sea, for example, or in sickness: in what\r circumstances then? must it not be in the most honourable? now such is\r death in war, because it is death","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":299},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-92","text":"He then may be most properly denominated Brave who is fearless in\r respect of honourable death and such sudden emergencies as threaten\r death; now such specially are those which arise in the course of war.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":300},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-93","text":"It is not meant but that the Brave man will be fearless also on the sea\r (and in sickness), but not in the same way as sea-faring men; for these\r are light-hearted and hopeful by reason of their experience, while\r landsmen though Brave are apt to give themselves up for lost and\r shudder at the notion of such a death: to which it should be added that\r Courage is exerted in circumstances which admit of doing something to\r help one’s self, or in which death would be honourable; now neither of\r these requisites attach to destruction by drowning or sickness.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":301},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-94","text":"Again, fearful is a term of relation, the same thing not being so to\r all, and there is according to common parlance somewhat so fearful as\r to be beyond human endurance: this of course would be fearful to every\r man of sense, but those objects which are level to the capacity of man\r differ in magnitude and admit of degrees, so too the objects of\r confidence or boldness.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":302},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-95","text":"Now the Brave man cannot be frighted from his propriety (but of course\r only so far as he is man); fear such things indeed he will, but he will\r stand up against them as he ought and as right reason may direct, with\r a view to what is honourable, because this is the end of the virtue.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":303},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-96","text":"Now it is possible to fear these things too much, or too little, or\r again to fear what is not really fearful as if it were such. So the\r errors come to be either that a man fears when he ought not to fear at\r all, or that he fears in an improper way, or at a wrong time, and so\r forth; and so too in respect of things inspiring confidence. He is\r Brave then who withstands, and fears, and is bold, in respect of right\r objects, from a right motive, in right manner, and at right times:\r since the Brave man suffers or acts as he ought and as right reason may\r direct.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":304},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-97","text":"Now the end of every separate act of working is that which accords with\r the habit, and so to the Brave man Courage; which is honourable;\r therefore such is also the End, since the character of each is\r determined by the End.[17]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":305},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-98","text":"So honour is the motive from which the Brave man withstands things\r fearful and performs the acts which accord with Courage.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":306},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-99","text":"Of the characters on the side of Excess, he who exceeds in utter\r absence of fear has no appropriate name (I observed before that many\r states have none), but he would be a madman or inaccessible to pain if\r he feared nothing, neither earthquake, nor the billows, as they tell of\r the Celts.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":307},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-100","text":"He again who exceeds in confidence in respect of things fearful is\r rash. He is thought moreover to be a braggart, and to advance unfounded\r claims to the character of Brave: the relation which the Brave man\r really bears to objects of fear this man wishes to appear to bear, and\r so imitates him in whatever points he can; for this reason most of them\r exhibit a curious mixture of rashness and cowardice; because, affecting\r rashness in these circumstances, they do not withstand what is truly\r fearful.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":308},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-101","text":"The man moreover who exceeds in feeling fear is a coward, since there\r attach to him the circumstances of fearing wrong objects, in wrong\r ways, and so forth. He is deficient also in feeling confidence, but he\r is most clearly seen as exceeding in the case of pains; he is a\r fainthearted kind of man, for he fears all things: the Brave man is\r just the contrary, for boldness is the property of the light-hearted\r and hopeful.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":309},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-102","text":"So the coward, the rash, and the Brave man have exactly the same\r object-matter, but stand differently related to it: the two\r first-mentioned respectively exceed and are deficient, the last is in a\r mean state and as he ought to be. The rash again are precipitate, and,\r being eager before danger, when actually in it fall away, while the\r Brave are quick and sharp in action, but before are quiet and composed.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":310},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-103","text":"Well then, as has been said, Courage is a mean state in respect of\r objects inspiring boldness or fear, in the circumstances which have\r been stated, and the Brave man chooses his line and withstands danger\r either because to do so is honourable, or because not to do so is base.\r But dying to escape from poverty, or the pangs of love, or anything\r that is simply painful, is the act not of a Brave man but of a coward;\r because it is mere softness to fly from what is toilsome, and the\r suicide braves the terrors of death not because it is honourable but to\r get out of the reach of evil.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":311},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-104","text":"Courage proper is somewhat of the kind I have described, but there are\r dispositions, differing in five ways,[18] which also bear in common\r parlance the name of Courage.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":312},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-105","text":"We will take first that which bears most resemblance to the true, the\r Courage of Citizenship, so named because the motives which are thought\r to actuate the members of a community in braving danger are the\r penalties and disgrace held out by the laws to cowardice, and the\r dignities conferred on the Brave; which is thought to be the reason why\r those are the bravest people among whom cowards are visited with\r disgrace and the Brave held in honour.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":313},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-106","text":"Such is the kind of Courage Homer exhibits in his characters; Diomed\r and Hector for example. The latter says,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":314},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-107","text":"This I say most nearly resembles the Courage before spoken of, because\r it arises from virtue, from a feeling of shame, and a desire of what is\r noble (that is, of honour), and avoidance of disgrace which is base.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":315},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-108","text":"In the same rank one would be inclined to place those also who act\r under compulsion from their commanders; yet are they really lower,\r because not a sense of honour but fear is the motive from which they\r act, and what they seek to avoid is not that which is base but that\r which is simply painful: commanders do in fact compel their men\r sometimes, as Hector says (to quote Homer again),","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":316},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-109","text":"“But whomsoever I shall find cowering afar from the fight,\r The teeth of dogs he shall by no means escape.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":317},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-110","text":"Those commanders who station staunch troops by doubtful ones,[19] or\r who beat their men if they flinch, or who draw their troops up in line\r with the trenches, or other similar obstacles, in their rear, do in\r effect the same as Hector, for they all use compulsion.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":318},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-111","text":"In the next place, Experience and Skill in the various particulars is\r thought to be a species of Courage: whence Socrates also thought that\r Courage was knowledge.[20]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":319},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-112","text":"This quality is exhibited of course by different men under different\r circumstances, but in warlike matters, with which we are now concerned,\r it is exhibited by the soldiers (“the regulars”): for there are, it\r would seem, many things in war of no real importance[21] which these\r have been constantly used to see; so they have a show of Courage\r because other people are not aware of the real nature of these things.\r Then again by reason of their skill they are better able than any\r others to inflict without suffering themselves, because they are able\r to use their arms and have such as are mos","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":320},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-113","text":"In fact, the regular troops come to be cowards whenever the danger is\r greater than their means of meeting it; supposing, for example, that\r they are inferior in numbers and resources: then they are the first to\r fly, but the mere militia stand and fall on the ground (which as you\r know really happened at the Hermæum),[22] for in the eyes of these\r flight was disgraceful and death preferable to safety bought at such a\r price: while “the regulars” originally went into the danger under a\r notion of their own superiority, but on discovering their error they\r took to flight,[23] having greater fea","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":321},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-114","text":"Thirdly, mere Animal Spirit is sometimes brought under the term\r Courage: they are thought to be Brave who are carried on by mere Animal\r Spirit, as are wild beasts against those who have wounded them, because\r in fact the really Brave have much Spirit, there being nothing like it\r for going at danger of any kind; whence those frequent expressions in\r Homer, “infused strength into his spirit,” “roused his strength and\r spirit,” or again, “and keen strength in his nostrils,” “his blood\r boiled:” for all these seem to denote the arousing and impetuosity of\r the Animal Spirit.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":322},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-115","text":"Now they that are truly Brave act from a sense of honour, and this\r Animal Spirit co-operates with them; but wild beasts from pain, that is\r because they have been wounded, or are frightened; since if they are\r quietly in their own haunts, forest or marsh, they do not attack men.\r Surely they are not Brave because they rush into danger when goaded on\r by pain and mere Spirit, without any view of the danger: else would\r asses be Brave when they are hungry, for though beaten they will not\r then leave their pasture: profligate men besides do many bold actions\r by reason of their lust. We may conc","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":323},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-116","text":"So men also are pained by a feeling of anger, and take pleasure in\r revenge; but they who fight from these causes may be good fighters, but\r they are not truly Brave (in that they do not act from a sense of\r honour, nor as reason directs, but merely from the present feeling),\r still they bear some resemblance to that character.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":324},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-117","text":"Nor, again, are the Sanguine and Hopeful therefore Brave: since their\r boldness in dangers arises from their frequent victories over numerous\r foes. The two characters are alike, however, in that both are\r confident; but then the Brave are so from the afore-mentioned causes,\r whereas these are so from a settled conviction of their being superior\r and not likely to suffer anything in return (they who are intoxicated\r do much the same, for they become hopeful when in that state); but when\r the event disappoints their expectations they run away: now it was said\r to be the character of a Brave man","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":325},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-118","text":"For this reason it is thought to be a greater proof of Courage to be\r fearless and undisturbed under the pressure of sudden fear than under\r that which may be anticipated, because Courage then comes rather from a\r fixed habit, or less from preparation: since as to foreseen dangers a\r man might take his line even from calculation and reasoning, but in\r those which are sudden he will do so according to his fixed habit of\r mind.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":326},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-119","text":"Fifthly and lastly, those who are acting under Ignorance have a show of\r Courage and are not very far from the Hopeful; but still they are\r inferior inasmuch as they have no opinion of themselves; which the\r others have, and therefore stay and contest a field for some little\r time; but they who have been deceived fly the moment they know things\r to be otherwise than they supposed, which the Argives experienced when\r they fell on the Lacedæmonians, taking them for the men of Sicyon.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":327},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-120","text":"We have described then what kind of men the Brave are, and what they\r who are thought to be, but are not really, Brave.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":328},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-121","text":"It must be remarked, however, that though Courage has for its\r object-matter boldness and fear it has not both equally so, but objects\r of fear much more than the former; for he that under pressure of these\r is undisturbed and stands related to them as he ought is better\r entitled to the name of Brave than he who is properly affected towards\r objects of confidence. So then men are termed Brave for withstanding\r painful things.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":329},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-122","text":"It follows that Courage involves pain and is justly praised, since it\r is a harder matter to withstand things that are painful than to abstain\r from such as are pleasant.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":330},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-123","text":"It must not be thought but that the End and object of Courage is\r pleasant, but it is obscured by the surrounding circumstances: which\r happens also in the gymnastic games; to the boxers the End is pleasant\r with a view to which they act, I mean the crown and the honours; but\r the receiving the blows they do is painful and annoying to flesh and\r blood, and so is all the labour they have to undergo; and, as these\r drawbacks are many, the object in view being small appears to have no\r pleasantness in it.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":331},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-124","text":"If then we may say the same of Courage, of course death and wounds must\r be painful to the Brave man and against his will: still he endures\r these because it is honourable so to do or because it is dishonourable\r not to do so. And the more complete his virtue and his happiness so\r much the more will he be pained at the notion of death: since to such a\r man as he is it is best worth while to live, and he with full\r consciousness is deprived of the greatest goods by death, and this is a\r painful idea. But he is not the less Brave for feeling it to be so, nay\r rather it may be he is shown to be m","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":332},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-125","text":"But there is perhaps no reason why not such men should make the best\r soldiers, but those who are less truly Brave but have no other good to\r care for: these being ready to meet danger and bartering their lives\r against small gain.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":333},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-126","text":"Let thus much be accepted as sufficient on the subject of Courage; the\r true nature of which it is not difficult to gather, in outline at\r least, from what has been said.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":334},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-127","text":"Next let us speak of Perfected Self-Mastery, which seems to claim the\r next place to Courage, since these two are the Excellences of the\r Irrational part of the Soul.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":335},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-128","text":"That it is a mean state, having for its object-matter Pleasures, we\r have already said (Pains being in fact its object-matter in a less\r degree and dissimilar manner), the state of utter absence of\r self-control has plainly the same object-matter; the next thing then is\r to determine what kind of Pleasures.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":336},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-129","text":"Let Pleasures then be understood to be divided into mental and bodily:\r instances of the former being love of honour or of learning: it being\r plain that each man takes pleasure in that of these two objects which\r he has a tendency to like, his body being no way affected but rather\r his intellect. Now men are not called perfectly self-mastering or\r wholly destitute of self-control in respect of pleasures of this class:\r nor in fact in respect of any which are not bodily; those for example\r who love to tell long stories, and are prosy, and spend their days\r about mere chance matters, we call go","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":337},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-130","text":"It is bodily Pleasures then which are the object-matter of Perfected\r Self-Mastery, but not even all these indifferently: I mean, that they\r who take pleasure in objects perceived by the Sight, as colours, and\r forms, and painting, are not denominated men of Perfected Self-Mastery,\r or wholly destitute of self-control; and yet it would seem that one may\r take pleasure even in such objects, as one ought to do, or excessively,\r or too little.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":338},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-131","text":"So too of objects perceived by the sense of Hearing; no one applies the\r terms before quoted respectively to those who are excessively pleased\r with musical tunes or acting, or to those who take such pleasure as\r they ought.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":339},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-132","text":"Nor again to those persons whose pleasure arises from the sense of\r Smell, except incidentally:[24] I mean, we do not say men have no\r self-control because they take pleasure in the scent of fruit, or\r flowers, or incense, but rather when they do so in the smells of\r unguents and sauces: since men destitute of self-control take pleasure\r herein, because hereby the objects of their lusts are recalled to their\r imagination (you may also see other men take pleasure in the smell of\r food when they are hungry): but to take pleasure in such is a mark of\r the character before named since these are ob","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":340},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-133","text":"Now not even brutes receive pleasure in right of these senses, except\r incidentally. I mean, it is not the scent of hares’ flesh but the\r eating it which dogs take pleasure in, perception of which pleasure is\r caused by the sense of Smell. Or again, it is not the lowing of the ox\r but eating him which the lion likes; but of the fact of his nearness\r the lion is made sensible by the lowing, and so he appears to take\r pleasure in this. In like manner, he has no pleasure in merely seeing\r or finding a stag or wild goat, but in the prospect of a meal.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":341},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-134","text":"The habits of Perfect Self-Mastery and entire absence of self-control\r have then for their object-matter such pleasures as brutes also share\r in, for which reason they are plainly servile and brutish: they are\r Touch and Taste.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":342},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-135","text":"But even Taste men seem to make little or no use of; for to the sense\r of Taste belongs the distinguishing of flavours; what men do, in fact,\r who are testing the quality of wines or seasoning “made dishes.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":343},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-136","text":"But men scarcely take pleasure at all in these things, at least those\r whom we call destitute of self-control do not, but only in the actual\r enjoyment which arises entirely from the sense of Touch, whether in\r eating or in drinking, or in grosser lusts. This accounts for the wish\r said to have been expressed once by a great glutton, “that his throat\r had been formed longer than a crane’s neck,” implying that his pleasure\r was derived from the Touch.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":344},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-137","text":"The sense then with which is connected the habit of absence of\r self-control is the most common of all the senses, and this habit would\r seem to be justly a matter of reproach, since it attaches to us not in\r so far as we are men but in so far as we are animals. Indeed it is\r brutish to take pleasure in such things and to like them best of all;\r for the most respectable of the pleasures arising from the touch have\r been set aside; those, for instance, which occur in the course of\r gymnastic training from the rubbing and the warm bath: because the\r touch of the man destitute of self-control is ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":345},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-138","text":"Now of lusts or desires some are thought to be universal, others\r peculiar and acquired; thus desire for food is natural since every one\r who really needs desires also food, whether solid or liquid, or both\r (and, as Homer says, the man in the prime of youth needs and desires\r intercourse with the other sex); but when we come to this or that\r particular kind, then neither is the desire universal nor in all men is\r it directed to the same objects. And therefore the conceiving of such\r desires plainly attaches to us as individuals. It must be admitted,\r however, that there is something natural i","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":346},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-139","text":"For this reason these men are called belly-mad, as filling it beyond\r what they ought, and it is the slavish who become of this character.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":347},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-140","text":"But in respect of the peculiar pleasures many men go wrong and in many\r different ways; for whereas the term “fond of so and so” implies either\r taking pleasure in wrong objects, or taking pleasure excessively, or as\r the mass of men do, or in a wrong way, they who are destitute of all\r self-control exceed in all these ways; that is to say, they take\r pleasure in some things in which they ought not to do so (because they\r are properly objects of detestation), and in such as it is right to\r take pleasure in they do so more than they ought and as the mass of men\r do.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":348},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-141","text":"Well then, that excess with respect to pleasures is absence of\r self-control, and blameworthy, is plain. But viewing these habits on\r the side of pains, we find that a man is not said to have the virtue\r for withstanding them (as in the case of Courage), nor the vice for not\r withstanding them; but the man destitute of self-control is such,\r because he is pained more than he ought to be at not obtaining things\r which are pleasant (and thus his pleasure produces pain to him), and\r the man of Perfected Self-Mastery is such in virtue of not being pained\r by their absence, that is, by having to ab","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":349},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-142","text":"Now the man destitute of self-control desires either all pleasant\r things indiscriminately or those which are specially pleasant, and he\r is impelled by his desire to choose these things in preference to all\r others; and this involves pain, not only when he misses the attainment\r of his objects but, in the very desiring them, since all desire is\r accompanied by pain. Surely it is a strange case this, being pained by\r reason of pleasure.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":350},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-143","text":"As for men who are defective on the side of pleasure, who take less\r pleasure in things than they ought, they are almost imaginary\r characters, because such absence of sensual perception is not natural\r to man: for even the other animals distinguish between different kinds\r of food, and like some kinds and dislike others. In fact, could a man\r be found who takes no pleasure in anything and to whom all things are\r alike, he would be far from being human at all: there is no name for\r such a character because it is simply imaginary.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":351},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-144","text":"But the man of Perfected Self-Mastery is in the mean with respect to\r these objects: that is to say, he neither takes pleasure in the things\r which delight the vicious man, and in fact rather dislikes them, nor at\r all in improper objects; nor to any great degree in any object of the\r class; nor is he pained at their absence; nor does he desire them; or,\r if he does, only in moderation, and neither more than he ought, nor at\r improper times, and so forth; but such things as are conducive to\r health and good condition of body, being also pleasant, these he will\r grasp at in moderation and as he","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":352},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-145","text":"Now the vice of being destitute of all Self-Control seems to be more\r truly voluntary than Cowardice, because pleasure is the cause of the\r former and pain of the latter, and pleasure is an object of choice,\r pain of avoidance. And again, pain deranges and spoils the natural\r disposition of its victim, whereas pleasure has no such effect and is\r more voluntary and therefore more justly open to reproach.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":353},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-146","text":"It is so also for the following reason; that it is easier to be inured\r by habit to resist the objects of pleasure, there being many things of\r this kind in life and the process of habituation being unaccompanied by\r danger; whereas the case is the reverse as regards the objects of fear.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":354},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-147","text":"Again, Cowardice as a confirmed habit would seem to be voluntary in a\r different way from the particular instances which form the habit;\r because it is painless, but these derange the man by reason of pain so\r that he throws away his arms and otherwise behaves himself unseemly,\r for which reason they are even thought by some to exercise a power of\r compulsion.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":355},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-148","text":"But to the man destitute of Self-Control the particular instances are\r on the contrary quite voluntary, being done with desire and direct\r exertion of the will, but the general result is less voluntary: since\r no man desires to form the habit.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":356},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-149","text":"The name of this vice (which signifies etymologically unchastened-ness)\r we apply also to the faults of children, there being a certain\r resemblance between the cases: to which the name is primarily applied,\r and to which secondarily or derivatively, is not relevant to the\r present subject, but it is evident that the later in point of time must\r get the name from the earlier. And the metaphor seems to be a very good\r one; for whatever grasps after base things, and is liable to great\r increase, ought to be chastened; and to this description desire and the\r child answer most truly, in that child","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":357},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-150","text":"Unless then the appetite be obedient and subjected to the governing\r principle it will become very great: for in the fool the grasping after\r what is pleasant is insatiable and undiscriminating; and every acting\r out of the desire increases the kindred habit, and if the desires are\r great and violent in degree they even expel Reason entirely; therefore\r they ought to be moderate and few, and in no respect to be opposed to\r Reason. Now when the appetite is in such a state we denominate it\r obedient and chastened.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":358},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-151","text":"In short, as the child ought to live with constant regard to the orders\r of its educator, so should the appetitive principle with regard to\r those of Reason.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":359},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-4-152","text":"So then in the man of Perfected Self-Mastery, the appetitive principle\r must be accordant with Reason: for what is right is the mark at which\r both principles aim: that is to say, the man of perfected self-mastery\r desires what he ought in right manner and at right times, which is\r exactly what Reason directs. Let this be taken for our account of\r Perfected Self-Mastery.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":360},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-1","text":"We will next speak of Liberality. Now this is thought to be the mean\r state, having for its object-matter Wealth: I mean, the Liberal man is\r praised not in the circumstances of war, nor in those which constitute\r the character of perfected self-mastery, nor again in judicial\r decisions, but in respect of giving and receiving Wealth, chiefly the\r former. By the term Wealth I mean “all those things whose worth is\r measured by money.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":361},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-2","text":"Now the states of excess and defect in regard of Wealth are\r respectively Prodigality and Stinginess: the latter of these terms we\r attach invariably to those who are over careful about Wealth, but the\r former we apply sometimes with a complex notion; that is to say, we\r give the name to those who fail of self-control and spend money on the\r unrestrained gratification of their passions; and this is why they are\r thought to be most base, because they have many vices at once.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":362},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-3","text":"It must be noted, however, that this is not a strict and proper use of\r the term, since its natural etymological meaning is to denote him who\r has one particular evil, viz. the wasting his substance: he is unsaved\r (as the term literally denotes) who is wasting away by his own fault;\r and this he really may be said to be; the destruction of his substance\r is thought to be a kind of wasting of himself, since these things are\r the means of living. Well, this is our acceptation of the term\r Prodigality.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":363},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-4","text":"Again. Whatever things are for use may be used well or ill, and Wealth\r belongs to this class. He uses each particular thing best who has the\r virtue to whose province it belongs: so that he will use Wealth best\r who has the virtue respecting Wealth, that is to say, the Liberal man.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":364},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-5","text":"Expenditure and giving are thought to be the using of money, but\r receiving and keeping one would rather call the possessing of it. And\r so the giving to proper persons is more characteristic of the Liberal\r man, than the receiving from proper quarters and forbearing to receive\r from the contrary. In fact generally, doing well by others is more\r characteristic of virtue than being done well by, and doing things\r positively honourable than forbearing to do things dishonourable; and\r any one may see that the doing well by others and doing things\r positively honourable attaches to the act of givi","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":365},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-6","text":"Besides, thanks are given to him who gives, not to him who merely\r forbears to receive, and praise even more. Again, forbearing to receive\r is easier than giving, the case of being too little freehanded with\r one’s own being commoner than taking that which is not one’s own.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":366},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-7","text":"And again, it is they who give that are denominated Liberal, while they\r who forbear to receive are commended, not on the score of Liberality\r but of just dealing, while for receiving men are not, in fact, praised\r at all.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":367},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-8","text":"And the Liberal are liked almost best of all virtuous characters,\r because they are profitable to others, and this their profitableness\r consists in their giving.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":368},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-9","text":"Furthermore: all the actions done in accordance with virtue are\r honourable, and done from the motive of honour: and the Liberal man,\r therefore, will give from a motive of honour, and will give rightly; I\r mean, to proper persons, in right proportion, at right times, and\r whatever is included in the term “right giving:” and this too with\r positive pleasure, or at least without pain, since whatever is done in\r accordance with virtue is pleasant or at least not unpleasant, most\r certainly not attended with positive pain.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":369},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-10","text":"But the man who gives to improper people, or not from a motive of\r honour but from some other cause, shall be called not Liberal but\r something else. Neither shall he be so denominated who does it with\r pain: this being a sign that he would prefer his wealth to the\r honourable action, and this is no part of the Liberal man’s character;\r neither will such an one receive from improper sources, because the so\r receiving is not characteristic of one who values not wealth: nor again\r will he be apt to ask, because one who does kindnesses to others does\r not usually receive them willingly; but from ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":370},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-11","text":"Again, it is a trait in the Liberal man’s character even to exceed very\r much in giving so as to leave too little for himself, it being\r characteristic of such an one not to have a thought of self.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":371},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-12","text":"Now Liberality is a term of relation to a man’s means, for the\r Liberal-ness depends not on the amount of what is given but on the\r moral state of the giver which gives in proportion to his means. There\r is then no reason why he should not be the more Liberal man who gives\r the less amount, if he has less to give out of.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":372},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-13","text":"Again, they are thought to be more Liberal who have inherited, not\r acquired for themselves, their means; because, in the first place, they\r have never experienced want, and next, all people love most their own\r works, just as parents do and poets.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":373},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-14","text":"It is not easy for the Liberal man to be rich, since he is neither apt\r to receive nor to keep but to lavish, and values not wealth for its own\r sake but with a view to giving it away. Hence it is commonly charged\r upon fortune that they who most deserve to be rich are least so. Yet\r this happens reasonably enough; it is impossible he should have wealth\r who does not take any care to have it, just as in any similar case.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":374},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-15","text":"Yet he will not give to improper people, nor at wrong times, and so on:\r because he would not then be acting in accordance with Liberality, and\r if he spent upon such objects, would have nothing to spend on those on\r which he ought: for, as I have said before, he is Liberal who spends in\r proportion to his means, and on proper objects, while he who does so in\r excess is prodigal (this is the reason why we never call despots\r prodigal, because it does not seem to be easy for them by their gifts\r and expenditure to go beyond their immense possessions).","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":375},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-16","text":"To sum up then. Since Liberality is a mean state in respect of the\r giving and receiving of wealth, the Liberal man will give and spend on\r proper objects, and in proper proportion, in great things and in small\r alike, and all this with pleasure to himself; also he will receive from\r right sources, and in right proportion: because, as the virtue is a\r mean state in respect of both, he will do both as he ought, and, in\r fact, upon proper giving follows the correspondent receiving, while\r that which is not such is contrary to it. (Now those which follow one\r another come to co-exist in the same ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":376},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-17","text":"Again, should it happen to him to spend money beyond what is needful,\r or otherwise than is well, he will be vexed, but only moderately and as\r he ought; for feeling pleasure and pain at right objects, and in right\r manner, is a property of Virtue.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":377},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-18","text":"The Liberal man is also a good man to have for a partner in respect of\r wealth: for he can easily be wronged, since he values not wealth, and\r is more vexed at not spending where he ought to have done so than at\r spending where he ought not, and he relishes not the maxim of\r Simonides.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":378},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-19","text":"But the Prodigal man goes wrong also in these points, for he is neither\r pleased nor pained at proper objects or in proper manner, which will\r become more plain as we proceed.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":379},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-20","text":"We have said already that Prodigality and Stinginess are respectively\r states of excess and defect, and this in two things, giving and\r receiving (expenditure of course we class under giving). Well now,\r Prodigality exceeds in giving and forbearing to receive and is\r deficient in receiving, while Stinginess is deficient in giving and\r exceeds in receiving, but it is in small things.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":380},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-21","text":"The two parts of Prodigality, to be sure, do not commonly go together;\r it is not easy, I mean, to give to all if you receive from none,\r because private individuals thus giving will soon find their means run\r short, and such are in fact thought to be prodigal. He that should\r combine both would seem to be no little superior to the Stingy man: for\r he may be easily cured, both by advancing in years, and also by the\r want of means, and he may come thus to the mean: he has, you see,\r already the _facts_ of the Liberal man, he gives and forbears to\r receive, only he does neither in right manner o","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":381},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-22","text":"Well then, he who is Prodigal in this fashion is thought far superior\r to the Stingy man for the aforementioned reasons, and also because he\r does good to many, but the Stingy man to no one, not even to himself.\r But most Prodigals, as has been said, combine with their other faults\r that of receiving from improper sources, and on this point are Stingy:\r and they become grasping, because they wish to spend and cannot do this\r easily, since their means soon run short and they are necessitated to\r get from some other quarter; and then again, because they care not for\r what is honourable, they rec","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":382},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-23","text":"And for this reason their givings are not Liberal, inasmuch as they are\r not honourable, nor purely disinterested, nor done in right fashion;\r but they oftentimes make those rich who should be poor, and to those\r who are quiet respectable kind of people they will give nothing, but to\r flatterers, or those who subserve their pleasures in any way, they will\r give much. And therefore most of them are utterly devoid of\r self-restraint; for as they are open-handed they are liberal in\r expenditure upon the unrestrained gratification of their passions, and\r turn off to their pleasures because they do","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":383},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-24","text":"Thus then the Prodigal, if unguided, slides into these faults; but if\r he could get care bestowed on him he might come to the mean and to what\r is right.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":384},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-25","text":"Stinginess, on the contrary, is incurable: old age, for instance, and\r incapacity of any kind, is thought to make people Stingy; and it is\r more congenial to human nature than Prodigality, the mass of men being\r fond of money rather than apt to give: moreover it extends far and has\r many phases, the modes of stinginess being thought to be many. For as\r it consists of two things, defect of giving and excess of receiving,\r everybody does not have it entire, but it is sometimes divided, and one\r class of persons exceed in receiving, the other are deficient in\r giving. I mean those who are designa","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":385},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-26","text":"There are some people whose motive, either supposed or alleged, for\r keeping their property is this, that they may never be driven to do\r anything dishonourable: to this class belongs the skinflint, and every\r one of similar character, so named from the excess of not-giving.\r Others again decline to receive their neighbour’s goods from a motive\r of fear; their notion being that it is not easy to take other people’s\r things yourself without their taking yours: so they are content neither\r to receive nor give.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":386},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-27","text":"The other class again who are Stingy in respect of receiving exceed in\r that they receive anything from any source; such as they who work at\r illiberal employments, brothel keepers, and such-like, and usurers who\r lend small sums at large interest: for all these receive from improper\r sources, and improper amounts. Their common characteristic is\r base-gaining, since they all submit to disgrace for the sake of gain\r and that small; because those who receive great things neither whence\r they ought, nor what they ought (as for instance despots who sack\r cities and plunder temples), we denominate ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":387},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-28","text":"Now the dicer and bath-plunderer and the robber belong to the class of\r the Stingy, for they are given to base gain: both busy themselves and\r submit to disgrace for the sake of gain, and the one class incur the\r greatest dangers for the sake of their booty, while the others make\r gain of their friends to whom they ought to be giving.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":388},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-29","text":"So both classes, as wishing to make gain from improper sources, are\r given to base gain, and all such receivings are Stingy. And with good\r reason is Stinginess called the contrary of Liberality: both because it\r is a greater evil than Prodigality, and because men err rather in this\r direction than in that of the Prodigality which we have spoken of as\r properly and completely such.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":389},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-30","text":"Let this be considered as what we have to say respecting Liberality and\r the contrary vices.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":390},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-31","text":"Next in order would seem to come a dissertation on Magnificence, this\r being thought to be, like liberality, a virtue having for its\r object-matter Wealth; but it does not, like that, extend to all\r transactions in respect of Wealth, but only applies to such as are\r expensive, and in these circumstances it exceeds liberality in respect\r of magnitude, because it is (what the very name in Greek hints at)\r fitting expense on a large scale: this term is of course relative: I\r mean, the expenditure of equipping and commanding a trireme is not the\r same as that of giving a public spectacle: “fitting","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":391},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-32","text":"but for doing so in great matters: that is to say, the Magnificent man\r is liberal, but the liberal is not thereby Magnificent. The falling\r short of such a state is called Meanness, the exceeding it Vulgar\r Profusion, Want of Taste, and so on; which are faulty, not because they\r are on an excessive scale in respect of right objects but, because they\r show off in improper objects, and in improper manner: of these we will\r speak presently. The Magnificent man is like a man of skill, because he\r can see what is fitting, and can spend largely in good taste; for, as\r we said at the commencement, t","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":392},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-33","text":"Well, the expenses of the Magnificent man are great and fitting: such\r also are his works (because this secures the expenditure being not\r great merely, but befitting the work). So then the work is to be\r proportionate to the expense, and this again to the work, or even above\r it: and the Magnificent man will incur such expenses from the motive of\r honour, this being common to all the virtues, and besides he will do it\r with pleasure and lavishly; excessive accuracy in calculation being\r Mean. He will consider also how a thing may be done most beautifully\r and fittingly, rather, than for how m","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":393},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-34","text":"So the Magnificent man must be also a liberal man, because the liberal\r man will also spend what he ought, and in right manner: but it is the\r Great, that is to say tke large scale, which is distinctive of the\r Magnificent man, the object-matter of liberality being the same, and\r without spending more money than another man he will make the work more\r magnificent. I mean, the excellence of a possession and of a work is\r not the same: as a piece of property that thing is most valuable which\r is worth most, gold for instance; but as a work that which is great and\r beautiful, because the contempl","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":394},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-35","text":"Now in all these, as has been already stated, respect is had also to\r the rank and the means of the man who is doing them: because they\r should be proportionate to these, and befit not the work only but also\r the doer of the work. For this reason a poor man cannot be a\r Magnificent man, since he has not means wherewith to spend largely and\r yet becomingly; and if he attempts it he is a fool, inasmuch as it is\r out of proportion and contrary to propriety, whereas to be in\r accordance with virtue a thing must be done rightly.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":395},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-36","text":"Such expenditure is fitting moreover for those to whom such things\r previously belong, either through themselves or through their ancestors\r or people with whom they are connected, and to the high-born or people\r of high repute, and so on: because all these things imply greatness and\r reputation.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":396},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-37","text":"So then the Magnificent man is pretty much as I have described him, and\r Magnificence consists in such expenditures: because they are the\r greatest and most honourable: and of private ones such as come but once\r for all, marriage to wit, and things of that kind; and any occasion\r which engages the interest of the community in general, or of those who\r are in power; and what concerns receiving and despatching strangers;\r and gifts, and repaying gifts: because the Magnificent man is not apt\r to spend upon himself but on the public good, and gifts are pretty much\r in the same case as dedicatory o","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":397},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-38","text":"It is characteristic also of the Magnificent man to furnish his house\r suitably to his wealth, for this also in a way reflects credit; and\r again, to spend rather upon such works as are of long duration, these\r being most honourable. And again, propriety in each case, because the\r same things are not suitable to gods and men, nor in a temple and a\r tomb. And again, in the case of expenditures, each must be great of its\r kind, and great expense on a great object is most magnificent, that is\r in any case what is great in these particular things.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":398},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-39","text":"There is a difference too between greatness of a work and greatness of\r expenditure: for instance, a very beautiful ball or cup is magnificent\r as a present to a child, while the price of it is small and almost\r mean. Therefore it is characteristic of the Magnificent man to do\r magnificently whatever he is about: for whatever is of this kind cannot\r be easily surpassed, and bears a proper proportion to the expenditure.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":399},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-40","text":"The man who is in the state of excess, called one of Vulgar Profusion,\r is in excess because he spends improperly, as has been said. I mean in\r cases requiring small expenditure he lavishes much and shows off out of\r taste; giving his club a feast fit for a wedding-party, or if he has to\r furnish a chorus for a comedy, giving the actors purple to wear in the\r first scene, as did the Megarians. And all such things he will do, not\r with a view to that which is really honourable, but to display his\r wealth, and because he thinks he shall be admired for these things; and\r he will spend little wher","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":400},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-41","text":"The Mean man will be deficient in every case, and even where he has\r spent the most he will spoil the whole effect for want of some trifle;\r he is procrastinating in all he does, and contrives how he may spend\r the least, and does even that with lamentations about the expense, and\r thinking that he does all things on a greater scale than he ought.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":401},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-42","text":"Of course, both these states are faulty, but they do not involve\r disgrace because they are neither hurtful to others nor very unseemly.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":402},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-43","text":"The very name of Great-mindedness implies, that great things are its\r object-matter; and we will first settle what kind of things. It makes\r no difference, of course, whether we regard the moral state in the\r abstract or as exemplified in an individual.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":403},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-44","text":"Well then, he is thought to be Great-minded who values himself highly\r and at the same time justly, because he that does so without grounds is\r foolish, and no virtuous character is foolish or senseless. Well, the\r character I have described is Great-minded. The man who estimates\r himself lowly, and at the same time justly, is modest; but not\r Great-minded, since this latter quality implies greatness, just as\r beauty implies a large bodily conformation while small people are neat\r and well made but not beautiful.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":404},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-45","text":"Again, he who values himself highly without just grounds is a Vain man:\r though the name must not be applied to every case of unduly high\r self-estimation. He that values himself below his real worth is\r Small-minded, and whether that worth is great, moderate, or small, his\r own estimate falls below it. And he is the strongest case of this error\r who is really a man of great worth, for what would he have done had his\r worth been less?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":405},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-46","text":"The Great-minded man is then, as far as greatness is concerned, at the\r summit, but in respect of propriety he is in the mean, because he\r estimates himself at his real value (the other characters respectively\r are in excess and defect). Since then he justly estimates himself at a\r high, or rather at the highest possible rate, his character will have\r respect specially to one thing: this term “rate” has reference of\r course to external goods: and of these we should assume that to be the\r greatest which we attribute to the gods, and which is the special\r object of desire to those who are in pow","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":406},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-47","text":"The Small-minded man is deficient, both as regards himself, and also as\r regards the estimation of the Great-minded: while the Vain man is in\r excess as regards himself, but does not get beyond the Great-minded\r man. Now the Great-minded man, being by the hypothesis worthy of the\r greatest things, must be of the highest excellence, since the better a\r man is the more is he worth, and he who is best is worth the most: it\r follows then, that to be truly Great-minded a man must be good, and\r whatever is great in each virtue would seem to belong to the\r Great-minded. It would no way correspond wit","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":407},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-48","text":"This virtue, then, of Great-mindedness seems to be a kind of ornament\r of all the other virtues, in that it makes them better and cannot be\r without them; and for this reason it is a hard matter to be really and\r truly Great-minded; for it cannot be without thorough goodness and\r nobleness of character.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":408},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-49","text":"Honour then and dishonour are specially the object-matter of the\r Great-minded man: and at such as is great, and given by good men, he\r will be pleased moderately as getting his own, or perhaps somewhat less\r for no honour can be quite adequate to perfect virtue: but still he\r will accept this because they have nothing higher to give him. But such\r as is given by ordinary people and on trifling grounds he will entirely\r despise, because these do not come up to his deserts: and dishonour\r likewise, because in his case there cannot be just ground for it.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":409},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-50","text":"Now though, as I have said, honour is specially the object-matter of\r the Great-minded man, I do not mean but that likewise in respect of\r wealth and power, and good or bad fortune of every kind, he will bear\r himself with moderation, fall out how they may, and neither in\r prosperity will he be overjoyed nor in adversity will he be unduly\r pained. For not even in respect of honour does he so bear himself; and\r yet it is the greatest of all such objects, since it is the cause of\r power and wealth being choice-worthy, for certainly they who have them\r desire to receive honour through them. So to","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":410},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-51","text":"It seems too that pieces of good fortune contribute to form this\r character of Great-mindedness: I mean, the nobly born, or men of\r influence, or the wealthy, are considered to be entitled to honour, for\r they are in a position of eminence and whatever is eminent by good is\r more entitled to honour: and this is why such circumstances dispose men\r rather to Great-mindedness, because they receive honour at the hands of\r some men.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":411},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-52","text":"Now really and truly the good man alone is entitled to honour; only if\r a man unites in himself goodness with these external advantages he is\r thought to be more entitled to honour: but they who have them without\r also having virtue are not justified in their high estimate of\r themselves, nor are they rightly denominated Great-minded; since\r perfect virtue is one of the indispensable conditions to such &\r character.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":412},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-53","text":"Further, such men become supercilious and insolent, it not being easy\r to bear prosperity well without goodness; and not being able to bear\r it, and possessed with an idea of their own superiority to others, they\r despise them, and do just whatever their fancy prompts; for they mimic\r the Great-minded man, though they are not like him, and they do this in\r such points as they can, so without doing the actions which can only\r flow from real goodness they despise others. Whereas the Great-minded\r man despises on good grounds (for he forms his opinions truly), but the\r mass of men do it at random","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":413},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-54","text":"Moreover, he is not a man to incur little risks, nor does he court\r danger, because there are but few things he has a value for; but he\r will incur great dangers, and when he does venture he is prodigal of\r his life as knowing that there are terms on which it is not worth his\r while to live. He is the sort of man to do kindnesses, but he is\r ashamed to receive them; the former putting a man in the position of\r superiority, the latter in that of inferiority; accordingly he will\r greatly overpay any kindness done to him, because the original actor\r will thus be laid under obligation and be in th","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":414},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-55","text":"Further, it is characteristic of the Great-minded man to ask favours\r not at all, or very reluctantly, but to do a service very readily; and\r to bear himself loftily towards the great or fortunate, but towards\r people of middle station affably; because to be above the former is\r difficult and so a grand thing, but to be above the latter is easy; and\r to be high and mighty towards the former is not ignoble, but to do it\r towards those of humble station would be low and vulgar; it would be\r like parading strength against the weak.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":415},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-56","text":"And again, not to put himself in the way of honour, nor to go where\r others are the chief men; and to be remiss and dilatory, except in the\r case of some great honour or work; and to be concerned in few things,\r and those great and famous. It is a property of him also to be open,\r both in his dislikes and his likings, because concealment is a\r consequent of fear. Likewise to be careful for reality rather than\r appearance, and talk and act openly (for his contempt for others makes\r him a bold man, for which same reason he is apt to speak the truth,\r except where the principle of reserve comes i","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":416},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-57","text":"And to be unable to live with reference to any other but a friend;\r because doing so is servile, as may be seen in that all flatterers are\r low and men in low estate are flatterers. Neither is his admiration\r easily excited, because nothing is great in his eyes; nor does he bear\r malice, since remembering anything, and specially wrongs, is no part of\r Great-mindedness, but rather overlooking them; nor does he talk of\r other men; in fact, he will not speak either of himself or of any\r other; he neither cares to be praised himself nor to have others\r blamed; nor again does he praise freely, and ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":417},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-58","text":"And he is by no means apt to make laments about things which cannot be\r helped, or requests about those which are trivial; because to be thus\r disposed with respect to these things is consequent only upon real\r anxiety about them. Again, he is the kind of man to acquire what is\r beautiful and unproductive rather than what is productive and\r profitable: this being rather the part of an independent man.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":418},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-59","text":"Also slow motion, deep-toned voice, and deliberate style of speech, are\r thought to be characteristic of the Great-minded man: for he who is\r earnest about few things is not likely to be in a hurry, nor he who\r esteems nothing great to be very intent: and sharp tones and quickness\r are the result of these.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":419},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-60","text":"This then is my idea of the Great-minded man; and he who is in the\r defect is a Small-minded man, he who is in the excess a Vain man.\r However, as we observed in respect of the last character we discussed,\r these extremes are not thought to be vicious exactly, but only\r mistaken, for they do no harm.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":420},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-61","text":"The Small-minded man, for instance, being really worthy of good\r deprives himself of his deserts, and seems to have somewhat faulty from\r not having a sufficiently high estimate of his own desert, in fact from\r self-ignorance: because, but for this, he would have grasped after what\r he really is entitled to, and that is good. Still such characters are\r not thought to be foolish, but rather laggards. But the having such an\r opinion of themselves seems to have a deteriorating effect on the\r character: because in all cases men’s aims are regulated by their\r supposed desert, and thus these men, un","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":421},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-62","text":"But the Vain are foolish and self-ignorant, and that palpably: because\r they attempt honourable things, as though they were worthy, and then\r they are detected. They also set themselves off, by dress, and\r carriage, and such-like things, and desire that their good\r circumstances may be seen, and they talk of them under the notion of\r receiving honour thereby. Small-mindedness rather than Vanity is\r opposed to Great-mindedness, because it is more commonly met with and\r is worse.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":422},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-63","text":"Well, the virtue of Great-mindedness has for its object great Honour,\r as we have said: and there seems to be a virtue having Honour also for\r its object (as we stated in the former book), which may seem to bear to\r Great-mindedness the same relation that Liberality does to\r Magnificence: that is, both these virtues stand aloof from what is\r great but dispose us as we ought to be disposed towards moderate and\r small matters. Further: as in giving and receiving of wealth there is a\r mean state, an excess, and a defect, so likewise in grasping after\r Honour there is the more or less than is righ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":423},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-64","text":"For we blame the lover of Honour as aiming at Honour more than he\r ought, and from wrong sources; and him who is destitute of a love of\r Honour as not choosing to be honoured even for what is noble. Sometimes\r again we praise the lover of Honour as manly and having a love for what\r is noble, and him who has no love for it as being moderate and modest\r (as we noticed also in the former discussion of these virtues).","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":424},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-65","text":"It is clear then that since “Lover of so and so” is a term capable of\r several meanings, we do not always denote the same quality by the term\r “Lover of Honour;” but when we use it as a term of commendation we\r denote more than the mass of men are; when for blame more than a man\r should be.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":425},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-66","text":"And the mean state having no proper name the extremes seem to dispute\r for it as unoccupied ground: but of course where there is excess and\r defect there must be also the mean. And in point of fact, men do grasp\r at Honour more than they should, and less, and sometimes just as they\r ought; for instance, this state is praised, being a mean state in\r regard of Honour, but without any appropriate name. Compared with what\r is called Ambition it shows like a want of love for Honour, and\r compared with this it shows like Ambition, or compared with both, like\r both faults: nor is this a singular case","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":426},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-67","text":"Meekness is a mean state, having for its object-matter Anger: and as\r the character in the mean has no name, and we may almost say the same\r of the extremes, we give the name of Meekness (leaning rather to the\r defect, which has no name either) to the character in the mean.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":427},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-68","text":"The excess may be called an over-aptness to Anger: for the passion is\r Anger, and the producing causes many and various. Now he who is angry\r at what and with whom he ought, and further, in right manner and time,\r and for proper length of time, is praised, so this Man will be Meek\r since Meekness is praised. For the notion represented by the term Meek\r man is the being imperturbable, and not being led away by passion, but\r being angry in that manner, and at those things, and for that length of\r time, which Reason may direct. This character however is thought to err\r rather on the side of defec","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":428},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-69","text":"As for the excess, it occurs in all forms; men are angry with those\r with whom, and at things with which, they ought not to be, and more\r than they ought, and too hastily, and for too great a length of time. I\r do not mean, however, that these are combined in any one person: that\r would in fact be impossible, because the evil destroys itself, and if\r it is developed in its full force it becomes unbearable.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":429},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-70","text":"Now those whom we term the Passionate are soon angry, and with people\r with whom and at things at which they ought not, and in an excessive\r degree, but they soon cool again, which is the best point about them.\r And this results from their not repressing their anger, but repaying\r their enemies (in that they show their feeings by reason of their\r vehemence), and then they have done with it.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":430},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-71","text":"The Choleric again are excessively vehement, and are angry at\r everything, and on every occasion; whence comes their Greek name\r signifying that their choler lies high.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":431},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-72","text":"The Bitter-tempered are hard to reconcile and keep their anger for a\r long while, because they repress the feeling: but when they have\r revenged themselves then comes a lull; for the vengeance destroys their\r anger by producing pleasure in lieu of pain. But if this does not\r happen they keep the weight on their minds: because, as it does not\r show itself, no one attempts to reason it away, and digesting anger\r within one’s self takes time. Such men are very great nuisances to\r themselves and to their best friends.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":432},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-73","text":"Again, we call those Cross-grained who are angry at wrong objects, and\r in excessive degree, and for too long a time, and who are not appeased\r without vengeance or at least punishing the offender.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":433},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-74","text":"To Meekness we oppose the excess rather than the defect, because it is\r of more common occurrence: for human nature is more disposed to take\r than to forgo revenge. And the Cross-grained are worse to live with\r [than they who are too phlegmatic].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":434},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-75","text":"Now, from what has been here said, that is also plain which was said\r before. I mean, it is no easy matter to define how, and with what\r persons, and at what kind of things, and how long one ought to be\r angry, and up to what point a person is right or is wrong. For he that\r transgresses the strict rule only a little, whether on the side of too\r much or too little, is not blamed: sometimes we praise those who are\r deficient in the feeling and call them Meek, sometimes we call the\r irritable Spirited as being well qualified for government. So it is not\r easy to lay down, in so many words, for w","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":435},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-76","text":"This then is to be taken as our account of the various moral states\r which have Anger for their object-matter.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":436},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-77","text":"Next, as regards social intercourse and interchange of words and acts,\r some men are thought to be Over-Complaisant who, with a view solely to\r giving pleasure, agree to everything and never oppose, but think their\r line is to give no pain to those they are thrown amongst: they, on the\r other hand, are called Cross and Contentious who take exactly the\r contrary line to these, and oppose in everything, and have no care at\r all whether they give pain or not.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":437},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-78","text":"Now it is quite clear of course, that the states I have named are\r blameable, and that the mean between them is praiseworthy, in virtue of\r which a man will let pass what he ought as he ought, and also will\r object in like manner. However, this state has no name appropriated,\r but it is most like Friendship; since the man who exhibits it is just\r the kind of man whom we would call the amiable friend, with the\r addition of strong earnest affection; but then this is the very point\r in which it differs from Friendship, that it is quite independent of\r any feeling or strong affection for those amo","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":438},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-79","text":"It has been stated in a general way that his social intercourse will be\r regulated by propriety, and his aim will be to avoid giving pain and to\r contribute to pleasure, but with a constant reference to what is noble\r and expedient.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":439},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-80","text":"His proper object-matter seems to be the pleasures and pains which\r arise out of social intercourse, but whenever it is not honourable or\r even hurtful to him to contribute to pleasure, in these instances he\r will run counter and prefer to give pain.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":440},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-81","text":"Or if the things in question involve unseemliness to the doer, and this\r not inconsiderable, or any harm, whereas his opposition will cause some\r little pain, here he will not agree but will run counter.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":441},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-82","text":"Again, he will regulate differently his intercourse with great men and\r with ordinary men, and with all people according to the knowledge he\r has of them; and in like manner, taking in any other differences which\r may exist, giving to each his due, and in itself preferring to give\r pleasure and cautious not to give pain, but still guided by the\r results, I mean by what is noble and expedient according as they\r preponderate.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":442},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-83","text":"Well, the man bearing the mean character is pretty well such as I have\r described him, but he has no name appropriated to him: of those who try\r to give pleasure, the man who simply and disinterestedly tries to be\r agreeable is called Over-Complaisant, he who does it with a view to\r secure some profit in the way of wealth, or those things which wealth\r may procure, is a Flatterer: I have said before, that the man who is\r “always non-content” is Cross and Contentious. Here the extremes have\r the appearance of being opposed to one another, because the mean has no\r appropriate name.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":443},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-84","text":"The mean state which steers clear of Exaggeration has pretty much the\r same object-matter as the last we described, and likewise has no name\r appropriated to it. Still it may be as well to go over these states:\r because, in the first place, by a particular discussion of each we\r shall be better acquainted with the general subject of moral character,\r and next we shall be the more convinced that the virtues are mean\r states by seeing that this is universally the case.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":444},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-85","text":"In respect then of living in society, those who carry on this\r intercourse with a view to pleasure and pain have been already spoken\r of; we will now go on to speak of those who are True or False, alike in\r their words and deeds and in the claims which they advance.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":445},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-86","text":"Now the Exaggerator is thought to have a tendency to lay claim to\r things reflecting credit on him, both when they do not belong to him at\r all and also in greater degree than that in which they really do:\r whereas the Reserved man, on the contrary, denies those which really\r belong to him or else depreciates them, while the mean character being\r a Plain-matter-of-fact person is Truthful in life and word, admitting\r the existence of what does really belong to him and making it neither\r greater nor less than the truth.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":446},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-87","text":"It is possible of course to take any of these lines either with or\r without some further view: but in general men speak, and act, and live,\r each according to his particular character and disposition, unless\r indeed a man is acting from any special motive.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":447},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-88","text":"Now since falsehood is in itself low and blameable, while truth is\r noble and praiseworthy, it follows that the Truthful man (who is also\r in the mean) is praiseworthy, and the two who depart from strict truth\r are both blameable, but especially the Exaggerator.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":448},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-89","text":"We will now speak of each, and first of the Truthful man: I call him\r Truthful, because we are not now meaning the man who is true in his\r agreements nor in such matters as amount to justice or injustice (this\r would come within the province of a different virtue), but, in such as\r do not involve any such serious difference as this, the man we are\r describing is true in life and word simply because he is in a certain\r moral state.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":449},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-90","text":"And he that is such must be judged to be a good man: for he that has a\r love for Truth as such, and is guided by it in matters indifferent,\r will be so likewise even more in such as are not indifferent; for\r surely he will have a dread of falsehood as base, since he shunned it\r even in itself: and he that is of such a character is praiseworthy, yet\r he leans rather to that which is below the truth, this having an\r appearance of being in better taste because exaggerations are so\r hateful.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":450},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-91","text":"As for the man who lays claim to things above what really belongs to\r him _without_ any special motive, he is like a base man because he\r would not otherwise have taken pleasure in falsehood, but he shows as a\r fool rather than as a knave. But if a man does this _with_ a special\r motive, suppose for honour or glory, as the Braggart does, then he is\r not so very blameworthy, but if, directly or indirectly, for pecuniary\r considerations, he is more unseemly.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":451},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-92","text":"Now the Braggart is such not by his power but by his purpose, that is\r to say, in virtue of his moral state, and because he is a man of a\r certain kind; just as there are liars who take pleasure in falsehood\r for its own sake while others lie from a desire of glory or gain. They\r who exaggerate with a view to glory pretend to such qualities as are\r followed by praise or highest congratulation; they who do it with a\r view to gain assume those which their neighbours can avail themselves\r of, and the absence of which can be concealed, as a man’s being a\r skilful soothsayer or physician; and accor","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":452},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-93","text":"The Reserved, who depreciate their own qualities, have the appearance\r of being more refined in their characters, because they are not thought\r to speak with a view to gain but to avoid grandeur: one very common\r trait in such characters is their denying common current opinions, as\r Socrates used to do. There are people who lay claim falsely to small\r things and things the falsity of their pretensions to which is obvious;\r these are called Factotums and are very despicable.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":453},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-94","text":"This very Reserve sometimes shows like Exaggeration; take, for\r instance, the excessive plainness of dress affected by the\r Lacedæmonians: in fact, both excess and the extreme of deficiency\r partake of the nature of Exaggeration. But they who practise Reserve in\r moderation, and in cases in which the truth is not very obvious and\r plain, give an impression of refinement. Here it is the Exaggerator (as\r being the worst character) who appears to be opposed to the Truthful\r Man.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":454},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-95","text":"Next, as life has its pauses and in them admits of pastime combined\r with Jocularity, it is thought that in this respect also there is a\r kind of fitting intercourse, and that rules may be prescribed as to the\r kind of things one should say and the manner of saying them; and in\r respect of hearing likewise (and there will be a difference between the\r saying and hearing such and such things). It is plain that in regard to\r these things also there will be an excess and defect and a mean.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":455},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-96","text":"Now they who exceed in the ridiculous are judged to be Buffoons and\r Vulgar, catching at it in any and every way and at any cost, and aiming\r rather at raising laughter than at saying what is seemly and at\r avoiding to pain the object of their wit. They, on the other hand, who\r would not for the world make a joke themselves and are displeased with\r such as do are thought to be Clownish and Stern. But they who are\r Jocular in good taste are denominated by a Greek term expressing\r properly ease of movement, because such are thought to be, as one may\r say, motions of the moral character; and as b","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":456},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-97","text":"Now as the ridiculous lies on the surface, and the majority of men take\r more pleasure than they ought in Jocularity and Jesting, the Buffoons\r too get this name of Easy Pleasantry, as if refined and gentlemanlike;\r but that they differ from these, and considerably too, is plain from\r what has been said.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":457},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-98","text":"One quality which belongs to the mean state is Tact: it is\r characteristic of a man of Tact to say and listen to such things as are\r fit for a good man and a gentleman to say and listen to: for there are\r things which are becoming for such a one to say and listen to in the\r way of Jocularity, and there is a difference between the Jocularity of\r the Gentleman and that of the Vulgarian; and again, between that of the\r educated and uneducated man. This you may see from a comparison of the\r Old and New Comedy: in the former obscene talk made the fun; in the\r latter it is rather innuendo: and this ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":458},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-99","text":"Well then, are we to characterise him who jests well by his saying what\r is becoming a gentleman, or by his avoiding to pain the object of his\r wit, or even by his giving him pleasure? or will not such a definition\r be vague, since different things are hateful and pleasant to different\r men?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":459},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-100","text":"Be this as it may, whatever he says such things will he also listen to,\r since it is commonly held that a man will do what he will bear to hear:\r this must, however, be limited; a man will not do quite all that he\r will hear: because jesting is a species of scurrility and there are\r some points of scurrility forbidden by law; it may be certain points of\r jesting should have been also so forbidden. So then the refined and\r gentlemanlike man will bear himself thus as being a law to himself.\r Such is the mean character, whether denominated the man of Tact or of\r Easy Pleasantry.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":460},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-101","text":"But the Buffoon cannot resist the ridiculous, sparing neither himself\r nor any one else so that he can but raise his laugh, saying things of\r such kind as no man of refinement would say and some which he would not\r even tolerate if said by others in his hearing.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":461},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-102","text":"The Clownish man is for such intercourse wholly useless: inasmuch as\r contributing nothing jocose of his own he is savage with all who do.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":462},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-103","text":"The three mean states which have been described do occur in life, and\r the object-matter of all is interchange of words and deeds. They\r differ, in that one of them is concerned with truth, and the other two\r with the pleasurable: and of these two again, the one is conversant\r with the jocosities of life, the other with all other points of social\r intercourse.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":463},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-104","text":"To speak of Shame as a Virtue is incorrect, because it is much more\r like a feeling than a moral state. It is defined, we know, to be “a\r kind of fear of disgrace,” and its effects are similar to those of the\r fear of danger, for they who feel Shame grow red and they who fear\r death turn pale. So both are evidently in a way physical, which is\r thought to be a mark of a feeling rather than a moral state.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":464},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-105","text":"Moreover, it is a feeling not suitable to every age, but only to youth:\r we do think that the young should be Shamefaced, because since they\r live at the beck and call of passion they do much that is wrong and\r Shame acts on them as a check. In fact, we praise such young men as are\r Shamefaced, but no one would ever praise an old man for being given to\r it, inasmuch as we hold that he ought not to do things which cause\r Shame; for Shame, since it arises at low bad actions, does not at all\r belong to the good man, because such ought not to be done at all: nor\r does it make any difference to all","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":465},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-106","text":"True it is, that Shame may be good on a certain supposition, as “if a\r man should do such things, he would feel Shame:” but then the Virtues\r are good in themselves, and not merely in supposed cases. And, granted\r that impudence and the not being ashamed to do what is disgraceful is\r base, it does not the more follow that it is good for a man to do such\r things and feel Shame.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":466},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-5-107","text":"Nor is Self-Control properly a Virtue, but a kind of mixed state:\r however, all about this shall be set forth in a future Book.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":467},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-1","text":"Now the points for our enquiry in respect of Justice and Injustice are,\r what kind of actions are their object-matter, and what kind of a mean\r state Justice is, and between what points the abstract principle of it,\r i.e. the Just, is a mean. And our enquiry shall be, if you please,\r conducted in the same method as we have observed in the foregoing parts\r of this Treatise.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":468},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-2","text":"We see then that all men mean by the term Justice a moral state such\r that in consequence of it men have the capacity of doing what is just,\r and actually do it, and wish it:[1] similarly also with respect to\r Injustice, a moral state such that in consequence of it men do unjustly\r and wish what is unjust: let us also be content then with these as a\r ground-work sketched out.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":469},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-3","text":"I mention the two, because the same does not hold with regard to States\r whether of mind or body as with regard to Sciences or Faculties: I mean\r that whereas it is thought that the same Faculty or Science embraces\r contraries, a State will not: from health, for instance, not the\r contrary acts are done but the healthy ones only; we say a man walks\r healthily when he walks as the healthy man would.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":470},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-4","text":"However, of the two contrary states the one may be frequently known\r from the other, and oftentimes the states from their subject-matter: if\r it be seen clearly what a good state of body is, then is it also seen\r what a bad state is, and from the things which belong to a good state\r of body the good state itself is seen, and _vice versâ_. If, for\r instance, the good state is firmness of flesh it follows that the bad\r state is flabbiness of flesh; and whatever causes firmness of flesh is\r connected with the good state.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":471},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-5","text":"It follows moreover in general,[2] that if of two contrary terms the\r one is used in many senses so also will the other be; as, for instance,\r if “the Just,” then also “the Unjust.” Now Justice and Injustice do\r seem to be used respectively in many senses, but, because the line of\r demarcation between these is very fine and minute,[3] it commonly\r escapes notice that they are thus used, and it is not plain and\r manifest as where the various significations of terms are widely\r different for in these last the visible difference is great, for\r instance, the word κλεὶς is used equivocally to denot","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":472},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-6","text":"Let it be ascertained then in how many senses the term “Unjust man” is\r used. Well, he who violates the law, and he who is a grasping man, and\r the unequal man, are all thought to be Unjust and so manifestly the\r Just man will be, the man who acts according to law, and the equal man\r “The Just” then will be the lawful and the equal, and “the Unjust” the\r unlawful and the unequal.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":473},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-7","text":"Well, since the Unjust man is also a grasping man, he will be so, of\r course, with respect to good things, but not of every kind, only those\r which are the subject-matter of good and bad fortune and which are in\r themselves always good but not always to the individual.[4] Yet men\r pray for and pursue these things: this they should not do but pray that\r things which are in the abstract good may be so also to them, and\r choose what is good for themselves.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":474},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-8","text":"But the Unjust man does not always choose actually the greater part,\r but even sometimes the less; as in the case of things which are simply\r evil: still, since the less evil is thought to be in a manner a good\r and the grasping is after good, therefore even in this case he is\r thought to be a grasping man, _i.e._ one who strives for more good than\r fairly falls to his share: of course he is also an unequal man, this\r being an inclusive and common term.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":475},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-9","text":"We said that the violator of Law is Unjust, and the keeper of the Law\r Just: further, it is plain that all Lawful things are in a manner Just,\r because by Lawful we understand what have been defined by the\r legislative power and each of these we say is Just. The Laws too give\r directions on all points, aiming either at the common good of all, or\r that of the best, or that of those in power (taking for the standard\r real goodness or adopting some other estimate); in one way we mean by\r Just, those things which are apt to produce and preserve happiness and\r its ingredients for the social communi","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":476},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-10","text":"Further, the Law commands the doing the deeds not only of the brave man\r (as not leaving the ranks, nor flying, nor throwing away one’s arms),\r but those also of the perfectly self-mastering man, as abstinence from\r adultery and wantonness; and those of the meek man, as refraining from\r striking others or using abusive language: and in like manner in\r respect of the other virtues and vices commanding some things and\r forbidding others, rightly if it is a good law, in a way somewhat\r inferior if it is one extemporised.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":477},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-11","text":"Now this Justice is in fact perfect Virtue, yet not simply so but as\r exercised towards one’s neighbour: and for this reason Justice is\r thought oftentimes to be the best of the Virtues, and","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":478},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-12","text":"And it is in a special sense perfect Virtue because it is the practice\r of perfect Virtue. And perfect it is because he that has it is able to\r practise his virtue towards his neighbour and not merely on himself; I\r mean, there are many who can practise virtue in the regulation of their\r own personal conduct who are wholly unable to do it in transactions\r with their neighbour. And for this reason that saying of Bias is\r thought to be a good one,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":479},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-13","text":"for he who bears Rule is necessarily in contact with others, i.e. in a\r community. And for this same reason Justice alone of all the Virtues is\r thought to be a good to others, because it has immediate relation to\r some other person, inasmuch as the Just man does what is advantageous\r to another, either to his ruler or fellow-subject. Now he is the basest\r of men who practises vice not only in his own person,[5] but towards\r his friends also; but he the best who practises virtue not merely in\r his own person but towards his neighbour, for this is a matter of some\r difficulty.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":480},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-14","text":"However, Justice in this sense is not a part of Virtue but is\r co-extensive with Virtue; nor is the Injustice which answers to it a\r part of Vice but co-extensive with Vice. Now wherein Justice in this\r sense differs from Virtue appears from what has been said: it is the\r same really, but the point of view is not the same: in so far as it has\r respect to one’s neighbour it is Justice, in so far as it is such and\r such a moral state it is simply Virtue.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":481},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-15","text":"But the object of our enquiry is Justice, in the sense in which it is a\r part of Virtue (for there is such a thing, as we commonly say), and\r likewise with respect to particular Injustice. And of the existence of\r this last the following consideration is a proof: there are many vices\r by practising which a man acts unjustly, of course, but does not grasp\r at more than his share of good; if, for instance, by reason of\r cowardice he throws away his shield, or by reason of ill-temper he uses\r abusive language, or by reason of stinginess does not give a friend\r pecuniary assistance; but whenever h","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":482},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-16","text":"Again, suppose one man seduces a man’s wife with a view to gain and\r actually gets some advantage by it,[6] and another does the same from\r impulse of lust, at an expense of money and damage; this latter will be\r thought to be rather destitute of self-mastery than a grasping man, and\r the former Unjust but not destitute of self-mastery: now why? plainly\r because of his gaining.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":483},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-17","text":"Again, all other acts of Injustice we refer to some particular\r depravity, as, if a man commits adultery, to abandonment to his\r passions; if he deserts his comrade, to cowardice; if he strikes\r another, to anger: but if he gains by the act to no other vice than to\r Injustice.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":484},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-18","text":"Thus it is clear that there is a kind of Injustice different from and\r besides that which includes all Vice, having the same name because the\r definition is in the same genus; for both have their force in dealings\r with others, but the one acts upon honour, or wealth, or safety, or by\r whatever one name we can include all these things, and is actuated by\r pleasure attendant on gain, while the other acts upon all things which\r constitute the sphere of the good man’s action.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":485},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-19","text":"Now that there is more than one kind of Justice, and that there is one\r which is distinct from and besides that which is co-extensive with,\r Virtue, is plain: we must next ascertain what it is, and what are its\r characteristics.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":486},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-20","text":"Well, the Unjust has been divided into the unlawful and the unequal,\r and the Just accordingly into the lawful and the equal: the\r aforementioned Injustice is in the way of the unlawful. And as the\r unequal and the more[7] are not the same, but differing as part to\r whole (because all more is unequal, but not all unequal more), so the\r Unjust and the Injustice we are now in search of are not the same with,\r but other than, those before mentioned, the one being the parts, the\r other the wholes; for this particular Injustice is a part of the\r Injustice co-extensive with Vice, and likewise this J","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":487},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-21","text":"Here then let us dismiss any further consideration of the Justice\r ranking as co-extensive with Virtue (being the practice of Virtue in\r all its bearings towards others), and of the co-relative Injustice\r (being similarly the practice of Vice). It is clear too, that we must\r separate off the Just and the Unjust involved in these: because one may\r pretty well say that most lawful things are those which naturally\r result in action from Virtue in its fullest sense, because the law\r enjoins the living in accordance with each Virtue and forbids living in\r accordance with each Vice. And the producin","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":488},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-22","text":"By the way, as to individual education, in respect of which a man is\r simply good without reference to others, whether it is the province of\r πολιτικὴ or some other science we must determine at a future time: for\r it may be it is not the same thing to be a good man and a good citizen\r in every case.[8]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":489},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-23","text":"Now of the Particular Justice, and the Just involved in it, one species\r is that which is concerned in the distributions of honour, or wealth,\r or such other things as are to be shared among the members of the\r social community (because in these one man as compared with another may\r have either an equal or an unequal share), and the other is that which\r is Corrective in the various transactions between man and man.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":490},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-24","text":"And of this latter there are two parts: because of transactions some\r are voluntary and some involuntary; voluntary, such as follow; selling,\r buying, use, bail, borrowing, deposit, hiring: and this class is called\r voluntary because the origination of these transactions is voluntary.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":491},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-25","text":"The involuntary again are either such as effect secrecy; as theft,\r adultery, poisoning, pimping, kidnapping of slaves, assassination,\r false witness; or accompanied with open violence; as insult, bonds,\r death, plundering, maiming, foul language, slanderous abuse.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":492},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-26","text":"Well, the unjust man we have said is unequal, and the abstract “Unjust”\r unequal: further, it is plain that there is some mean of the unequal,\r that is to say, the equal or exact half (because in whatever action\r there is the greater and the less there is also the equal, i.e. the\r exact half). If then the Unjust is unequal the Just is equal, which all\r must allow without further proof: and as the equal is a mean the Just\r must be also a mean. Now the equal implies two terms at least: it\r follows then that the Just is both a mean and equal, and these to\r certain persons; and, in so far as it is","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":493},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-27","text":"And there will be the same equality between the terms representing the\r persons, as between those representing the things: because as the\r latter are to one another so are the former: for if the persons are not\r equal they must not have equal shares; in fact this is the very source\r of all the quarrelling and wrangling in the world, when either they who\r are equal have and get awarded to them things not equal, or being not\r equal those things which are equal. Again, the necessity of this\r equality of ratios is shown by the common phrase “according to rate,”\r for all agree that the Just in dist","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":494},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-28","text":"The Just, then, is a certain proportionable thing. For proportion does\r not apply merely to number in the abstract,[10] but to number\r generally, since it is equality of ratios, and implies four terms at\r least (that this is the case in what may be called discrete proportion\r is plain and obvious, but it is true also in continual proportion, for\r this uses the one term as two, and mentions it twice; thus A:B:C may be\r expressed A:B::B:C. In the first, B is named twice; and so, if, as in\r the second, B is actually written twice, the proportionals will be\r four): and the Just likewise implies fo","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":495},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-29","text":"The Just then is this proportionate, and the Unjust that which violates\r the proportionate; and so there comes to be the greater and the less:\r which in fact is the case in actual transactions, because he who acts\r unjustly has the greater share and he who is treated unjustly has the\r less of what is good: but in the case of what is bad this is reversed:\r for the less evil compared with the greater comes to be reckoned for\r good, because the less evil is more choice-worthy than the greater, and\r what is choice-worthy is good, and the more so the greater good.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":496},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-30","text":"And the remaining one is the Corrective, which arises in voluntary as\r well as involuntary transactions. Now this just has a different form\r from the aforementioned; for that which is concerned in distribution of\r common property is always according to the aforementioned proportion: I\r mean that, if the division is made out of common property, the shares\r will bear the same proportion to one another as the original\r contributions did: and the Unjust which is opposite to this Just is\r that which violates the proportionate.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":497},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-31","text":"But the Just which arises in transactions between men is an equal in a\r certain sense, and the Unjust an unequal, only not in the way of that\r proportion but of arithmetical.[12] Because it makes no difference\r whether a robbery, for instance, is committed by a good man on a bad or\r by a bad man on a good, nor whether a good or a bad man has committed\r adultery: the law looks only to the difference created by the injury\r and treats the men as previously equal, where the one does and the\r other suffers injury, or the one has done and the other suffered harm.\r And so this Unjust, being unequal, ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":498},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-32","text":"For these terms gain and loss are applied to these cases, though\r perhaps the term in some particular instance may not be strictly\r proper, as gain, for instance, to the man who has given a blow, and\r loss to him who has received it: still, when the suffering has been\r estimated, the one is called loss and the other gain.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":499},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-33","text":"And so the equal is a mean between the more and the less, which\r represent gain and loss in contrary ways (I mean, that the more of good\r and the less of evil is gain, the less of good and the more of evil is\r loss): between which the equal was stated to be a mean, which equal we\r say is Just: and so the Corrective Just must be the mean between loss\r and gain. And this is the reason why, upon a dispute arising, men have\r recourse to the judge: going to the judge is in fact going to the Just,\r for the judge is meant to be the personification of the Just.[13] And\r men seek a judge as one in the ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":500},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-34","text":"So it is the office of a judge to make things equal, and the line, as\r it were, having been unequally divided, he takes from the greater part\r that by which it exceeds the half, and adds this on to the less. And\r when the whole is divided into two exactly equal portions then men say\r they have their own, when they have gotten the equal; and the equal is\r a mean between the greater and the less according to arithmetical\r equality.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":501},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-35","text":"This, by the way, accounts for the etymology of the term by which we in\r Greek express the ideas of Just and Judge; (δίκαιον quasi δίχαιον, that\r is in two parts, and δικάστης quasi διχάστης, he who divides into two\r parts). For when from one of two equal magnitudes somewhat has been\r taken and added to the other, this latter exceeds the former by twice\r that portion: if it had been merely taken from the former and not added\r to the latter, then the latter would have exceeded the former only by\r that one portion; but in the other case, the greater exceeds the mean\r by one, and the mean exceeds","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":502},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-36","text":"Thus let there be three straight lines equal to one another. From one\r of them cut off a portion, and add as much to another of them. The\r whole line thus made will exceed the remainder of the first-named line,\r by twice the portion added, and will exceed the untouched line by that\r portion.[14] And these terms loss and gain are derived from voluntary\r exchange: that is to say, the having more than what was one’s own is\r called gaining, and the having less than one’s original stock is called\r losing; for instance, in buying or selling, or any other transactions\r which are guaranteed by law: bu","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":503},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-37","text":"So then the Just we have been speaking of is a mean between loss and\r gain arising in involuntary transactions; that is, it is the having the\r same after the transaction as one had before it took place.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":504},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-38","text":"There are people who have a notion that Reciprocation is simply just,\r as the Pythagoreans said: for they defined the Just simply and without\r qualification as “That which reciprocates with another.” But this\r simple Reciprocation will not fit on either to the Distributive Just,\r or the Corrective (and yet this is the interpretation they put on the\r Rhadamanthian rule of Just,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":505},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-39","text":"If a man should suffer what he hath done, then there would be\r straightforward justice;”)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":506},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-40","text":"for in many cases differences arise: as, for instance, suppose one in\r authority has struck a man, he is not to be struck in turn; or if a man\r has struck one in authority, he must not only be struck but punished\r also.[16] And again, the voluntariness or involuntariness of actions\r makes a great difference.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":507},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-41","text":"But in dealings of exchange such a principle of Justice as this\r Reciprocation forms the bond of union, but then it must be\r Reciprocation according to proportion and not exact equality, because\r by proportionate reciprocity of action the social community is held\r together, For either Reciprocation of evil is meant, and if this be not\r allowed it is thought to be a servile condition of things: or else\r Reciprocation of good, and if this be not effected then there is no\r admission to participation which is the very bond of their union.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":508},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-42","text":"And this is the moral of placing the Temple of the Graces (χάριτες) in\r the public streets; to impress the notion that there may be requital,\r this being peculiar to χάρις[17] because a man ought to requite with a\r good turn the man who has done him a favour and then to become himself\r the originator of another χάρις, by doing him a favour.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":509},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-43","text":"Now the acts of mutual giving in due proportion may be represented by\r the diameters of a parallelogram, at the four angles of which the\r parties and their wares are so placed that the side connecting the\r parties be opposite to that connecting the wares, and each party be\r connected by one side with his own ware, as in the accompanying\r diagram.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":510},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-44","text":"The builder is to receive from the shoemaker of his ware, and to give\r him of his own: if then there be first proportionate equality, and\r _then_ the Reciprocation takes place, there will be the just result\r which we are speaking of: if not, there is not the equal, nor will the\r connection stand: for there is no reason why the ware of the one may\r not be better than that of the other, and therefore before the exchange\r is made they must have been equalised. And this is so also in the other\r arts: for they would have been destroyed entirely if there were not a\r correspondence in point of quanti","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":511},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-45","text":"It is therefore indispensable that all things which can be exchanged\r should be capable of comparison, and for this purpose money has come\r in, and comes to be a kind of medium, for it measures all things and so\r likewise the excess and defect; for instance, how many shoes are equal\r to a house or a given quantity of food. As then the builder to the\r shoemaker, so many shoes must be to the house (or food, if instead of a\r builder an agriculturist be the exchanging party); for unless there is\r this proportion there cannot be exchange or dealing, and this\r proportion cannot be unless the terms a","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":512},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-46","text":"And money has come to be, by general agreement, a representative of\r Demand: and the account of its Greek name νομισμα is this, that it is\r what it is not naturally but by custom or law (νόμος), and it rests\r with us to change its value, or make it wholly useless.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":513},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-47","text":"Very well then, there will be Reciprocation when the terms have been\r equalised so as to stand in this proportion; Agriculturist : Shoemaker\r : : wares of Shoemaker : wares of Agriculturist; but you must bring\r them to this form of proportion when they exchange, otherwise the one\r extreme will combine both exceedings of the mean:[18] but when they\r have exactly their own then they are equal and have dealings, because\r the same equality can come to be in their case. Let A represent an\r agriculturist, C food, B a shoemaker, D his wares equalised with A’s.\r Then the proportion will be correct, A:","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":514},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-48","text":"Now that what connects men in such transactions is Demand, as being\r some one thing, is shown by the fact that, when either one does not\r want the other or neither want one another, they do not exchange at\r all: whereas they do[19] when one wants what the other man has, wine\r for instance, giving in return corn for exportation.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":515},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-49","text":"And further, money is a kind of security to us in respect of exchange\r at some future time (supposing that one wants nothing now that we shall\r have it when we do): the theory of money being that whenever one brings\r it one can receive commodities in exchange: of course this too is\r liable to depreciation, for its purchasing power is not always the\r same, but still it is of a more permanent nature than the commodities\r it represents. And this is the reason why all things should have a\r price set upon them, because thus there may be exchange at any time,\r and if exchange then dealing. So money,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":516},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-50","text":"It is obvious also that exchange was thus conducted before the\r existence of money: for it makes no difference whether you give for a\r house five beds or the price of five beds.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":517},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-51","text":"We have now said then what the abstract Just and Unjust are, and these\r having been defined it is plain that just acting is a mean between\r acting unjustly and being acted unjustly towards: the former being\r equivalent to having more, and the latter to having less.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":518},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-52","text":"But Justice, it must be observed, is a mean state not after the same\r manner as the forementioned virtues, but because it aims at producing\r the mean, while Injustice occupies _both_ the extremes.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":519},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-53","text":"And Justice is the moral state in virtue of which the just man is said\r to have the aptitude for practising the Just in the way of moral\r choice, and for making division between, himself and another, or\r between two other men, not so as to give to himself the greater and to\r his neighbour the less share of what is choice-worthy and contrariwise\r of what is hurtful, but what is proportionably equal, and in like\r manner when adjudging the rights of two other men.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":520},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-54","text":"Injustice is all this with respect to the Unjust: and since the Unjust\r is excess or defect of what is good or hurtful respectively, in\r violation of the proportionate, therefore Injustice is both excess and\r defect because it aims at producing excess and defect; excess, that is,\r in a man’s own case of what is simply advantageous, and defect of what\r is hurtful: and in the case of other men in like manner generally\r speaking, only that the proportionate is violated not always in one\r direction as before but whichever way it happens in the given case. And\r of the Unjust act the less is being a","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":521},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-55","text":"Let this way of describing the nature of Justice and Injustice, and\r likewise the Just and the Unjust generally, be accepted as sufficient.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":522},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-56","text":"[Again, since a man may do unjust acts and not yet have formed a\r character of injustice, the question arises whether a man is unjust in\r each particular form of injustice, say a thief, or adulterer, or\r robber, by doing acts of a given character.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":523},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-57","text":"We may say, I think, that this will not of itself make any difference;\r a man may, for instance, have had connection with another’s wife,\r knowing well with whom he was sinning, but he may have done it not of\r deliberate choice but from the impulse of passion: of course he acts\r unjustly, but he has not necessarily formed an unjust character: that\r is, he may have stolen yet not be a thief; or committed an act of\r adultery but still not be an adulterer, and so on in other cases which\r might be enumerated.][21]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":524},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-58","text":"Of the relation which Reciprocation bears to the Just we have already\r spoken: and here it should be noticed that the Just which we are\r investigating is both the Just in the abstract and also as exhibited in\r Social Relations, which latter arises in the case of those who live in\r communion with a view to independence and who are free and equal either\r proportionately or numerically.[22]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":525},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-59","text":"It follows then that those who are not in this position have not among\r themselves the Social Just, but still Just of some kind and resembling\r that other. For Just implies mutually acknowledged law, and law the\r possibility of injustice, for adjudication is the act of distinguishing\r between the Just and the Unjust.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":526},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-60","text":"And among whomsoever there is the possibility of injustice among these\r there is that of acting unjustly; but it does not hold conversely that\r injustice attaches to all among whom there is the possibility of acting\r unjustly, since by the former we mean giving one’s self the larger\r share of what is abstractedly good and the less of what is abstractedly\r evil.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":527},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-61","text":"This, by the way, is the reason why we do not allow a man to govern,\r but Principle, because a man governs for himself and comes to be a\r despot: but the office of a ruler is to be guardian of the Just and\r therefore of the Equal. Well then, since he seems to have no peculiar\r personal advantage, supposing him a Just man, for in this case he does\r not allot to himself the larger share of what is abstractedly good\r unless it falls to his share proportionately (for which reason he\r really governs for others, and so Justice, men say, is a good not to\r one’s self so much as to others, as was menti","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":528},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-62","text":"But the Just which arises in the relations of Master and Father, is not\r identical with, but similar to, these; because there is no possibility\r of injustice towards those things which are absolutely one’s own; and a\r slave or child (so long as this last is of a certain age and not\r separated into an independent being), is, as it were, part of a man’s\r self, and no man chooses to hurt himself, for which reason there cannot\r be injustice towards one’s own self: therefore neither is there the\r social Unjust or Just, which was stated to be in accordance with law\r and to exist between those among ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":529},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-63","text":"Hence also there is Just rather between a man and his wife than between\r a man and his children or slaves; this is in fact the Just arising in\r domestic relations: and this too is different from the Social Just.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":530},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-64","text":"Further, this last-mentioned Just is of two kinds, natural and\r conventional; the former being that which has everywhere the same force\r and does not depend upon being received or not; the latter being that\r which originally may be this way or that indifferently but not after\r enactment: for instance, the price of ransom being fixed at a mina, or\r the sacrificing a goat instead of two sheep; and again, all cases of\r special enactment, as the sacrificing to Brasidas as a hero; in short,\r all matters of special decree.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":531},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-65","text":"But there are some men who think that all the Justs are of this latter\r kind, and on this ground: whatever exists by nature, they say, is\r unchangeable and has everywhere the same force; fire, for instance,\r burns not here only but in Persia as well, but the Justs they see\r changed in various places.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":532},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-66","text":"Now this is not really so, and yet it is in a way (though among the\r gods perhaps by no means): still even amongst ourselves there is\r somewhat existing by nature: allowing that everything is subject to\r change, still there is that which does exist by nature, and that which\r does not.[23]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":533},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-67","text":"Nay, we may go further, and say that it is practically plain what among\r things which can be otherwise does exist by nature, and what does not\r but is dependent upon enactment and conventional, even granting that\r both are alike subject to be changed: and the same distinctive\r illustration will apply to this and other cases; the right hand is\r naturally the stronger, still some men may become equally strong in\r both.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":534},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-68","text":"A parallel may be drawn between the Justs which depend upon convention\r and expedience, and measures; for wine and corn measures are not equal\r in all places, but where men buy they are large, and where these same\r sell again they are smaller: well, in like manner the Justs which are\r not natural, but of human invention, are not everywhere the same, for\r not even the forms of government are, and yet there is one only which\r by nature would be best in all places.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":535},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-69","text":"Now of Justs and Lawfuls each bears to the acts which embody and\r exemplify it the relation of an universal to a particular; the acts\r being many, but each of the principles only singular because each is an\r universal. And so there is a difference between an unjust act and the\r abstract Unjust, and the just act and the abstract Just: I mean, a\r thing is unjust in itself, by nature or by ordinance; well, when this\r has been embodied in act, there is an unjust act, but not till then,\r only some unjust thing.[24] And similarly of a just act. (Perhaps\r δικαιοπράγημα is more correctly the common or","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":536},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-70","text":"For the present we proceed to say that, the Justs and the Unjusts being\r what have been mentioned, a man is said to act unjustly or justly when\r he embodies these abstracts in voluntary actions, but when in\r involuntary, then he neither acts unjustly or justly except\r accidentally; I mean that the being just or unjust is really only\r accidental to the agents in such cases.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":537},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-71","text":"So both unjust and just actions are limited by the being voluntary or\r the contrary: for when an embodying of the Unjust is voluntary, then it\r is blamed and is at the same time also an unjust action: but, if\r voluntariness does not attach, there will be a thing which is in itself\r unjust but not yet an unjust action.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":538},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-72","text":"By voluntary, I mean, as we stated before, whatsoever of things in his\r own power a man does with knowledge, and the absence of ignorance as to\r the person to whom, or the instrument with which, or the result with\r which he does; as, for instance, whom he strikes, what he strikes him\r with, and with what probable result; and each of these points again,\r not accidentally nor by compulsion; as supposing another man were to\r seize his hand and strike a third person with it, here, of course, the\r owner of the hand acts not voluntarily, because it did not rest with\r him to do or leave undone: or ag","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":539},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-73","text":"I mention these cases, because there are many natural things which we\r do and suffer knowingly but still no one of which is either voluntary\r or involuntary, growing old, or dying, for instance.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":540},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-74","text":"Again, accidentality may attach to the unjust in like manner as to the\r just acts. For instance, a man may have restored what was deposited\r with him, but against his will and from fear of the consequences of a\r refusal: we must not say that he either does what is just, or does\r justly, except accidentally: and in like manner the man who through\r compulsion and against his will fails to restore a deposit, must be\r said to do unjustly, or to do what is unjust, accidentally only.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":541},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-75","text":"Again, voluntary actions we do either from deliberate choice or without\r it; from it, when we act from previous deliberation; without it, when\r without any previous deliberation. Since then hurts which may be done\r in transactions between man and man are threefold, those mistakes which\r are attended with ignorance are, when a man either does a thing not to\r the man to whom he meant to do it, or not the thing he meant to do, or\r not with the instrument, or not with the result which he intended:\r either he did not think he should hit him at all, or not with this, or\r this is not the man he thoug","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":542},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-76","text":"Now when the hurt has come about contrary to all reasonable\r expectation, it is a Misadventure; when though not contrary to\r expectation yet without any viciousness, it is a Mistake; for a man\r makes a mistake when the origination of the cause rests with himself,\r he has a misadventure when it is external to himself. When again he\r acts with knowledge, but not from previous deliberation, it is an\r unjust action; for instance, whatever happens to men from anger or\r other passions which are necessary or natural: for when doing these\r hurts or making these mistakes they act unjustly of course and","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":543},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-77","text":"And on this principle acts done from anger are fairly judged not to be\r from malice prepense, because it is not the man who acts in wrath who\r is the originator really but he who caused his wrath. And again, the\r question at issue in such cases is not respecting the fact but\r respecting the justice of the case, the occasion of anger being a\r notion of injury.[25] I mean, that the parties do not dispute about the\r fact, as in questions of contract (where one of the two must be a\r rogue, unless real forgetfulness can be pleaded), but, admitting the\r fact, they dispute on which side the justice o","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":544},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-78","text":"Well then, a man acts unjustly if he has hurt another of deliberate\r purpose, and he who commits such acts of injustice is _ipso facto_ an\r unjust character when they are in violation of the proportionate or the\r equal; and in like manner also a man is a just character when he acts\r justly of deliberate purpose, and he does act justly if he acts\r voluntarily.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":545},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-79","text":"Then as for involuntary acts of harm, they are either such as are\r excusable or such as are not: under the former head come all errors\r done not merely in ignorance but from ignorance; under the latter all\r that are done not from ignorance but in ignorance caused by some\r passion which is neither natural nor fairly attributable to human\r infirmity.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":546},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-80","text":"Now a question may be raised whether we have spoken with sufficient\r distinctness as to being unjustly dealt with, and dealing unjustly\r towards others.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":547},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-81","text":"First, whether the case is possible which Euripides has put, saying\r somewhat strangely,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":548},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-82","text":"“My mother he hath slain;  the tale is short,\r Either he willingly did slay her willing,\r Or else with her will but against his own.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":549},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-83","text":"I mean then, is it really possible for a person to be unjustly dealt\r with with his own consent, or must every case of being unjustly dealt\r with be against the will of the sufferer as every act of unjust dealing\r is voluntary?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":550},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-84","text":"And next, are cases of being unjustly dealt with to be ruled all one\r way as every act of unjust dealing is voluntary? or may we say that\r some cases are voluntary and some involuntary?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":551},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-85","text":"Similarly also as regards being justly dealt with: all just acting is\r voluntary, so that it is fair to suppose that the being dealt with\r unjustly or justly must be similarly opposed, as to being either\r voluntary or involuntary.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":552},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-86","text":"Now as for being justly dealt with, the position that every case of\r this is voluntary is a strange one, for some are certainly justly dealt\r with without their will.[27] The fact is a man may also fairly raise\r this question, whether in every case he who has suffered what is unjust\r is therefore unjustly dealt with, or rather that the case is the same\r with suffering as it is with acting; namely that in both it is possible\r to participate in what is just, but only accidentally. Clearly the case\r of what is unjust is similar: for doing things in themselves unjust is\r not identical with acting ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":553},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-87","text":"Now if acting unjustly is simply “hurting another voluntarily” (by\r which I mean, knowing whom you are hurting, and wherewith, and how you\r are hurting him), and the man who fails of self-control voluntarily\r hurts himself, then this will be a case of being voluntarily dealt\r unjustly with, and it will be possible for a man to deal unjustly with\r himself. (This by the way is one of the questions raised, whether it is\r possible for a man to deal unjustly with himself.) Or again, a man may,\r by reason of failing of self-control, receive hurt from another man\r acting voluntarily, and so here will","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":554},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-88","text":"The solution, I take it, is this: the definition of being unjustly\r dealt with is not correct, but we must add, to the hurting with the\r knowledge of the person hurt and the instrument and the manner of\r hurting him, the fact of its being against the wish of the man who is\r hurt.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":555},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-89","text":"So then a man may be hurt and suffer what is in itself unjust\r voluntarily, but unjustly dealt with voluntarily no man can be: since\r no man wishes to be hurt, not even he who fails of self-control, who\r really acts contrary to his wish: for no man wishes for that which he\r does not _think_ to be good, and the man who fails of self-control does\r not what he thinks he ought to do.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":556},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-90","text":"And again, he that gives away his own property (as Homer says Glaucus\r gave to Diomed, “armour of gold for brass, armour worth a hundred oxen\r for that which was worth but nine”) is not unjustly dealt with, because\r the giving rests entirely with himself; but being unjustly dealt with\r does not, there must be some other person who is dealing unjustly\r towards him.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":557},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-91","text":"With respect to being unjustly dealt with then, it is clear that it is\r not voluntary.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":558},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-92","text":"There remain yet two points on which we purposed to speak: first, is he\r chargeable with an unjust act who in distribution has _given_ the\r larger share to one party contrary to the proper rate, or he that _has_\r the larger share? next, can a man deal unjustly by himself?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":559},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-93","text":"In the first question, if the first-named alternative is possible and\r it is the distributor who acts unjustly and not he who has the larger\r share, then supposing that a person knowingly and willingly gives more\r to another than to himself here is a case of a man dealing unjustly by\r himself; which, in fact, moderate men are thought to do, for it is a\r characteristic of the equitable man to take less than his due.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":560},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-94","text":"Is not this the answer? that the case is not quite fairly stated,\r because of some other good, such as credit or the abstract honourable,\r in the supposed case the man did get the larger share. And again, the\r difficulty is solved by reference to the definition of unjust dealing:\r for the man suffers nothing contrary to his own wish, so that, on this\r score at least, he is not unjustly dealt with, but, if anything, he is\r hurt only.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":561},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-95","text":"It is evident also that it is the distributor who acts unjustly and not\r the man who has the greater share: because the mere fact of the\r abstract Unjust attaching to what a man does, does not constitute\r unjust action, but the doing this voluntarily: and voluntariness\r attaches to that quarter whence is the origination of the action, which\r clearly is in the distributor not in the receiver. And again the term\r doing is used in several senses; in one sense inanimate objects kill,\r or the hand, or the slave by his master’s bidding; so the man in\r question does not act unjustly but does things w","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":562},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-96","text":"Again, suppose that a man has made a wrongful award in ignorance; in\r the eye of the law he does not act unjustly nor is his awarding unjust,\r but yet he is in a certain sense: for the Just according to law and\r primary or natural Just are not coincident: but, if he knowingly\r decided unjustly, then he himself as well as the receiver got the\r larger share, that is, either of favour from the receiver or private\r revenge against the other party: and so the man who decided unjustly\r from these motives gets a larger share, in exactly the same sense as a\r man would who received part of the actual m","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":563},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-97","text":"Now men suppose that acting Unjustly rests entirely with themselves,\r and conclude that acting Justly is therefore also easy. But this is not\r really so; to have connection with a neighbour’s wife, or strike one’s\r neighbour, or give the money with one’s hand, is of course easy and\r rests with one’s self: but the doing these acts with certain inward\r dispositions neither is easy nor rests entirely with one’s self. And in\r like way, the knowing what is Just and what Unjust men think no great\r instance of wisdom because it is not hard to comprehend those things of\r which the laws speak. They for","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":564},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-98","text":"From this very same mistake they suppose also, that acting Unjustly is\r equally in the power of the Just man, for the Just man no less, nay\r even more, than the Unjust, may be able to do the particular acts; he\r may be able to have intercourse with a woman or strike a man; or the\r brave man to throw away his shield and turn his back and run this way\r or that. True: but then it is not the mere doing these things which\r constitutes acts of cowardice or injustice (except accidentally), but\r the doing them with certain inward dispositions: just as it is not the\r mere using or not using the knife, ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":565},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-99","text":"Again the abstract principles of Justice have their province among\r those who partake of what is abstractedly good, and can have too much\r or too little of these.[28] Now there are beings who cannot have too\r much of them, as perhaps the gods; there are others, again, to whom no\r particle of them is of use, those who are incurably wicked to whom all\r things are hurtful; others to whom they are useful to a certain degree:\r for this reason then the province of Justice is among _Men_.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":566},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-100","text":"We have next to speak of Equity and the Equitable, that is to say, of\r the relations of Equity to Justice and the Equitable to the Just; for\r when we look into the matter the two do not appear identical nor yet\r different in kind; and we sometimes commend the Equitable and the man\r who embodies it in his actions, so that by way of praise we commonly\r transfer the term also to other acts instead of the term good, thus\r showing that the more Equitable a thing is the better it is: at other\r times following a certain train of reasoning we arrive at a difficulty,\r in that the Equitable though disti","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":567},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-101","text":"This is a tolerably fair statement of the difficulty which on these\r grounds arises in respect of the Equitable; but, in fact, all these may\r be reconciled and really involve no contradiction: for the Equitable is\r Just, being also better than one form of Just, but is not better than\r the Just as though it were different from it in kind: Just and\r Equitable then are identical, and, both being good, the Equitable is\r the better of the two.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":568},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-102","text":"What causes the difficulty is this; the Equitable is Just, but not the\r Just which is in accordance with written law, being in fact a\r correction of that kind of Just. And the account of this is, that every\r law is necessarily universal while there are some things which it is\r not possible to speak of rightly in any universal or general statement.\r Where then there is a necessity for general statement, while a general\r statement cannot apply rightly to all cases, the law takes the\r generality of cases, being fully aware of the error thus involved; and\r rightly too notwithstanding, because the ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":569},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-103","text":"When then the law has spoken in general terms, and there arises a case\r of exception to the general rule, it is proper, in so far as the\r lawgiver omits the case and by reason of his universality of statement\r is wrong, to set right the omission by ruling it as the lawgiver\r himself would rule were he there present, and would have provided by\r law had he foreseen the case would arise. And so the Equitable is Just\r but better than one form of Just; I do not mean the abstract Just but\r the error which arises out of the universality of statement: and this\r is the nature of the Equitable, “a corre","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":570},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-104","text":"This is the reason why not all things are according to law, because\r there are things about which it is simply impossible to lay down a law,\r and so we want special enactments for particular cases. For to speak\r generally, the rule of the undefined must be itself undefined also,\r just as the rule to measure Lesbian building is made of lead: for this\r rule shifts according to the form of each stone and the special\r enactment according to the facts of the case in question.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":571},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-105","text":"It is clear then what the Equitable is; namely that it is Just but\r better than one form of Just: and hence it appears too who the\r Equitable man is: he is one who has a tendency to choose and carry out\r these principles, and who is not apt to press the letter of the law on\r the worse side but content to waive his strict claims though backed by\r the law: and this moral state is Equity, being a species of Justice,\r not a different moral state from Justice.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":572},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-106","text":"The answer to the second of the two questions indicated above, “whether\r it is possible for a man to deal unjustly by himself,” is obvious from\r what has been already stated.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":573},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-107","text":"In the first place, one class of Justs is those which are enforced by\r law in accordance with Virtue in the most extensive sense of the term:\r for instance, the law does not bid a man kill himself; and whatever it\r does not bid it forbids: well, whenever a man does hurt contrary to the\r law (unless by way of requital of hurt), voluntarily, i.e. knowing to\r whom he does it and wherewith, he acts Unjustly. Now he that from rage\r kills himself, voluntarily, does this in contravention of Right Reason,\r which the law does not permit. He therefore acts Unjustly: but towards\r whom? towards the Commun","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":574},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-108","text":"Next, a man cannot deal Unjustly by himself in the sense in which a man\r is Unjust who only does Unjust acts without being entirely bad (for the\r two things are different, because the Unjust man is in a way bad, as\r the coward is, not as though he were chargeable with badness in the\r full extent of the term, and so he does not act Unjustly in this\r sense), because if it were so then it would be possible for the same\r thing to have been taken away from and added to the same person:[29]\r but this is really not possible, the Just and the Unjust always\r implying a plurality of persons.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":575},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-109","text":"Again, an Unjust action must be voluntary, done of deliberate purpose,\r and aggressive (for the man who hurts because he has first suffered and\r is merely requiting the same is not thought to act Unjustly), but here\r the man does to himself and suffers the same things at the same time.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":576},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-110","text":"Again, it would imply the possibility of being Unjustly dealt with with\r one’s own consent.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":577},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-111","text":"And, besides all this, a man cannot act Unjustly without his act\r falling under some particular crime; now a man cannot seduce his own\r wife, commit a burglary on his own premises, or steal his own property.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":578},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-112","text":"After all, the general answer to the question is to allege what was\r settled respecting being Unjustly dealt with with one’s own consent.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":579},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-113","text":"It is obvious, moreover, that being Unjustly dealt by and dealing\r Unjustly by others are both wrong; because the one is having less, the\r other having more, than the mean, and the case is parallel to that of\r the healthy in the healing art, and that of good condition in the art\r of training: but still the dealing Unjustly by others is the worst of\r the two, because this involves wickedness and is blameworthy;\r wickedness, I mean, either wholly, or nearly so (for not all voluntary\r wrong implies injustice), but the being Unjustly dealt by does not\r involve wickedness or injustice.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":580},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-114","text":"In itself then, the being Unjustly dealt by is the least bad, but\r accidentally it may be the greater evil of the two. However, scientific\r statement cannot take in such considerations; a pleurisy, for instance,\r is called a greater physical evil than a bruise: and yet this last may\r be the greater accidentally; it may chance that a bruise received in a\r fall may cause one to be captured by the enemy and slain.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":581},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-115","text":"Further: Just, in the way of metaphor and similitude, there may be I do\r not say between a man and himself exactly but between certain parts of\r his nature; but not Just of every kind, only such as belongs to the\r relation of master and slave, or to that of the head of a family. For\r all through this treatise the rational part of the Soul has been viewed\r as distinct from the irrational.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":582},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-116","text":"Now, taking these into consideration, there is thought to be a\r possibility of injustice towards one’s self, because herein it is\r possible for men to suffer somewhat in contradiction of impulses really\r their own; and so it is thought that there is Just of a certain kind\r between these parts mutually, as between ruler and ruled.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":583},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-6-117","text":"Let this then be accepted as an account of the distinctions which we\r recognise respecting Justice and the rest of the moral virtues.[30]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":584},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-1","text":"Having stated in a former part of this treatise that men should choose\r the mean instead of either the excess or defect, and that the mean is\r according to the dictates of Right Reason; we will now proceed to\r explain this term.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":585},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-2","text":"For in all the habits which we have expressly mentioned, as likewise in\r all the others, there is, so to speak, a mark with his eye fixed on\r which the man who has Reason tightens or slacks his rope;[1] and there\r is a certain limit of those mean states which we say are in accordance\r with Right Reason, and lie between excess on the one hand and defect on\r the other.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":586},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-3","text":"Now to speak thus is true enough but conveys no very definite meaning:\r as, in fact, in all other pursuits requiring attention and diligence on\r which skill and science are brought to bear; it is quite true of course\r to say that men are neither to labour nor relax too much or too little,\r but in moderation, and as Right Reason directs; yet if this were all a\r man had he would not be greatly the wiser; as, for instance, if in\r answer to the question, what are proper applications to the body, he\r were to be told, “Oh! of course, whatever the science of medicine, and\r in such manner as the physi","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":587},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-4","text":"And so in respect of the mental states it is requisite not merely that\r this should be true which has been already stated, but further that it\r should be expressly laid down what Right Reason is, and what is the\r definition of it.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":588},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-5","text":"Now in our division of the Excellences of the Soul, we said there were\r two classes, the Moral and the Intellectual: the former we have already\r gone through; and we will now proceed to speak of the others, premising\r a few words respecting the Soul itself. It was stated before, you will\r remember, that the Soul consists of two parts, the Rational, and\r Irrational: we must now make a similar division of the Rational.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":589},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-6","text":"Let it be understood then that there are two parts of the Soul\r possessed of Reason; one whereby we realise those existences whose\r causes cannot be otherwise than they are, and one whereby we realise\r those which can be otherwise than they are,[2] (for there must be,\r answering to things generically different, generically different parts\r of the soul naturally adapted to each, since these parts of the soul\r possess their knowledge in virtue of a certain resemblance and\r appropriateness in themselves to the objects of which they are\r percipients);[3] and let us name the former, “that which is ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":590},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-7","text":"We must discover, then, which is the best state of each of these,\r because that will be the Excellence of each; and this again is relative\r to the work each has to do.[4]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":591},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-8","text":"There are in the Soul three functions on which depend moral action and\r truth; Sense, Intellect, Appetition, whether vague Desire or definite\r Will. Now of these Sense is the originating cause of no moral action,\r as is seen from the fact that brutes have Sense but are in no way\r partakers of moral action.[5]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":592},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-9","text":"[Intellect and Will are thus connected,] what in the Intellectual\r operation is Affirmation and Negation that in the Will is Pursuit and\r Avoidance, And so, since Moral Virtue is a State apt to exercise Moral\r Choice and Moral Choice is Will consequent on deliberation, the Reason\r must be true and the Will right, to constitute good Moral Choice, and\r what the Reason affirms the Will must pursue.[6]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":593},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-10","text":"Now this Intellectual operation and this Truth is what bears upon Moral\r Action; of course truth and falsehood must be the good and the bad of\r that Intellectual Operation which is purely Speculative, and concerned\r neither with action nor production, because this is manifestly the work\r of every Intellectual faculty, while of the faculty which is of a mixed\r Practical and Intellectual nature, the work is that Truth which, as I\r have described above, corresponds to the right movement of the Will.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":594},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-11","text":"Now the starting-point of moral action is Moral Choice, (I mean, what\r actually sets it in motion, not the final cause,)[7] and of Moral\r Choice, Appetition, and Reason directed to a certain result: and thus\r Moral Choice is neither independent of intellect, i. e. intellectual\r operation, nor of a certain moral state: for right or wrong action\r cannot be, independently of operation of the Intellect, and moral\r character.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":595},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-12","text":"But operation of the Intellect by itself moves nothing, only when\r directed to a certain result, i. e. exercised in Moral Action: (I say\r nothing of its being exercised in production, because this function is\r originated by the former: for every one who makes makes with a view to\r somewhat further; and that which is or may be made, is not an End in\r itself, but only relatively to somewhat else, and belonging to some\r one:[8] whereas that which is or may be done is an End in itself,\r because acting well is an End in itself, and this is the object of the\r Will,) and so Moral Choice is either[9] ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":596},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-13","text":"But nothing which is done and past can be the object of Moral Choice;\r for instance, no man chooses to have sacked Troy; because, in fact, no\r one ever deliberates about what is past, but only about that which is\r future, and which may therefore be influenced, whereas what has been\r cannot not have been: and so Agathon is right in saying","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":597},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-14","text":"Thus then Truth is the work of both the Intellectual Parts of the Soul;\r those states therefore are the Excellences of each in which each will\r best attain truth.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":598},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-15","text":"Commencing then from the point stated above we will now speak of these\r Excellences again. Let those faculties whereby the Soul attains truth\r in Affirmation or Negation, be assumed to be in number five:[10] viz.\r Art, Knowledge, Practical Wisdom, Science, Intuition: (Supposition and\r Opinion I do not include, because by these one may go wrong.)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":599},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-16","text":"What Knowledge is, is plain from the following of considerations, if\r one is to speak accurately, instead of being led away by resemblances.\r For we all conceive that what we strictly speaking know, cannot be\r otherwise than it is, because as to those things which can be otherwise\r than they are, we are uncertain whether they are or are not, the moment\r they cease to be within the sphere of our actual observation.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":600},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-17","text":"So then, whatever comes within the range of Knowledge is by necessity,\r and therefore eternal, (because all things are so which exist\r necessarily,) and all eternal things are without beginning, and\r indestructible.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":601},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-18","text":"Again, all Knowledge is thought to be capable of being taught, and what\r comes within its range capable of being learned. And all teaching is\r based upon previous knowledge; (a statement you will find in the\r Analytics also,)[11] for there are two ways of teaching, by Syllogism\r and by Induction. In fact. Induction is the source of universal\r propositions, and Syllogism reasons from these universals.[12]\r Syllogism then may reason from principles which cannot be themselves\r proved Syllogistically: and therefore must by Induction.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":602},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-19","text":"So Knowledge is “a state or mental faculty apt to demonstrate\r syllogistically,” &c. as in the Analytics:[13] because a man, strictly\r and properly speaking, _knows_, when he establishes his conclusion in a\r certain way, and the principles are known to him: for if they are not\r better known to him than the conclusion, such knowledge as he has will\r be merely accidental.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":603},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-20","text":"Matter which may exist otherwise than it actually does in any given\r case (commonly called Contingent) is of two kinds, that which is the\r object of Making, and that which is the object of Doing; now Making and\r Doing are two different things (as we show in the exoteric treatise),\r and so that state of mind, conjoined with Reason, which is apt to Do,\r is distinct from that also conjoined with Reason, which is apt to Make:\r and for this reason they are not included one by the other, that is,\r Doing is not Making, nor Making Doing.[14] Now[15] as Architecture is\r an Art, and is the same as “a ce","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":604},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-21","text":"Now all Art has to do with production, and contrivance, and seeing how\r any of those things may be produced which may either be or not be, and\r the origination of which rests with the maker and not with the thing\r made.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":605},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-22","text":"And, so neither things which exist or come into being necessarily, nor\r things in the way of nature, come under the province of Art, because\r these are self-originating. And since Making and Doing are distinct,\r Art must be concerned with the former and not the latter. And in a\r certain sense Art and Fortune are concerned with the same things, as,\r Agathon says by the way,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":606},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-23","text":"So Art, as has been stated, is “a certain state of mind, apt to Make,\r conjoined with true Reason;” its absence, on the contrary, is the same\r state conjoined with false Reason, and both are employed upon\r Contingent matter.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":607},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-24","text":"As for Practical Wisdom, we shall ascertain its nature by examining to\r what kind of persons we in common language ascribe it.[16]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":608},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-25","text":"It is thought then to be the property of the Practically Wise man to be\r able to deliberate well respecting what is good and expedient for\r himself, not in any definite line,[17] as what is conducive to health\r or strength, but what to living well. A proof of this is that we call\r men Wise in this or that, when they calculate well with a view to some\r good end in a case where there is no definite rule. And so, in a\r general way of speaking, the man who is good at deliberation will be\r Practically Wise. Now no man deliberates respecting things which cannot\r be otherwise than they are, nor such ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":609},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-26","text":"It remains then that it must be “a state of mind true, conjoined with\r Reason, and apt to Do, having for its object those things which are\r good or bad for Man:” because of Making something beyond itself is\r always the object, but cannot be of Doing because the very well-doing\r is in itself an End.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":610},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-27","text":"For this reason we think Pericles and men of that stamp to be\r Practically Wise, because they can see what is good for themselves and\r for men in general, and we also think those to be such who are skilled\r in domestic management or civil government. In fact, this is the reason\r why we call the habit of perfected self-mastery by the name which in\r Greek it bears, etymologically signifying “that which preserves the\r Practical Wisdom:” for what it does preserve is the Notion I have\r mentioned, _i.e._ of one’s own true interest.[18]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":611},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-28","text":"For it is not every kind of Notion which the pleasant and the painful\r corrupt and pervert, as, for instance, that “the three angles of every\r rectilineal triangle are equal to two right angles,” but only those\r bearing on moral action.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":612},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-29","text":"For the Principles of the matters of moral action are the final cause\r of them:[19] now to the man who has been corrupted by reason of\r pleasure or pain the Principle immediately becomes obscured, nor does\r he see that it is his duty to choose and act in each instance with a\r view to this final cause and by reason of it: for viciousness has a\r tendency to destroy the moral Principle: and so Practical Wisdom must\r be “a state conjoined with reason, true, having human good for its\r object, and apt to do.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":613},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-30","text":"Then again Art admits of degrees of excellence, but Practical Wisdom\r does not:[20] and in Art he who goes wrong purposely is preferable to\r him who does so unwittingly,[21] but not so in respect of Practical\r Wisdom or the other Virtues. It plainly is then an Excellence of a\r certain kind, and not an Art.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":614},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-31","text":"Now as there are two parts of the Soul which have Reason, it must be\r the Excellence of the Opinionative [which we called before calculative\r or deliberative], because both Opinion and Practical Wisdom are\r exercised upon Contingent matter. And further, it is not simply a state\r conjoined with Reason, as is proved by the fact that such a state may\r be forgotten and so lost while Practical Wisdom cannot.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":615},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-32","text":"Now Knowledge is a conception concerning universals and Necessary\r matter, and there are of course certain First Principles in all trains\r of demonstrative reasoning (that is of all Knowledge because this is\r connected with reasoning): that faculty, then, which takes in the first\r principles of that which comes under the range of Knowledge, cannot be\r either Knowledge, or Art, or Practical Wisdom: not Knowledge, because\r what is the object of Knowledge must be derived from demonstrative\r reasoning; not either of the other two, because they are exercised upon\r Contingent matter only. Nor can it","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":616},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-33","text":"It comes then to this: since the faculties whereby we always attain\r truth and are never deceived when dealing with matter Necessary or even\r Contingent are Knowledge, Practical Wisdom, Science, and Intuition, and\r the faculty which takes in First Principles cannot be any of the three\r first; the last, namely Intuition, must be it which performs this\r function.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":617},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-34","text":"Science is a term we use principally in two meanings: in the first\r place, in the Arts we ascribe it to those who carry their arts to the\r highest accuracy;[22] Phidias, for instance, we call a Scientific or\r cunning sculptor; Polycleitus a Scientific or cunning statuary;\r meaning, in this instance, nothing else by Science than an excellence\r of art: in the other sense, we think some to be Scientific in a general\r way, not in any particular line or in any particular thing, just as\r Homer says of a man in his Margites; “Him the Gods made neither a\r digger of the ground, nor ploughman, nor in an","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":618},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-35","text":"So it is plain that Science must mean the most accurate of all\r Knowledge; but if so, then the Scientific man must not merely know the\r deductions from the First Principles but be in possession of truth\r respecting the First Principles. So that Science must be equivalent to\r Intuition and Knowledge; it is, so to speak, Knowledge of the most\r precious objects, _with a head on_.[23]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":619},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-36","text":"I say of the most precious things, because it is absurd to suppose\r πολιτικὴ,[24] or Practical Wisdom, to be the highest, unless it can be\r shown that Man is the most excellent of all that exists in the\r Universe. Now if “healthy” and “good” are relative terms, differing\r when applied to men or to fish, but “white” and “straight” are the same\r always, men must allow that the Scientific is the same always, but the\r Practically Wise varies: for whatever provides all things well for\r itself, to this they would apply the term Practically Wise, and commit\r these matters to it; which is the reason, ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":620},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-37","text":"And it is quite plain that Science and πολιτικὴ cannot be identical:\r because if men give the name of Science to that faculty which is\r employed upon what is expedient for themselves, there will be many\r instead of one, because there is not one and the same faculty employed\r on the good of all animals collectively, unless in the same sense as\r you may say there is one art of healing with respect to all living\r beings.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":621},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-38","text":"If it is urged that man is superior to all other animals, that makes no\r difference: for there are many other things more Godlike in their\r nature than Man, as, most obviously, the elements of which the Universe\r is composed.[25]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":622},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-39","text":"It is plain then that Science is the union of Knowledge and Intuition,\r and has for its objects those things which are most precious in their\r nature. Accordingly, Anexagoras, Thales, and men of that stamp, people\r call Scientific, but not Practically Wise because they see them\r ignorant of what concerns themselves; and they say that what they know\r is quite out of the common run certainly, and wonderful, and hard, and\r very fine no doubt, but still useless because they do not seek after\r what is good for them as men.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":623},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-40","text":"But Practical Wisdom is employed upon human matters, and such as are\r objects of deliberation (for we say, that to deliberate well is most\r peculiarly the work of the man who possesses this Wisdom), and no man\r deliberates about things which cannot be otherwise than they are, nor\r about any save those that have some definite End and this End good\r resulting from Moral Action; and the man to whom we should give the\r name of Good in Counsel, simply and without modification, is he who in\r the way of calculation has a capacity for attaining that of practical\r goods which is the best for Man.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":624},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-41","text":"Nor again does Practical Wisdom consist in a knowledge of general\r principles only, but it is necessary that one should know also the\r particular details, because it is apt to act, and action is concerned\r with details: for which reason sometimes men who have not much\r knowledge are more practical than others who have; among others, they\r who derive all they know from actual experience: suppose a man to know,\r for instance, that light meats are easy of digestion and wholesome, but\r not what kinds of meat are light, he will not produce a healthy state;\r that man will have a much better chance o","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":625},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-42","text":"Further: πολιτικὴ and Practical Wisdom are the same mental state, but\r the point of view is not the same.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":626},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-43","text":"Of Practical Wisdom exerted upon a community that which I would call\r the Supreme is the faculty of Legislation; the subordinate, which is\r concerned with the details, generally has the common name πολιτικὴ, and\r its functions are Action and Deliberation (for the particular enactment\r is a matter of action, being the ultimate issue of this branch of\r Practical Wisdom, and therefore people commonly say, that these men\r alone are really engaged in government, because they alone act, filling\r the same place relatively to legislators, that workmen do to a\r master).[27]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":627},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-44","text":"Again, that is thought to be Practical Wisdom in the most proper sense\r which has for its object the interest of the Individual: and this\r usually appropriates the common name: the others are called\r respectively Domestic Management, Legislation, Executive Government\r divided into two branches, Deliberative and Judicial.[28] Now of\r course, knowledge for one’s self is one kind of knowledge, but it\r admits of many shades of difference: and it is a common notion that the\r man who knows and busies himself about his own concerns merely is the\r man of Practical Wisdom, while they who extend their s","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":628},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-45","text":"Euripides has thus embodied this sentiment; “How,” says one of his\r Characters, “How foolish am I, who whereas I might have shared equally,\r idly numbered among the multitude of the army *** for them that are\r busy and meddlesome [Jove hates],” because the generality of mankind\r seek their own good and hold that this is their proper business. It is\r then from this opinion that the notion has arisen that such men are the\r Practically-Wise. And yet it is just possible that the good of the\r individual cannot be secured independently of connection with a family\r or a community. And again, how a ma","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":629},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-46","text":"A corroboration of what I have said is[30] the fact, that the young\r come to be geometricians, and mathematicians, and Scientific in such\r matters, but it is not thought that a young man can come to be\r possessed of Practical Wisdom: now the reason is, that this Wisdom has\r for its object particular facts, which come to be known from\r experience, which a young man has not because it is produced only by\r length of time.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":630},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-47","text":"By the way, a person might also enquire,[31] why a boy may be made a\r mathematician but not Scientific or a natural philosopher. Is not this\r the reason? that mathematics are taken in by the process of\r abstraction, but the principles of Science[32] and natural philosophy\r must be gained by experiment; and the latter young men talk of but do\r not realise, while the nature of the former is plain and clear.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":631},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-48","text":"Again, in matter of practice, error attaches either to the general\r rule, in the process of deliberation, or to the particular fact: for\r instance, this would be a general rule, “All water of a certain gravity\r is bad;” the particular fact, “this water is of that gravity.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":632},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-49","text":"And that Practical Wisdom is not Knowledge is plain, for it has to do\r with the ultimate issue,[33] as has been said, because every object of\r action is of this nature.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":633},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-50","text":"To Intuition it is opposed, for this takes in those principles which\r cannot be proved by reasoning, while Practical Wisdom is concerned with\r the ultimate particular fact which cannot be realised by Knowledge but\r by Sense; I do not mean one of the five senses, but the same by which\r we take in the mathematical fact, that no rectilineal figure can be\r contained by less than three lines, i.e. that a triangle is the\r ultimate figure, because here also is a stopping point.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":634},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-51","text":"This however is Sense rather than Practical Wisdom, which is of another\r kind.[34]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":635},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-52","text":"Now the acts of enquiring and deliberating differ, though deliberating\r is a kind of enquiring. We ought to ascertain about Good Counsel\r likewise what it is, whether a kind of Knowledge, or Opinion, or Happy\r Conjecture, or some other kind of faculty. Knowledge it obviously is\r not, because men do not enquire about what they know, and Good Counsel\r is a kind of deliberation, and the man who is deliberating is enquiring\r and calculating.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":636},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-53","text":"Neither is it Happy Conjecture; because this is independent of\r reasoning, and a rapid operation; but men deliberate a long time, and\r it is a common saying that one should execute speedily what has been\r resolved upon in deliberation, but deliberate slowly.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":637},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-54","text":"Quick perception of causes[35] again is a different faculty from good\r counsel, for it is a species of Happy Conjecture. Nor is Good Counsel\r Opinion of any kind.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":638},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-55","text":"Well then, since he who deliberates ill goes wrong, and he who\r deliberates well does so rightly, it is clear that Good Counsel is\r rightness of some kind, but not of Knowledge nor of Opinion: for\r Knowledge cannot be called right because it cannot be wrong, and\r Rightness of Opinion is Truth: and again, all which is the object of\r opinion is definitely marked out.[36]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":639},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-56","text":"Still, however, Good Counsel is not independent of Reason, Does it\r remain then that it is a rightness of Intellectual Operation simply,\r because this does not amount to an assertion; and the objection to\r Opinion was that it is not a process of enquiry but already a definite\r assertion; whereas whosoever deliberates, whether well or ill, is\r engaged in enquiry and calculation.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":640},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-57","text":"Well, Good Counsel is a Rightness of deliberation, and so the first\r question must regard the nature and objects of deliberation. Now\r remember Rightness is an equivocal term; we plainly do not mean\r Rightness of any kind whatever; the ἀκρατὴς, for instance, or the bad\r man, will obtain by his calculation what he sets before him as an\r object, and so he may be said to have deliberated _rightly_ in one\r sense, but will have attained a great evil. Whereas to have deliberated\r well is thought to be a good, because Good Counsel is Rightness of\r deliberation of such a nature as is apt to attain goo","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":641},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-58","text":"But even this again you may get by false reasoning, and hit upon the\r right effect though not through right means,[37] your middle term being\r fallacious: and so neither will this be yet Good Counsel in consequence\r of which you get what you ought but not through proper means.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":642},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-59","text":"Again, one man may hit on a thing after long deliberation, another\r quickly. And so that before described will not be yet Good Counsel, but\r the Rightness must be with reference to what is expedient; and you must\r have a proper end in view, pursue it in a right manner and right time.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":643},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-60","text":"Once more. One may deliberate well either generally or towards some\r particular End.[38] Good counsel in the general then is that which goes\r right towards that which is the End in a general way of consideration;\r in particular, that which does so towards some particular End.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":644},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-61","text":"Since then deliberating well is a quality of men possessed of Practical\r Wisdom, Good Counsel must be “Rightness in respect of what conduces to\r a given End, of which[39] Practical Wisdom is the true conception.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":645},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-62","text":"There is too the faculty of Judiciousness, and also its absence, in\r virtue of which we call men Judicious or the contrary.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":646},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-63","text":"Now Judiciousness is neither entirely identical with Knowledge or\r Opinion (for then all would have been Judicious), nor is it any one\r specific science, as medical science whose object matter is things\r wholesome; or geometry whose object matter is magnitude: for it has not\r for its object things which always exist and are immutable, nor of\r those things which come into being just any which may chance; but those\r in respect of which a man might doubt and deliberate.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":647},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-64","text":"And so it has the same object matter as Practical Wisdom; yet the two\r faculties are not identical, because Practical Wisdom has the capacity\r for commanding and taking the initiative, for its End is “what one\r should do or not do:” but Judiciousness is only apt to decide upon\r suggestions (though we do in Greek put “well” on to the faculty and its\r concrete noun, these really mean exactly the same as the plain words),\r and Judiciousness is neither the having Practical Wisdom, nor attaining\r it: but just as learning is termed συνιέναι when a man uses his\r knowledge, so judiciousness consists i","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":648},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-65","text":"The faculty called γνώμη,[40] in right of which we call men εὐγνώμονες,\r or say they have γνώμη, is “the right judgment of the equitable man.” A\r proof of which is that we most commonly say that the equitable man has\r a tendency to make allowance, and the making allowance in certain cases\r is equitable. And συγγνώμη (the word denoting allowance) is right γνώμη\r having a capacity of making equitable decisions, By “right” I mean that\r of the Truthful man.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":649},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-66","text":"Now all these mental states[41] tend to the same object, as indeed\r common language leads us to expect: I mean, we speak of γνώμη,\r Judiciousness, Practical Wisdom, and Practical Intuition, attributing\r the possession of γνώμη and Practical Intuition to the same Individuals\r whom we denominate Practically-Wise and Judicious: because all these\r faculties are employed upon the extremes,[42] i.e. on particular\r details; and in right of his aptitude for deciding on the matters which\r come within the province of the Practically-Wise, a man is Judicious\r and possessed of good γνώμη; i.e. he is dispo","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":650},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-67","text":"And all matters of Moral Action belong to the class of particulars,\r otherwise called extremes: for the man of Practical Wisdom must know\r them, and Judiciousness and γνώμη are concerned with matters of Moral\r Actions, which are extremes.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":651},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-68","text":"Intuition, moreover, takes in the extremes at both ends:[43] I mean,\r the first and last terms must be taken in not by reasoning but by\r Intuition [so that Intuition comes to be of two kinds], and that which\r belongs to strict demonstrative reasonings takes in immutable, i.e.\r Necessary, first terms; while that which is employed in practical\r matters takes in the extreme, the Contingent, and the minor\r Premiss:[44] for the minor Premisses are the source of the Final Cause,\r Universals being made up out of Particulars.[45] To take in these, of\r course, we must have Sense, i.e. in other words Pr","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":652},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-69","text":"And for this reason these are thought to be simply gifts of nature; and\r whereas no man is thought to be Scientific by nature, men are thought\r to have γνώμη, and Judiciousness, and Practical Intuition: a proof of\r which is that we think these faculties are a consequence even of\r particular ages, and this given age has Practical Intuition and γνώμη,\r we say, as if under the notion that nature is the cause. And thus\r Intuition is both the beginning and end, because the proofs are based\r upon the one kind of extremes and concern the other.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":653},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-70","text":"And so[46] one should attend to the undemonstrable dicta and opinions\r of the skilful, the old and the Practically-Wise, no less than to those\r which are based on strict reasoning, because they see aright, having\r gained their power of moral vision from experience.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":654},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-71","text":"Well, we have now stated the nature and objects of Practical Wisdom and\r Science respectively, and that they belong each to a different part of\r the Soul. But I can conceive a person questioning their utility.\r “Science,” he would say, “concerns itself with none of the causes of\r human happiness (for it has nothing to do with producing anything):\r Practical Wisdom has this recommendation, I grant, but where is the\r need of it, since its province is those things which are just and\r honourable, and good for man, and these are the things which the good\r man as such does; but we are not a bit the ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":655},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-72","text":"“If it be urged that _knowing what is_ good does not by itself make a\r Practically-Wise man but _becoming_ good; still this Wisdom will be no\r use either to those that are good, and so have it already, or to those\r who have it not; because it will make no difference to them whether\r they have it themselves or put themselves under the guidance of others\r who have; and we might be contented to be in respect of this as in\r respect of health: for though we wish to be healthy still we do not set\r about learning the art of healing.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":656},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-73","text":"“Furthermore, it would seem to be strange that, though lower in the\r scale than Science, it is to be its master; which it is, because\r whatever produces results takes the rule and directs in each matter.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":657},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-74","text":"This then is what we are to talk about, for these are the only points\r now raised.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":658},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-75","text":"Now first we say that being respectively Excellences of different parts\r of the Soul they must be choice-worthy, even on the supposition that\r they neither of them produce results.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":659},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-76","text":"In the next place we say that they _do_ produce results; that Science\r makes Happiness, not as the medical art but as healthiness makes\r health:[48] because, being a part of Virtue in its most extensive\r sense, it makes a man happy by being possessed and by working.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":660},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-77","text":"Next, Man’s work _as Man_ is accomplished by virtue of Practical Wisdom\r and Moral Virtue, the latter giving the right aim and direction, the\r former the right means to its attainment;[49] but of the fourth part of\r the Soul, the mere nutritive principle, there is no such Excellence,\r because nothing is in its power to do or leave undone.[50]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":661},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-78","text":"As to our not being more apt to do what is noble and just by reason of\r possessing Practical Wisdom, we must begin a little higher up,[51]\r taking this for our starting-point. As we say that men may do things in\r themselves just and yet not be just men; for instance, when men do what\r the laws require of them, either against their will, or by reason of\r ignorance or something else, at all events not for the sake of the\r things themselves; and yet they do what they ought and all that the\r good man should do; so it seems that to be a good man one must do each\r act in a particular frame of mind, ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":662},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-79","text":"There is then a certain faculty, commonly named Cleverness, of such a\r nature as to be able to do and attain whatever conduces to _any_ given\r purpose: now if that purpose be a good one the faculty is praiseworthy;\r if otherwise, it goes by a name which, denoting strictly the ability,\r implies the willingness to do _anything_; we accordingly call the\r Practically-Wise Clever, and also those who can and will do\r anything.[52]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":663},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-80","text":"Now Practical Wisdom is not identical with Cleverness, nor is it\r without this power of adapting means to ends: but this Eye of the Soul\r (as we may call it) does not attain its proper state without goodness,\r as we have said before and as is quite plain, because the syllogisms\r into which Moral Action may be analysed have for their Major\r Premiss,[53] “since —— is the End and the Chief Good”[54] (fill up the\r blank with just anything you please, for we merely want to exhibit the\r Form, so that anything will do), but _how_ this blank should be filled\r is seen only by the good man: because Vice","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":664},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-81","text":"It is clear, therefore, that a man cannot be a Practically-Wise,\r without being a good, man.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":665},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-82","text":"We must enquire again also about Virtue: for it may be divided into\r Natural Virtue and Matured, which two bear to each other a relation\r similar to that which Practical Wisdom bears to Cleverness, one not of\r identity but resemblance. I speak of Natural Virtue, because men hold\r that each of the moral dispositions attach to us all somehow by nature:\r we have dispositions[56] towards justice, self-mastery and courage, for\r instance, immediately from our birth: but still we seek Goodness in its\r highest sense as something distinct from these, and that these\r dispositions should attach to us in ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":666},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-83","text":"So that, as in the case of the Opinionative faculty, there are two\r forms, Cleverness and Practical Wisdom; so also in the case of the\r Moral there are two, Natural Virtue and Matured; and of these the\r latter cannot be formed without Practical Wisdom.[58]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":667},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-84","text":"This leads some to say that all the Virtues are merely intellectual\r Practical Wisdom, and Socrates was partly right in his enquiry and\r partly wrong: wrong in that he thought all the Virtues were merely\r intellectual Practical Wisdom, right in saying they were not\r independent of that faculty.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":668},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-85","text":"A proof of which is that now all, in defining Virtue, add on the\r “state” [mentioning also to what standard it has reference, namely\r that] “which is accordant with Right Reason:” now “right” means in\r accordance with Practical Wisdom. So then all seem to have an\r instinctive notion that that state which is in accordance with\r Practical Wisdom is Virtue; however, we must make a slight change in\r their statement, because that state is Virtue, not merely which is in\r accordance with but which implies the possession of Right Reason;\r which, upon such matters, is Practical Wisdom. The difference b","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":669},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-86","text":"From what has been said then it is clear that one cannot be, strictly\r speaking, good without Practical Wisdom nor Practically-Wise without\r moral goodness.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":670},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-87","text":"And by the distinction between Natural and Matured Virtue one can meet\r the reasoning by which it might be argued “that the Virtues are\r separable because the same man is not by nature most inclined to all at\r once so that he will have acquired this one before he has that other:”\r we would reply that this is possible with respect to the Natural\r Virtues but not with respect to those in right of which a man is\r denominated simply good: because they will all belong to him together\r with the one faculty of Practical Wisdom.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":671},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-88","text":"It is plain too that even had it not been apt to act we should have\r needed it, because it is the Excellence of a part of the Soul; and that\r the moral choice cannot be right independently of Practical Wisdom and\r Moral Goodness; because this gives the right End, that causes the doing\r these things which conduce to the End.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":672},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-89","text":"Then again, it is not Master of Science (i.e. of the superior part of\r the Soul), just as neither is the healing art Master of health; for it\r does not make use of it, but looks how it may come to be: so it\r commands for the sake of it but does not command it.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":673},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-90","text":"The objection is, in fact, about as valid as if a man should say\r πολιτικὴ governs the gods because it gives orders about all things in\r the communty.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":674},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-91","text":"All teaching, and all intellectual learning, proceeds on the basis of\r previous knowledge, as will appear on an examination of all. The\r Mathematical Sciences, and every other system, draw their conclusions\r in this method. So too of reasonings, whether by syllogism, or\r induction: for both teach through what is previously known, the former\r assuming the premisses as from wise men, the latter proving universals\r from the evidentness of the particulars. In like manner too\r rhetoricians persuade, either through examples (which amounts to\r induction), or through enthymemes (which amounts to syllo","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":675},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-92","text":"Well, we suppose that we _know_ things (in the strict and proper sense\r of the word) when we suppose ourselves to know the cause by reason of\r which the thing is to be the cause of it; and that this cannot be\r otherwise. It is plain that the idea intended to be conveyed by the\r term _knowing_ is something of this kind; because they who do not\r really know suppose themselves thus related to the matter in hand and\r they who do know really are so that of whatsoever there is properly\r speaking Knowledge this cannot be otherwise than it is Whether or no\r there is another way of knowing we will say ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":676},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-93","text":"If Knowledge then is such as we have described it, the Knowledge\r produced by demonstrative reasoning must be drawn from premisses _true_\r and _first_, and _incapable of syllogistic proof_, and _better known_,\r and _prior in order of time_, and _causes of the conclusion_, for so\r the principles will be akin to the conclusion demonstrated.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":677},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-94","text":"(Syllogism, of course there may be without such premisses, but it will\r not be demonstration because it will not produce knowledge).","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":678},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-95","text":"_First_, that is indemonstrable, because, if demonstrable, he cannot be\r said to _know_ them who has no demonstration of them for knowing such\r things as are demonstrable is the same as having demonstration of them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":679},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-96","text":"_Causes_ they must be, and _better known_, and _prior_ in time,\r _causes_, because we then know when we are acquainted with the cause,\r and _prior_, if causes, and _known beforehand_, not merely comprehended\r in idea but known to exist (The terms prior, and better known, bear two\r senses for _prior by nature_ and _prior relatively to ourselves_ are\r not the same, nor _better known by nature_, and _better known to us_ I\r mean, by _prior_ and _better known relatively to ourselves_, such\r things as are nearer to sensation, but abstractedly so such as are\r further Those are furthest which are most","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":680},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-97","text":"And by _first_, I mean _principles akin to the conclusion_, for\r principle means the same as first And the principle or first step in\r demonstration is a proposition incapable of syllogistic proof, _i.e._\r one to which there is none prior. Now of such syllogistic principles I\r call that a θέσις which you cannot demonstrate, and which is\r unnecessary with a view to learning something else. That which is\r necessary in order to learn something else is an Axiom.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":681},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-98","text":"Further, since one is to believe and know the thing by having a\r syllogism of the kind called demonstration, and what constitutes it to\r be such is the nature of the premisses, it is necessary not merely to\r _know before_, but to _know better than the conclusion_, either all or\r at least some of, the principles, because that which is the cause of a\r quality inhering in something else always inheres itself more as the\r cause of our loving is itself more lovable. So, since the principles\r are the cause of our knowing and behoving we know and believe them\r more, because by reason of them we know ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":682},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-7-99","text":"Further: the man who is to have the Knowledge which comes through\r demonstration must not merely know and believe his principles better\r than he does his conclusion, but he must believe nothing more firmly\r than the contradictories of those principles out of which the contrary\r fallacy may be constructed: since he who _knows_, is to be simply and\r absolutely infallible.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":683},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-1","text":"Next we must take a different point to start from,[1] and observe that\r of what is to be avoided in respect of moral character there are three\r forms; Vice, Imperfect Self-Control, and Brutishness. Of the two former\r it is plain what the contraries are, for we call the one Virtue, the\r other Self-Control; and as answering to Brutishness it will be most\r suitable to assign Superhuman, i.e. heroical and godlike Virtue, as, in\r Homer, Priam says of Hector “that he was very excellent, nor was he\r like the offspring of mortal man, but of a god.” and so, if, as is\r commonly said, men are raised to t","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":684},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-2","text":"And as, on the one hand, it is a rare thing for a man to be godlike (a\r term the Lacedæmonians are accustomed to use when they admire a man\r exceedingly; σεῖος ἀνὴρ  they call him), so the brutish man is rare;\r the character is found most among barbarians, and some cases of it are\r caused by disease or maiming; also such men as exceed in vice all\r ordinary measures we therefore designate by this opprobrious term.\r Well, we must in a subsequent place make some mention of this\r disposition, and Vice has been spoken of before: for the present we\r must speak of Imperfect Self-Control and its kindr","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":685},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-3","text":"And we should adopt the same course as before, i.e. state the\r phenomena, and, after raising and discussing difficulties which suggest\r themselves, then exhibit, if possible, all the opinions afloat\r respecting these affections of the moral character; or, if not all, the\r greater part and the most important: for we may consider we have\r illustrated the matter sufficiently when the difficulties have been\r solved, and such theories as are most approved are left as a residuum.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":686},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-4","text":"I. That Self-Control and Endurance belong to the class of things good\r and praiseworthy, while Imperfect Self-Control and Softness belong to\r that of things low and blameworthy.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":687},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-5","text":"II. That the man of Self-Control is identical with the man who is apt\r to abide by his resolution, and the man of Imperfect Self-Control with\r him who is apt to depart from his resolution.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":688},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-6","text":"III. That the man of Imperfect Self-Control does things at the\r instigation of his passions, knowing them to be wrong, while the man of\r Self-Control, knowing his lusts to be wrong, refuses, by the influence\r of reason, to follow their suggestions.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":689},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-7","text":"IV. That the man of Perfected Self-Mastery unites the qualities of\r Self-Control and Endurance, and some say that every one who unites\r these is a man of Perfect Self-Mastery, others do not.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":690},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-8","text":"V. Some confound the two characters of the man who has _no_\r Self-Control, and the man of _Imperfect Self-Control_, while others\r distinguish between them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":691},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-9","text":"VI. It is sometimes said that the man of Practical Wisdom cannot be a\r man of Imperfect Self-Control, sometimes that men who are Practically\r Wise and Clever are of Imperfect Self-Control.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":692},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-10","text":"VII. Again, men are said to be of Imperfect Self-Control, not simply\r but with the addition of the thing wherein, as in respect of anger, of\r honour, and gain.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":693},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-11","text":"Now a man may raise a question as to the nature of the right conception\r in violation of which a man fails of Self-Control.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":694},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-12","text":"That he can so fail when _knowing_ in the strict sense what is right\r some say is impossible: for it is a strange thing, as Socrates thought,\r that while Knowledge is present in his mind something else should\r master him and drag him about like a slave. Socrates in fact contended\r generally against the theory, maintaining there is no such state as\r that of Imperfect Self-Control, for that no one acts contrary to what\r is best conceiving it to be best but by reason of ignorance what is\r best.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":695},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-13","text":"With all due respect to Socrates, his account of the matter is at\r variance with plain facts, and we must enquire with respect to the\r affection, if it be caused by ignorance what is the nature of the\r ignorance: for that the man so failing does not suppose his acts to be\r right before he is under the influence of passion is quite plain.[2]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":696},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-14","text":"There are people who partly agree with Socrates and partly not: that\r nothing can be stronger than Knowledge they agree, but that no man acts\r in contravention of his conviction of what is better they do not agree;\r and so they say that it is not Knowledge, but only Opinion, which the\r man in question has and yet yields to the instigation of his pleasures.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":697},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-15","text":"But then, if it is Opinion and not Knowledge, that is it the opposing\r conception be not strong but only mild (as in the case of real doubt),\r the not abiding by it in the face of strong lusts would be excusable:\r but wickedness is not excusable, nor is anything which deserves blame.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":698},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-16","text":"Well then, is it Practical Wisdom which in this case offers opposition:\r for that is the strongest principle? The supposition is absurd, for we\r shall have the same man uniting Practical Wisdom and Imperfect\r Self-Control, and surely no single person would maintain that it is\r consistent with the character of Practical Wisdom to do voluntarily\r what is very wrong; and besides we have shown before that the very mark\r of a man of this character is aptitude to act, as distinguished from\r mere knowledge of what is right; because he is a man conversant with\r particular details, and possessed of all","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":699},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-17","text":"Again, if the having strong and bad lusts is necessary to the idea of\r the man of Self-Control, this character cannot be identical with the\r man of Perfected Self-Mastery, because the having strong desires or bad\r ones does not enter into the idea of this latter character: and yet the\r man of Self-Control must have such: for suppose them good; then the\r moral state which should hinder a man from following their suggestions\r must be bad, and so Self-Control would not be in all cases good:\r suppose them on the other hand to be weak and not wrong, it would be\r nothing grand; nor anything great, s","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":700},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-18","text":"Again, if Self-Control makes a man apt to abide by all opinions without\r exception, it may be bad, as suppose the case of a false opinion: and\r if Imperfect Self-Control makes a man apt to depart from all without\r exception, we shall have cases where it will be good; take that of\r Neoptolemus in the Philoctetes of Sophocles, for instance: he is to be\r praised for not abiding by what he was persuaded to by Ulysses, because\r he was pained at being guilty of falsehood.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":701},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-19","text":"Or again, false sophistical reasoning presents a difficulty: for\r because men wish to prove paradoxes that they may be counted clever\r when they succeed, the reasoning that has been used becomes a\r difficulty: for the intellect is fettered; a man being unwilling to\r abide by the conclusion because it does not please his judgment, but\r unable to advance because he cannot disentangle the web of sophistical\r reasoning.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":702},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-20","text":"Or again, it is conceivable on this supposition that folly joined with\r Imperfect Self-Control may turn out, in a given case, goodness: for by\r reason of his imperfection of self-control a man acts in a way which\r contradicts his notions; now his notion is that what is really good is\r bad and ought not to be done; and so he will eventually do what is good\r and not what is bad.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":703},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-21","text":"Again, on the same supposition, the man who acting on conviction\r pursues and chooses things because they are pleasant must be thought a\r better man than he who does so not by reason of a quasi-rational\r conviction but of Imperfect Self-Control: because he is more open to\r cure by reason of the possibility of his receiving a contrary\r conviction. But to the man of Imperfect Self-Control would apply the\r proverb, “when water chokes, what should a man drink then?” for had he\r never been convinced at all in respect of what he does,[3] then by a\r conviction in a contrary direction he might have st","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":704},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-22","text":"Again, if any and every thing is the object-matter of Imperfect and\r Perfect Self-Control, who is the man of Imperfect Self-Control simply?\r because no one unites all cases of it, and we commonly say that some\r men are so simply, not adding any particular thing in which they are\r so.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":705},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-23","text":"Well, the difficulties raised are pretty near such as I have described\r them, and of these theories we must remove some and leave others as\r established; because the solving of a difficulty is a positive act of\r establishing something as true.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":706},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-24","text":"Now we must examine first whether men of Imperfect Self-Control act\r with a knowledge of what is right or not: next, if with such knowledge,\r in what sense; and next what are we to assume is the object-matter of\r the man of Imperfect Self-Control, and of the man of Self-Control; I\r mean, whether pleasure and pain of all kinds or certain definite ones;\r and as to Self-Control and Endurance, whether these are designations of\r the same character or different. And in like manner we must go into all\r questions which are connected with the present.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":707},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-25","text":"But the real starting point of the enquiry is, whether the two\r characters of Self-Control and Imperfect Self-Control are distinguished\r by their object-matter, or their respective relations to it. I mean,\r whether the man of Imperfect Self-Control is such simply by virtue of\r having such and such object-matter; or not, but by virtue of his being\r related to it in such and such a way, or by virtue of both: next,\r whether Self-Control and Imperfect Self-Control are unlimited in their\r object-matter: because he who is designated without any addition a man\r of Imperfect Self-Control is not unlimi","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":708},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-26","text":"Now as to the notion that it is True Opinion and not Knowledge in\r contravention of which men fail in Self-Control, it makes no difference\r to the point in question, because some of those who hold Opinions have\r no doubt about them but suppose themselves to have accurate Knowledge;\r if then it is urged that men holding Opinions will be more likely than\r men who have Knowledge to act in contravention of their conceptions, as\r having but a moderate belief in them; we reply, Knowledge will not\r differ in this respect from Opinion: because some men believe their own\r Opinions no less firmly than o","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":709},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-27","text":"Rather the following is the account of it: the term _knowing_ has two\r senses; both the man who does not use his Knowledge, and he who does,\r are said to _know_: there will be a difference between a man’s acting\r wrongly, who though possessed of Knowledge does not call it into\r operation, and his doing so who has it and actually exercises it: the\r latter is a strange case, but the mere having, if not exercising,\r presents no anomaly.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":710},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-28","text":"Again, as there are two kinds of propositions affecting action,[4]\r universal and particular, there is no reason why a man may not act\r against his Knowledge, having both propositions in his mind, using the\r universal but not the particular, for the particulars are the objects\r of moral action.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":711},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-29","text":"There is a difference also in universal propositions;[5] a universal\r proposition may relate partly to a man’s self and partly to the thing\r in question: take the following for instance; “dry food is good for\r every man,” this may have the two minor premisses, “this is a man,” and\r “so and so is dry food;” but whether a given substance is so and so a\r man either has not the Knowledge or does not exert it. According to\r these different senses there will be an immense difference, so that for\r a man to _know_ in the one sense, and yet act wrongly, would be nothing\r strange, but in any of the othe","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":712},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-30","text":"Again, men may have Knowledge in a way different from any of those\r which have been now stated: for we constantly see a man’s state so\r differing by having and not using Knowledge, that he has it in a sense\r and also has not; when a man is asleep, for instance, or mad, or drunk:\r well, men under the actual operation of passion are in exactly similar\r conditions; for anger, lust, and some other such-like things,\r manifestly make changes even in the body, and in some they even cause\r madness; it is plain then that we must say the men of Imperfect\r Self-Control are in a state similar to these.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":713},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-31","text":"And their saying what embodies Knowledge is no proof of their actually\r then exercising it, because they who are under the operation of these\r passions repeat demonstrations; or verses of Empedocles,[6] just as\r children, when first learning, string words together, but as yet know\r nothing of their meaning, because they must grow into it, and this is a\r process requiring time: so that we must suppose these men who fail in\r Self-Control to say these moral sayings just as actors do.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":714},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-32","text":"Furthermore, a man may look at the account of the phænomenon in the\r following way, from an examination of the actual working of the mind:\r All action may be analysed into a syllogism, in which the one premiss\r is an universal maxim and the other concerns particulars of which Sense\r [moral or physical, as the case may be] is cognisant: now when one\r results from these two, it follows necessarily that, as far as theory\r goes the mind must assert the conclusion, and in practical propositions\r the man must act accordingly.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":715},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-33","text":"For instance, let the universal be, “All that is sweet should be\r tasted,” the particular, “This is sweet;” it follows necessarily that\r he who is able and is not hindered should not only draw, but put in\r practice, the conclusion “This is to be tasted.” When then there is in\r the mind one universal proposition forbidding to taste, and the other\r “All that is sweet is pleasant” with its minor “This is sweet” (which\r is the one that really works), and desire happens to be in the man, the\r first universal bids him avoid this but the desire leads him on to\r taste; for it has the power of moving t","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":716},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-34","text":"As to the manner in which the ignorance is removed and the man of\r Imperfect Self-Control recovers his Knowledge, the account is the same\r as with respect to him who is drunk or asleep, and is not peculiar to\r this affection, so physiologists[8] are the right people to apply to.\r But whereas the minor premiss of every practical syllogism is an\r opinion on matter cognisable by Sense and determines the actions; he\r who is under the influence of passion either has not this, or so has it\r that his having does not amount to _knowing_ but merely saying, as a\r man when drunk might repeat Empedocles’ ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":717},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-35","text":"Let this account then be accepted of the question respecting the\r failure in Self-Control, whether it is with Knowledge, and the manner\r in which such failure is possible or not, though a man possesses\r Knowledge.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":718},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-36","text":"The next question to be discussed is whether there is a character to be\r designated by the term “of Imperfect Self-Control” simply, or whether\r all who are so are to be accounted such, in respect of some particular\r thing; and, if there is such a character, what is his object-matter.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":719},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-37","text":"Now that pleasures and pains are the object-matter of men of\r Self-Control and of Endurance, and also of men of Imperfect\r Self-Control and Softness, is plain.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":720},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-38","text":"Further, things which produce pleasure are either necessary, or objects\r of choice in themselves but yet admitting of excess. All bodily things\r which produce pleasure are necessary; and I call such those which\r relate to food and other grosser appetities, in short such bodily\r things as we assumed were the Object-matter of absence of Self-Control\r and of Perfected Self-Mastery.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":721},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-39","text":"The other class of objects are not necessary, but objects of choice in\r themselves: I mean, for instance, victory, honour, wealth, and\r such-like good or pleasant things. And those who are excessive in their\r liking for such things contrary to the principle of Right Reason which\r is in their own breasts we do not designate men of Imperfect\r Self-Control simply, but with the addition of the thing wherein, as in\r respect of money, or gain, or honour, or anger, and not simply; because\r we consider them as different characters and only having that title in\r right of a kind of resemblance (as when ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":722},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-40","text":"But of those who have for their object-matter the bodily enjoyments,\r which we say are also the object-matter of the man of Perfected\r Self-Mastery and the man who has lost all Self-Control, he that pursues\r excessive pleasures and too much avoids[10] things which are painful\r (as hunger and thirst, heat and cold, and everything connected with\r touch and taste), not from moral choice but in spite of his moral\r choice and intellectual conviction, is termed “a man of Imperfect\r Self-Control,” not with the addition of any particular object-matter as\r we do in respect of want of control of anger b","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":723},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-41","text":"And a proof that the term is thus applied is that the kindred term\r “Soft” is used in respect of these enjoyments but not in respect of any\r of those others. And for this reason we put into the same rank the man\r of Imperfect Self-Control, the man who has lost it entirely, the man\r who has it, and the man of Perfected Self-Mastery; but not any of those\r other characters, because the former have for their object-matter the\r same pleasures and pains: but though they have the same object-matter,\r they are not related to it in the same way, but two of them act upon\r moral choice, two without it. A","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":724},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-42","text":"Well then, since of desires and pleasures there are some which are in\r kind honourable and good (because things pleasant are divisible, as we\r said before, into such as are naturally objects of choice, such as are\r naturally objects of avoidance, and such as are in themselves\r indifferent, money, gain, honour, victory, for instance); in respect of\r all such and those that are indifferent, men are blamed not merely[11]\r for being affected by or desiring or liking them, but for exceeding in\r any way in these feelings.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":725},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-43","text":"And so they are blamed, whosoever in spite of Reason are mastered by,\r that is pursue, any object, though in its nature noble and good; they,\r for instance, who are more earnest than they should be respecting\r honour, or their children or parents; not but what these are good\r objects and men are praised for being earnest about them: but still\r they admit of excess; for instance, if any one, as Niobe did, should\r fight even against the gods, or feel towards his father as Satyrus, who\r got therefrom the nickname of φιλοπάτωρ, because he was thought to be\r very foolish.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":726},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-44","text":"Now depravity there is none in regard of these things, for the reason\r assigned above, that each of them in itself is a thing naturally\r choice-worthy, yet the excesses in respect of them are wrong and matter\r for blame: and similarly there is no Imperfect Self-Control in respect\r of these things; that being not merely a thing that should be avoided\r but blameworthy.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":727},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-45","text":"But because of the resemblance of the affection to the Imperfection of\r Self-Control the term is used with the addition in each case of the\r particular object-matter, just as men call a man a bad physician, or\r bad actor, whom they would not think of calling simply bad. As then in\r these cases we do not apply the term simply because each of the states\r is not a vice, but only like a vice in the way of analogy,[12] so it is\r plain that in respect of Imperfect Self-Control and Self-Control we\r must limit the names to those states which have the same object-matter\r as Perfected Self-Mastery and u","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":728},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-46","text":"As there are some things naturally pleasant, and of these two kinds;\r those, namely, which are pleasant generally, and those which are so\r relatively to particular kinds of animals and men; so there are others\r which are not naturally pleasant but which come to be so in consequence\r either of maimings, or custom, or depraved natural tastes: and one may\r observe moral states similar to those we have been speaking of, having\r respectively these classes of things for their object-matter.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":729},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-47","text":"I mean the Brutish, as in the case of the female who, they say, would\r rip up women with child and eat the foetus; or the tastes which are\r found among the savage tribes bordering on the Pontus, some liking raw\r flesh, and some being cannibals, and some lending one another their\r children to make feasts of; or what is said of Phalaris. These are\r instances of Brutish states, caused in some by disease or madness;\r take, for instance, the man who sacrificed and ate his mother, or him\r who devoured the liver of his fellow-servant. Instances again of those\r caused by disease or by custom, would be","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":730},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-48","text":"The having any of these inclinations is something foreign to what is\r denominated Vice, just as Brutishness is: and when a man has them his\r mastering them is not properly Self-Control, nor his being mastered by\r them Imperfection of Self-Control in the proper sense, but only in the\r way of resemblance; just as we may say a man of ungovernable wrath\r fails of Self-Control in respect of anger but not simply fails of\r Self-Control. For all excessive folly, cowardice, absence of\r Self-Control, or irritability, are either Brutish or morbid. The man,\r for instance, who is naturally afraid of all th","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":731},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-49","text":"So then, of these inclinations, a man may sometimes merely have one\r without yielding to it: I mean, suppose that Phalaris had restrained\r his unnatural desire to eat a child: or he may both have and yield to\r it. As then Vice when such as belongs to human nature is called Vice\r simply, while the other is so called with the addition of “brutish” or\r “morbid,” but not simply Vice, so manifestly there is Brutish and\r Morbid Imperfection of Self-Control, but that alone is entitled to the\r name without any qualification which is of the nature of utter absence\r of Self-Control, as it is found in Ma","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":732},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-50","text":"It is plain then that the object-matter of Imperfect Self-Control and\r Self-Control is restricted to the same as that of utter absence of\r Self-Control and that of Perfected Self-Mastery, and that the rest is\r the object-matter of a different species so named metaphorically and\r not simply: we will now examine the position, “that Imperfect\r Self-Control in respect of Anger is less disgraceful than that in\r respect of Lusts.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":733},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-51","text":"In the first place, it seems that Anger does in a way listen to Reason\r but mishears it; as quick servants who run out before they have heard\r the whole of what is said and then mistake the order; dogs, again, bark\r at the slightest stir, before they have seen whether it be friend or\r foe; just so Anger, by reason of its natural heat and quickness,\r listening to Reason, but without having heard the command of Reason,\r rushes to its revenge. That is to say, Reason or some impression on the\r mind shows there is insolence or contempt[14] in the offender, and then\r Anger, reasoning as it were that","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":734},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-52","text":"Again, a man is more excusable for following such desires as are\r natural, just as he is for following such Lusts as are common to all\r and to that degree in which they are common. Now Anger and irritability\r are more natural than Lusts when in excess and for objects not\r necessary. (This was the ground of the defence the man made who beat\r his father, “My father,” he said, “used to beat his, and his father his\r again, and this little fellow here,” pointing to his child, “will beat\r me when he is grown a man: it runs in the family.” And the father, as\r he was being dragged along, bid his son l","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":735},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-53","text":"Again, characters are less unjust in proportion as they involve less\r insidiousness. Now the Angry man is not insidious, nor is Anger, but\r quite open: but Lust is: as they say of Venus,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":736},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-54","text":"And so since this kind of Imperfect Self-Control is more unjust, it is\r also more disgraceful than that in respect of Anger, and is simply\r Imperfect Self-Control, and Vice in a certain sense.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":737},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-55","text":"Again, no man feels pain in being insolent, but every one who acts\r through Anger does act with pain; and he who acts insolently does it\r with pleasure. If then those things are most unjust with which we have\r most right to be angry, then Imperfect Self-Control, arising from Lust,\r is more so than that arising from Anger: because in Anger there is no\r insolence.[15]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":738},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-56","text":"Well then, it is clear that Imperfect Self-Control in respect of Lusts\r is more disgraceful than that in respect of Anger, and that the\r object-matter of Self-Control, and the Imperfection of it, are bodily\r Lusts and pleasures; but of these last we must take into account the\r differences; for, as was said at the commencement, some are proper to\r the human race and natural both in kind and degree, others Brutish, and\r others caused by maimings and diseases.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":739},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-57","text":"Now the first of these only are the object-matter of Perfected\r Self-Mastery and utter absence of Self-Control; and therefore we never\r attribute either of these states to Brutes (except metaphorically, and\r whenever any one kind of animal differs entirely from another in\r insolence, mischievousness, or voracity), because they have not moral\r choice or process of deliberation, but are quite different from that\r kind of creature just as are madmen from other men.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":740},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-58","text":"Brutishness is not so low in the scale as Vice, yet it is to be\r regarded with more fear: because it is not that the highest principle\r has been corrupted, as in the human creature, but the subject has it\r not at all.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":741},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-59","text":"It is much the same, therefore, as if one should compare an inanimate\r with an animate being, which were the worse: for the badness of that\r which has no principle of origination is always less harmful; now\r Intellect is a principle of origination. A similar case would be the\r comparing injustice and an unjust man together: for in different ways\r each is the worst: a bad man would produce ten thousand times as much\r harm as a bad brute.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":742},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-60","text":"Now with respect to the pleasures and pains which come to a man through\r Touch and Taste, and the desiring or avoiding such (which we determined\r before to constitute the object-matter of the states of utter absence\r of Self-Control and Perfected Self-Mastery), one may be so disposed as\r to yield to temptations to which most men would be superior, or to be\r superior to those to which most men would yield: in respect of\r pleasures, these characters will be respectively the man of Imperfect\r Self-Control, and the man of Self-Control; and, in respect of pains,\r the man of Softness and the man of ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":743},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-61","text":"Again, since of the pleasures indicated some are necessary and some are\r not, others are so to a certain degree but not the excess or defect of\r them, and similarly also of Lusts and pains, the man who pursues the\r excess of pleasant things, or such as are in themselves excess, or from\r moral choice, for their own sake, and not for anything else which is to\r result from them, is a man utterly void of Self-Control: for he must be\r incapable of remorse, and so incurable, because he that has not remorse\r is incurable. (He that has too little love of pleasure is the opposite\r character, and the ma","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":744},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-62","text":"But of the characters who go wrong without _choosing_ so to do, the one\r is led on by reason of pleasure, the other because he avoids the pain\r it would cost him to deny his lust; and so they are different the one\r from the other. Now every one would pronounce a man worse for doing\r something base without any impulse of desire, or with a very slight\r one, than for doing the same from the impulse of a very strong desire;\r for striking a man when not angry than if he did so in wrath: because\r one naturally says, “What would he have done had he been under the\r influence of passion?” (and on this ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":745},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-63","text":"Furthermore, to the character of Imperfect Self-Control is opposed that\r of Self-Control, and to that of Softness that of Endurance: because\r Endurance consists in continued resistance but Self-Control in actual\r mastery, and continued resistance and actual mastery are as different\r as not being conquered is from conquering; and so Self-Control is more\r choice-worthy than Endurance.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":746},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-64","text":"Again, he who fails when exposed to those temptations against which the\r common run of men hold out, and are well able to do so, is Soft and\r Luxurious (Luxury being a kind of Softness): the kind of man, I mean,\r to let his robe drag in the dirt to avoid the trouble of lifting it,\r and who, aping the sick man, does not however suppose himself wretched\r though he is like a wretched man. So it is too with respect to\r Self-Control and the Imperfection of it: if a man yields to pleasures\r or pains which are violent and excessive it is no matter for wonder,\r but rather for allowance if he made what","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":747},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-65","text":"Again, the man who is a slave to amusement is commonly thought to be\r destitute of Self-Control, but he really is Soft; because amusement is\r an act of relaxing, being an act of resting, and the character in\r question is one of those who exceed due bounds in respect of this.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":748},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-66","text":"Moreover of Imperfect Self-Control there are two forms, Precipitancy\r and Weakness: those who have it in the latter form though they have\r made resolutions do not abide by them by reason of passion; the others\r are led by passion because they have never formed any resolutions at\r all: while there are some who, like those who by tickling themselves\r beforehand get rid of ticklishness, having felt and seen beforehand the\r approach of temptation, and roused up themselves and their resolution,\r yield not to passion; whether the temptation be somewhat pleasant or\r somewhat painful. The Precipitate ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":749},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-67","text":"Again, the man utterly destitute of Self-Control, as was observed\r before, is not given to remorse: for it is part of his character that\r he abides by his moral choice: but the man of Imperfect Self-Control is\r almost made up of remorse: and so the case is not as we determined it\r before, but the former is incurable and the latter may be cured: for\r depravity is like chronic diseases, dropsy and consumption for\r instance, but Imperfect Self-Control is like acute disorders: the\r former being a continuous evil, the latter not so. And, in fact,\r Imperfect Self-Control and Confirmed Vice are diffe","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":750},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-68","text":"But, of the different forms of Imperfect Self-Control, those are better\r who are carried off their feet by a sudden access of temptation than\r they who have Reason but do not abide by it; these last being overcome\r by passion less in degree, and not wholly without premeditation as are\r the others: for the man of Imperfect Self-Control is like those who are\r soon intoxicated and by little wine and less than the common run of\r men.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":751},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-69","text":"Well then, that Imperfection of Self-Control is not Confirmed\r Viciousness is plain: and yet perhaps it is such in a way, because in\r one sense it is contrary to moral choice and in another the result of\r it:[18] at all events, in respect of the actions, the case is much like\r what Demodocus said of the Miletians. “The people of Miletus are not\r fools, but they do just the kind of things that fools do;” and so they\r of Imperfect Self-Control are not unjust, but they do unjust acts.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":752},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-70","text":"But to resume. Since the man of Imperfect Self-Control is of such a\r character as to follow bodily pleasures in excess and in defiance of\r Right Reason, without acting on any deliberate conviction, whereas the\r man utterly destitute of Self-Control does act upon a conviction which\r rests on his natural inclination to follow after these pleasures; the\r former may be easily persuaded to a different course, but the latter\r not: for Virtue and Vice respectively preserve and corrupt the moral\r principle; now the motive is the principle or starting point in moral\r actions, just as axioms and postula","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":753},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-71","text":"Again, there is a character liable to be taken off his feet in defiance\r of Right Reason because of passion; whom passion so far masters as to\r prevent his acting in accordance with Right Reason, but not so far as\r to make him be convinced that it is his proper line to follow after\r such pleasures without limit: this character is the man of Imperfect\r Self- Control, better than he who is utterly destitute of it, and not a\r bad man simply and without qualification: because in him the highest\r and best part, i.e. principle, is preserved: and there is another\r character opposed to him who is apt ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":754},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-72","text":"It is evident then from all this, that Self-Control is a good state and\r the Imperfection of it a bad one.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":755},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-73","text":"Next comes the question, whether a man is a man of Self-Control for\r abiding by his conclusions and moral choice be they of what kind they\r may, or only by the right one; or again, a man of Imperfect\r Self-Control for not abiding by his conclusions and moral choice be\r they of whatever kind; or, to put the case we did before, is he such\r for not abiding by false conclusions and wrong moral choice?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":756},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-74","text":"Is not this the truth, that _incidentally_ it is by conclusions and\r moral choice of any kind that the one character abides and the other\r does not, but _per se_ true conclusions and right moral choice:[19] to\r explain what is meant by incidentally, and _per se_; suppose a man\r chooses or pursues this thing for the sake of that, he is said to\r pursue and choose that _per se_, but this only incidentally. For the\r term _per se_ we use commonly the word “simply,” and so, in a way, it\r is opinion of any kind soever by which the two characters respectively\r abide or not, but he is “simply” entitled","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":757},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-75","text":"There are also people, who have a trick of abiding by their, own\r opinions, who are commonly called Positive, as they who are hard to be\r persuaded, and whose convictions are not easily changed: now these\r people bear some resemblance to the character of Self-Control, just as\r the prodigal to the liberal or the rash man to the brave, but they are\r different in many points. The man of Self-Control does not change by\r reason of passion and lust, yet when occasion so requires he will be\r easy of persuasion: but the Positive man changes not at the call of\r Reason, though many of this class take up","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":758},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-76","text":"Again, there are some who depart from their resolutions not by reason\r of any Imperfection of Self-Control; take, for instance, Neoptolemus in\r the Philoctetes of Sophocles. Here certainly pleasure was the motive of\r his departure from his resolution, but then it was one of a noble sort:\r for to be truthful was noble in his eyes and he had been persuaded by\r Ulysses to lie.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":759},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-77","text":"So it is not every one who acts from the motive of pleasure who is\r utterly destitute of Self-Control or base or of Imperfect Self-Control,\r only he who acts from the impulse of a base pleasure.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":760},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-78","text":"Moreover as there is a character who takes less pleasure than he ought\r in bodily enjoyments, and he also fails to abide by the conclusion of\r his Reason,[20] the man of Self-Control is the mean between him and the\r man of Imperfect Self-Control: that is to say, the latter fails to\r abide by them because of somewhat too much, the former because of\r somewhat too little; while the man of Self-Control abides by them, and\r never changes by reason of anything else than such conclusions.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":761},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-79","text":"Now of course since Self-Control is good both the contrary States must\r be bad, as indeed they plainly are: but because the one of them is seen\r in few persons, and but rarely in them, Self-Control comes to be viewed\r as if opposed only to the Imperfection of it, just as Perfected\r Self-Mastery is thought to be opposed only to utter want of\r Self-Control.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":762},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-80","text":"Again, as many terms are used in the way of similitude, so people have\r come to talk of the Self-Control of the man of Perfected Self-Mastery\r in the way of similitude: for the man of Self-Control and the man of\r Perfected Self-Mastery have this in common, that they do nothing\r against Right Reason on the impulse of bodily pleasures, but then the\r former has bad desires, the latter not; and the latter is so\r constituted as not even to feel pleasure contrary to his Reason, the\r former feels but does not yield to it.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":763},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-81","text":"Like again are the man of Imperfect Self-Control and he who is utterly\r destitute of it, though in reality distinct: both follow bodily\r pleasures, but the latter under a notion that it is the proper line for\r him to take, his former without any such notion.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":764},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-82","text":"And it is not possible for the same man to be at once a man of\r Practical Wisdom and of Imperfect Self-Control: because the character\r of Practical Wisdom includes, as we showed before, goodness of moral\r character. And again, it is not knowledge merely, but aptitude for\r action, which constitutes Practical Wisdom: and of this aptitude the\r man of Imperfect Self-Control is destitute. But there is no reason why\r the Clever man should not be of Imperfect Self-Control: and the reason\r why some men are occasionally thought to be men of Practical Wisdom,\r and yet of Imperfect Self-Control, is this,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":765},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-83","text":"Nor is the man of Imperfect Self-Control like the man who both has and\r calls into exercise his knowledge, but like the man who, having it, is\r overpowered by sleep or wine. Again, he acts voluntarily (because he\r knows, in a certain sense, what he does and the result of it), but he\r is not a confirmed bad man, for his moral choice is good, so he is at\r all events only half bad. Nor is he unjust, because he does not act\r with deliberate intent: for of the two chief forms of the character,\r the one is not apt to abide by his deliberate resolutions, and the\r other, the man of constitutional stre","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":766},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-84","text":"So in fact the man of Imperfect Self-Control is like a community which\r makes all proper enactments, and has admirable laws, only does not act\r on them, verifying the scoff of Anaxandrides,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":767},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-85","text":"whereas the bad man is like one which acts upon its laws, but then\r unfortunately they are bad ones.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":768},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-86","text":"Imperfection of Self-Control and Self-Control, after all, are above the\r average state of men; because he of the latter character is more true\r to his Reason, and the former less so, than is in the power of most\r men.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":769},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-87","text":"Again, of the two forms of Imperfect Self-Control that is more easily\r cured which they have who are constitutionally of strong passions, than\r that of those who form resolutions and break them; and they that are so\r through habituation than they that are so naturally; since of course\r custom is easier to change than nature, because the very resemblance of\r custom to nature is what constitutes the difficulty of changing it; as\r Evenus says,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":770},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-88","text":"“Practice, I say, my friend, doth long endure,\r And at the last is even very nature.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":771},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-89","text":"We have now said then what Self-Control is, what Imperfection of\r Self-Control, what Endurance, and what Softness, and how these states\r are mutually related.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":772},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-90","text":"To consider the subject of Pleasure and Pain falls within the province\r of the Social-Science Philosopher, since he it is who has to fix the\r Master-End which is to guide us in dominating any object absolutely\r evil or good.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":773},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-91","text":"But we may say more: an enquiry into their nature is absolutely\r necessary. First, because we maintained that Moral Virtue and Moral\r Vice are both concerned with Pains and Pleasures: next, because the\r greater part of mankind assert that Happiness must include Pleasure\r (which by the way accounts for the word they use, μακάριος; χαίρειν\r being the root of that word).","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":774},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-92","text":"Now some hold that no one Pleasure is good, either in itself or as a\r matter of result, because Good and Pleasure are not identical. Others\r that some Pleasures are good but the greater number bad. There is yet a\r third view; granting that every Pleasure is good, still the Chief Good\r cannot possibly be Pleasure.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":775},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-93","text":"In support of the first opinion (that Pleasure is utterly not-good) it\r is urged that:","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":776},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-94","text":"1. Every Pleasure is a sensible process towards a complete state; but\r no such process is akin to the end to be attained: _e.g._ no process of\r building to the completed house.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":777},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-95","text":"3. The man of Practical Wisdom aims at avoiding Pain, not at attaining\r Pleasure.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":778},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-96","text":"4. Pleasures are an impediment to thought, and the more so the more\r keenly they are felt. An obvious instance will readily occur.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":779},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-97","text":"5. Pleasure cannot be referred to any Art: and yet every good is the\r result of some Art.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":780},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-98","text":"In support of the second (that not all Pleasures are good), That there\r are some base and matter of reproach, and some even hurtful: because\r some things that are pleasant produce disease.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":781},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-99","text":"In support of the third (that Pleasure is not the Chief Good), That it\r is not an End but a process towards creating an End.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":782},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-100","text":"But that the reasons alleged do not prove it either to be not-good or\r the Chief Good is plain from the following considerations.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":783},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-101","text":"First. Good being either absolute or relative, of course the natures\r and states embodying it will be so too; therefore also the movements\r and the processes of creation. So, of those which are thought to be bad\r some will be bad absolutely, but relatively not bad, perhaps even\r choice-worthy; some not even choice-worthy relatively to any particular\r person, only at certain times or for a short time but not in themselves\r choice-worthy.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":784},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-102","text":"Others again are not even Pleasures at all though they produce that\r impression on the mind: all such I mean as imply pain and whose purpose\r is cure; those of sick people, for instance.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":785},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-103","text":"Next, since Good may be either an active working or a state, those\r [κινήσεις or γενέσεις] which tend to place us in our natural state are\r pleasant incidentally because of that tendency: but the active working\r is really in the desires excited in the remaining (sound) part of our\r state or nature: for there are Pleasures which have no connection with\r pain or desire: the acts of contemplative intellect, for instance, in\r which case there is no deficiency in the nature or state of him who\r performs the acts.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":786},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-104","text":"A proof of this is that the same pleasant thing does not produce the\r sensation of Pleasure when the natural state is being filled up or\r completed as when it is already in its normal condition: in this latter\r case what give the sensation are things pleasant _per se_, in the\r former even those things which are contrary. I mean, you find people\r taking pleasure in sharp or bitter things of which no one is naturally\r or in itself pleasant; of course not therefore the Pleasures arising\r from them, because it is obvious that as is the classification of\r pleasant things such must be that of the Pl","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":787},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-105","text":"Next, it does not follow that there must be something else better than\r any given pleasure because (as some say) the End must be better than\r the process which creates it. For it is not true that all Pleasures are\r processes or even attended by any process, but (some are) active\r workings or even Ends: in fact they result not from our coming to be\r something but from our using our powers. Again, it is not true that the\r End is, in every case, distinct from the process: it is true only in\r the case of such processes as conduce to the perfecting of the natural\r state.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":788},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-106","text":"For which reason it is wrong to say that Pleasure is “a sensible\r process of production.” For “process etc.” should be substituted\r “active working of the natural state,” for “sensible” “unimpeded.” The\r reason of its being thought to be a “process etc.” is that it is good\r in the highest sense: people confusing “active working” and “process,”\r whereas they really are distinct.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":789},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-107","text":"Next, as to the argument that there are bad Pleasures because some\r things which are pleasant are also hurtful to health, it is the same as\r saying that some healthful things are bad for “business.” In this\r sense, of course, both may be said to be bad, but then this does not\r make them out to be bad _simpliciter_: the exercise of the pure\r Intellect sometimes hurts a man’s health: but what hinders Practical\r Wisdom or any state whatever is, not the Pleasure peculiar to, but some\r Pleasure foreign to it: the Pleasures arising from the exercise of the\r pure Intellect or from learning only promo","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":790},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-108","text":"Next. “No Pleasure is the work of any Art.” What else would you expect?\r No active working is the work of any Art, only the faculty of so\r working. Still the perfumer’s Art or the cook’s are thought to belong\r to Pleasure.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":791},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-109","text":"Next. “The man of Perfected Self-Mastery avoids Pleasures.” “The man of\r Practical Wisdom aims at escaping Pain rather than at attaining\r Pleasure.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":792},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-110","text":"We have already said in what sense all Pleasures are good _per se_ and\r in what sense not all are good: it is the latter class that brutes and\r children pursue, such as are accompanied by desire and pain, that is\r the bodily Pleasures (which answer to this description) and the\r excesses of them: in short, those in respect of which the man utterly\r destitute of Self-Control is thus utterly destitute. And it is the\r absence of the pain arising from these Pleasures that the man of\r Practical Wisdom aims at. It follows that these Pleasures are what the\r man of Perfected Self-Mastery avoids: for ob","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":793},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-111","text":"Then again, it is allowed that Pain is an evil and a thing to be\r avoided partly as bad _per se_, partly as being a hindrance in some\r particular way. Now the contrary of that which is to be avoided, _quâ_\r it is to be avoided, _i.e._ evil, is good. Pleasure then must be _a_\r good.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":794},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-112","text":"The attempted answer of Speusippus, “that Pleasure may be opposed and\r yet not contrary to Pain, just as the greater portion of any magnitude\r is contrary to the less but only opposed to the exact half,” will not\r hold: for he cannot say that Pleasure is identical with evil of any\r kind.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":795},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-113","text":"Again. Granting that some Pleasures are low, there is no reason why\r some particular Pleasure may not be very good, just as some particular\r Science may be although there are some which are low.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":796},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-114","text":"Perhaps it even follows, since each state may have active working\r unimpeded, whether the active workings of all be Happiness or that of\r some one of them, that this active working, if it be unimpeded, must be\r choice-worthy: now Pleasure is exactly this. So that the Chief Good may\r be Pleasure of some kind, though most Pleasures be (let us assume) low\r _per se_.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":797},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-115","text":"And for this reason all men think the happy life is pleasant, and\r interweave Pleasure with Happiness. Reasonably enough: because\r Happiness is perfect, but no impeded active working is perfect; and\r therefore the happy man needs as an addition the goods of the body and\r the goods external and fortune that in these points he may not be\r fettered. As for those who say that he who is being tortured on the\r wheel, or falls into great misfortunes is happy provided only he be\r good, they talk nonsense, whether they mean to do so or not. On the\r other hand, because fortune is needed as an addition, ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":798},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-116","text":"The fact that all animals, brute and human alike, pursue Pleasure, is\r some presumption of its being in a sense the Chief Good;","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":799},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-117","text":"(“There must be something in what most folks say,”) only as one and the\r same nature or state neither is nor is thought to be the best, so\r neither do all pursue the same Pleasure, Pleasure nevertheless all do.\r Nay further, what they pursue is, perhaps, not what they think nor what\r they would say they pursue, but really one and the same: for in all\r there is some instinct above themselves. But the bodily Pleasures have\r received the name exclusively, because theirs is the most frequent form\r and that which is universally partaken of; and so, because to many\r these alone are known they believ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":800},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-118","text":"It is plain too that, unless Pleasure and its active working be good,\r it will not be true that the happy man’s life embodies Pleasure: for\r why will he want it on the supposition that it is not good and that he\r can live even with Pain? because, assuming that Pleasure is not good,\r then Pain is neither evil nor good, and so why should he avoid it?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":801},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-119","text":"Besides, the life of the good man is not more pleasurable than any\r other unless it be granted that his active workings are so too.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":802},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-120","text":"Some enquiry into the bodily Pleasures is also necessary for those who\r say that some Pleasures, to be sure, are highly choice-worthy (the good\r ones to wit), but not the bodily Pleasures; that is, those which are\r the object-matter of the man utterly destitute of Self-Control.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":803},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-121","text":"If so, we ask, why are the contrary Pains bad? they cannot be (on their\r assumption) because the contrary of bad is good.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":804},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-122","text":"May we not say that the necessary bodily Pleasures are good in the\r sense in which that which is not-bad is good? or that they are good\r only up to a certain point? because such states or movements as cannot\r have too much of the better cannot have too much of Pleasure, but those\r which can of the former can also of the latter. Now the bodily\r Pleasures do admit of excess: in fact the low bad man is such because\r he pursues the excess of them instead of those which are necessary\r (meat, drink, and the objects of other animal appetites do give\r pleasure to all, but not in right manner or degree","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":805},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-123","text":"It is not enough however merely to state the truth, we should also show\r how the false view arises; because this strengthens conviction. I mean,\r when we have given a probable reason why that impresses people as true\r which really is not true, it gives them a stronger conviction of the\r truth. And so we must now explain why the bodily Pleasures appear to\r people to be more choice-worthy than any others.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":806},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-124","text":"The first obvious reason is, that bodily Pleasure drives out Pain; and\r because Pain is felt in excess men pursue Pleasure in excess, _i.e._\r generally bodily Pleasure, under the notion of its being a remedy for\r that Pain. These remedies, moreover, come to be violent ones; which is\r the very reason they are pursued, since the impression they produce on\r the mind is owing to their being looked at side by side with their\r contrary.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":807},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-125","text":"And, as has been said before, there are the two following reasons why\r bodily Pleasure is thought to be not-good.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":808},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-126","text":"1. Some Pleasures of this class are actings of a low nature, whether\r congenital as in brutes, or acquired by custom as in low bad men.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":809},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-127","text":"2. Others are in the nature of cures, cures that is of some deficiency;\r now of course it is better to have [the healthy state] originally than\r that it should accrue afterwards.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":810},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-128","text":"(But some Pleasures result when natural states are being perfected:\r these therefore are good as a matter of result.)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":811},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-129","text":"Again, the very fact of their being violent causes them to be pursued\r by such as can relish no others: such men in fact create violent\r thirsts for themselves (if harmless ones then we find no fault, if\r harmful then it is bad and low) because they have no other things to\r take pleasure in, and the neutral state is distasteful to some people\r constitutionally; for toil of some kind is inseparable from life, as\r physiologists testify, telling us that the acts of seeing or hearing\r are painful, only that we are used to the pain and do not find it out.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":812},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-130","text":"Similarly in youth the constant growth produces a state much like that\r of vinous intoxication, and youth is pleasant. Again, men of the\r melancholic temperament constantly need some remedial process (because\r the body, from its temperament, is constantly being worried), and they\r are in a chronic state of violent desire. But Pleasure drives out Pain;\r not only such Pleasure as is directly contrary to Pain but even any\r Pleasure provided it be strong: and this is how men come to be utterly\r destitute of Self-Mastery, _i.e._ low and bad.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":813},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-131","text":"But those Pleasures which are unconnected with Pains do not admit of\r excess: _i.e._ such as belong to objects which are naturally pleasant\r and not merely as a matter of result: by the latter class I mean such\r as are remedial, and the reason why these are thought to be pleasant is\r that the cure results from the action in some way of that part of the\r constitution which remains sound. By “pleasant naturally” I mean such\r as put into action a nature which is pleasant.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":814},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-132","text":"The reason why no one and the same thing is invariably pleasant is that\r our nature is, not simple, but complex, involving something different\r from itself (so far as we are corruptible beings). Suppose then that\r one part of this nature be doing something, this something is, to the\r other part, unnatural: but, if there be an equilibrium of the two\r natures, then whatever is being done is indifferent. It is obvious that\r if there be any whose nature is simple and not complex, to such a being\r the same course of acting will always be the most pleasurable.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":815},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-133","text":"For this reason it is that the Divinity feels Pleasure which is always\r one, _i.e._ simple: not motion merely but also motionlessness acts, and\r Pleasure resides rather in the absence than in the presence of motion.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":816},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-134","text":"The reason why the Poet’s dictum “change is of all things most\r pleasant” is true, is “a baseness in our blood;” for as the bad man is\r easily changeable, bad must be also the nature that craves change,\r _i.e._ it is neither simple nor good.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":817},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-8-135","text":"We have now said our say about Self-Control and its opposite; and about\r Pleasure and Pain. What each is, and how the one set is good the other\r bad. We have yet to speak of Friendship.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":818},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-1","text":"Next would seem properly to follow a dissertation on Friendship:\r because, in the first place, it is either itself a virtue or connected\r with virtue; and next it is a thing most necessary for life, since no\r one would choose to live without friends though he should have all the\r other good things in the world: and, in fact, men who are rich or\r possessed of authority and influence are thought to have special need\r of friends: for where is the use of such prosperity if there be taken\r away the doing of kindnesses of which friends are the most usual and\r most commendable objects? Or how can it ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":819},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-2","text":"Furthermore, Friendship helps the young to keep from error: the old, in\r respect of attention and such deficiencies in action as their weakness\r makes them liable to; and those who are in their prime, in respect of\r noble deeds (“They _two_ together going,” Homer says, you may\r remember), because they are thus more able to devise plans and carry\r them out.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":820},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-3","text":"Again, it seems to be implanted in us by Nature: as, for instance, in\r the parent towards the offspring and the offspring towards the parent\r (not merely in the human species, but likewise in birds and most\r animals), and in those of the same tribe towards one another, and\r specially in men of the same nation; for which reason we commend those\r men who love their fellows: and one may see in the course of travel how\r close of kin and how friendly man is to man.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":821},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-4","text":"Furthermore, Friendship seems to be the bond of Social Communities, and\r legislators seem to be more anxious to secure it than Justice even. I\r mean, Unanimity is somewhat like to Friendship, and this they certainly\r aim at and specially drive out faction as being inimical.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":822},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-5","text":"Again, where people are in Friendship Justice is not required;[1] but,\r on the other hand, though they are just they need Friendship in\r addition, and that principle which is most truly just is thought to\r partake of the nature of Friendship.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":823},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-6","text":"Lastly, not only is it a thing necessary but honourable likewise: since\r we praise those who are fond of friends, and the having numerous\r friends is thought a matter of credit to a man; some go so far as to\r hold, that “good man” and “friend” are terms synonymous.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":824},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-7","text":"Yet the disputed points respecting it are not few: some men lay down\r that it is a kind of resemblance, and that men who are like one another\r are friends: whence come the common sayings, “Like will to like,”\r “Birds of a feather,” and so on. Others, on the contrary, say, that all\r such come under the maxim, “Two of a trade never agree.”[2]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":825},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-8","text":"Again, some men push their enquiries on these points higher and reason\r physically: as Euripides, who says,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":826},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-9","text":"“The earth by drought consumed doth love the rain,\r And the great heaven, overcharged with rain,\r Doth love to fall in showers upon the earth.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":827},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-10","text":"Heraclitus, again, maintains, that “contrariety is expedient, and that\r the best agreement arises from things differing, and that all things\r come into being in the way of the principle of antagonism.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":828},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-11","text":"Empedocles, among others, in direct opposition to these, affirms, that\r “like aims at like.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":829},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-12","text":"These physical questions we will take leave to omit, inasmuch as they\r are foreign to the present enquiry; and we will examine such as are\r proper to man and concern moral characters and feelings: as, for\r instance, “Does Friendship arise among all without distinction, or is\r it impossible for bad men to be friends?” and, “Is there but one\r species of Friendship, or several?” for they who ground the opinion\r that there is but one on the fact that Friendship admits of degrees\r hold that upon insufficient proof; because things which are different\r in species admit likewise of degrees (on this po","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":830},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-13","text":"Our view will soon be cleared on these points when we have ascertained\r what is properly the object-matter of Friendship: for it is thought\r that not everything indiscriminately, but some peculiar matter alone,\r is the object of this affection; that is to say, what is good, or\r pleasurable, or useful. Now it would seem that that is useful through\r which accrues any good or pleasure, and so the objects of Friendship,\r as absolute Ends, are the good and the pleasurable.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":831},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-14","text":"A question here arises; whether it is good absolutely or that which is\r good to the individuals, for which men feel Friendship (these two being\r sometimes distinct): and similarly in respect of the pleasurable. It\r seems then that each individual feels it towards that which is good to\r himself, and that abstractedly it is the real good which is the object\r of Friendship, and to each individual that which is good to each. It\r comes then to this; that each individual feels Friendship not for what\r _is_ but for that which _conveys to his mind the impression of being_\r good to himself. But this wi","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":832},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-15","text":"There are then three causes from which men feel Friendship: but the\r term is not applied to the case of fondness for things inanimate\r because there is no requital of the affection nor desire for the good\r of those objects: it certainly savours of the ridiculous to say that a\r man fond of wine wishes well to it: the only sense in which it is true\r being that he wishes it to be kept safe and sound for his own use and\r benefit.[3] But to the friend they say one should wish all good for his\r sake. And when men do thus wish good to another (he not reciprocating\r the feeling), people call them Kind","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":833},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-16","text":"Well, these are plainly Kindly-disposed towards one another: but how\r can one call them friends while their mutual feelings are unknown to\r one another? to complete the idea of Friendship, then, it is requisite\r that they have kindly feelings towards one another, and wish one\r another good from one of the aforementioned causes, and that these\r kindly feelings should be mutually known.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":834},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-17","text":"As the motives to Friendship differ in kind so do the respective\r feelings and Friendships. The species then of Friendship are three, in\r number equal to the objects of it, since in the line of each there may\r be “mutual affection mutually known.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":835},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-18","text":"Now they who have Friendship for one another desire one another’s good\r according to the motive of their Friendship; accordingly they whose\r motive is utility have no Friendship for one another really, but only\r in so far as some good arises to them from one another.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":836},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-19","text":"And they whose motive is pleasure are in like case: I mean, they have\r Friendship for men of easy pleasantry, not because they are of a given\r character but because they are pleasant to themselves. So then they\r whose motive to Friendship is utility love their friends for what is\r good to themselves; they whose motive is pleasure do so for what is\r pleasurable to themselves; that is to say, not in so far as the friend\r beloved _is_ but in so far as he is useful or pleasurable. These\r Friendships then are a matter of result: since the object is not\r beloved in that he is the man he is but in th","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":837},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-20","text":"Such Friendships are of course very liable to dissolution if the\r parties do not continue alike: I mean, that the others cease to have\r any Friendship for them when they are no longer pleasurable or useful.\r Now it is the nature of utility not to be permanent but constantly\r varying: so, of course, when the motive which made them friends is\r vanished, the Friendship likewise dissolves; since it existed only\r relatively to those circumstances.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":838},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-21","text":"Friendship of this kind is thought to exist principally among the old\r (because men at that time of life pursue not what is pleasurable but\r what is profitable); and in such, of men in their prime and of the\r young, as are given to the pursuit of profit. They that are such have\r no intimate intercourse with one another; for sometimes they are not\r even pleasurable to one another; nor, in fact, do they desire such\r intercourse unless their friends are profitable to them, because they\r are pleasurable only in so far as they have hopes of advantage. With\r these Friendships is commonly ranked that","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":839},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-22","text":"But the Friendship of the young is thought to be based on the motive of\r pleasure: because they live at the beck and call of passion and\r generally pursue what is pleasurable to themselves and the object of\r the present moment: and as their age changes so likewise do their\r pleasures.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":840},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-23","text":"This is the reason why they form and dissolve Friendships rapidly:\r since the Friendship changes with the pleasurable object and such\r pleasure changes quickly.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":841},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-24","text":"The young are also much given up to Love; this passion being, in great\r measure, a matter of impulse and based on pleasure: for which cause\r they conceive Friendships and quickly drop them, changing often in the\r same day: but these wish for society and intimate intercourse with\r their friends, since they thus attain the object of their Friendship.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":842},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-25","text":"That then is perfect Friendship which subsists between those who are\r good and whose similarity consists in their goodness: for these men\r wish one another’s good in similar ways; in so far as they are good\r (and good they are in themselves); and those are specially friends who\r wish good to their friends for their sakes, because they feel thus\r towards them on their own account and not as a mere matter of result;\r so the Friendship between these men continues to subsist so long as\r they are good; and goodness, we know, has in it a principle of\r permanence.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":843},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-26","text":"Moreover, each party is good abstractedly and also relatively to his\r friend, for all good men are not only abstractedly good but also useful\r to one another. Such friends are also mutually pleasurable because all\r good men are so abstractedly, and also relatively to one another,\r inasmuch as to each individual those actions are pleasurable which\r correspond to his nature, and all such as are like them. Now when men\r are good these will be always the same, or at least similar.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":844},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-27","text":"Friendship then under these circumstances is permanent, as we should\r reasonably expect, since it combines in itself all the requisite\r qualifications of friends. I mean, that Friendship of whatever kind is\r based upon good or pleasure (either abstractedly or relatively to the\r person entertaining the sentiment of Friendship), and results from a\r similarity of some sort; and to this kind belong all the aforementioned\r requisites in the parties themselves, because in this the parties are\r similar, and so on:[4] moreover, in it there is the abstractedly good\r and the abstractedly pleasant, and a","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":845},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-28","text":"Rare it is probable Friendships of this kind will be, because men of\r this kind are rare. Besides, all requisite qualifications being\r presupposed, there is further required time and intimacy: for, as the\r proverb says, men cannot know one another “till they have eaten the\r requisite quantity of salt together;” nor can they in fact admit one\r another to intimacy, much less be friends, till each has appeared to\r the other and been proved to be a fit object of Friendship. They who\r speedily commence an interchange of friendly actions may be said to\r wish to be friends, but they are not so unless","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":846},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-29","text":"Well, this Friendship is perfect both in respect of the time and in all\r other points; and exactly the same and similar results accrue to each\r party from the other; which ought to be the case between friends.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":847},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-30","text":"The friendship based upon the pleasurable is, so to say, a copy of\r this, since the good are sources of pleasure to one another: and that\r based on utility likewise, the good being also useful to one another.\r Between men thus connected Friendships are most permanent when the same\r result accrues to both from one another, pleasure, for instance; and\r not merely so but from the same source, as in the case of two men of\r easy pleasantry; and not as it is in that of a lover and the object of\r his affection, these not deriving their pleasure from the same causes,\r but the former from seeing the la","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":848},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-31","text":"Where people do not interchange pleasure but profit in matters of Love,\r the Friendship is both less intense in degree and also less permanent:\r in fact, they who are friends because of advantage commonly part when\r the advantage ceases; for, in reality, they never were friends of one\r another but of the advantage.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":849},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-32","text":"So then it appears that from motives of pleasure or profit bad men may\r be friends to one another, or good men to bad men or men of neutral\r character to one of any character whatever: but disinterestedly, for\r the sake of one another, plainly the good alone can be friends; because\r bad men have no pleasure even in themselves unless in so far as some\r advantage arises.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":850},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-33","text":"And further, the Friendship of the good is alone superior to calumny;\r it not being easy for men to believe a third person respecting one whom\r they have long tried and proved: there is between good men mutual\r confidence, and the feeling that one’s friend would never have done one\r wrong, and all other such things as are expected in Friendship really\r worthy the name; but in the other kinds there is nothing to prevent all\r such suspicions.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":851},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-34","text":"I call them Friendships, because since men commonly give the name of\r friends to those who are connected from motives of profit (which is\r justified by political language, for alliances between states are\r thought to be contracted with a view to advantage), and to those who\r are attached to one another by the motive of pleasure (as children\r are), we may perhaps also be allowed to call such persons friends, and\r say there are several species of Friendship; primarily and specially\r that of the good, in that they are good, and the rest only in the way\r of resemblance: I mean, people connected ot","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":852},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-35","text":"These secondary Friendships, however, do not combine very well; that is\r to say, the same persons do not become friends by reason of advantage\r and by reason of the pleasurable, for these matters of result are not\r often combined. And Friendship having been divided into these kinds,\r bad men will be friends by reason of pleasure or profit, this being\r their point of resemblance; while the good are friends for one\r another’s sake, that is, in so far as they are good.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":853},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-36","text":"These last may be termed abstractedly and simply friends, the former as\r a matter of result and termed friends from their resemblance to these\r last.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":854},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-37","text":"Further; just as in respect of the different virtues some men are\r termed good in respect of a certain inward state, others in respect of\r acts of working, so is it in respect of Friendship: I mean, they who\r live together take pleasure in, and impart good to, one another: but\r they who are asleep or are locally separated do not perform acts, but\r only are in such a state as to act in a friendly way if they acted at\r all: distance has in itself no direct effect upon Friendship, but only\r prevents the acting it out: yet, if the absence be protracted, it is\r thought to cause a forgetfulness even","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":855},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-38","text":"Accordingly, neither the old nor the morose appear to be calculated for\r Friendship, because the pleasurableness in them is small, and no one\r can spend his days in company with that which is positively painful or\r even not pleasurable; since to avoid the painful and aim at the\r pleasurable is one of the most obvious tendencies of human nature. They\r who get on with one another very fairly, but are not in habits of\r intimacy, are rather like people having kindly feelings towards one\r another than friends; nothing being so characteristic of friends as the\r living with one another, because the n","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":856},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-39","text":"The connection then subsisting between the good is Friendship _par\r excellence_, as has already been frequently said: since that which is\r abstractedly good or pleasant is thought to be an object of Friendship\r and choice-worthy, and to each individual whatever is such to him; and\r the good man to the good man for both these reasons.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":857},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-40","text":"(Now the entertaining the sentiment is like a feeling, but Friendship\r itself like a state: because the former may have for its object even\r things inanimate, but requital of Friendship is attended with moral\r choice which proceeds from a moral state: and again, men wish good to\r the objects of their Friendship for their sakes, not in the way of a\r mere feeling but of moral state.)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":858},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-41","text":"And the good, in loving their friend, love their own good (inasmuch as\r the good man, when brought into that relation, becomes a good to him\r with whom he is so connected), so that either party loves his own good,\r and repays his friend equally both in wishing well and in the\r pleasurable: for equality is said to be a tie of Friendship. Well,\r these points belong most to the Friendship between good men.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":859},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-42","text":"But between morose or elderly men Friendship is less apt to arise,\r because they are somewhat awkward-tempered, and take less pleasure in\r intercourse and society; these being thought to be specially friendly\r and productive of Friendship: and so young men become friends quickly,\r old men not so (because people do not become friends with any, unless\r they take pleasure in them); and in like manner neither do the morose.\r Yet men of these classes entertain kindly feelings towards one another:\r they wish good to one another and render mutual assistance in respect\r of their needs, but they are no","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":860},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-43","text":"To be a friend to many people, in the way of the perfect Friendship, is\r not possible; just as you cannot be in love with many at once: it is,\r so to speak, a state of excess which naturally has but one object; and\r besides, it is not an easy thing for one man to be very much pleased\r with many people at the same time, nor perhaps to find many really\r good. Again, a man needs experience, and to be in habits of close\r intimacy, which is very difficult.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":861},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-44","text":"But it _is_ possible to please many on the score of advantage and\r pleasure: because there are many men of the kind, and the services may\r be rendered in a very short time.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":862},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-45","text":"Of the two imperfect kinds that which most resembles the perfect is the\r Friendship based upon pleasure, in which the same results accrue from\r both and they take pleasure in one another or in the same objects; such\r as are the Friendships of the young, because a generous spirit is most\r found in these. The Friendship because of advantage is the connecting\r link of shopkeepers.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":863},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-46","text":"Then again, the very happy have no need of persons who are profitable,\r but of pleasant ones they have because they wish to have people to live\r intimately with; and what is painful they bear for a short time indeed,\r but continuously no one could support it, nay, not even the Chief Good\r itself, if it were painful to him individually: and so they look out\r for pleasant friends: perhaps they ought to require such to be good\r also; and good moreover to themselves individually, because then they\r will have all the proper requisites of Friendship.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":864},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-47","text":"Men in power are often seen to make use of several distinct friends:\r for some are useful to them and others pleasurable, but the two are not\r often united: because they do not, in fact, seek such as shall combine\r pleasantness and goodness, nor such as shall be useful for honourable\r purposes: but with a view to attain what is pleasant they look out for\r men of easy-pleasantry; and again, for men who are clever at executing\r any business put into their hands: and these qualifications are not\r commonly found united in the same man.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":865},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-48","text":"It has been already stated that the good man unites the qualities of\r pleasantness and usefulness: but then such a one will not be a friend\r to a superior unless he be also his superior in goodness: for if this\r be not the case, he cannot, being surpassed in one point, make things\r equal by a proportionate degree of Friendship.[5] And characters who\r unite superiority of station and goodness are not common.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":866},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-49","text":"Now all the kinds of Friendship which have been already mentioned exist\r in a state of equality, inasmuch as either the same results accrue to\r both and they wish the same things to one another, or else they barter\r one thing against another; pleasure, for instance, against profit: it\r has been said already that Friendships of this latter kind are less\r intense in degree and less permanent.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":867},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-50","text":"And it is their resemblance or dissimilarity to the same thing which\r makes them to be thought to be and not to be Friendships: they show\r like Friendships in right of their likeness to that which is based on\r virtue (the one kind having the pleasurable, the other the profitable,\r both of which belong also to the other); and again, they do not show\r like Friendships by reason of their unlikeness to that true kind; which\r unlikeness consists herein, that while that is above calumny and so\r permanent these quickly change and differ in many other points.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":868},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-51","text":"But there is another form of Friendship, that, namely, in which the one\r party is superior to the other; as between father and son, elder and\r younger, husband and wife, ruler and ruled. These also differ one from\r another: I mean, the Friendship between parents and children is not the\r same as between ruler and the ruled, nor has the father the same\r towards the son as the son towards the father, nor the husband towards\r the wife as she towards him; because the work, and therefore the\r excellence, of each of these is different, and different therefore are\r the causes of their feeling Friendsh","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":869},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-52","text":"And the same results do not accrue to each from the other, nor in fact\r ought they to be looked for: but, when children render to their parents\r what they ought to the authors of their being, and parents to their\r sons what they ought to their offspring, the Friendship between such\r parties will be permanent and equitable.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":870},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-53","text":"Further; the feeling of Friendship should be in a due proportion in all\r Friendships which are between superior and inferior; I mean, the better\r man, or the more profitable, and so forth, should be the object of a\r stronger feeling than he himself entertains, because when the feeling\r of Friendship comes to be after a certain rate then equality in a\r certain sense is produced, which is thought to be a requisite in\r Friendship.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":871},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-54","text":"(It must be remembered, however, that the equal is not in the same case\r as regards Justice and Friendship: for in strict Justice the exactly\r proportioned equal ranks first, and the actual numerically equal ranks\r second, while in Friendship this is exactly reversed.)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":872},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-55","text":"And that equality is thus requisite is plainly shown by the occurrence\r of a great difference of goodness or badness, or prosperity, or\r something else: for in this case, people are not any longer friends,\r nay they do not even feel that they ought to be. The clearest\r illustration is perhaps the case of the gods, because they are most\r superior in all good things. It is obvious too, in the case of kings,\r for they who are greatly their inferiors do not feel entitled to be\r friends to them; nor do people very insignificant to be friends to\r those of very high excellence or wisdom. Of course, i","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":873},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-56","text":"This has given room for a doubt, whether friends do really wish to\r their friends the very highest goods, as that they may be gods:\r because, in case the wish were accomplished, they would no longer have\r them for friends, nor in fact would they have the good things they had,\r because friends are good things. If then it has been rightly said that\r a friend wishes to his friend good things for that friend’s sake, it\r must be understood that he is to remain such as he now is: that is to\r say, he will wish the greatest good to him of which as man he is\r capable: yet perhaps not all, because each ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":874},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-57","text":"It is thought that desire for honour makes the mass of men wish rather\r to be the objects of the feeling of Friendship than to entertain it\r themselves (and for this reason they are fond of flatterers, a\r flatterer being a friend inferior or at least pretending to be such and\r rather to entertain towards another the feeling of Friendship than to\r be himself the object of it), since the former is thought to be nearly\r the same as being honoured, which the mass of men desire. And yet men\r seem to choose honour, not for its own sake, but incidentally:[6] I\r mean, the common run of men delight to ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":875},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-58","text":"Since then Friendship stands rather in the entertaining, than in being\r the object of, the sentiment, and they are praised who are fond of\r their friends, it seems that entertaining the sentiment is the\r Excellence of friends; and so, in whomsoever this exists in due\r proportion these are stable friends and their Friendship is permanent.\r And in this way may they who are unequal best be friends, because they\r may thus be made equal.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":876},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-59","text":"Equality, then, and similarity are a tie to Friendship, and specially\r the similarity of goodness, because good men, being stable in\r themselves, are also stable as regards others, and neither ask\r degrading services nor render them, but, so to say, rather prevent\r them: for it is the part of the good neither to do wrong themselves nor\r to allow their friends in so doing.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":877},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-60","text":"The bad, on the contrary, have no principle of stability: in fact, they\r do not even continue like themselves: only they come to be friends for\r a short time from taking delight in one another’s wickedness. Those\r connected by motives of profit, or pleasure, hold together somewhat\r longer: so long, that is to say, as they can give pleasure or profit\r mutually.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":878},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-61","text":"The Friendship based on motives of profit is thought to be most of all\r formed out of contrary elements: the poor man, for instance, is thus a\r friend of the rich, and the ignorant of the man of information; that is\r to say, a man desiring that of which he is, as it happens, in want,\r gives something else in exchange for it. To this same class we may\r refer the lover and beloved, the beautiful and the ill-favoured. For\r this reason lovers sometimes show in a ridiculous light by claiming to\r be the objects of as intense a feeling as they themselves entertain: of\r course if they are equally fit ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":879},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-62","text":"Perhaps, moreover, the contrary does not aim at its contrary for its\r own sake but incidentally: the mean is really what is grasped at; it\r being good for the dry, for instance, not to become wet but to attain\r the mean, and so of the hot, etc.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":880},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-63","text":"However, let us drop these questions, because they are in fact somewhat\r foreign to our purpose.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":881},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-64","text":"It seems too, as was stated at the commencement, that Friendship and\r Justice have the same object-matter, and subsist between the same\r persons: I mean that in every Communion there is thought to be some\r principle of Justice and also some Friendship: men address as friends,\r for instance, those who are their comrades by sea, or in war, and in\r like manner also those who are brought into Communion with them in\r other ways: and the Friendship, because also the Justice, is\r co-extensive with the Communion, This justifies the common proverb,\r “the goods of friends are common,” since Friendship r","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":882},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-65","text":"Now brothers and intimate companions have all in common, but other\r people have their property separate, and some have more in common and\r others less, because the Friendships likewise differ in degree. So too\r do the various principles of Justice involved, not being the same\r between parents and children as between brothers, nor between\r companions as between fellow-citizens merely, and so on of all the\r other conceivable Friendships. Different also are the principles of\r Injustice as regards these different grades, and the acts become\r intensified by being done to friends; for instance, it i","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":883},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-66","text":"All cases of Communion are parts, so to say, of the great Social one,\r since in them men associate with a view to some advantage and to\r procure some of those things which are needful for life; and the great\r Social Communion is thought originally to have been associated and to\r continue for the sake of some advantage: this being the point at which\r legislators aim, affirming that to be just which is generally\r expedient.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":884},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-67","text":"All the other cases of Communion aim at advantage in particular points;\r the crew of a vessel at that which is to result from the voyage which\r is undertaken with a view to making money, or some such object;\r comrades in war at that which is to result from the war, grasping\r either at wealth or victory, or it may be a political position; and\r those of the same tribe, or Demus, in like manner.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":885},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-68","text":"Some of them are thought to be formed for pleasure’s sake, those, for\r instance, of bacchanals or club-fellows, which are with a view to\r Sacrifice or merely company. But all these seem to be ranged under the\r great Social one, inasmuch as the aim of this is, not merely the\r expediency of the moment but, for life and at all times; with a view to\r which the members of it institute sacrifices and their attendant\r assemblies, to render honour to the gods and procure for themselves\r respite from toil combined with pleasure. For it appears that\r sacrifices and religious assemblies in old times were","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":886},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-69","text":"So then it appears that all the instances of Communion are parts of the\r great Social one: and corresponding Friendships will follow upon such\r Communions.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":887},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-70","text":"Of Political Constitutions there are three kinds; and equal in number\r are the deflections from them, being, so to say, corruptions of them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":888},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-71","text":"The former are Kingship, Aristocracy, and that which recognises the\r principle of wealth, which it seems appropriate to call Timocracy (I\r give to it the name of a political constitution because people commonly\r do so). Of these the best is Monarchy, and Timocracy the worst.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":889},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-72","text":"From Monarchy the deflection is Despotism; both being Monarchies but\r widely differing from each other; for the Despot looks to his own\r advantage, but the King to that of his subjects: for he is in fact no\r King who is not thoroughly independent and superior to the rest in all\r good things, and he that is this has no further wants: he will not then\r have to look to his own advantage but to that of his subjects, for he\r that is not in such a position is a mere King elected by lot for the\r nonce.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":890},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-73","text":"But Despotism is on a contrary footing to this Kingship, because the\r Despot pursues his own good: and in the case of this its inferiority is\r most evident, and what is worse is contrary to what is best. The\r Transition to Despotism is made from Kingship, Despotism being a\r corrupt form of Monarchy, that is to say, the bad King comes to be a\r Despot.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":891},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-74","text":"From Aristocracy to Oligarchy the transition is made by the fault of\r the Rulers in distributing the public property contrary to right\r proportion; and giving either all that is good, or the greatest share,\r to themselves; and the offices to the same persons always, making\r wealth their idol; thus a few bear rule and they bad men in the place\r of the best.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":892},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-75","text":"From Timocracy the transition is to Democracy, they being contiguous:\r for it is the nature of Timocracy to be in the hands of a multitude,\r and all in the same grade of property are equal. Democracy is the least\r vicious of all, since herein the form of the constitution undergoes\r least change.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":893},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-76","text":"Well, these are generally the changes to which the various\r Constitutions are liable, being the least in degree and the easiest to\r make.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":894},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-77","text":"Likenesses, and, as it were, models of them, one may find even in\r Domestic life: for instance, the Communion between a Father and his\r Sons presents the figure of Kingship, because the children are the\r Father’s care: and hence Homer names Jupiter Father because Kingship is\r intended to be a paternal rule. Among the Persians, however, the\r Father’s rule is Despotic, for they treat their Sons as slaves. (The\r relation of Master to Slaves is of the nature of Despotism because the\r point regarded herein is the Master’s interest): this now strikes me to\r be as it ought, but the Persian custom to ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":895},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-78","text":"Between Husband and Wife the relation takes the form of Aristocracy,\r because he rules by right and in such points only as the Husband\r should, and gives to the Wife all that befits her to have. Where the\r Husband lords it in everything he changes the relation into an\r Oligarchy; because he does it contrary to right and not as being the\r better of the two. In some instances the Wives take the reins of\r government, being heiresses: here the rule is carried on not in right\r of goodness but by reason of wealth and power, as it is in Oligarchies.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":896},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-79","text":"Timocracy finds its type in the relation of Brothers: they being equal\r except as to such differences as age introduces: for which reason, if\r they are very different in age, the Friendship comes to be no longer a\r fraternal one: while Democracy is represented specially by families\r which have no head (all being there equal), or in which the proper head\r is weak and so every member does that which is right in his own eyes.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":897},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-80","text":"Attendant then on each form of Political Constitution there plainly is\r Friendship exactly co-extensive with the principle of Justice; that\r between a King and his Subjects being in the relation of a superiority\r of benefit, inasmuch as he benefits his subjects; it being assumed that\r he is a good king and takes care of their welfare as a shepherd tends\r his flock; whence Homer (to quote him again) calls Agamemnon, “shepherd\r of the people.” And of this same kind is the Paternal Friendship, only\r that it exceeds the former in the greatness of the benefits done;\r because the father is the autho","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":898},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-81","text":"These friendships are also between superiors and inferiors, for which\r reason parents are not merely loved but also honoured. The principle of\r Justice also between these parties is not exactly the same but\r according to proportiton, because so also is the Friendship.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":899},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-82","text":"Now between Husband and Wife there is the same Friendship as in\r Aristocracy: for the relation is determined by relative excellence, and\r the better person has the greater good and each has what befits: so too\r also is the principle of Justice between them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":900},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-83","text":"The Fraternal Friendship is like that of Companions, because brothers\r are equal and much of an age, and such persons have generally like\r feelings and like dispositions. Like to this also is the Friendship of\r a Timocracy, because the citizens are intended to be equal and\r equitable: rule, therefore, passes from hand to hand, and is\r distributed on equal terms: so too is the Friendship accordingly.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":901},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-84","text":"In the deflections from the constitutional forms, just as the principle\r of Justice is but small so is the Friendship also: and least of all in\r the most perverted form: in Despotism there is little or no Friendship.\r For generally wherever the ruler and the ruled have nothing in common\r there is no Friendship because there is no Justice; but the case is as\r between an artisan and his tool, or between soul and body, and master\r and slave; all these are benefited by those who use them, but towards\r things inanimate there is neither Friendship nor Justice: nor even\r towards a horse or an ox, or ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":902},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-85","text":"Now of course all Friendship is based upon Communion, as has been\r already stated: but one would be inclined to separate off from the rest\r the Friendship of Kindred, and that of Companions: whereas those of men\r of the same city, or tribe, or crew, and all such, are more peculiarly,\r it would seem, based upon Communion, inasmuch as they plainly exist in\r right of some agreement expressed or implied: among these one may rank\r also the Friendship of Hospitality,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":903},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-86","text":"The Friendship of Kindred is likewise of many kinds, and appears in all\r its varieties to depend on the Parental: parents, I mean, love their\r children as being a part of themselves, children love their parents as\r being themselves somewhat derived from them. But parents know their\r offspring more than these know that they are from the parents, and the\r source is more closely bound to that which is produced than that which\r is produced is to that which formed it: of course, whatever is derived\r from one’s self is proper to that from which it is so derived (as, for\r instance, a tooth or a hair,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":904},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-87","text":"Then again the greater length of time comes in: the parents love their\r offspring from the first moment of their being, but their offspring\r them only after a lapse of time when they have attained intelligence or\r instinct. These considerations serve also to show why mothers have\r greater strength of affection than fathers.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":905},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-88","text":"Now parents love their children as themselves (since what is derived\r from themselves becomes a kind of other Self by the fact of\r separation), but children their parents as being sprung from them. And\r brothers love one another from being sprung from the same; that is,\r their sameness with the common stock creates a sameness with one\r another;[7] whence come the phrases, “same blood,” “root,” and so on.\r In fact they are the same, in a sense, even in the separate distinct\r individuals.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":906},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-89","text":"Then again the being brought up together, and the nearness of age, are\r a great help towards Friendship, for a man likes one of his own age and\r persons who are used to one another are companions, which accounts for\r the resemblance between the Friendship of Brothers and that of\r Companions.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":907},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-90","text":"And cousins and all other relatives derive their bond of union from\r these, that is to say, from their community of origin: and the strength\r of this bond varies according to their respective distances from the\r common ancestor.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":908},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-91","text":"Further: the Friendship felt by children towards parents, and by men\r towards the gods, is as towards something good and above them; because\r these have conferred the greatest possible benefits, in that they are\r the causes of their being and being nourished, and of their having been\r educated after they were brought into being.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":909},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-92","text":"And Friendship of this kind has also the pleasurable and the profitable\r more than that between persons unconnected by blood, in proportion as\r their life is also more shared in common. Then again in the Fraternal\r Friendship there is all that there is in that of Companions, and more\r in the good, and generally in those who are alike; in proportion as\r they are more closely tied and from their very birth have a feeling of\r affection for one another to begin with, and as they are more like in\r disposition who spring from the same stock and have grown up together\r and been educated alike: and be","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":910},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-93","text":"Between Husband and Wife there is thought to be Friendship by a law of\r nature: man being by nature disposed to pair, more than to associate in\r Communities: in proportion as the family is prior in order of time and\r more absolutely necessary than the Community. And procreation is more\r common to him with other animals; all the other animals have Communion\r thus far, but human creatures cohabit not merely for the sake of\r procreation but also with a view to life in general::[8] because in\r this connection the works are immediately divided, and some belong to\r the man, others to the woman: thus","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":911},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-94","text":"And for these reasons this Friendship is thought to combine the\r profitable and the pleasurable: it will be also based upon virtue if\r they are good people; because each has goodness and they may take\r delight in this quality in each other. Children too are thought to be a\r tie: accordingly the childless sooner separate, for the children are a\r good common to both and anything in common is a bond of union.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":912},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-95","text":"The question how a man is to live with his wife, or (more generally)\r one friend with another, appears to be no other than this, how it is\r just that they should: because plainly there is not the same principle\r of Justice between a friend and friend, as between strangers, or\r companions, or mere chance fellow-travellers.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":913},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-96","text":"There are then, as was stated at the commencement of this book, three\r kinds of Friendship, and in each there may be friends on a footing of\r equality and friends in the relation of superior and inferior; we find,\r I mean, that people who are alike in goodness, become friends, and\r better with worse, and so also pleasant people; again, because of\r advantage people are friends, either balancing exactly their mutual\r profitableness or differing from one another herein. Well then, those\r who are equal should in right of this equality be equalised also by the\r degree of their Friendship and the ot","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":914},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-97","text":"Fault-finding and blame arises, either solely or most naturally, in\r Friendship of which utility is the motive: for they who are friends by\r reason of goodness, are eager to do kindnesses to one another because\r this is a natural result of goodness and Friendship; and when men are\r vying with each other for this End there can be no fault-finding nor\r contention: since no one is annoyed at one who entertains for him the\r sentiment of Friendship and does kindnesses to him, but if of a refined\r mind he requites him with kind actions. And suppose that one of the two\r exceeds the other, yet as he i","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":915},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-98","text":"Neither can there well be quarrels between men who are friends for\r pleasure’s sake: because supposing them to delight in living together\r then both attain their desire; or if not a man would be put in a\r ridiculous light who should find fault with another for not pleasing\r him, since it is in his power to forbear intercourse with him. But the\r Friendship because of advantage is very liable to fault-finding;\r because, as the parties use one another with a view to advantage, the\r requirements are continually enlarging, and they think they have less\r than of right belongs to them, and find fault","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":916},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-99","text":"It seems also, that as the Just is of two kinds, the unwritten and the\r legal, so Friendship because of advantage is of two kinds, what may be\r called the Moral, and the Legal: and the most fruitful source of\r complaints is that parties contract obligations and discharge them not\r in the same line of Friendship. The Legal is upon specified conditions,\r either purely tradesmanlike from hand to hand or somewhat more\r gentlemanly as regards time but still by agreement a _quid pro quo_.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":917},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-100","text":"In this Legal kind the obligation is clear and admits of no dispute,\r the friendly element is the delay in requiring its discharge: and for\r this reason in some countries no actions can be maintained at Law for\r the recovery of such debts, it being held that they who have dealt on\r the footing of credit must be content to abide the issue.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":918},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-101","text":"That which may be termed the Moral kind is not upon specified\r conditions, but a man gives as to his friend and so on: but still he\r expects to receive an equivalent, or even more, as though he had not\r given but lent: he also will find fault, because he does not get the\r obligation discharged in the same way as it was contracted.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":919},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-102","text":"Now this results from the fact, that all men, or the generality at\r least, _wish_ what is honourable, but, when tested, _choose_ what is\r profitable; and the doing kindnesses disinterestedly is honourable\r while receiving benefits is profitable. In such cases one should, if\r able, make a return proportionate to the good received, and do so\r willingly, because one ought not to make a disinterested friend[9] of a\r man against his inclination: one should act, I say, as having made a\r mistake originally in receiving kindness from one from whom one ought\r not to have received it, he being not a fri","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":920},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-103","text":"A question admitting of dispute is whether one is to measure a kindness\r by the good done to the receiver of it, and make this the standard by\r which to requite, or by the kind intention of the doer?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":921},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-104","text":"For they who have received kindnesses frequently plead in depreciation\r that they have received from their benefactors such things as were\r small for them to give, or such as they themselves could have got from\r others: while the doers of the kindnesses affirm that they gave the\r best they had, and what could not have been got from others, and under\r danger, or in such-like straits.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":922},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-105","text":"May we not say, that as utility is the motive of the Friendship the\r advantage conferred on the receiver must be the standard? because he it\r is who requests the kindness and the other serves him in his need on\r the understanding that he is to get an equivalent: the assistance\r rendered is then exactly proportionate to the advantage which the\r receiver has obtained, and he should therefore repay as much as he\r gained by it, or even more, this being more creditable.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":923},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-106","text":"In Friendships based on goodness, the question, of course, is never\r raised, but herein the motive of the doer seems to be the proper\r standard, since virtue and moral character depend principally on\r motive.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":924},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-107","text":"Quarrels arise also in those Friendships in which the parties are\r unequal because each party thinks himself entitled to the greater\r share, and of course, when this happens, the Friendship is broken up.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":925},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-108","text":"The man who is better than the other thinks that having the greater\r share pertains to him of right, for that more is always awarded to the\r good man: and similarly the man who is more profitable to another than\r that other to him: “one who is useless,” they say, “ought not to share\r equally, for it comes to a tax, and not a Friendship, unless the fruits\r of the Friendship are reaped in proportion to the works done:” their\r notion being, that as in a money partnership they who contribute more\r receive more so should it be in Friendship likewise.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":926},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-109","text":"On the other hand, the needy man and the less virtuous advance the\r opposite claim: they urge that “it is the very business of a good\r friend to help those who are in need, else what is the use of having a\r good or powerful friend if one is not to reap the advantage at all?”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":927},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-110","text":"Now each seems to advance a right claim and to be entitled to get more\r out of the connection than the other, only _not more of the same\r thing_: but the superior man should receive more respect, the needy man\r more profit: respect being the reward of goodness and beneficence,\r profit being the aid of need.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":928},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-111","text":"This is plainly the principle acted upon in Political Communities: he\r receives no honour who gives no good to the common stock: for the\r property of the Public is given to him who does good to the Public, and\r honour is the property of the Public; it is not possible both to make\r money out of the Public and receive honour likewise; because no one\r will put up with the less in every respect: so to him who suffers loss\r as regards money they award honour, but money to him who can be paid by\r gifts: since, as has been stated before, the observing due proportion\r equalises and preserves Friendshi","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":929},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-112","text":"Like rules then should be observed in the intercourse of friends who\r are unequal; and to him who advantages another in respect of money, or\r goodness, that other should repay honour, making requital according to\r his power; because Friendship requires what is possible, not what is\r strictly due, this being not possible in all cases, as in the honours\r paid to the gods and to parents: no man could ever make the due return\r in these cases, and so he is thought to be a good man who pays respect\r according to his ability.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":930},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-9-113","text":"For this reason it may be judged never to be allowable for a son to\r disown his father, whereas a father may his son: because he that owes\r is bound to pay; now a son can never, by anything he has done, fully\r requite the benefits first conferred on him by his father, and so is\r always a debtor. But they to whom anything is owed may cast off their\r debtors: therefore the father may his son. But at the same time it must\r perhaps be admitted, that it seems no father ever _would_ sever himself\r utterly from a son, except in a case of exceeding depravity: because,\r independently of the natural Fri","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 9","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"9"},"sequenceIndex":931},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-1","text":"Well, in all the Friendships the parties to which are dissimilar it is\r the proportionate which equalises and preserves the Friendship, as has\r been already stated: I mean, in the Social Friendship the cobbler, for\r instance, gets an equivalent for his shoes after a certain rate; and\r the weaver, and all others in like manner. Now in this case a common\r measure has been provided in money, and to this accordingly all things\r are referred and by this are measured: but in the Friendship of Love\r the complaint is sometimes from the lover that, though he loves\r exceedingly, his love is not requited","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":932},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-2","text":"Quarrels arise also when the parties realise different results and not\r those which they desire; for the not attaining one’s special object is\r all one, in this case, with getting nothing at all: as in the\r well-known case where a man made promises to a musician, rising in\r proportion to the excellence of his music; but when, the next morning,\r the musician claimed the performance of his promises, he said that he\r had given him pleasure for pleasure: of course, if each party had\r intended this, it would have been all right: but if the one desires\r amusement and the other gain, and the one gets","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":933},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-3","text":"The question then arises, who is to fix the rate? the man who first\r gives, or the man who first takes? because, _primâ facie_, the man who\r first gives seems to leave the rate to be fixed by the other party.\r This, they say, was in fact the practice of Protagoras: when he taught\r a man anything he would bid the learner estimate the worth of the\r knowledge gained by his own private opinion; and then he used to take\r so much from him. In such cases some people adopt the rule,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":934},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-4","text":"They are certainly fairly found fault with who take the money in\r advance and then do nothing of what they said they would do, their\r promises having been so far beyond their ability; for such men do not\r perform what they agreed, The Sophists, however, are perhaps obliged to\r take this course, because no one would give a sixpence for their\r knowledge. These then, I say, are fairly found fault with, because they\r do not what they have already taken money for doing.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":935},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-5","text":"In cases where no stipulation as to the respective services is made\r they who disinterestedly do the first service will not raise the\r question (as we have said before), because it is the nature of\r Friendship, based on mutual goodness to be reference to the intention\r of the other, the intention being characteristic of the true friend and\r of goodness.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":936},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-6","text":"And it would seem the same rule should be laid down for those who are\r connected with one another as teachers and learners of philosophy; for\r here the value of the commodity cannot be measured by money, and, in\r fact, an exactly equivalent price cannot be set upon it, but perhaps it\r is sufficient to do what one can, as in the case of the gods or one’s\r parents.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":937},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-7","text":"But where the original giving is not upon these terms but avowedly for\r some return, the most proper course is perhaps for the requital to be\r such as _both_ shall allow to be proportionate, and, where this cannot\r be, then for the receiver to fix the value would seem to be not only\r necessary but also fair: because when the first giver gets that which\r is equivalent to the advantage received by the other, or to what he\r would have given to secure the pleasure he has had, then he has the\r value from him: for not only is this seen to be the course adopted in\r matters of buying and selling but a","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":938},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-8","text":"Questions also arise upon such points as the following: Whether one’s\r father has an unlimited claim on one’s services and obedience, or\r whether the sick man is to obey his physician? or, in an election of a\r general, the warlike qualities of the candidates should be alone\r regarded?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":939},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-9","text":"In like manner whether one should do a service rather to one’s friend\r or to a good man? whether one should rather requite a benefactor or\r give to one’s companion, supposing that both are not within one’s\r power?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":940},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-10","text":"Is not the true answer that it is no easy task to determine all such\r questions accurately, inasmuch as they involve numerous differences of\r all kinds, in respect of amount and what is honourable and what is\r necessary? It is obvious, of course, that no one person can unite in\r himself all claims. Again, the requital of benefits is, in general, a\r higher duty than doing unsolicited kindnesses to one’s companion; in\r other words, the discharging of a debt is more obligatory upon one than\r the duty of giving to a companion. And yet this rule may admit of\r exceptions; for instance, which is the ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":941},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-11","text":"Well then, as has been said already, as a general rule the debt should\r be discharged, but if in a particular case the giving greatly\r preponderates as being either honourable or necessary, we must be\r swayed by these considerations: I mean, in some cases the requital of\r the obligation previously existing may not be equal; suppose, for\r instance, that the original benefactor has conferred a kindness on a\r good man, knowing him to be such, whereas this said good man has to\r repay it believing him to be a scoundrel.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":942},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-12","text":"And again, in certain cases no obligation lies on a man to lend to one\r who has lent to him; suppose, for instance, that a bad man lent to him,\r as being a good man, under the notion that he should get repaid,\r whereas the said good man has no hope of repayment from him being a bad\r man. Either then the case is really as we have supposed it and then the\r claim is not equal, or it is not so but supposed to be; and still in so\r acting people are not to be thought to act wrongly. In short, as has\r been oftentimes stated before, all statements regarding feelings and\r actions can be definite only i","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":943},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-13","text":"And this is seen to be the course commonly pursued: to marriages men\r commonly invite their relatives, because these are from a common stock\r and therefore all the actions in any way pertaining thereto are common\r also: and to funerals men think that relatives ought to assemble in\r preference to other people, for the same reason.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":944},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-14","text":"And it would seem that in respect of maintenance it is our duty to\r assist our parents in preference to all others, as being their debtors,\r and because it is more honourable to succour in these respects the\r authors of our existence than ourselves. Honour likewise we ought to\r pay to our parents just as to the gods, but then, not all kinds of\r honour: not the same, for instance, to a father as to a mother: nor\r again to a father the honour due to a scientific man or to a general\r but that which is a father’s due, and in like manner to a mother that\r which is a mother’s.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":945},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-15","text":"To all our elders also the honour befitting their age, by rising up in\r their presence, turning out of the way for them, and all similar marks\r of respect: to our companions again, or brothers, frankness and free\r participation in all we have. And to those of the same family, or\r tribe, or city, with ourselves, and all similarly connected with us, we\r should constantly try to render their due, and to discriminate what\r belongs to each in respect of nearness of connection, or goodness, or\r intimacy: of course in the case of those of the same class the\r discrimination is easier; in that of those","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":946},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-16","text":"A question is also raised as to the propriety of dissolving or not\r dissolving those Friendships the parties to which do not remain what\r they were when the connection was formed.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":947},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-17","text":"Now surely in respect of those whose motive to Friendship is utility or\r pleasure there can be nothing wrong in breaking up the connection when\r they no longer have those qualities; because they were friends [not of\r one another, but] of those qualities: and, these having failed, it is\r only reasonable to expect that they should cease to entertain the\r sentiment.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":948},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-18","text":"But a man has reason to find fault if the other party, being really\r attached to him because of advantage or pleasure, pretended to be so\r because of his moral character: in fact, as we said at the\r commencement, the most common source of quarrels between friends is\r their not being friends on the same grounds as they suppose themselves\r to be.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":949},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-19","text":"Now when a man has been deceived in having supposed himself to excite\r the sentiment of Friendship by reason of his moral character, the other\r party doing nothing to indicate he has but himself to blame: but when\r he has been deceived by the pretence of the other he has a right to\r find fault with the man who has so deceived him, aye even more than\r with utterers of false coin, in proportion to the greater preciousness\r of that which is the object-matter of the villany.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":950},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-20","text":"But suppose a man takes up another as being a good man, who turns out,\r and is found by him, to be a scoundrel, is he bound still to entertain\r Friendship for him? or may we not say at once it is impossible? since\r it is not everything which is the object-matter of Friendship, but only\r that which is good; and so there is no obligation to be a bad man’s\r friend, nor, in fact, ought one to be such: for one ought not to be a\r lover of evil, nor to be assimilated to what is base; which would be\r implied, because we have said before, like is friendly to like.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":951},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-21","text":"Are we then to break with him instantly? not in all cases; only where\r our friends are incurably depraved; when there is a chance of amendment\r we are bound to aid in repairing the moral character of our friends\r even more than their substance, in proportion as it is better and more\r closely related to Friendship. Still he who should break off the\r connection is not to be judged to act wrongly, for he never was a\r friend to such a character as the other now is, and therefore, since\r the man is changed and he cannot reduce him to his original state, he\r backs out of the connection.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":952},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-22","text":"To put another case: suppose that one party remains what he was when\r the Friendship was formed, while the other becomes morally improved and\r widely different from his friend in goodness; is the improved character\r to treat the other as a friend?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":953},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-23","text":"May we not say it is impossible? The case of course is clearest where\r there is a great difference, as in the Friendships of boys: for suppose\r that of two boyish friends the one still continues a boy in mind and\r the other becomes a man of the highest character, how can they be\r friends? since they neither are pleased with the same objects nor like\r and dislike the same things: for these points will not belong to them\r as regards one another, and without them it was assumed they cannot be\r friends because they cannot live in intimacy: and of the case of those\r who cannot do so we have spoken ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":954},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-24","text":"Well then, is the improved party to bear himself towards his former\r friend in no way differently to what he would have done had the\r connection never existed?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":955},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-25","text":"Surely he ought to bear in mind the intimacy of past times, and just as\r we think ourselves bound to do favours for our friends in preference to\r strangers, so to those who have been friends and are so no longer we\r should allow somewhat on the score of previous Friendship, whenever the\r cause of severance is not excessive depravity on their part.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":956},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-26","text":"Now the friendly feelings which are exhibited towards our friends, and\r by which Friendships are characterised, seem to have sprung out of\r those which we entertain toward ourselves.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":957},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-27","text":"I mean, people define a friend to be “one who intends and does what is\r good (or what he believes to be good) to another for that other’s\r sake,” or “one who wishes his friend to be and to live for that\r friend’s own sake” (which is the feeling of mothers towards their\r children, and of friends who have come into collision). Others again,\r “one who lives with another and chooses the same objects,” or “one who\r sympathises with his friend in his sorrows and in his joys” (this too\r is especially the case with mothers).","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":958},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-28","text":"Well, by some one of these marks people generally characterise\r Friendship: and each of these the good man has towards himself, and all\r others have them in so far as they suppose themselves to be good. (For,\r as has been said before, goodness, that is the good man, seems to be a\r measure to every one else.)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":959},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-29","text":"For he is at unity in himself, and with every part of his soul he\r desires the same objects; and he wishes for himself both what is, and\r what he believes to be, good; and he does it (it being characteristic\r of the good man to work at what is good), and for the sake of himself,\r inasmuch as he does it for the sake of his Intellectual Principle which\r is generally thought to be a man’s Self. Again, he wishes himself And\r specially this Principle whereby he is an intelligent being, to live\r and be preserved in life, because existence is a good to him that is a\r good man.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":960},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-30","text":"But it is to himself that each individual wishes what is good, and no\r man, conceiving the possibility of his becoming other than he now is,\r chooses that that New Self should have all things indiscriminately: a\r god, for instance, has at the present moment the Chief Good, but he has\r it in right of being whatever he actually now is: and the Intelligent\r Principle must be judged to be each man’s Self, or at least eminently\r so [though other Principles help, of course, to constitute him the man\r he is].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":961},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-31","text":"Furthermore, the good man wishes to continue to live with himself; for\r he can do it with pleasure, in that his memories of past actions are\r full of delight and his anticipations of the future are good and such\r are pleasurable. Then, again, he has good store of matter for his\r Intellect to contemplate, and he most especially sympathises with his\r Self in its griefs and joys, because the objects which give him pain\r and pleasure are at all times the same, not one thing to-day and a\r different one to-morrow: because he is not given to repentance,[1] if\r one may so speak. It is then because eac","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":962},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-32","text":"But it may be urged that the aforesaid requisites are to all appearance\r found in the common run of men, though they are men of a low stamp.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":963},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-33","text":"May it not be answered, that they share in them only in so far as they\r please themselves, and conceive themselves to be good? for certainly,\r they are not either really, or even apparently, found in any one of\r those who are very depraved and villainous; we may almost say not even\r in those who are bad men at all: for they are at variance with\r themselves and lust after different things from those which in cool\r reason they wish for, just as men who fail of Self-Control: I mean,\r they choose things which, though hurtful, are pleasurable, in\r preference to those which in their own minds they b","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":964},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-34","text":"Neither, in fact, can they who are of this character sympathise with\r their Selves in their joys and sorrows, because their soul is, as it\r were, rent by faction, and the one principle, by reason of the\r depravity in them, is grieved at abstaining from certain things, while\r the other and better principle is pleased thereat; and the one drags\r them this way and the other that way, as though actually tearing them\r asunder.[2] And though it is impossible actually to have at the same\r time the sensations of pain and pleasure; yet after a little time the\r man is sorry for having been pleased, and ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":965},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-35","text":"It is plain then that the wicked man cannot be in the position of a\r friend even towards himself, because he has in himself nothing which\r can excite the sentiment of Friendship. If then to be thus is\r exceedingly wretched it is a man’s duty to flee from wickedness with\r all his might and to strive to be good, because thus may he be friends\r with himself and may come to be a friend to another.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":966},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-36","text":"Kindly Feeling, though resembling Friendship, is not identical with it,\r because it may exist in reference to those whom we do not know and\r without the object of it being aware of its existence, which Friendship\r cannot. (This, by the way, has also been said before.) And further, it\r is not even Affection because it does not imply intensity nor yearning,\r which are both consequences of Affection. Again Affection requires\r intimacy but Kindly Feeling may arise quite suddenly, as happens\r sometimes in respect of men against whom people are matched in any way,\r I mean they come to be kindly disp","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":967},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-37","text":"What it does seem to be is the starting point of a Friendship; just as\r pleasure, received through the sight, is the commencement of Love: for\r no one falls in love without being first pleased with the personal\r appearance of the beloved object, and yet he who takes pleasure in it\r does not therefore necessarily love, but when he wearies for the object\r in its absence and desires its presence. Exactly in the same way men\r cannot be friends without having passed through the stage of Kindly\r Feeling, and yet they who are in that stage do not necessarily advance\r to Friendship: they merely have a","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":968},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-38","text":"I mean, he who has received a kindness requites it by Kindly Feeling\r towards his benefactor, and is right in so doing: but he who wishes\r another to be prosperous, because he has hope of advantage through his\r instrumentality, does not seem to be kindly disposed to that person but\r rather to himself; just as neither is he his friend if he pays court to\r him for any interested purpose.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":969},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-39","text":"Kindly Feeling always arises by reason of goodness and a certain\r amiability, when one man gives another the notion of being a fine\r fellow, or brave man, etc., as we said was the case sometimes with\r those matched against one another.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":970},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-40","text":"Unity of Sentiment is also plainly connected with Friendship, and\r therefore is not the same as Unity of Opinion, because this might exist\r even between people unacquainted with one another.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":971},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-41","text":"Nor do men usually say people are united in sentiment merely because\r they agree in opinion on _any_ point, as, for instance, on points of\r astronomical science (Unity of Sentiment herein not having any\r connection with Friendship), but they say that Communities have Unity\r of Sentiment when they agree respecting points of expediency and take\r the same line and carry out what has been determined in common\r consultation.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":972},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-42","text":"Thus we see that Unity of Sentiment has for its object matters of\r action, and such of these as are of importance, and of mutual, or, in\r the case of single States, common, interest: when, for instance, all\r agree in the choice of magistrates, or forming alliance with the\r Lacedæmonians, or appointing Pittacus ruler (that is to say, supposing\r he himself was willing). But when each wishes himself to be in power\r (as the brothers in the Phœnissæ), they quarrel and form parties: for,\r plainly, Unity of Sentiment does not merely imply that each entertains\r the same idea be it what it may, but tha","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":973},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-43","text":"Thus Unity of Sentiment is plainly a social Friendship, as it is also\r said to be: since it has for its object-matter things expedient and\r relating to life.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":974},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-44","text":"And this Unity exists among the good: for they have it towards\r themselves and towards one another, being, if I may be allowed the\r expression, in the same position: I mean, the wishes of such men are\r steady and do not ebb and flow like the Euripus, and they wish what is\r just and expedient and aim at these things in common.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":975},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-45","text":"The bad, on the contrary, can as little have Unity of Sentiment as they\r can be real friends, except to a very slight extent, desiring as they\r do unfair advantage in things profitable while they shirk labour and\r service for the common good: and while each man wishes for these things\r for himself he is jealous of and hinders his neighbour: and as they do\r not watch over the common good it is lost. The result is that they\r quarrel while they are for keeping one another to work but are not\r willing to perform their just share.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":976},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-46","text":"Benefactors are commonly held to have more Friendship for the objects\r of their kindness than these for them: and the fact is made a subject\r of discussion and enquiry, as being contrary to reasonable expectation.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":977},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-47","text":"The account of the matter which satisfies most persons is that the one\r are debtors and the others creditors: and therefore that, as in the\r case of actual loans the debtors wish their creditors out of the way\r while the creditors are anxious for the preservation of their debtors,\r so those who have done kindnesses desire the continued existence of the\r people they have done them to, under the notion of getting a return of\r their good offices, while these are not particularly anxious about\r requital.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":978},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-48","text":"Epicharmus, I suspect, would very probably say that they who give this\r solution judge from their own baseness; yet it certainly is like human\r nature, for the generality of men have short memories on these points,\r and aim rather at receiving than conferring benefits.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":979},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-49","text":"But the real cause, it would seem, rests upon nature, and the case is\r not parallel to that of creditors; because in this there is no\r affection to the persons, but merely a wish for their preservation with\r a view to the return: whereas, in point of fact, they who have done\r kindnesses feel friendship and love for those to whom they have done\r them, even though they neither are, nor can by possibility hereafter\r be, in a position to serve their benefactors.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":980},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-50","text":"And this is the case also with artisans; every one, I mean, feels more\r affection for his own work than that work possibly could for him if it\r were animate. It is perhaps specially the case with poets: for these\r entertain very great affection for their poems, loving them as their\r own children. It is to this kind of thing I should be inclined to\r compare the case of benefactors: for the object of their kindness is\r their own work, and so they love this more than this loves its creator.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":981},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-51","text":"And the account of this is that existence is to all a thing\r choice-worthy and an object of affection; now we exist by acts of\r working, that is, by living and acting; he then that has created a\r given work exists, it may be said, by his act of working: therefore he\r loves his work because he loves existence. And this is natural, for the\r work produced displays in act what existed before potentially.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":982},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-52","text":"Then again, the benefactor has a sense of honour in right of his\r action, so that he may well take pleasure in him in whom this resides;\r but to him who has received the benefit there is nothing honourable in\r respect of his benefactor, only something advantageous which is both\r less pleasant and less the object of Friendship.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":983},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-53","text":"Again, pleasure is derived from the actual working out of a present\r action, from the anticipation of a future one, and from the\r recollection of a past one: but the highest pleasure and special object\r of affection is that which attends on the actual working. Now the\r benefactor’s work abides (for the honourable is enduring), but the\r advantage of him who has received the kindness passes away.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":984},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-54","text":"Again, there is pleasure in recollecting honourable actions, but in\r recollecting advantageous ones there is none at all or much less (by\r the way though, the contrary is true of the expectation of advantage).","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":985},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-55","text":"Further, the entertaining the feeling of Friendship is like acting on\r another; but being the object of the feeling is like being acted upon.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":986},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-56","text":"So then, entertaining the sentiment of Friendship, and all feelings\r connected with it, attend on those who, in the given case of a\r benefaction, are the superior party.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":987},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-57","text":"Once more: all people value most what has cost them much labour in the\r production; for instance, people who have themselves made their money\r are fonder of it than those who have inherited it: and receiving\r kindness is, it seems, unlaborious, but doing it is laborious. And this\r is the reason why the female parents are most fond of their offspring;\r for their part in producing them is attended with most labour, and they\r know more certainly that they are theirs. This feeling would seem also\r to belong to benefactors.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":988},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-58","text":"A question is also raised as to whether it is right to love one’s Self\r best, or some one else: because men find fault with those who love\r themselves best, and call them in a disparaging way lovers of Self; and\r the bad man is thought to do everything he does for his own sake\r merely, and the more so the more depraved he is; accordingly men\r reproach him with never doing anything unselfish: whereas the good man\r acts from a sense of honour (and the more so the better man he is), and\r for his friend’s sake, and is careless of his own interest.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":989},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-59","text":"But with these theories facts are at variance, and not unnaturally: for\r it is commonly said also that a man is to love most him who is most his\r friend, and he is most a friend who wishes good to him to whom he\r wishes it for that man’s sake even though no one knows. Now these\r conditions, and in fact all the rest by which a friend is\r characterised, belong specially to each individual in respect of his\r Self: for we have said before that all the friendly feelings are\r derived to others from those which have Self primarily for their\r object. And all the current proverbs support this view; for","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":990},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-60","text":"It is with good reason questioned which of the two parties one should\r follow, both having plausibility on their side. Perhaps then, in\r respect of theories of this kind, the proper course is to distinguish\r and define how far each is true, and in what way. If we could ascertain\r the sense in which each uses the term “Self-loving,” this point might\r be cleared up.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":991},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-61","text":"Well now, they who use it disparagingly give the name to those who, in\r respect of wealth, and honours, and pleasures of the body, give to\r themselves the larger share: because the mass of mankind grasp after\r these and are earnest about them as being the best things; which is the\r reason why they are matters of contention. They who are covetous in\r regard to these gratify their lusts and passions in general, that is to\r say the irrational part of their soul: now the mass of mankind are so\r disposed, for which reason the appellation has taken its rise from that\r mass which is low and bad. Of c","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":992},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-62","text":"And that the generality of men are accustomed to apply the term to\r denominate those who do give such things to themselves is quite plain:\r suppose, for instance, that a man were anxious to do, more than other\r men, acts of justice, or self-mastery, or any other virtuous acts, and,\r in general, were to secure to himself that which is abstractedly noble\r and honourable, no one would call him Self-loving, nor blame him.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":993},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-63","text":"Yet might such an one be judged to be more truly Self-loving: certainly\r he gives to himself the things which are most noble and most good, and\r gratifies that Principle of his nature which is most rightfully\r authoritative, and obeys it in everything: and just as that which\r possesses the highest authority is thought to constitute a Community or\r any other system, so also in the case of Man: and so he is most truly\r Self-loving who loves and gratifies this Principle.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":994},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-64","text":"Again, men are said to have, or to fail of having, self-control,\r according as the Intellect controls or not, it being plainly implied\r thereby that this Principle constitutes each individual; and people are\r thought to have done of themselves, and voluntarily, those things\r specially which are done with Reason.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":995},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-65","text":"It is plain, therefore, that this Principle does, either entirely or\r specially constitute the individual man, and that the good man\r specially loves this. For this reason then he must be specially\r Self-loving, in a kind other than that which is reproached, and as far\r superior to it as living in accordance with Reason is to living at the\r beck and call of passion, and aiming at the truly noble to aiming at\r apparent advantage.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":996},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-66","text":"Now all approve and commend those who are eminently earnest about\r honourable actions, and if all would vie with one another in respect of\r the καλὸν, and be intent upon doing what is most truly noble and\r honourable, society at large would have all that is proper while each\r individual in particular would have the greatest of goods, Virtue being\r assumed to be such.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":997},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-67","text":"And so the good man ought to be Self-loving: because by doing what is\r noble he will have advantage himself and will do good to others: but\r the bad man ought not to be, because he will harm himself and his\r neighbours by following low and evil passions. In the case of the bad\r man, what he ought to do and what he does are at variance, but the good\r man does what he ought to do, because all Intellect chooses what is\r best for itself and the good man puts himself under the direction of\r Intellect.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":998},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-68","text":"Of the good man it is true likewise that he does many things for the\r sake of his friends and his country, even to the extent of dying for\r them, if need be: for money and honours, and, in short, all the good\r things which others fight for, he will throw away while eager to secure\r to himself the καλὸν: he will prefer a brief and great joy to a tame\r and enduring one, and to live nobly for one year rather than ordinarily\r for many, and one great and noble action to many trifling ones. And\r this is perhaps that which befals men who die for their country and\r friends; they choose great glory for","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":999},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-69","text":"In short, in all praiseworthy things the good man does plainly give to\r himself a larger share of the honourable. In this sense it is right to\r be Self-loving, in the vulgar acceptation of the term it is not.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1000},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-70","text":"A question is raised also respecting the Happy man, whether he will\r want Friends, or no?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1001},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-71","text":"Some say that they who are blessed and independent have no need of\r Friends, for they already have all that is good, and so, as being\r independent, want nothing further: whereas the notion of a friend’s\r office is to be as it were a second Self and procure for a man what he\r cannot get by himself: hence the saying,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1002},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-72","text":"On the other hand, it looks absurd, while we are assigning to the Happy\r man all other good things, not to give him Friends, which are, after\r all, thought to be the greatest of external goods.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1003},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-73","text":"Again, if it is more characteristic of a friend to confer than to\r receive kindnesses, and if to be beneficent belongs to the good man and\r to the character of virtue, and if it is more noble to confer\r kindnesses on friends than strangers, the good man will need objects\r for his benefactions. And out of this last consideration springs a\r question whether the need of Friends be greater in prosperity or\r adversity, since the unfortunate man wants people to do him kindnesses\r and they who are fortunate want objects for their kind acts.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1004},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-74","text":"Again, it is perhaps absurd to make our Happy man a solitary, because\r no man would choose the possession of all goods in the world on the\r condition of solitariness, man being a social animal and formed by\r nature for living with others: of course the Happy man has this\r qualification since he has all those things which are good by nature:\r and it is obvious that the society of friends and good men must be\r preferable to that of strangers and ordinary people, and we conclude,\r therefore, that the Happy man does need Friends.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1005},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-75","text":"But then, what do they mean whom we quoted first, and how are they\r right? Is it not that the mass of mankind mean by Friends those who are\r useful? and of course the Happy man will not need such because he has\r all good things already; neither will he need such as are Friends with\r a view to the pleasurable, or at least only to a slight extent; because\r his life, being already pleasurable, does not want pleasure imported\r from without; and so, since the Happy man does not need Friends of\r these kinds, he is thought not to need any at all.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1006},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-76","text":"But it may be, this is not true: for it was stated originally, that\r Happiness is a kind of Working; now Working plainly is something that\r must come into being, not be already there like a mere piece of\r property.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1007},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-77","text":"If then the being happy consists in living and working, and the good\r man’s working is in itself excellent and pleasurable (as we said at the\r commencement of the treatise), and if what is our own reckons among\r things pleasurable, and if we can view our neighbours better than\r ourselves and their actions better than we can our own, then the\r actions of their Friends who are good men are pleasurable to the good;\r inasmuch as they have both the requisites which are naturally pleasant.\r So the man in the highest state of happiness will need Friends of this\r kind, since he desires to contemplate ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1008},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-78","text":"Again, common opinion requires that the Happy man live with pleasure to\r himself: now life is burthensome to a man in solitude, for it is not\r easy to work continuously by one’s self, but in company with, and in\r regard to others, it is easier, and therefore the working, being\r pleasurable in itself will be more continuous (a thing which should be\r in respect of the Happy man); for the good man, in that he is good\r takes pleasure in the actions which accord with Virtue and is annoyed\r at those which spring from Vice, just as a musical man is pleased with\r beautiful music and annoyed by bad. An","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1009},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-79","text":"And, upon the following considerations more purely metaphysical, it\r will probably appear that the good friend is naturally choice-worthy to\r the good man. We have said before, that whatever is naturally good is\r also in itself good and pleasant to the good man; now the fact of\r living, so far as animals are concerned, is characterised generally by\r the power of sentience, in man it is characterised by that of\r sentience, or of rationality (the faculty of course being referred to\r the actual operation of the faculty, certainly the main point is the\r actual operation of it); so that living seem","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1010},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-80","text":"If then the fact of living is in itself good and pleasant (and this\r appears from the fact that all desire it, and specially those who are\r good and in high happiness; their course of life being most\r choice-worthy and their existence most choice-worthy likewise), then\r also he that sees perceives that he sees; and he that hears perceives\r that he hears; and he that walks perceives that he walks; and in all\r the other instances in like manner there is a faculty which reflects\r upon and perceives the fact that we are working, so that we can\r perceive that we perceive and intellectually know tha","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1011},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-81","text":"Therefore the fact of living is choice-worthy, and to the good\r specially so since existence is good and pleasant to them: for they\r receive pleasure from the internal consciousness of that which in\r itself is good.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1012},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-82","text":"But the good man is to his friend as to himself, friend being but a\r name for a second Self; therefore as his own existence is choice-worthy\r to each so too, or similarly at least, is his friend’s existence. But\r the ground of one’s own existence being choice-worthy is the perceiving\r of one’s self being good, any such perception being in itself pleasant.\r Therefore one ought to be thoroughly conscious of one’s friend’s\r existence, which will result from living with him, that is sharing in\r his words and thoughts: for this is the meaning of the term as applied\r to the human species, not mere f","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1013},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-83","text":"If then to the man in a high state of happiness existence is in itself\r choice-worthy, being naturally good and pleasant, and so too a friend’s\r existence, then the friend also must be among things choice-worthy. But\r whatever is choice-worthy to a man he should have or else he will be in\r this point deficient. The man therefore who is to come up to our notion\r “Happy” will need good Friends.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1014},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-84","text":"Are we then to make our friends as numerous as possible? or, as in\r respect of acquaintance it is thought to have been well said “have not\r thou many acquaintances yet be not without;” so too in respect of\r Friendship may we adopt the precept, and say that a man should not be\r without friends, nor again have exceeding many friends?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1015},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-85","text":"Now as for friends who are intended for use, the maxim I have quoted\r will, it seems, fit in exceedingly well, because to requite the\r services of many is a matter of labour, and a whole life would not be\r long enough to do this for them. So that, if more numerous than what\r will suffice for one’s own life, they become officious, and are\r hindrances in respect of living well: and so we do not want them. And\r again of those who are to be for pleasure a few are quite enough, just\r like sweetening in our food.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1016},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-86","text":"But of the good are we to make as many as ever we can, or is there any\r measure of the number of friends, as there is of the number to\r constitute a Political Community? I mean, you cannot make one out of\r ten men, and if you increase the number to one hundred thousand it is\r not any longer a Community. However, the number is not perhaps some one\r definite number but any between certain extreme limits.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1017},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-87","text":"Well, of friends likewise there is a limited number, which perhaps may\r be laid down to be the greatest number with whom it would be possible\r to keep up intimacy; this being thought to be one of the greatest marks\r of Friendship, and it being quite obvious that it is not possible to be\r intimate with many, in other words, to part one’s self among many. And\r besides it must be remembered that they also are to be friends to one\r another if they are all to live together: but it is a matter of\r difficulty to find this in many men at once.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1018},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-88","text":"It comes likewise to be difficult to bring home to one’s self the joys\r and sorrows of many: because in all probability one would have to\r sympathise at the same time with the joys of this one and the sorrows\r of that other.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1019},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-89","text":"Perhaps then it is well not to endeavour to have very many friends but\r so many as are enough for intimacy: because, in fact, it would seem not\r to be possible to be very much a friend to many at the same time: and,\r for the same reason, not to be in love with many objects at the same\r time: love being a kind of excessive Friendship which implies but one\r object: and all strong emotions must be limited in the number towards\r whom they are felt.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1020},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-90","text":"And if we look to facts this seems to be so: for not many at a time\r become friends in the way of companionship, all the famous Friendships\r of the kind are between _two_ persons: whereas they who have many\r friends, and meet everybody on the footing of intimacy, seem to be\r friends really to no one except in the way of general society; I mean\r the characters denominated as over-complaisant.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1021},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-91","text":"To be sure, in the way merely of society, a man may be a friend to many\r without being necessarily over-complaisant, but being truly good: but\r one cannot be a friend to many because of their virtue, and for the\r persons’ own sake; in fact, it is a matter for contentment to find even\r a few such.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1022},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-92","text":"Again: are friends most needed in prosperity or in adversity? they are\r required, we know, in both states, because the unfortunate need help\r and the prosperous want people to live with and to do kindnesses to:\r for they have a desire to act kindly to some one.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1023},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-93","text":"To have friends is more necessary in adversity, and therefore in this\r case useful ones are wanted; and to have them in prosperity is more\r honourable, and this is why the prosperous want good men for friends,\r it being preferable to confer benefits on, and to live with, these. For\r the very presence of friends is pleasant even in adversity: since men\r when grieved are comforted by the sympathy of their friends.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1024},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-94","text":"And from this, by the way, the question might be raised, whether it is\r that they do in a manner take part of the weight of calamities, or only\r that their presence, being pleasurable, and the consciousness of their\r sympathy, make the pain of the sufferer less.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1025},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-95","text":"However, we will not further discuss whether these which have been\r suggested or some other causes produce the relief, at least the effect\r we speak of is a matter of plain fact.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1026},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-96","text":"But their presence has probably a mixed effect: I mean, not only is the\r very seeing friends pleasant, especially to one in misfortune, and\r actual help towards lessening the grief is afforded (the natural\r tendency of a friend, if he is gifted with tact, being to comfort by\r look and word, because he is well acquainted with the sufferer’s temper\r and disposition and therefore knows what things give him pleasure and\r pain), but also the perceiving a friend to be grieved at his\r misfortunes causes the sufferer pain, because every one avoids being\r cause of pain to his friends. And for this reas","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1027},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-97","text":"On the other hand, the advantages of friends in our prosperity are the\r pleasurable intercourse and the consciousness that they are pleased at\r our good fortune.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1028},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-98","text":"It would seem, therefore, that we ought to call in friends readily on\r occasion of good fortune, because it is noble to be ready to do good to\r others: but on occasion of bad fortune, we should do so with\r reluctance; for we should as little as possible make others share in\r our ills; on which principle goes the saying, “I am unfortunate, let\r that suffice.” The most proper occasion for calling them in is when\r with small trouble or annoyance to themselves they can be of very great\r use to the person who needs them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1029},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-99","text":"But, on the contrary, it is fitting perhaps to go to one’s friends in\r their misfortunes unasked and with alacrity (because kindness is the\r friend’s office and specially towards those who are in need and who do\r not demand it as a right, this being more creditable and more pleasant\r to both); and on occasion of their good fortune to go readily, if we\r can forward it in any way (because men need their friends for this\r likewise), but to be backward in sharing it, any great eagerness to\r receive advantage not being creditable.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1030},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-100","text":"One should perhaps be cautious not to present the appearance of\r sullenness in declining the sympathy or help of friends, for this\r happens occasionally.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1031},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-101","text":"It appears then that the presence of friends is, under all\r circumstances, choice-worthy.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1032},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-102","text":"May we not say then that, as seeing the beloved object is most prized\r by lovers and they choose this sense rather than any of the others\r because Love","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1033},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-103","text":"in like manner intimacy is to friends most choice-worthy, Friendship\r being communion? Again, as a man is to himself so is he to his friend;\r now with respect to himself the perception of his own existence is\r choice-worthy, therefore is it also in respect of his friend.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1034},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-104","text":"And besides, their Friendship is acted out in intimacy, and so with\r good reason they desire this. And whatever in each man’s opinion\r constitutes existence, or whatsoever it is for the sake of which they\r choose life, herein they wish their friends to join with them; and so\r some men drink together, others gamble, others join in gymnastic\r exercises or hunting, others study philosophy together: in each case\r spending their days together in that which they like best of all things\r in life, for since they wish to be intimate with their friends they do\r and partake in those things whereby they t","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1035},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-105","text":"Therefore the Friendship of the wicked comes to be depraved; for, being\r unstable, they share in what is bad and become depraved in being made\r like to one another: but the Friendship of the good is good, growing\r with their intercourse; they improve also, as it seems, by repeated\r acts, and by mutual correction, for they receive impress from one\r another in the points which give them pleasure; whence says the Poet,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1036},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-10-106","text":"Here then we will terminate our discourse of Friendship. The next thing\r is to go into the subject of Pleasure.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 10","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"10"},"sequenceIndex":1037},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-1","text":"Next, it would seem, follows a discussion respecting Pleasure, for it\r is thought to be most closely bound up with our kind: and so men train\r the young, guiding them on their course by the rudders of Pleasure and\r Pain. And to like and dislike what one ought is judged to be most\r important for the formation of good moral character: because these\r feelings extend all one’s life through, giving a bias towards and\r exerting an influence on the side of Virtue and Happiness, since men\r choose what is pleasant and avoid what is painful.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1038},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-2","text":"Subjects such as these then, it would seem, we ought by no means to\r pass by, and specially since they involve much difference of opinion.\r There are those who call Pleasure the Chief Good; there are others who\r on the contrary maintain that it is exceedingly bad;[1] some perhaps\r from a real conviction that such is the case, others from a notion that\r it is better, in reference to our life and conduct, to show up Pleasure\r as bad, even if it is not so really; arguing that, as the mass of men\r have a bias towards it and are the slaves of their pleasures, it is\r right to draw them to the contra","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1039},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-3","text":"I confess I suspect the soundness of this policy; in matters respecting\r men’s feelings and actions theories are less convincing than facts:\r whenever, therefore, they are found conflicting with actual experience,\r they not only are despised but involve the truth in their fall: he, for\r instance, who deprecates Pleasure, if once seen to aim at it, gets the\r credit of backsliding to it as being universally such as he said it\r was, the mass of men being incapable of nice distinctions.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1040},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-4","text":"Real accounts, therefore, of such matters seem to be most expedient,\r not with a view to knowledge merely but to life and conduct: for they\r are believed as being in harm with facts, and so they prevail with the\r wise to live in accordance with them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1041},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-5","text":"But of such considerations enough: let us now proceed to the current\r maxims respecting Pleasure.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1042},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-6","text":"Now Eudoxus thought Pleasure to be the Chief Good because he saw all,\r rational and irrational alike, aiming at it: and he argued that, since\r in all what was the object of choice must be good and what most so the\r best, the fact of all being drawn to the same thing proved this thing\r to be the best for all: “For each,” he said, “finds what is good for\r itself just as it does its proper nourishment, and so that which is\r good for all, and the object of the aim of all, is their Chief Good.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1043},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-7","text":"(And his theories were received, not so much for their own sake, as\r because of his excellent moral character; for he was thought to be\r eminently possessed of perfect self-mastery, and therefore it was not\r thought that he said these things because he was a lover of Pleasure\r but that he really was so convinced.)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1044},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-8","text":"And he thought his position was not less proved by the argument from\r the contrary: that is, since Pain was in itself an object of avoidance\r to all the contrary must be in like manner an object of choice.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1045},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-9","text":"Again he urged that that is most choice-worthy which we choose, not by\r reason of, or with a view to, anything further; and that Pleasure is\r confessedly of this kind because no one ever goes on to ask to what\r purpose he is pleased, feeling that Pleasure is in itself\r choice-worthy.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1046},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-10","text":"Again, that when added to any other good it makes it more\r choice-worthy; as, for instance, to actions of justice, or perfected\r self-mastery; and good can only be increased by itself.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1047},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-11","text":"However, this argument at least seems to prove only that it belongs to\r the class of goods, and not that it does so more than anything else:\r for every good is more choicewortby in combination with some other than\r when taken quite alone. In fact, it is by just such an argument that\r Plato proves that Pleasure is not the Chief Good:[3] “For,” says he,\r “the life of Pleasure is more choice-worthy in combination with\r Practical Wisdom than apart from it; but, if the compound better then\r simple Pleasure cannot be the Chief Good; because the very Chief Good\r cannot by any addition become choice-w","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1048},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-12","text":"What is there then of such a nature? (meaning, of course, whereof we\r can partake; because that which we are in search of must be such).","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1049},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-13","text":"As for those who object that “what all aim at is not necessarily good,”\r I confess I cannot see much in what they say, because what all _think_\r we say _is_. And he who would cut away this ground from under us will\r not bring forward things more dependable: because if the argument had\r rested on the desires of irrational creatures there might have been\r something in what he says, but, since the rational also desire\r Pleasure, how can his objection be allowed any weight? and it may be\r that, even in the lower animals, there is some natural good principle\r above themselves which aims at the good","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1050},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-14","text":"Nor does that seem to be sound which is urged respecting the argument\r from the contrary: I mean, some people say “it does not follow that\r Pleasure must be good because Pain is evil, since evil may be opposed\r to evil, and both evil and good to what is indifferent:” now what they\r say is right enough in itself but does not hold in the present\r instance. If both Pleasure and Pain were bad both would have been\r objects of avoidance; or if neither then neither would have been, at\r all events they must have fared alike: but now men do plainly avoid the\r one as bad and choose the other as good, an","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1051},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-15","text":"Nor again is Pleasure therefore excluded from being good because it\r does not belong to the class of qualities:[4] the acts of Virtue are\r not qualities, neither is Happiness [yet surely both are goods].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1052},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-16","text":"Again, they say the Chief Good is limited but Pleasure unlimited, in\r that it admits of degrees.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1053},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-17","text":"Now if they judge this from the act of feeling Pleasure then the same\r thing will apply to justice and all the other virtues,[5] in respect of\r which clearly it is said that men are more or less of such and such\r characters (according to the different virtues), they are more just or\r more brave, or one may practise justice and self-mastery more or less.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1054},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-18","text":"If, on the other hand, they judge in respect of the Pleasures\r themselves then it may be they miss the true cause, namely that some\r are unmixed and others mixed: for just as health being in itself\r limited, admits of degrees, why should not Pleasure do so and yet be\r limited? in the former case we account for it by the fact that there is\r not the same adjustment of parts in all men, nor one and the same\r always in the same individual: but health, though relaxed, remains up\r to a certain point, and differs in degrees; and of course the same may\r be the case with Pleasure.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1055},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-19","text":"Again, assuming the Chief Good to be perfect and all Movements[6] and\r Generations imperfect, they try to shew that Pleasure is a Movement and\r a Generation.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1056},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-20","text":"Yet they do not seem warranted in saying even that it is a Movement:\r for to every Movement are thought to belong swiftness and slowness, and\r if not in itself, as to that of the universe, yet relatively: but to\r Pleasure neither of these belongs: for though one may have got quickly\r into the state Pleasure, as into that of anger, one cannot be in the\r state quickly,[7] nor relatively to the state of any other person; but\r we can walk or grow, and so on, quickly or slowly.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1057},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-21","text":"Of course it is possible to change into the state of Pleasure quickly\r or slowly, but to act in the state (by which, I mean, have the\r perception of Pleasure) quickly, is not possible.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1058},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-22","text":"And how can it be a Generation? because, according to notions generally\r held, not _any_thing is generated from _any_thing, but a thing resolves\r itself into that out of which it was generated: whereas of that of\r which Pleasure is a Generation Pain is a Destruction.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1059},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-23","text":"Again, they say that Pain is a lack of something suitable to nature and\r Pleasure a supply of it.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1060},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-24","text":"But these are affections of the body: now if Pleasure really is a\r supplying of somewhat suitable to nature, that must feel the Pleasure\r in which the supply takes place, therefore the body of course: yet this\r is not thought to be so: neither then is Pleasure a supplying, only a\r person of course will be pleased when a supply takes place just as he\r will be pained when he is cut short.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1061},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-25","text":"This notion would seem to have arisen out of the Pains and Pleasures\r connected with natural nourishment; because, when people have felt a\r lack and so have had Pain first, they, of course, are pleased with the\r supply of their lack.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1062},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-26","text":"But this is not the case with all Pleasures: those attendant on\r mathematical studies, for instance, are unconnected with any Pain; and\r of such as attend on the senses those which arise through the sense of\r Smell; and again, many sounds, and sights, and memories, and hopes: now\r of what can these be Generations? because there has been here no lack\r of anything to be afterwards supplied.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1063},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-27","text":"And to those who bring forward disgraceful Pleasures we may reply that\r these are not really pleasant things; for it does not follow because\r they are pleasant to the ill-disposed that we are to admit that they\r are pleasant except to them; just as we should not say that those\r things are really wholesome, or sweet, or bitter, which are so to the\r sick, or those objects really white which give that impression to\r people labouring under ophthalmia.[8]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1064},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-28","text":"Or we might say thus, that the Pleasures are choice-worthy but not as\r derived from these sources: just as wealth is, but not as the price of\r treason; or health, but not on the terms of eating anything however\r loathsome.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1065},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-29","text":"Or again, may we not say that Pleasures differ in kind? those derived\r from honourable objects, for instance are different from those arising\r from disgraceful ones; and it is not possible to experience the\r Pleasure of the just man without being just, or of the musical man\r without being musical; and so on of others.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1066},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-30","text":"The distinction commonly drawn between the friend and the flatterer\r would seem to show clearly either that Pleasure is not a good, or that\r there are different kinds of Pleasure: for the former is thought to\r have good as the object of his intercourse, the latter Pleasure only;\r and this last is reproached, but the former men praise as having\r different objects in his intercourse.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1067},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-31","text":"Again, no one would choose to live with a child’s intellect all his\r life through, though receiving the highest possible Pleasure from such\r objects as children receive it from; or to take Pleasure in doing any\r of the most disgraceful things, though sure never to be pained.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1068},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-32","text":"There are many things also about which we should be diligent even\r though they brought no Pleasure; as seeing, remembering, knowing,\r possessing the various Excellences; and the fact that Pleasures do\r follow on these naturally makes no difference, because we should\r certainly choose them even though no Pleasure resulted from them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1069},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-33","text":"It seems then to be plain that Pleasure is not the Chief Good, nor is\r every kind of it choice-worthy: and that there are some choice-worthy\r in themselves, differing in kind, _i.e._ in the sources from which they\r are derived. Let this then suffice by way of an account of the current\r maxims respecting Pleasure and Pain.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1070},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-34","text":"Now what it is, and how characterised, will be more plain if we take up\r the subject afresh.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1071},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-35","text":"An act of Sight is thought to be complete at any moment; that is to\r say, it lacks nothing the accession of which subsequently will complete\r its whole nature.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1072},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-36","text":"Well, Pleasure resembles this: because it is a whole, as one may say;\r and one could not at any moment of time take a Pleasure whose whole\r nature would be completed by its lasting for a longer time. And for\r this reason it is not a Movement: for all Movement takes place in time\r of certain duration and has a certain End to accomplish; for instance,\r the Movement of house-building[9] is then only complete when the\r builder has produced what he intended, that is, either in the whole\r time [necessary to complete the whole design], or in a given\r portion.[10] But all the subordinate Movements are","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1073},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-37","text":"As I said then, they differ in kind, and you cannot at any time you\r choose find a Movement complete in its whole nature, but, if at all, in\r the whole time requisite.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1074},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-38","text":"And so it is with the Movement of walking and all others: for, if\r motion be a Movement from one place to another place, then of it too\r there are different kinds, flying, walking, leaping, and such-like. And\r not only so, but there are different kinds even in walking: the\r where-from and where-to are not the same in the whole Course as in a\r portion of it; nor in one portion as in another; nor is crossing this\r line the same as crossing that: because a man is not merely crossing a\r line but a line in a given place, and this is in a different place from\r that.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1075},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-39","text":"Of Movement I have discoursed exactly in another treatise. I will now\r therefore only say that it seems not to be complete at any given\r moment; and that most movements are incomplete and specifically\r different, since the whence and whither constitute different species.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1076},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-40","text":"But of Pleasure the whole nature is complete at any given moment: it is\r plain then that Pleasure and Movement must be different from one\r another, and that Pleasure belongs to the class of things whole and\r complete. And this might appear also from the impossibility of moving\r except in a definite time, whereas there is none with respect to the\r sensation of Pleasure, for what exists at the very present moment is a\r kind of “whole.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1077},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-41","text":"From these considerations then it is plain that people are not\r warranted in saying that Pleasure is a Movement or a Generation:\r because these terms are not applicable to all things, only to such as\r are divisible and not “wholes:” I mean that of an act of Sight there is\r no Generation, nor is there of a point, nor of a monad, nor is any one\r of these a Movement or a Generation: neither then of Pleasure is there\r Movement or Generation, because it is, as one may say, “a whole.”[11]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1078},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-42","text":"Now since every Percipient Faculty works upon the Object answering to\r it, and perfectly the Faculty in a good state upon the most excellent\r of the Objects within its range (for Perfect Working is thought to be\r much what I have described; and we will not raise any question about\r saying “the Faculty” works, instead of, “that subject wherein the\r Faculty resides”), in each case the best Working is that of the Faculty\r in its best state upon the best of the Objects answering to it. And\r this will be, further, most perfect and most pleasant: for Pleasure is\r attendant upon every Percipient Facu","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1079},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-43","text":"And Pleasure perfects the Working. But Pleasure does not perfect it in\r the same way as the Faculty and Object of Perception do, being good;\r just as health and the physician are not in similar senses causes of a\r healthy state.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1080},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-44","text":"And that Pleasure does arise upon the exercise of every Percipient\r Faculty is evident, for we commonly say that sights and sounds are\r pleasant; it is plain also that this is especially the case when the\r Faculty is most excellent and works upon a similar Object: and when\r both the Object and Faculty of Perception are such, Pleasure will\r always exist, supposing of course an agent and a patient.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1081},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-45","text":"Furthermore, Pleasure perfects the act of Working not in the way of an\r inherent state but as a supervening finish, such as is bloom in people\r at their prime. Therefore so long as the Object of intellectual or\r sensitive Perception is such as it should be and also the Faculty which\r discerns or realises the Object, there will be Pleasure in the Working:\r because when that which has the capacity of being acted on and that\r which is apt to act are alike and similarly related, the same result\r follows naturally.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1082},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-46","text":"How is it then that no one feels Pleasure continuously? is it not that\r he wearies, because all human faculties are incapable of unintermitting\r exertion; and so, of course, Pleasure does not arise either, because\r that follows upon the act of Working. But there are some things which\r please when new, but afterwards not in the like way, for exactly the\r same reason: that at first the mind is roused and works on these\r Objects with its powers at full tension; just as they who are gazing\r stedfastly at anything; but afterwards the act of Working is not of the\r kind it was at first, but careless,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1083},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-47","text":"Again, a person may conclude that all men grasp at Pleasure, because\r all aim likewise at Life and Life is an act of Working, and every man\r works at and with those things which also he best likes; the musical\r man, for instance, works with his hearing at music; the studious man\r with his intellect at speculative questions, and so forth. And Pleasure\r perfects the acts of Working, and so Life after which men grasp. No\r wonder then that they aim also at Pleasure, because to each it perfects\r Life, which is itself choice-worthy. (We will take leave to omit the\r question whether we choose Life fo","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1084},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-48","text":"And this is one reason why Pleasures are thought to differ in kind,\r because we suppose that things which differ in kind must be perfected\r by things so differing: it plainly being the case with the productions\r of Nature and Art; as animals, and trees, and pictures, and statues,\r and houses, and furniture; and so we suppose that in like manner acts\r of Working which are different in kind are perfected by things\r differing in kind. Now Intellectual Workings differ specifically from\r those of the Senses, and these last from one another; therefore so do\r the Pleasures which perfect them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1085},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-49","text":"This may be shown also from the intimate connection subsisting between\r each Pleasure and the Working which it perfects: I mean, that the\r Pleasure proper to any Working increases that Working; for they who\r work with Pleasure sift all things more closely and carry them out to a\r greater degree of nicety; for instance, those men become geometricians\r who take Pleasure in geometry, and they apprehend particular points\r more completely: in like manner men who are fond of music, or\r architecture, or anything else, improve each on his own pursuit,\r because they feel Pleasure in them. Thus the Plea","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1086},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-50","text":"Yet even more clearly may this be shown from the fact that the\r Pleasures arising from one kind of Workings hinder other Workings; for\r instance, people who are fond of flute-music cannot keep their\r attention to conversation or discourse when they catch the sound of a\r flute; because they take more Pleasure in flute-playing than in the\r Working they are at the time engaged on; in other words, the Pleasure\r attendant on flute-playing destroys the Working of conversation or\r discourse.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1087},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-51","text":"Much the same kind of thing takes place in other cases, when a person\r is engaged in two different Workings at the same time: that is, the\r pleasanter of the two keeps pushing out the other, and, if the\r disparity in pleasantness be great, then more and more till a man even\r ceases altogether to work at the other.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1088},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-52","text":"This is the reason why, when we are very much pleased with anything\r whatever, we do nothing else, and it is only when we are but moderately\r pleased with one occupation that we vary it with another: people, for\r instance, who eat sweetmeats in the theatre do so most when the\r performance is indifferent.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1089},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-53","text":"Since then the proper and peculiar Pleasure gives accuracy to the\r Workings and makes them more enduring and better of their kind, while\r those Pleasures which are foreign to them mar them, it is plain there\r is a wide difference between them: in fact, Pleasures foreign to any\r Working have pretty much the same effect as the Pains proper to it,[12]\r which, in fact, destroy the Workings; I mean, if one man dislikes\r writing, or another calculation, the one does not write, the other does\r not calculate; because, in each case, the Working is attended with some\r Pain: so then contrary effects are ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1090},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-54","text":"Well then, as Workings differ from one another in goodness and badness,\r some being fit objects of choice, others of avoidance, and others in\r their nature indifferent, Pleasures are similarly related; since its\r own proper Pleasure attends or each Working: of course that proper to a\r good Working is good, that proper to a bad, bad: for even the desires\r for what is noble are praiseworthy, and for what is base blameworthy.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1091},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-55","text":"Furthermore, the Pleasures attendant on Workings are more closely\r connected with them even than the desires after them: for these last\r are separate both in time and nature, but the former are close to the\r Workings, and so indivisible from them as to raise a question whether\r the Working and the Pleasure are identical; but Pleasure does not seem\r to be an Intellectual Operation nor a Faculty of Perception, because\r that is absurd; but yet it gives some the impression of being the same\r from not being separated from these.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1092},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-56","text":"As then the Workings are different so are their Pleasures; now Sight\r differs from Touch in purity, and Hearing and Smelling from Taste;\r therefore, in like manner, do their Pleasures; and again, Intellectual\r Pleasures from these Sensual, and the different kinds both of\r Intellectual and Sensual from one another.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1093},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-57","text":"It is thought, moreover, that each animal has a Pleasure proper to\r itself, as it has a proper Work; that Pleasure of course which is\r attendant on the Working. And the soundness of this will appear upon\r particular inspection: for horse, dog, and man have different\r Pleasures; as Heraclitus says, an ass would sooner have hay than gold;\r in other words, provender is pleasanter to asses than gold. So then the\r Pleasures of animals specifically different are also specifically\r different, but those of the same, we may reasonably suppose, are\r without difference.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1094},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-58","text":"Yet in the case of human creatures they differ not a little: for the\r very same things please some and pain others: and what are painful and\r hateful to some are pleasant to and liked by others. The same is the\r case with sweet things: the same will not seem so to the man in a fever\r as to him who is in health: nor will the invalid and the person in\r robust health have the same notion of warmth. The same is the case with\r other things also.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1095},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-59","text":"Now in all such cases that is held to _be_ which impresses the good man\r with the notion of being such and such; and if this is a second maxim\r (as it is usually held to be), and Virtue, that is, the Good man, in\r that he is such, is the measure of everything, then those must be real\r Pleasures which gave him the impression of being so and those things\r pleasant in which he takes Pleasure. Nor is it at all astonishing that\r what are to him unpleasant should give another person the impression of\r being pleasant, for men are liable to many corruptions and marrings;\r and the things in question ar","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1096},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-60","text":"Well of course, you may say, it is obvious that we must assert those\r which are confessedly disgraceful to be real Pleasures, except to\r depraved tastes: but of those which are thought to be good what kind,\r or which, must we say is _The Pleasure of Man?_ is not the answer plain\r from considering the Workings, because the Pleasures follow upon these?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1097},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-61","text":"If then there be one or several Workings which belong to the perfect\r and blessed man, the Pleasures which perfect these Workings must be\r said to be specially and properly _The Pleasures of Man;_ and all the\r rest in a secondary sense, and in various degrees according as the\r Workings are related to those highest and best ones.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1098},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-62","text":"Now that we have spoken about the Excellences of both kinds, and\r Friendship in its varieties, and Pleasures, it remains to sketch out\r Happiness, since we assume that to be the one End of all human things:\r and we shall save time and trouble by recapitulating what was stated\r before.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1099},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-63","text":"Well then, we said that it is not a State merely; because, if it were,\r it might belong to one who slept all his life through and merely\r vegetated, or to one who fell into very great calamities: and so, if\r these possibilities displease us and we would rather put it into the\r rank of some kind of Working (as was also said before), and Workings\r are of different kinds (some being necessary and choice-worthy with a\r view to other things, while others are so in themselves), it is plain\r we must rank Happiness among those choice-worthy for their own sakes\r and not among those which are so with a ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1100},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-64","text":"By choice-worthy in themselves are meant those from which nothing is\r sought beyond the act of Working: and of this kind are thought to be\r the actions according to Virtue, because doing what is noble and\r excellent is one of those things which are choice-worthy for their own\r sake alone.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1101},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-65","text":"And again, such amusements as are pleasant; because people do not\r choose them with any further purpose: in fact they receive more harm\r than profit from them, neglecting their persons and their property.\r Still the common run of those who are judged happy take refuge in such\r pastimes, which is the reason why they who have varied talent in such\r are highly esteemed among despots; because they make themselves\r pleasant in those things which these aim at, and these accordingly want\r such men.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1102},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-66","text":"Now these things are thought to be appurtenances of Happiness because\r men in power spend their leisure herein: yet, it may be, we cannot\r argue from the example of such men: because there is neither Virtue nor\r Intellect necessarily involved in having power, and yet these are the\r only sources of good Workings: nor does it follow that because these\r men, never having tasted pure and generous Pleasure, take refuge in\r bodily ones, we are therefore to believe them to be more choice-worthy:\r for children too believe that those things are most excellent which are\r precious in their eyes.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1103},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-67","text":"We may well believe that as children and men have different ideas as to\r what is precious so too have the bad and the good: therefore, as we\r have many times said, those things are really precious and pleasant\r which seem so to the good man: and as to each individual that Working\r is most choice-worthy which is in accordance with his own state to the\r good man that is so which is in accordance with Virtue.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1104},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-68","text":"Happiness then stands not in amusement; in fact the very notion is\r absurd of the End being amusement, and of one’s toiling and enduring\r hardness all one’s life long with a view to amusement: for everything\r in the world, so to speak, we choose with some further End in view,\r except Happiness, for that is the End comprehending all others. Now to\r take pains and to labour with a view to amusement is plainly foolish\r and very childish: but to amuse one’s self with a view to steady\r employment afterwards, as Anacharsis says, is thought to be right: for\r amusement is like rest, and men want rest ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1105},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-69","text":"Rest, therefore, is not an End, because it is adopted with a view to\r Working afterwards.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1106},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-70","text":"Again, it is held that the Happy Life must be one in the way of\r Excellence, and this is accompanied by earnestness,[13] and stands not\r in amusement. Moreover those things which are done in earnest, we say,\r are better than things merely ludicrous and joined with amusement: and\r we say that the Working of the better part, or the better man, is more\r earnest; and the Working of the better is at once better and more\r capable of Happiness.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1107},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-71","text":"Then, again, as for bodily Pleasures, any ordinary person, or even a\r slave, might enjoy them, just as well as the best man living but\r Happiness no one supposes a slave to share except so far as it is\r implied in life: because Happiness stands not in such pastimes but in\r the Workings in the way of Excellence, as has also been stated before.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1108},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-72","text":"Now if Happiness is a Working in the way of Excellence of course that\r Excellence must be the highest, that is to say, the Excellence of the\r best Principle. Whether then this best Principle is Intellect or some\r other which is thought naturally to rule and to lead and to conceive of\r noble and divine things, whether being in its own nature divine or the\r most divine of all our internal Principles, the Working of this in\r accordance with its own proper Excellence must be the perfect\r Happiness.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1109},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-73","text":"That it is Contemplative has been already stated: and this would seem\r to be consistent with what we said before and with truth: for, in the\r first place, this Working is of the highest kind, since the Intellect\r is the highest of our internal Principles and the subjects with which\r it is conversant the highest of all which fall within the range of our\r knowledge.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1110},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-74","text":"Next, it is also most Continuous: for we are better able to contemplate\r than to do anything else whatever, continuously.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1111},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-75","text":"Again, we think Pleasure must be in some way an ingredient in\r Happiness, and of all Workings in accordance with Excellence that in\r the way of Science is confessedly most pleasant: at least the pursuit\r of Science is thought to contain Pleasures admirable for purity and\r permanence; and it is reasonable to suppose that the employment is more\r pleasant to those who have mastered, than to those who are yet seeking\r for, it.[14]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1112},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-76","text":"And the Self-Sufficiency which people speak of will attach chiefly to\r the Contemplative Working: of course the actual necessaries of life are\r needed alike by the man of science, and the just man, and all the other\r characters; but, supposing all sufficiently supplied with these, the\r just man needs people towards whom, and in concert with whom, to\r practise his justice; and in like manner the man of perfected\r self-mastery, and the brave man, and so on of the rest; whereas the man\r of science can contemplate and speculate even when quite alone, and the\r more entirely he deserves the appellat","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1113},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-77","text":"Again, this alone would seem to be rested in for its own sake, since\r nothing results from it beyond the fact of having contemplated; whereas\r from all things which are objects of moral action we do mean to get\r something beside the doing them, be the same more or less.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1114},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-78","text":"Also, Happiness is thought to stand in perfect rest;[15] for we toil\r that we may rest, and war that we may be at peace. Now all the\r Practical Virtues require either society or war for their Working, and\r the actions regarding these are thought to exclude rest; those of war\r entirely, because no one chooses war, nor prepares for war, for war’s\r sake: he would indeed be thought a bloodthirsty villain who should make\r enemies of his friends to secure the existence of fighting and\r bloodshed. The Working also of the statesman excludes the idea of rest,\r and, beside the actual work of government,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1115},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-79","text":"If then of all the actions in accordance with the various virtues those\r of policy and war are pre-eminent in honour and greatness, and these\r are restless, and aim at some further End and are not choice-worthy for\r their own sakes, but the Working of the Intellect, being apt for\r contemplation, is thought to excel in earnestness, and to aim at no End\r beyond itself and to have Pleasure of its own which helps to increase\r the Working, and if the attributes of Self-Sufficiency, and capacity of\r rest, and unweariedness (as far as is compatible with the infirmity of\r human nature), and all other ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1116},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-80","text":"But such a life will be higher than mere human nature, because a man\r will live thus, not in so far as he is man but in so far as there is in\r him a divine Principle: and in proportion as this Principle excels his\r composite nature so far does the Working thereof excel that in\r accordance with any other kind of Excellence: and therefore, if pure\r Intellect, as compared with human nature, is divine, so too will the\r life in accordance with it be divine compared with man’s ordinary life.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1117},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-81","text":"Yet must we not give ear to those who bid one as man to mind only man’s\r affairs, or as mortal only mortal things; but, so far as we can, make\r ourselves like immortals and do all with a view to living in accordance\r with the highest Principle in us, for small as it may be in bulk yet in\r power and preciousness it far more excels all the others.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1118},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-82","text":"In fact this Principle would seem to constitute each man’s “Self,”\r since it is supreme and above all others in goodness it _would_ be\r absurd then for a man not to choose his own life but that of some\r other.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1119},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-83","text":"And here will apply an observation made before, that whatever is proper\r to each is naturally best and pleasantest to him: such then is to Man\r the life in accordance with pure Intellect (since this Principle is\r most truly Man), and if so, then it is also the happiest.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1120},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-84","text":"And second in degree of Happiness will be that Life which is in\r accordance with the other kind of Excellence, for the Workings in\r accordance with this are proper to Man: I mean, we do actions of\r justice, courage, and the other virtues, towards one another, in\r contracts, services of different kinds, and in all kinds of actions and\r feelings too, by observing what is befitting for each: and all these\r plainly are proper to man. Further, the Excellence of the Moral\r character is thought to result in some points from physical\r circumstances, and to be, in many, very closely connected with the\r","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1121},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-85","text":"Again, Practical Wisdom[17] and Excellence of the Moral character are\r very closely united; since the Principles of Practical Wisdom are in\r accordance with the Moral Virtues and these are right when they accord\r with Practical Wisdom.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1122},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-86","text":"These moreover, as bound up with the passions, must belong to the\r composite nature, and the Excellences or Virtues of the composite\r nature are proper to man: therefore so too will be the life and\r Happiness which is in accordance with them. But that of the Pure\r Intellect is separate and distinct: and let this suffice upon the\r subject, since great exactness is beyond our purpose,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1123},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-87","text":"It would seem, moreover, to require supply of external goods to a small\r degree, or certainly less than the Moral Happiness: for, as far as\r necessaries of life are concerned, we will suppose both characters to\r need them equally (though, in point of fact, the man who lives in\r society does take more pains about his person and all that kind of\r thing; there will really be some little difference), but when we come\r to consider their Workings there will be found a great difference.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1124},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-88","text":"I mean, the liberal man must have money to do his liberal actions with,\r and the just man to meet his engagements (for mere intentions are\r uncertain, and even those who are unjust make a pretence of _wishing_\r to do justly), and the brave man must have power, if he is to perform\r any of the actions which appertain to his particular Virtue, and the\r man of perfected self-mastery must have opportunity of temptation, else\r how shall he or any of the others display his real character?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1125},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-89","text":"(By the way, a question is sometimes raised, whether the moral choice\r or the actions have most to do with Virtue, since it consists in both:\r it is plain that the perfection of virtuous action requires both: but\r for the actions many things are required, and the greater and more\r numerous they are the more.) But as for the man engaged in\r Contemplative Speculation, not only are such things unnecessary for his\r Working, but, so to speak, they are even hindrances: as regards the\r Contemplation at least; because of course in so far as he is Man and\r lives in society he chooses to do what Virtue ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1126},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-90","text":"And that the perfect Happiness must be a kind of Contemplative Working\r may appear also from the following consideration: our conception of the\r gods is that they are above all blessed and happy: now what kind of\r Moral actions are we to attribute to them? those of justice? nay, will\r they not be set in a ridiculous light if represented as forming\r contracts, and restoring deposits, and so on? well then, shall we\r picture them performing brave actions, withstanding objects of fear and\r meeting dangers, because it is noble to do so? or liberal ones? but to\r whom shall they be giving? and furthe","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1127},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-91","text":"Still, every one believes that they live, and therefore that they Work\r because it is not supposed that they sleep their time away like\r Endymion: now if from a living being you take away Action, still more\r if Creation, what remains but Contemplation? So then the Working of the\r Gods, eminent in blessedness, will be one apt for Contemplative\r Speculation; and of all human Workings that will have the greatest\r capacity for Happiness which is nearest akin to this.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1128},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-92","text":"A corroboration of which position is the fact that the other animals do\r not partake of Happiness, being completely shut out from any such\r Working.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1129},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-93","text":"To the Gods then all their life is blessed; and to men in so far as\r there is in it some copy of such Working, but of the other animals none\r is happy because it in no way shares in Contemplative Speculation.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1130},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-94","text":"Happiness then is co-extensive with this Contemplative Speculation, and\r in proportion as people have the act of Contemplation so far have they\r also the being happy, not incidentally, but in the way of Contemplative\r Speculation because it is in itself precious.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1131},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-95","text":"So Happiness must be a kind of Contemplative Speculation; but since it\r is Man we are speaking of he will need likewise External Prosperity,\r because his Nature is not by itself sufficient for Speculation, but\r there must be health of body, and nourishment, and tendance of all\r kinds.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1132},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-96","text":"However, it must not be thought, because without external goods a man\r cannot enjoy high Happiness, that therefore he will require many and\r great goods in order to be happy: for neither Self-sufficiency, nor\r Action, stand in Excess, and it is quite possible to act nobly without\r being ruler of sea and land, since even with moderate means a man may\r act in accordance with Virtue.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1133},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-97","text":"And this may be clearly seen in that men in private stations are\r thought to act justly, not merely no less than men in power but even\r more: it will be quite enough that just so much should belong to a man\r as is necessary, for his life will be happy who works in accordance\r with Virtue.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1134},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-98","text":"Solon perhaps drew a fair picture of the Happy, when he said that they\r are men moderately supplied with external goods, and who have achieved\r the most noble deeds, as he thought, and who have lived with perfect\r self-mastery: for it is quite possible for men of moderate means to act\r as they ought.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1135},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-99","text":"Anaxagoras also seems to have conceived of the Happy man not as either\r rich or powerful, saying that he should not wonder if he were accounted\r a strange man in the judgment of the multitude: for they judge by\r outward circumstances of which alone they have any perception.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1136},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-100","text":"And thus the opinions of the Wise seem to be accordant with our account\r of the matter: of course such things carry some weight, but truth, in\r matters of moral action, is judged from facts and from actual life, for\r herein rests the decision. So what we should do is to examine the\r preceding statements by referring them to facts and to actual life, and\r when they harmonise with facts we may accept them, when they are at\r variance with them conceive of them as mere theories.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1137},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-101","text":"Now he that works in accordance with, and pays observance to, Pure\r Intellect, and tends this, seems likely to be both in the best frame of\r mind and dearest to the Gods: because if, as is thought, any care is\r bestowed on human things by the Gods then it must be reasonable to\r think that they take pleasure in what is best and most akin to\r themselves (and this must be the Pure Intellect); and that they requite\r with kindness those who love and honour this most, as paying observance\r to what is dear to them, and as acting rightly and nobly. And it is\r quite obvious that the man of Science chie","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1138},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-102","text":"Now then that we have said enough in our sketchy kind of way on these\r subjects; I mean, on the Virtues, and also on Friendship and Pleasure;\r are we to suppose that our original purpose is completed? Must we not\r rather acknowledge, what is commonly said, that in matters of moral\r action mere Speculation and Knowledge is not the real End but rather\r Practice: and if so, then neither in respect of Virtue is Knowledge\r enough; we must further strive to have and exert it, and take whatever\r other means there are of becoming good.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1139},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-103","text":"Now if talking and writing were of themselves sufficient to make men\r good, they would justly, as Theognis observes have reaped numerous and\r great rewards, and the thing to do would be to provide them: but in\r point of fact, while they plainly have the power to guide and stimulate\r the generous among the young and to base upon true virtuous principle\r any noble and truly high-minded disposition, they as plainly are\r powerless to guide the mass of men to Virtue and goodness; because it\r is not their nature to be amenable to a sense of shame but only to\r fear; nor to abstain from what is low an","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1140},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-104","text":"Men such as these then what mere words can transform? No, indeed! it is\r either actually impossible, or a task of no mean difficulty, to alter\r by words what has been of old taken into men’s very dispositions: and,\r it may be, it is a ground for contentment if with all the means and\r appliances for goodness in our hands we can attain to Virtue.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1141},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-105","text":"The formation of a virtuous character some ascribe to Nature, some to\r Custom, and some to Teaching. Now Nature’s part, be it what it may,\r obviously does not rest with us, but belongs to those who in the truest\r sense are fortunate, by reason of certain divine agency,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1142},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-106","text":"Then, as for Words and Precept, they, it is to be feared, will not\r avail with all; but it may be necessary for the mind of the disciple to\r have been previously prepared for liking and disliking as he ought;\r just as the soil must, to nourish the seed sown. For he that lives in\r obedience to passion cannot hear any advice that would dissuade him,\r nor, if he heard, understand: now him that is thus how can one reform?\r in fact, generally, passion is not thought to yield to Reason but to\r brute force. So then there must be, to begin with, a kind of affinity\r to Virtue in the disposition; which ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1143},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-107","text":"Yet perhaps it is not sufficient that men while young should get right\r food and tendance, but, inasmuch as they will have to practise and\r become accustomed to certain things even after they have attained to\r man’s estate, we shall want laws on these points as well, and, in fine,\r respecting one’s whole life, since the mass of men are amenable to\r compulsion rather than Reason, and to punishment rather than to a sense\r of honour.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1144},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-108","text":"And therefore some men hold that while lawgivers should employ the\r sense of honour to exhort and guide men to Virtue, under the notion\r that they will then obey who have been well trained in habits; they\r should impose chastisement and penalties on those who disobey and are\r of less promising nature; and the incurable expel entirely: because the\r good man and he who lives under a sense of honour will be obedient to\r reason; and the baser sort, who grasp at pleasure, will be kept in\r check, like beasts of burthen by pain. Therefore also they say that the\r pains should be such as are most contr","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1145},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-109","text":"As has been said already, he who is to be good must have been brought\r up and habituated well, and then live accordingly under good\r institutions, and never do what is low and mean, either against or with\r his will. Now these objects can be attained only by men living in\r accordance with some guiding Intellect and right order, with power to\r back them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1146},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-110","text":"As for the Paternal Rule, it possesses neither strength nor compulsory\r power, nor in fact does the Rule of any one man, unless he is a king or\r some one in like case: but the Law has power to compel, since it is a\r declaration emanating from Practical Wisdom and Intellect. And people\r feel enmity towards their fellow-men who oppose their impulses, however\r rightly they may do so: the Law, on the contrary, is not the object of\r hatred, though enforcing right rules.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1147},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-111","text":"The Lacedæmonian is nearly the only State in which the framer of the\r Constitution has made any provision, it would seem, respecting the food\r and manner of living of the people: in most States these points are\r entirely neglected, and each man lives just as he likes, ruling his\r wife and children Cyclops-Fashion.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1148},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-112","text":"Of course, the best thing would be that there should be a right Public\r System and that we should be able to carry it out: but, since as a\r public matter those points are neglected, the duty would seem to\r devolve upon each individual to contribute to the cause of Virtue with\r his own children and friends, or at least to make this his aim and\r purpose: and this, it would seem, from what has been said, he will be\r best able to do by making a Legislator of himself: since all public\r systems, it is plain, are formed by the instrumentality of laws and\r those are good which are formed by that of go","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1149},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-113","text":"For just as in Communities laws and customs prevail, so too in families\r the express commands of the Head, and customs also: and even more in\r the latter, because of blood-relationship and the benefits conferred:\r for there you have, to begin with, people who have affection and are\r naturally obedient to the authority which controls them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1150},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-114","text":"Then, furthermore, Private training has advantages over Public, as in\r the case of the healing art: for instance, as a general rule, a man who\r is in a fever should keep quiet, and starve; but in a particular case,\r perhaps, this may not hold good; or, to take a different illustration,\r the boxer will not use the same way of fighting with all antagonists.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1151},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-115","text":"It would seem then that the individual will be most exactly attended to\r under Private care, because so each will be more likely to obtain what\r is expedient for him. Of course, whether in the art of healing, or\r gymnastics, or any other, a man will treat individual cases the better\r for being acquainted with general rules; as, “that so and so is good\r for all, or for men in such and such cases:” because general maxims are\r not only said to be but are the object-matter of sciences: still this\r is no reason against the possibility of a man’s taking excellent care\r of some _one_ case, though he ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1152},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-116","text":"If then it appears that we may become good through the instrumentality\r of laws, of course whoso wishes to make men better by a system of care\r and training must try to make a Legislator of himself; for to treat\r skilfully just any one who may be put before you is not what any\r ordinary person can do, but, if any one, he who has knowledge; as in\r the healing art, and all others which involve careful practice and\r skill.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1153},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-117","text":"Will not then our next business be to enquire from what sources, or how\r one may acquire this faculty of Legislation; or shall we say, that, as\r in similar cases, Statesmen are the people to learn from, since this\r faculty was thought to be a part of the Social Science? Must we not\r admit that the Political Science plainly does not stand on a similar\r footing to that of other sciences and faculties? I mean, that while in\r all other cases those who impart the faculties and themselves exert\r them are identical (physicians and painters for instance) matters of\r Statesmanship the Sophists profess ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1154},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-118","text":"One can hardly suppose but that they would have done so if they could,\r seeing that they could have bequeathed no more precious legacy to their\r communities, nor would they have preferred, for themselves or their\r dearest friends, the possession of any faculty rather than this.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1155},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-119","text":"Practice, however, seems to contribute no little to its acquisition;\r merely breathing the atmosphere of politics would never have made\r Statesmen of them, and therefore we may conclude that they who would\r acquire a knowledge of Statesmanship must have in addition practice.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1156},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-120","text":"But of the Sophists they who profess to teach it are plainly a long way\r off from doing so: in fact, they have no knowledge at all of its nature\r and objects; if they had, they would never have put it on the same\r footing with Rhetoric or even on a lower: neither would they have\r conceived it to be “an easy matter to legislate by simply collecting\r such laws as are famous because of course one could select the best,”\r as though the selection were not a matter of skill, and the judging\r aright a very great matter, as in Music: for they alone, who have\r practical knowledge of a thing, can judge ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1157},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-121","text":"Now laws may be called the performances or tangible results of\r Political Science; how then can a man acquire from these the faculty of\r Legislation, or choose the best? we do not see men made physicians by\r compilations: and yet in these treatises men endeavour to give not only\r the cases but also how they may be cured, and the proper treatment in\r each case, dividing the various bodily habits. Well, these are thought\r to be useful to professional men, but to the unprofessional useless. In\r like manner it may be that collections of laws and Constitutions would\r be exceedingly useful to such a","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1158},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-122","text":"Since then those who have preceded us have left uninvestigated the\r subject of Legislation, it will be better perhaps for us to investigate\r it ourselves, and, in fact, the whole subject of Polity, that thus what\r we may call Human Philosophy may be completed as far as in us lies.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1159},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-11-123","text":"First then, let us endeavour to get whatever fragments of good there\r may be in the statements of our predecessors, next, from the Polities\r we have collected, ascertain what kind of things preserve or destroy\r Communities, and what, particular Constitutions; and the cause why some\r are well and others ill managed, for after such enquiry, we shall be\r the better able to take a concentrated view as to what kind of\r Constitution is best, what kind of regulations are best for each, and\r what laws and customs.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 11","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"11"},"sequenceIndex":1160},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-1","text":"[1] For this term, as here employed, our language contains no\r equivalent expression except an inconvenient paraphrase.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1161},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-2","text":"There are three senses which it bears in this treatise: the first (in\r which it is here employed) is its strict etymological signfication “The\r science of Society,” and this includes everything which can bear at all\r upon the well-being of Man in his social capacity, “Quicquid agunt\r homines nostri est farrago libelli.” It is in this view that it is\r fairly denominated most commanding and inclusive.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1162},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-3","text":"The second sense (in which it occurs next, just below) is “Moral\r Philosophy.” Aristotle explains the term in this sense in the Rhetoric\r (1 2) [Greek: hae peri ta aethae pragmateia aen dikaion esti\r prosagoreuen politikaen]. He has principally in view in this treatise\r the moral training of the Individual, the branch of the Science of\r Society which we call Ethics Proper, bearing the same relation to the\r larger Science as the hewing and squaring of the stones to the building\r of the Temple, or the drill of the Recruit to the manoeuvres of the\r field. Greek Philosophy viewed men principally a","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1163},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-4","text":"The third sense is “The detail of Civil Government,” which Aristotle\r expressly states (vi. 8) was the most common acceptation of the term.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1164},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-5","text":"[2] Matters of which a man is to judge either belong to some\r definite art or science, or they do not. In the former case he is the\r best judge who has thorough acquaintance with that art or science, in\r the latter, the man whose powers have been developed and matured by\r education. A lame horse one would show to a farmer, not to the best and\r wisest man of one’s acquaintance; to the latter, one would apply in a\r difficult case of conduct.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1165},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-6","text":"[3] In the last chapter of the third book of this treatise it\r is said of the fool, that his desire of pleasure is not only\r insatiable, but indiscriminate in its objects, πανταχόθεν.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1166},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-7","text":"[4] Ἀρχὴ is a word used in this treatise in various significations. The\r primary one is “beginning or first cause,” and this runs through all\r its various uses.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1167},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-8","text":"“Rule,” and sometimes “Rulers,” are denoted by this term the initiative\r being a property of Rule.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1168},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-9","text":"“Principle” is a very usual signification of it, and in fact the most\r characteristic of the Ethics. The word Principle means\r “starting-point.” Every action has two beginnings, that of Resolve οὗ\r ἕνεκα, and that of Action (ὅθεν ἡ κινήσις). I desire praise of men this\r then is the beginning of Resolve. Having considered how it is to be\r attained, I resolve upon some course and this Resolve is the beginning\r of Action.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1169},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-10","text":"The beginnings of Resolve, Ἀρχὶ or Motives, when formally stated, are\r the major premisses of what Aristotle calls the συλλογίσμοι τῶν\r πρακτῶν, i.e. the reasoning into which actions may be analysed.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1170},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-11","text":"Thus we say that the desire of human praise was the motive of the\r Pharisees, or the principle on which they acted.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1171},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-12","text":"Whatever gains human praise is to be done;\r Public praying and almsgiving gave human praise:\r [ergo] Public praying and almsgiving are to be done.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1172},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-13","text":"The major premisses may be stored up in the mind as rules of action,\r and this is what is commonly meant by having principles good or bad.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1173},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-14","text":"[5] The difficulty of this passage consists in determining the\r signification of the terms [Greek: gnorima aemin] and [Greek: gnorima\r aplos]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1174},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-15","text":"I have translated them without reference to their use elsewhere, as\r denoting respectively what _is_ and what _may_ be known. All truth is\r [Greek: gnorimon aplos], but that alone [Greek: aemin] which we\r individually realise, therefore those principles alone are [Greek:\r gnorima aemin] which _we have received as true_. From this appears\r immediately the necessity of good training as preparatory to the study\r of Moral Philosophy for good training in habits will either work\r principles into our nature, or make us capable of accepting them as\r soon as they are put before us; which no mere intell","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1175},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-16","text":"But these terms are employed elsewhere (Analytica Post I cap. 11. sect.\r 10) to denote respectively particulars and universals The latter are so\r denominated, because principles or laws must be supposed to have\r existed before the instances of their operation. Justice must have\r existed before just actions, Redness before red things, but since what\r we meet with are the concrete instances (from which we gather the\r principles and laws), the particulars are said to be [Greek:\r gnorimotera aemin]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1176},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-17","text":"Adopting this signification gives greater unity to the whole passage,\r which will then stand thus. The question being whether we are to assume\r principles, or obtain them by an analysis of facts, Aristotle says, “We\r must begin of course with what is known but then this term denotes\r either particulars or universals perhaps we then must begin with\r particulars and hence the necessity of a previous good training in\r habits, etc. (which of course is beginning with particular facts), for\r a fact is a starting point, and if this be sufficiently clear, there\r will be no want of the reason for the f","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1177},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-18","text":"The objection to this method of translation is, that [Greek: archai]\r occurs immediately afterwards in the sense of “principles.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1178},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-19","text":"[6] Or “prove themselves good,” as in the Prior Analytics, ii 25,\r [Greek: apanta pisteuomen k.t l] but the other rendering is supported\r by a passage in Book VIII. chap. ix. [Greek: oi d’ upo ton epieikon kai\r eidoton oregomenoi timaes bebaiosai ten oikeian doxan ephientai peri\r auton chairousi de oti eisin agathoi, pisteuontes te ton legonton\r krisei]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1179},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-20","text":"[7] [Greek: thesis] meant originally some paradoxical statement by any\r philosopher of name enough to venture on one, but had come to mean any\r dialectical question. Topics, I. chap. ix.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1180},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-21","text":"[8] A lost work, supposed to have been so called, because\r containing miscellaneous questions.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1181},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-22","text":"[9] It is only quite at the close of the treatise that Aristotle refers\r to this, and allows that [Greek: theoria] constitutes the highest\r happiness because it is the exercise of the highest faculty in man the\r reason of thus deferring the statement being that till the lower, that\r is the moral, nature has been reduced to perfect order, [Greek:\r theoria] cannot have place, though, had it been held out from the\r first, men would have been for making the experiment at once, without\r the trouble of self-discipline.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1182},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-23","text":"[11] The ἰδέα is the archetype, the εἶδος the concrete embodying the\r resemblance of it; hence Aristotle alludes to the theory under both\r names, and this is the reason for retaining the Greek terms.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1183},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-24","text":"[Greek:\r   to peras     to apeiron      |    to euthu\r   to perisson  to artion       |    to phos\r   to en        to plethos      |    to tetragonon\r   to dexion    to aristeron    |    to aeremoun\r   to arren     to thelu        |    to agathon\r   ]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1184},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-25","text":"[14] This is the capital defect in Aristotle’s eyes, who being\r eminently practical, could not like a theory which not only did not\r necessarily lead to action, but had a tendency to discourage it by\r enabling unreal men to talk finely. If true, the theory is merely a way\r of stating facts, and leads to no action.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1185},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-26","text":"[17] And then Happiness would at once be shown not to be the Chief\r Good. It is a contradiction in terms to speak of adding to the Chief\r Good. See Book X. chap. 11. [Greek: delon os oud allo ouden tagathon an\r eiae o meta tenos ton kath’ auto agathon airetoteron ginetai.]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1186},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-27","text":"[18] Compare Bishop Butler’s account of “Human Nature as a System” in\r the Preface to his Sermons.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1187},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-28","text":"[20] The mere translation of this term would convey no idea of its\r meaning, I have therefore retained the Greek term. It is afterwards\r explained to include space of time and external appliances requisite\r for the full development of Man’s energies; here the time only is\r alluded to.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1188},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-29","text":"[21] This principle is more fully stated, with illustrations,\r in the Topics, I. chap. ix.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1189},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-30","text":"[22] Either that of the bodily senses, or that of the moral senses.\r “Fire burns,” is an instance of the former, “Treason is odious,” of the\r latter.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1190},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-31","text":"[23] I have thought it worthwhile to vary the interpretation of this\r word, because though “habitus” may be equivalent to all the senses of\r [Greek: exis], “habit” is not, at least according to our colloquial\r usage we commonly denote by “habit” a state formed by habituation.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1191},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-32","text":"[24] Another and perhaps more obvious method of rendering this passage\r is to apply [Greek: kalon kagathon] to things, and let them depend\r grammatically on [Greek: epaeboli]. It is to be remembered, however,\r that [Greek: kalos kagathos] bore a special and well-known meaning also\r the comparison is in the text more complete, and the point of the\r passage seems more completely brought out.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1192},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-33","text":"[25] “Goodness always implies the love of itself, an affection to\r goodness.” (Bishop Butler, Sermon xiii ) Aristotle describes pleasure\r in the Tenth Book of this Treatise as the result of any faculty of\r perception meeting with the corresponding object, vicious pleasure\r being as truly pleasure as the most refined and exalted. If Goodness\r then implies the love of itself, the percipient will always have its\r object present, and pleasure continually result.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1193},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-34","text":"[26] In spite of theory, we know as a matter of fact that external\r circumstances are necessary to complete the idea of Happiness not that\r Happiness is capable of addition, but that when we assert it to be\r identical with virtuous action we must understand that it is to have a\r fair field; in fact, the other side of [Greek: bios teleios].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1194},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-35","text":"[27] It is remarkable how Aristotle here again shelves what he\r considers an unpractical question. If Happiness were really a direct\r gift from Heaven, independently of human conduct, all motive to\r self-discipline and moral improvement would vanish He shows therefore\r that it is no depreciation of the value of Happiness to suppose it to\r come partly at least from ourselves, and he then goes on with other\r reasons why we should think with him.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1195},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-36","text":"[28] This term is important, what has been maimed was once perfect; he\r does not contemplate as possible the case of a man being born incapable\r of virtue, and so of happiness.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1196},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-37","text":"[32] Solon says, “Call no man happy till he is dead.” He must mean\r either, The man when dead _is_ happy (a), or, The man when dead _may be\r said to have been happy_ (b). If the former, does he mean positive\r happiness (a)? or only freedom from unhappiness (β)? _We_ cannot allow\r (a), Men’s opinions disallow (β), We revert now to the consideration of\r (b).","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1197},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-38","text":"[33] The difficulty was raised by the clashing of a notion commonly\r held, and a fact universally experienced. Most people conceive that\r Happiness should be abiding, every one knows that fortune is\r changeable. It is the notion which supports the definition, because we\r have therein based Happiness on the most abiding cause.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1198},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-39","text":"[34] I have taken τούτον αὐτῶν to refer to ἐπιστημῶν, against Magirus\r and the Paraphrase of Andronicus Rhodius. I would refer to Aristotle’s\r account of θεωρία in the Tenth Book, chap. vii. where he expressly says\r of the working of νοῦς or pure intelect, that it is “most continuous.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1199},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-40","text":"[35] The term seems to be employed advisedly. The Choragus, of\r course, dressed his actors _for their parts;_ not according to their\r fancies or his own.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1200},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-41","text":"Hooker has (E. P. v. ixxvi. 5) a passage which seems to be an admirable\r paraphrase on this.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1201},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-42","text":"“Again, that the measure of our outward prosperity be taken by\r proportion with that which every man’s estate in this present life\r requireth. External abilities are instruments of action. It contenteth\r wise artificers to have their instruments proportionable to their work,\r rather fit for use than huge and goodly to please the eye. Seeing then\r the actions of a servant do not need that which may be necessary for\r men of calling and place in the world, neither men of inferior\r condition many things which greater personages can hardly want; surely\r they are blessed in worldly respects who have","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1202},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-43","text":"[37] The meaning is this: personal fortunes, we have said, must be in\r certain weight and number to affect our own happiness, this will be\r true, of course, of those which are reflected on us from our friends:\r and these are the only ones to which the dead are supposed to be\r liable? add then the difference of sensibility which it is fair to\r presume, and there is a very small residuum of joy or sorrow.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1203},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-44","text":"[38] This is meant for an exhaustive division of goods, which are\r either so _in esse_ or _in posse_.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1204},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-45","text":"If _in esse_, they are either above praise, or subjects of praise.\r Those _in posse_, here called faculties, are good only when rightly\r used. Thus Rhetoric is a faculty which may be used to promote justice\r or abused to support villainy. Money in like way.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1205},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-46","text":"[39] The doubt is, whether [Greek] or [Greek] is the subject of the\r sentence. It is translated as above, not merely with reference to the\r sense of this passage, but on a comparison with a similar one in Book\r X. chap 8. [Greek].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1206},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-47","text":"[40] Eudoxus, a philosopher holding the doctrine afterwards adopted by\r Epicurus respecting pleasure, but (as Aristotle testifies in the Tenth\r Book) of irreproachable character.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1207},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-48","text":"[43] The terms are borrowed from the Seventh Book and are here used in\r their strict philosophical meaning. The [Greek: enkrates] is he who has\r bad or unruly appetites, but whose reason is strong enough to keep them\r under. The [Greek: akrates] is he whose appetites constantly prevail\r over his reason and previous good resolutions.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1208},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-49","text":"By the law of habits the former is constantly approximating to a state\r in which the appetites are wholly quelled. This state is called [Greek:\r sophrosyne], and the man in it [Greek: sophron]. By the same law the\r remonstrances of reason in the latter grow fainter and fainter till\r they are silenced for ever. This state is called [Greek: akolasia], and\r the man in it [Greek: akolastos].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1209},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-50","text":"[44] This is untranslateable. As the Greek phrase, [Greek: echein logon\r tinos], really denotes substituting that person’s [Greek: logos] for\r one’s own, so the Irrational nature in a man of self-control or\r perfected self-mastery substitutes the orders of Reason for its own\r impulses. The other phrase means the actual possession of mathematical\r truths as part of the mental furniture, _i.e._ knowing them.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1210},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-12-51","text":"[45] [Greek: xin] may be taken as opposed to [Greek: energeian], and\r the meaning will be, to show a difference between Moral and\r Intellectual Excellences, that men are commended for merely having the\r latter, but only for exerting and using the former.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 12","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1211},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-1","text":"[5] It is, in truth, in the application of rules to particular details\r of practice that our moral Responsibility chiefly lies no rule can be\r so framed, that evasion shall be impossible. See Bishop Butler’s Sermon\r on the character of Balaam, and that on Self-Deceit.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1212},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-2","text":"[6] The words ἀκόλαστος and δειλὸς are not used here in their strict\r significations to denote confirmed states of vice: the ἐγκρατὴς\r necessarily feels pain, because he must always be thwarting passions\r which are a real part of his nature; though this pain will grow less\r and less as he nears the point of σωφροσύνη or perfected Self-Mastery,\r which being attained the pain will then and then only cease entirely.\r So a certain degree of fear is necessary to the _formation_ of true\r courage. All that is meant here is, that no habit of courage or\r self-mastery can be said to be matured, until pa","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1213},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-3","text":"[7] Virtue consists in the due regulation of _all_ the parts of our\r nature our passions are a real part of that nature, and as such have\r their proper office, it is an error then to aim at their extirpation.\r It is true that in a perfect moral state emotion will be rare, but then\r this will have been gained by regular process, being the legitimate\r result of the law that “passive impressions weaken as active habits are\r strengthened, by repetition.” If musical instruments are making\r discord, I may silence or I may bring them into harmony in either case\r I get rid of discord, but in the latte","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1214},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-4","text":"[8] I have adopted this word from our old writers, because our word\r _act_ is so commonly interchanged with _action_. [Greek: Praxis]\r (action) properly denotes the whole process from the conception to the\r performance. [Greek: Pragma] (fact) only the result. The latter may be\r right when the former is wrong if, for example, a murderer was killed\r by his accomplices. Again, the [Greek: praxis] may be _good_ though the\r [Greek: pragma] be wrong, as if a man under erroneous impressions does\r what would have been right if his impressions had been true (subject of\r course to the question how far h","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1215},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-5","text":"[9] Being about to give a strict logical definition of Virtue,\r Aristotle ascertains first what is its genus [Greek: ti estin].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1216},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-6","text":"See Bishop Butler’s account of our nature as containing “particular\r propensions,” in sect. iv. of the chapter on Moral discipline, and in\r the Preface to the Sermons.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1217},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-7","text":"[11] This refers to the division of quantity ([Greek: poson]) in the\r Categories. Those Quantities are called by Aristotle Continuous whose\r parts have position relatively to one another, as a line, surface, or\r solid, those discrete, whose parts have no such relation, as numbers\r themselves, or any string of words grammatically unconnected.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1218},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-8","text":"[12] Numbers are in arithmetical proportion (more usually called\r progression), when they increase or decrease by a common difference\r thus, 2, 6, 10 are so, because 2 + 4 = 6, 6 + 4= 10, or _vice versa_,\r 10 - 4 = 6, 6 - 4 = 2.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1219},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-9","text":"[13] If the mina be taken at 15 oz. avoirdupois, (Dict. of G. and R.\r Antiquities, article _Talentum_,) we must be sadly degenerate in our\r gastric capacity.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1220},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-10","text":"[14] The two are necessary, because since the reason itself may be\r perverted, a man must have recourse to an external standard; we may\r suppose his [Greek: logos] originally to have been a sufficient guide,\r but when he has injured his moral perceptions in any degree, he must go\r out of himself for direction.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1221},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-11","text":"[15] This is one of the many expressions which seem to imply that this\r treatise is rather a collection of notes of a _vivâ voce_ lecture than\r a set formal treatise. “The table” of virtues and vices probably was\r sketched out and exhibited to the audience.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1222},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-12","text":"[17] We have no term exactly equivalent; it may be illustrated by\r Horace’s use of the term _hiatus_:","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1223},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-13","text":"“Quid dignum tanto feret hic promissor hiatu?” Opening the mouth wide\r gives a promise of something great to come, if nothing great does come,\r this is a case of [Greek: chaunotes] or fruitless and unmeaning\r _hiatus_; the transference to the present subject is easy.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1224},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-14","text":"[18] In like manner _we_ talk of laudable ambition, implying of course\r there may be that which is not laudable.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1225},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-15","text":"[19] An expression of Bishop Butler’s, which corresponds exactly to the\r definition of [Greek: nemesis] in the Rhetoric.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1226},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-16","text":"[20] That is, in the same genus; to be contraries, things must be\r generically connected: [Greek: ta pleiston allelon diestekota ton en to\r auto genei enantia orizontai]. Categories, iv. 15.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1227},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-17","text":"[21] “[Greek: Deuteros plous] is a proverb,” says the Scholiast on the\r Phaedo, “used of those who do anything safely and cautiously inasmuch\r as they who have miscarried in their first voyage, set about then:\r preparations for the second cautiously,” and he then alludes to this\r passage.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1228},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-18","text":"[22] That is, you must allow for the _recoil_. “Naturam expellas furca\r tamen usque recurret.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1229},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-19","text":"P. 43, l. 2. This illustration sets in so clear a light the doctrines\r entertained respectively by Aristotle, Eudoxus, and the Stoics\r regarding pleasure, that it is worth while to go into it fully.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1230},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-20","text":"The reference is to Iliad iii. 154-160. The old counsellors, as Helen\r comes upon the city wall, acknowledge her surpassing beauty, and have\r no difficulty in understanding how both nations should have incurred\r such suffering for her sake still, fair as she is, home she must go,\r that she bring not ruin on themselves and their posterity.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1231},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-21","text":"This exactly represents Aristotle’s relation to Pleasure he does not,\r with Eudoxus and his followers, exalt it into the Summum Bonum (as\r Paris would risk all for Helen), nor does he the the Stoics call it\r wholly evil, as Hector might have said that the woes Helen had caused\r had “banished all the beauty from her cheek,” but, with the aged\r counsellors, admits its charms, but aware of their dangerousness\r resolves to deny himself, he “feels her sweetness, yet defies her\r thrall.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1232},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-13-22","text":"[24] Αἴσθησις is here used as an analogous noun, to denote the faculty\r which, in respect of moral matters, discharges the same function that\r bodily sense does in respect of physical objects. It is worth while to\r notice how in our colloquial language we carry out the same analogy. We\r say of a transaction, that it “looks ugly,” “sounds oddly,” is a “nasty\r job,” “stinks in our nostrils,” is a “hard dealing.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 13","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"13"},"sequenceIndex":1233},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-1","text":"[1] A man is not responsible for being [Greek: theratos], because\r “particular propensions, from their very nature, must be felt, the\r objects of them being present, though they cannot be gratified at all,\r or not with the allowance of the moral principle.” But he is\r responsible for being [Greek: eutheratos], because, though thus formed,\r he “might have improved and raised himself to an higher and more secure\r state of virtue by the contrary behaviour, by steadily following the\r moral principle, supposed to be one part of his nature, and thus\r withstanding that unavoidable danger of defection","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1234},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-2","text":"[2] Virtue is not only the duty, but (by the laws of the Moral\r Government of the World) also the interest of Man, or to express it in\r Bishop Butler’s manner, Conscience and Reasonable self-love are the two\r principles in our nature which of right have supremacy over the rest,\r and these two lead in point of fact the same course of action. (Sermon\r II.)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1235},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-3","text":"[3] Any ignorance of particular facts affects the rightness not of the\r [Greek: praxis], but of the [Greek: pragma], but ignorance of _i.e._\r incapacity to discern, Principles, shows the Moral Constitution to have\r been depraved, _i.e._ shows Conscience to be perverted, or the sight of\r Self-love to be impaired.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1236},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-4","text":"[4] [Greek: eneka] primarily denotes the relation of cause and effect\r all circumstances which in any way contribute to a cert result are\r [Greek: eneka] that result.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1237},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-5","text":"From the power which we have or acquire of deducing future results from\r present causes we are enabled to act towards, with a view to produce,\r these results thus [Greek: eneka] comes to mean not causation merely,\r but _designed_ causation and so [Greek: on eneka] is used for Motive,\r or final cause.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1238},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-6","text":"It is the primary meaning which is here intended, it would be a\r contradiction in terms to speak of a man’s being ignorant of his own\r Motive of action.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1239},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-7","text":"When the man “drew a bow at a venture and smote the King of Israel\r between the joints of the harnesss” (i Kings xxii 34) he did it [Greek:\r eneka ton apdkteinai] the King of Israel, in the primary sense of\r [Greek: eneka] that is to say, the King’s death was _in fact the\r result_, but could not have been the motive, of the shot, because the\r King was disguised and the shot was at a venture.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1240},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-8","text":"[5] Bishop Butler would agree to this: he says of settled deliberate\r anger, “It seems in us plainly connected with a sense of virtue and\r vice, of moral good and evil.” See the whole Sermon on Resentment.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1241},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-9","text":"[6] Aristotle has, I venture to think, rather quibbled here, by using\r [Greek: epithumia] and its verb, equivocally as there is no following\r his argument without condescending to the same device, I have used our\r word lust in its ancient signification Ps. xxiv. 12, “What man is he\r that lusteth to live?”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1242},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-10","text":"[7] The meaning is, that the _onus probandi_ is thrown upon the person\r who maintains the distinction, Aristotle has a _prima facie_ case. The\r whole passage is one of difficulty. Card wells text gives the passage\r from [Greek: dokei de] as a separate argument Bekker’s seems to intend\r al 81 ir/jd£eis as a separate argument but if so, the argument would be\r a mere _petitio principii_. I have adopted Cardwell’s reading in part,\r but retain the comma at [Greek: dmpho] and have translated the last\r four words as applying to the whole discussion, whereas Cardwell’s\r reading seems to restrict them ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1243},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-11","text":"[8] _i.e._ on objects of Moral Choice, opinion of this kind is not the\r same as Moral Choice, because actions alone form habits and constitute\r character, opinions are in general _signs_ of character, but when they\r begin to be acted on they cease to be opinions, and merge in Moral\r Choice.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1244},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-12","text":"“Treason doth never prosper, what’s the reason?\r When it doth prosper, none dare call it Treason.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1245},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-13","text":"[9] The introduction of the words [Greek: dia tinos] seems a mere\r useless repetition, as in the second chapter [Greek: en tini] added to\r [Greek: peri ti]. These I take for some among the many indications that\r the treatise is a collection of notes for lectures, and not a finished\r or systematic one.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1246},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-14","text":"[10] Suppose that three alternatives lay before a man, each of the\r three is of course an object of Deliberation; when he has made his\r choice, the alternative chosen does not cease to be in nature an object\r of Deliberation, but superadds the character of being chosen and so\r distinguished. Three men are admitted candidates for an office, the one\r chosen is the successful candidate, so of the three [Greek: bouleuta],\r the one chosen is the [Greek: bouleuton proaireton].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1247},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-15","text":"[11] Compare Bishop Butler’s “System of Human Nature,” in the Preface\r to the Sermons.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1248},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-16","text":"[12] These words, [Greek: ek tou bouleusasthai—bouleusin], contain the\r account of the whole mental machinery of any action. The first step is\r a Wish, implied in the first here mentioned, viz. Deliberation, for it\r has been already laid down that Deliberation has for its object-matter\r means to Ends supposed to be set before the mind, the next step is\r Deliberation, the next Decision, the last the definite extending of the\r mental hand towards the object thus selected, the two last constitute\r [Greek: proairesis] in its full meaning. The word [Greek: orexis] means\r literally “a grasping at or","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1249},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-17","text":"The illustration then afforded by the polities alluded to is this, as\r the Kings first decided and then announced their decision for\r acceptance and execution by their subjects, so Reason, having decided\r on the course to be taken, communicates its decision to the Will, which\r then proceeds to move [Greek: ta organika merae]. To instance in an\r action of the mixed kind mentioned in the first chapter, safe arrival\r at land is naturally desired, two means are suggested, either a certain\r loss of goods, or trying to save both lives and goods, the question\r being debated, the former is chosen, thi","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1250},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-18","text":"[13] Compare the statement in the Rhetoric, 1 10, [Greek: esti d hae\r men boulaeis agathou orexis (oudeis gar bouletai all ae otan oiaetho\r einai agathon)]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1251},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-19","text":"[14] A stone once set in motion cannot be recalled, because it is then\r placed under the operation of natural laws which cannot be controlled\r or altered, so too in Moral declension, there is a point at which\r gravitation operates irretrievably, “there is a certain bound to\r imprudence and misbehaviour which being transgressed, there remains no\r place for repentance in the natural course of things.” Bishop Butler’s\r Analogy, First Part, chap 11.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1252},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-20","text":"[15] Habits being formed by acting in a certain way under certain\r circumstances we can only choose how we will act not what circumstances\r we will have to act under.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1253},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-21","text":"[17] The meaning of this passage can scarcely be conveyed except by a\r paraphrase.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1254},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-22","text":"“The object of each separate act of working is that which accords with\r the habit they go to form. Courage is the habit which separate acts of\r bravery go to form, therefore the object of these is that which accords\r with Courage, _i.e._ Courage itself. But Courage is honourable (which\r implies that the end and object of it is honour, since things are\r denominated according to their end and object), therefore the object of\r each separate act of bravery is honour.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1255},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-23","text":"[18] For true Courage is required, i. Exact appreciation of danger. 2.\r A Proper motive for resisting fear. Each of the Spurious kinds will be\r found to fail in one or other, or both.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1256},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-24","text":"[19] This may merely mean, “who give strict orders” not to flinch,\r which would imply the necessity of compulsion The word is capable of\r the sense given above, which seems more forcible.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1257},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-25","text":"[20] See Book VI. chap. xiii. near the end [Greek: sokrataes aehen oun\r logous tas aretas oeto einai (epiotaemas gar einai pasas)]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1258},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-26","text":"[21] Such as the noise, the rapid movements, and apparent confusion\r which to an inexperienced eye and ear would be alarming. So Livy says\r of the Gauls, v. 37, Nata in _vanos_ tumultus gens.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1259},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-27","text":"[22]In Coronea in Bœotia, on the occasion of the citadel being betrayed\r to some Phocians. “The regulars” were Boeotian troops, the [Greek:\r politika] Coroneans.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1260},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-28","text":"[23] By the difference of tense it seems Aristotle has mixed up two\r things, beginning to speak of the particular instance, and then carried\r into the general statement again. This it is scarce worth while to\r imitate.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1261},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-14-29","text":"[24] The meaning of the phrase [Greek: kata sumbebaekos], as here used,\r in given in the Seventh Book, chap. X. [Greek: ei gar tis todi dia todi\r aireitai ae diokei, kath ahuto men touto diokei kai aireitai, kata\r sumbebaekos de to proteron].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 14","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"14"},"sequenceIndex":1262},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-1","text":"[1] Each term is important to make up the character of Justice, men\r must have the capacity, do the acts, and do them from moral choice.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1263},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-2","text":"[2] But not always. [Greek: Philein], for instance, has two senses, “to\r love” and “to kiss,” [Greek: misein] but one. Topics, I. chap. XIII. 5.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1264},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-3","text":"[3] _Things_ are [Greek: homonuma] which have only their name in\r common, being in themselves different. The [Greek: homonumia] is\r _close_ therefore when the difference though real is but slight. There\r is no English expression for [Greek: homonumia], “equivocal” being\r applied to a term and not to its various significates.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1265},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-4","text":"[4] See Book I. chap. 1. [Greek: toiautaen de tina planaen echei kai\r tagatha k.t.l.]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1266},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-5","text":"[5] A man habitually drunk in private is viewed by our law as confining\r his vice to himself, and the law therefore does not attempt to touch\r him; a religious hermit may be viewed as one who confines his virtue to\r his own person.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1267},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-6","text":"[7] Cardwell’s text, which here gives [Greek: paranomon], yields a much\r easier and more natural sense. All Injustice violates law, but only the\r particular kinds violate equality; and therefore the unlawful : the\r unequal :: universal Injustice the particular _i.e._ as whole to part.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1268},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-7","text":"There is a reading which also alters the words within the parenthesis,\r but this hardly affects the gist of the passage.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1269},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-8","text":"[8] There are two reasons why the characters are not necessarily\r coincident. He is a good citizen, who does his best to carry out the\r [Greek: politeia] under which he lives, but this may be faulty, so\r therefore _pro tanto_ is he.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1270},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-9","text":"Again, it is sufficient, so far as the Community is concerned, that he\r does the _facts_ of a good man but for the perfection of his own\r individual character, he must do them virtuously. A man may move\r rightly in his social orbit, without revolving rightly on his own axis.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1271},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-10","text":"The question is debated in the Politics, III. 2. Compare also the\r distinction between the brave man, and good soldier (supra, Book III.\r chap. xii.), and also Bishop Butler’s first Sermon.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1272},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-11","text":"[10] By [Greek:——] is meant numbers themselves, 4, 20, 50, etc, by\r [Greek:——] these numbers exemplified, 4 horses, 20 sheep, etc.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1273},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-12","text":"[11] The profits of a mercantile transaction (say £1000) are to be\r divided between A and B, in the ratio of 2 to 3 (which is the real\r point to be settled); then,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1274},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-13","text":"A : 400 :: B : 600 (permutando, and assuming a value for A and B, so as\r to make them commensurable with the respectiy sums).","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1275},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-14","text":"A+400 : B+600 :: A : B. This represents the actual distribution; its\r fairness depending entirely on that of the first proportion.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1276},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-15","text":"[14] I have omitted the next three lines, as they seem to be out of\r place here, and to occur much more naturally afterwards; it not being\r likely that they were originally twice written, one is perhaps at\r liberty to give Aristotle the benefit of the doubt, and conclude that\r he put them where they made the best sense.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1277},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-16","text":"[15] This I believe to be the meaning of the passage but do not pretend\r to be able to get it out of the words.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1278},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-17","text":"[16] This is apparently contrary to what was said before, but not\r really so. Aristotle does not mean that the man in authority struck\r wrongfully, but he takes the extreme case of simple Reciprocation, and\r in the second case, the man who strikes one in authority commits two\r offences, one against the person (and so far they are equal), and\r another against the office.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1279},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-18","text":"[17] χάρις denotes, 1st, a kindly feeling issuing in a gratuitous act\r of kindness, 2ndly, the effect of this act of kindness on a generous\r mind; 3rdly, this effect issuing in a requital of the kindness.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1280},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-19","text":"[18] The Shoemaker would get a house while the Builder only had (say)\r one pair of shoes, or at all events not so many as he ought to have.\r Thus the man producing the least valuable ware would get the most\r valuable, and _vice versa_.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1281},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-20","text":"Adopting, as I have done, the reading which omits [Greek:——] at\r [Greek:——], we have simply a repetition of the caution, that before\r Reciprocation is attempted, there must be the same ratio between the\r wares as between the persons, _i.e._ the ratio of equality.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1282},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-21","text":"If we admit [Greek: ou], the meaning may be, that you must not bring\r into the proportion the difference mentioned above [Greek: eteron kai\r ouk ison], since for the purposes of commerce all men are equal.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1283},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-22","text":"Say that the Builder is to the Shoemaker as 10:1. Then there must be\r the same ratio between the wares, consequently the highest artist will\r carry off the most valuable wares, thus combining in himself both\r [Greek: uperochai]. The following are the three cases, given 100 pr.\r shoes = 1 house.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1284},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-23","text":"Builder : Shoemaker : : 1  pr.  shoes      : 1 house—_wrong_.\r      ——          ——          100 pr. shoes      : 1 house—_right_\r      ——          ——          10 (100 pr. shoes) : 1 house—_wrong_.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1285},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-24","text":"[19] [Greek] Compare a similar use of [Greek]. De Interpretatione, II.\r 2. [Greek].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1286},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-25","text":"[20] Every unjust act embodies [Greek: to adikon], which is a violation\r of [Greek: to ison], and so implies a greater and a less share, the\r former being said to fall to the doer, the latter to the sufferer, of\r injury.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1287},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-26","text":"[21] This passage certainly occurs awkwardly here. If attached to the\r close of the preceding Chapter it would leave that Chapter incomplete,\r for the question is not gone into, but only stated. As the commencement\r of this Chapter it is yet more out of place; I should propose to insert\r it at the commencement of the following Chapter, to which it forms an\r appropriate introduction.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1288},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-27","text":"[22] In a pure democracy men are absolutely, _i.e._ numerically, equal,\r in other forms only proportionately equal. Thus the meanest British\r subject is proportionately equal to the Sovereign, that is to say, is\r as fully secured in his rights as the Sovereign in hers.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1289},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-28","text":"[23] Or, according to Cardwell’s reading ([Greek: kineton ou mentoi\r pan]) “but amongst ourselves there is Just, which is naturally\r variable, but certainly all Just is not such.” The sense of the passage\r is not affected by the reading. In Bekker’s text we must take [Greek:\r kineton] to mean the same as [Greek: kinoumenon], _i.e._ “we admit\r there is no Just which has not been sometimes disallowed, still,” etc.\r With Cardwell’s, [Greek: kineton] will mean “which not only _does_ but\r naturally _may_ vary.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1290},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-29","text":"[24] Murder is unjust by the law of nature, Smuggling by enactment.\r Therefore any act which can be referred to either of these heads is an\r unjust act, or, as Bishop Butler phrases it, an act _materially_\r unjust. Thus much may be decided without reference to the agent. See\r the note on page 32, l. 16.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1291},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-30","text":"[25] “As distinct from pain or loss.” Bishop Butler’s Sermon on\r Resentment. See also, Rhet. 11. 2 Def. of [Greek: orgae].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1292},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-31","text":"[26] This method of reading the passage is taken from Zell as quoted in\r Cardwell’s Notes, and seems to yield the best sense. The Paraphrast\r gives it as follows:","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1293},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-32","text":"“But the aggressor is not ignorant that he began, and so he feels\r himself to be wrong [and will not acknowledge that he is the\r aggressor], but the other does not.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1294},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-33","text":"[28] Where the stock of good is limited, if any individual takes more\r than his share some one else must have less than his share; where it is\r infinite, or where there is no good at all this cannot happen.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1295},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-34","text":"[29] The reference is to chap. vii. where it was said that the law\r views the parties in a case of particular injustice as originally\r equal, but now unequal, the wrong doer the gainer and the sufferer the\r loser by the wrong, but in the case above supposed there is but _one_\r party.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1296},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-35","text":"_Hae men gar psuchae tou somatos archei despotikaen archaen, o de nous\r taes orexeos politikaen kai despotikaev._","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1297},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-15-36","text":"Compare also Bishop Butler’s account of human nature as a system—of the\r different authority of certain principles, and specially the supremacy\r of Conscience.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 15","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"15"},"sequenceIndex":1298},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-1","text":"[1] I understand the illustration to be taken from the process of\r lowering a weight into its place; a block of marble or stone, for\r instance, in a building.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1299},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-2","text":"[3] One man learns Mathematics more easily than another, in common\r language, _he has a turn for_ Mathematics, _i e_ something in his\r mental conformation answers to that science The Phrenologist shows the\r bump denoting this aptitude.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1300},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-3","text":"[4] And therefore the question resolves itself into this, “What is the\r work of the Speculative, and what of the Practical, faculty of Reason.”\r See the description of _apetae_ II. 5.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1301},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-4","text":"[6] That is to say, the Will waits upon deliberation in which Reason is the\r judge; when the decision is pronounced, the Will must act accordingly.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1302},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-5","text":"The question at issue always is, _Is this Good?_ because the Will is\r only moved by an impression of Good; the Decision then will be always\r _Aye or No_, and the mental hand is put forth to grasp in the former\r case, and retracted in the later.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1303},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-6","text":"So far as what must take place in _every_ Moral Action, right or wrong,\r the Machinery of the mind being supposed uninjured but to constitute a\r good Moral Choice, _i e._. a good Action, the Reason must have said Aye\r when it ought.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1304},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-7","text":"The cases of faulty action will be, either when the Machinery is\r perfect but wrongly directed, as in the case of a deliberate crime, or\r when the direction given by the Reason is right but the Will does not\r move in accordance with that direction, in other words, when the\r Machinery is out of order; as in the case of the [Greek: akrates]—video\r meliora proboque, Deteriora sequor.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1305},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-8","text":"[8] The cobbler is at his last, why? to make shoes, which are to clothe\r the feet of someone and the price to be paid, _i.e._ the produce of his\r industry, is to enable him to support his wife and children; thus his\r production is subordinate to Moral Action.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1306},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-9","text":"[9] It may be fairly presumed that Aristotle would not thus have varied\r his phrase without some real difference of meaning. That difference is\r founded, I think, on the two senses of [Greek: orexis] before alluded\r to (note, p. 53, l. 33). The first impulse of the mind towards Action\r may be given either by a vague desire or by the suggestion of Reason.\r The vague desire passing through the deliberate stage would issue in\r Moral Choice. Reason must enlist the Will before any Action can take\r place.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1307},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-10","text":"Reason ought to be the originator in all cases, as Bishop Butler\r observes that Conscience should be. If this were so, every act of Moral\r Choice would be [Greek: orektikos nous].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1308},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-11","text":"But one obvious function of the feelings and passions in our composite\r nature is to instigate Action, when Reason and Conscience by themselves\r do not: so that as a matter of fact our Moral Choice is, in general,\r fairly described as [Greek: orexis dianoetike]. See Bishop Butler’s\r Sermon II. and the First upon Compassion.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1309},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-12","text":"[10] The mind attains truth, either for the sake of truth itself\r ([Greek: aplos]), or for the sake of something further ([Greek: eneka\r tinos]). If the first then either syllogistically ([Greek: episteme]),\r non-syllogistically ([Greek: nous]), or by union of the two methods\r ([Greek: sophla]). If the second, either with a view to _act_ ([Greek:\r phronesis]), or with a view to _make_ ([Greek: techne]).","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1310},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-13","text":"Otherwise. The mind contemplates Matter Necessary or Contingent. If\r necessary, Principles ([Greek: nous]), Deductions ([Greek: episteme]),\r or Mixed ([Greek: sophla]). If Contingent, Action ([Greek: phronesis]),\r Production ([Greek: techen]). (Giphanius quoted in Cardwell’s notes.)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1311},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-14","text":"[12] Aristotle in his logical analysis of Induction, Prior. Analytics\r II. 25, defines it to be “the proving the inherence of the major term\r in the middle (_i.e._ proving the truth of the major premiss in fig. 1)\r through the minor term.” He presupposes a Syllogism in the first Figure\r with an universal affirmative conclusion, which reasons, of course,\r from an universal, which universal is to be taken as proved by\r Induction. His doctrine turns upon a canon which he there quotes. “If\r of one and the same term two others be predicated, one of which is\r coextensive with that one and the same, ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1312},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-15","text":"All Magnets attract iron (Major premiss of the last Syllogism proved by\r taking the minor term of that for the middle term of this.)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1313},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-16","text":"Or, according to the canon quoted above: A B C are Magnets. A B C\r attract iron.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1314},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-17","text":"But [Greek: nous] tells me that the term Magnets is coextensive with\r the term A B C, therefore of all Magnets I may predicate that they\r attract iron.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1315},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-18","text":"Induction is said by Aristotle to be [Greek: hoia phanton], but he says\r in the same place that for this reason we must _conceive_ ([Greek:\r noehin]) the term containing the particular Instances (as A B C above)\r as composed of all the Individuals.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1316},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-19","text":"If Induction implied actual examination of all particular instances it\r would cease to be Reasoning at all and sink into repeated acts of\r Simple Apprehension it is really the bridging over of a chasm, not the\r steps cut in the rock on either side to enable us to walk down into and\r again out of it. It is a branch of probable Reasoning, and its validity\r depends _entirely_ upon the quality of the particular mind which\r performs it. Rapid Induction has always been a distinguishing mark of\r Genius the certainty produced by it is Subjective and not Objective. It\r may be useful to exhibit it Syllo","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1317},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-20","text":"[13] The reference is made to the Post Analyt I II and it is impossible\r to understand the account of [Greek: epistaemae] without a perusal of\r the chapter, the additions to the definition referred to relate to the\r nature of the premisses from which [Greek: epistaemae] draws its\r conclusions they are to be “true, first principles incapable of any\r syllogistic proof, better known than the conclusion, prior to it, and\r causes of it.” (See the appendix to this Book.)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1318},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-21","text":"[14] This is the test of correct logical division, that the _membra\r dividentia_ shall be opposed, _i.e._ not included the one by the other.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1319},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-22","text":"[15] The meaning of the [Greek: hepehi] appears to be this: the appeal\r is made in the first instance to popular language, just as it the case\r of [Greek: epistaemae], and will be in those of [Greek: phronaesis] and\r [Greek: sophia]. We commonly call Architecture an Art, and it is so and\r so, therefore the name Art and this so and so are somehow connected to\r prove that connection to be “coextensiveness,” we predicate one of the\r other and then simply convert the proposition, which is the proper test\r of any logical definition, or of any specific property. See the Topics,\r 1. vi.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1320},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-23","text":"[16] See the parable of the unjust Steward, in which the popular sense\r of [Greek: phronaesis] is strongly brought out; [Greek: ephaenesen ho\r kurios ton oikonomon taes adikias oti phronimos epoiaesen hoti ohi\r viohi tou aionos toutou phronimoteroi, k.t.l.]—Luke xvi. 8.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1321},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-24","text":"[17] Compare the [Greek: aplos] and [Greek: kath’ ekasta pepaideumenos]\r of Book I. chap. 1.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1322},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-25","text":"[18] The two aspects under which Virtue may be considered as claiming\r the allegiance of moral agents are, that of being right, and that of\r being truly expedient, because Conscience and Reasonable Self-Love are\r the two Principles of our moral constitution naturally supreme and\r “Conscience and Self-Love, _if we understand our true happiness_,\r always lead us the same way.” Bishop Butler, end of Sermon III.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1323},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-26","text":"“If by _a sense of interest_ is meant a practical regard to what is\r upon the whole our Happiness this is not only coincident with the\r principle of Virtue or Moral Rectitude, but is a part of the idea\r itself. And it is evident this Reasonable Self-Love wants to be\r improved as really as any principle in our nature. So little cause is\r there for Moralists to disclaim this principle.” From the note on sect.\r iv. of the chapter on Moral Discipline, Analogy, part I chap. v.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1324},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-27","text":"The student will find it worth while to compare this passage with the\r following—Chap. xiii. of this book beginning [Greek: e d’ exis to\r ommati touto k. t. l]—vii. 4. [Greek: eti kai ode physikos. k.t.l.]\r vii. 9.—[Greek: ae gar arethae kai ae mochthaeria. k.t.l.]—iii. 7 _ad\r finem_. [Greek: ei de tis legoi. k.t.l.]","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1325},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-28","text":"[20] This is not quite fair. Used in its strict sense, Art does not\r admit of degrees of excellence any more than Practical Wisdom. In\r popular language we use the term “wiser man,” as readily as “better\r artist” really denoting in each case different degrees of approximation\r to Practical Wisdom and Art respectively, [Greek: dia to ginesthai tous\r epainous di anaphoras]. I. 12.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1326},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-29","text":"[21] He would be a _better Chymist_ who should poison intentionally,\r than he on whose mind the prevailing impression was that “Epsom Salts\r mean Oxalic Acid, and Syrup of Senna Laudanum.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1327},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-30","text":"[22]The term Wisdom is used in our English Translation of the Old\r Testament in the sense first given to [Greek:——] here. “Then wrought\r Bezaleel and Ahohab, and every _wise-hearted man, in whom the Lord put\r wisdom and understanding_ to know how to work all manner of work for\r the service of the Sanctuary” Exodus xxxvi. i.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1328},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-31","text":"[23] [Greek:——] and [Greek:——], (in the strict sense, for it is used in\r many different senses in this book) are different parts of the whole\r function [Greek:——], [Greek:——] takes in conclusions, drawn by strict\r reasoning from Principles of a certain kind which [Greek: ——] supplies.\r It is conceivable that a man might go on gaining these principles by\r Intuition and never reasoning from them, and so [Greek: ——] might exist\r independent of [Greek:——], but not this without that. Put the two\r together, the head to the trunk, and you form the living being\r [Greek:——]. There are three branches of","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1329},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-32","text":"[24][Greek:——] is here used in its most extensive sense, [Greek:——]\r would be its chief Instrument.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1330},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-33","text":"[26] In every branch of Moral Action in which Practical Wisdom is\r employed there will be general principles, and the application of them,\r but in some branches there are distinct names appropriated to the\r operations of Practical Wisdom, in others there are not.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1331},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-34","text":"Thus Practical Wisdom, when employed on the general principles of Civil\r Government, is called Legislation, as administering its particular\r functions it is called simply Government. In Domestic Management, there\r are of course general Rules, and also the particular application of\r them; but here the faculty is called only by one name. So too when\r Self-Interest is the object of Practical Wisdom.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1332},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-35","text":"[28] Practical Wisdom may be employed either respecting Self, (which is\r [Greek:——] proper) or not-Self, _i.e._ either one’s family=[Greek:——],\r or one’s community=[Greek:——], but here the supreme and subordinate are\r distinguished, the former is [Greek:——], the latter [Greek:——] proper,\r whose functions are deliberation and the administration of justice.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1333},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-36","text":"[29] But where can this be done, if there be no community? see Horace’s\r account of the way in which his father made him reap instruction from\r the examples in the society around him. 1. Sat. iv. 105, etc. See also\r Bishop Butler, Analogy, part I. chap. v. sect. iii.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1334},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-37","text":"The whole question of the Selfish Morality is treated in Bishop\r Butler’s first three and the eleventh Sermons, in which he shows the\r coincidence in _fact_ of enlightened Self-Love and Benevolence _i.e._\r love of others. Compare also what is said in the first Book of this\r treatise, chap. v., about [Greek: autarkeia].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1335},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-38","text":"[30] More truly “implied,” namely, that Practical Wisdom results from\r experience.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1336},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-39","text":"[31] This observation seems to be introduced, simply because suggested\r by the last, and not because at all relevant to the matter in hand.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1337},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-40","text":"[32]  An instance of Principles gained [Greek: aisthesei]. (Book 1.\r chap. viii.)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1338},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-41","text":"[33] Particulars are called [Greek: eschata] because they are last\r arrived at in the deliberative process, but a little further on we have\r the term applied to first principles, because they stand at one\r extremity, and facts at the other, of the line of action.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1339},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-42","text":"[34] I prefer the reading [Greek: e phronesis], which gives this sense,\r “Well, as I have said, Practical Wisdom is this kind of sense, and the\r other we mentioned is different in kind.” In a passage so utterly\r unimportant, and thrown in almost colloquially, it is not worth while\r to take much trouble about such a point.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1340},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-43","text":"[35] The definition of it in the Organon (Post Analyt. 1. xxiv.), “a\r happy conjecture of the middle term without time to consider of it.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1341},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-44","text":"The quaestio states the phenomena, and the middle term the causation\r the rapid ascertaining of which constitutes [Greek: anchinoia]. All\r that receives light from the sun is bright on the side next to the sun.\r The moon receives light from the sun, The moon is bright on the side\r next the sun. The [Greek: anchinoia] consists in rapidly and correctly\r accounting for the observed fact, that the moon is bright on the side\r next to the sun.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1342},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-45","text":"[38] The meaning is, there is one End including all others; and in this\r sense [Greek: phronesis] is concerned with means, not Ends but there\r are also many subordinate Ends which are in fact Means to the Great End\r of all. Good counsel has reference not merely to the grand End, but to\r the subordinate Ends which [Greek: phronesis] selects as being right\r means to the Grand End of all.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1343},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-46","text":"[39] The relative [Greek: on] might be referred to [Greek: sumpheron],\r but that [Greek: eubonlia] has been already divided into two kinds, and\r this construction would restrict the name to one of them, namely that\r [Greek: pros ti telos] as opposed to that [Greek: pros to telos aplos].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1344},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-47","text":"[40] We have no term which at all approximates to the meaning of this\r word, much less will our language admit of the play upon it which\r connects it with [Greek: suggnomae].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1345},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-48","text":"[41] Meaning, of course, all those which relate to Moral Action.\r [Greek: psronaesis ] is equivalent to [Greek: euboulia, ounesis,\r gnomae, and nous] (in the new sense here given to it).","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1346},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-49","text":"The faculty which guides us truly in all matters of Moral Action is\r [Greek: phronaesis], i.e. Reason directed by Goodness or Goodness\r informed by Reason. But just as every faculty of body and soul is not\r actually in operation at the same time, though the Man is acting, so\r proper names are given to the various Functions of Practical Wisdom.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1347},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-50","text":"Is the [Greek: phronimos] forming plans to attain some particular End?\r he is then [Greek: euboulos]—is he passing under review the suggestions\r of others? he is [Greek: sunetos]—is he judging of the acts of others?\r he admits [Greek: gnomae] to temper the strictness of justness—is he\r applying general Rules to particular cases? he is exercising [Greek:\r nous praktikos] or [Greek: agsthaesis]—while in each and all he is\r [Greek: phronimos]?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1348},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-51","text":"[43] There are cases where we must simply accept or reject without\r proof: either when Principles are propounded which are prior to all\r reasoning, or when particular facts are brought before us which are\r simply matters of [Greek: agsthaesis]. Aristotle here brings both these\r cases within the province of [Greek: nous], _i.e._ he calls by this\r name the Faculty which attains Truth in each.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1349},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-52","text":"[45] See the note on [Greek: Archae] on p. 4,1 30. As a matter of fact\r and mental experience the Major Premiss of the Practica Syllogism is\r wrought into the mind by repeatedly acting upon the Minor Premiss\r (_i.e._ by [Greek: ethismos]).","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1350},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-53","text":"All that is pleasant is to be done,\r      This is pleasant,\r      This is to be done","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1351},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-54","text":"By habitually acting on the Minor Premiss, _i.e._ on the suggestions of\r [Greek: epithymia], a man comes really to hold the Major Premiss.\r Aristotle says of the man destitute of all self-control that he is\r firmly persuaded that it is his proper line to pursue the gratification\r of his bodily appetites, [Greek: dia to toioytos einai oios diokein\r aytas]. And his analysis of [Greek: akrasia] (the state of progress\r towards this utter abandonment to passion) shows that each case of\r previous good resolution succumbing to temptation is attributable to\r [Greek: epithymia] suggesting its own Minor","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1352},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-55","text":"There are cases both of principles and facts which cannot admit of\r reasoning, and must be authoritatively determined by [Greek: nous].\r What makes [Greek: nous] to be a true guide? only practice, i.e.\r Experience, and _therefore_, etc.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1353},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-56","text":"[47] This is a note to explain [Greek: hygieina] and [Greek: euektika],\r he gives these three uses of the term [Greek: hygieinon] in the Topics,\r I. xiii. 10,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1354},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-57","text":"{ [Greek: to men hygieias poiætikon], [Greek: hygieinon legetai]\r      { [Greek: to de phylaktikon],\r      { [Greek: to de sæmantikon].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1355},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-58","text":"[48] Healthiness is the formal cause of health.\r      Medicine is the efficient cause of health.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1356},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-59","text":"See Book X. chap. iv. [Greek: hosper oud hæ hygieia kai ho iatros\r homoios aitia esti tou ugiainein].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1357},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-60","text":"[49] [Greek: phronæsis] is here used in a partial sense to signify the\r Intellectual, as distinct from the Moral, element of Practical Wisdom.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1358},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-61","text":"[50] This is another case of an observation being thrown in _obiter_,\r not relevant to, but suggested by, the matter in hand.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1359},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-62","text":"[52]The article is supplied at [Greek: panourgous], because the\r abstract word has just been used expressly in a bad sense. “Up to\r anything” is the nearest equivalent to [Greek: panourgos], but too\r nearly approaches to a colloquial vulgarism.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1360},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-63","text":"We may paraphrase [Greek: to telos] by [Greek: ti dei prattein—ti gar\r dei prattein hæ mæ, to telos autæs estin] i.e. [Greek: tæs\r phronæseos].—(Chap. xi. of this Book.)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1361},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-64","text":"[56] The term [Greek: sophronikoi] must be understood as governing the\r signification of the other two terms, there being no single Greek term\r to denote in either case mere dispositions towards these Virtues.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1362},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-65","text":"[57] Compare the passage at the commencement of Book X. [Greek: nun de\r phainontai] [Greek: katokochimon ek tæs aretæs].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1363},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-16-66","text":"[58] It must be remembered, that [Greek: phronæsis] is used throughout\r this chapter in two senses, its proper and complete sense of Practical\r Wisdom, and its incomplete one of merely the Intellectual Element of\r it.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 16","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"16"},"sequenceIndex":1364},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-1","text":"[1] The account of Virtue and Vice hitherto given represents rather\r what men _may be_ than what they _are_. In this book we take a\r practical view of Virtue and Vice, in their ordinary, every day\r development.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1365},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-2","text":"[3] Another reading omits the [Greek:——]; the meaning of the whole\r passage would be exactly the same—it would then run, “if he had been\r convinced of the rightness of what he does, _i.e._ if he were now\r acting on conviction, he might stop in his course on a change of\r conviction.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1366},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-3","text":"[7] That is, as I understand it, either the major or the minor premise,\r it is true, that “all that is sweet is pleasant,” it is true also, that\r “this is sweet,” what is contrary to Right Reason is the bringing in\r this minor to the major _i.e._ the universal maxim, forbidding to\r taste. Thus, a man goes to a convivial meeting with the maxim in his\r mind “All excess is to be avoided,” at a certain time his [Greek:——]\r tells him “This glass is excess.” As a matter of mere reasoning, he\r cannot help receiving the conclusion “This glass is to be avoided,” and\r supposing him to be morally sound h","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1367},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-4","text":"The solution then of the phænomenon of [Greek:——] is this that\r [Greek:——], by its direct action on the animal nature, swamps the\r suggestions of Right Reason.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1368},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-5","text":"On the high ground of Universals, [Greek:——] i.e. [Greek:——] easily\r defeats [Greek:——]. The [Greek:——], an hour before he is in temptation,\r would never deliberately prefer the maxim “All that is sweet is to be\r tasted” to “All excess is to be avoided.” The [Greek:——] would.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1369},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-6","text":"Quæ virtus et quanta, bom, sit vivere parvo\r      Discite, _non inter lances mensasque nitentes_\r      Verum hic _impransi_ mecum disquirite","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1370},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-7","text":"Compare also Proverbs XXIII. 31. “Look not thou upon the wine when it\r is red,” etc.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1371},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-8","text":"[8] As we commonly speak, Metaphysicians. Physiology of course includes\r Metaphysics.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1372},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-9","text":"[9] [Greek: oron]. Aristotle’s own account of this word (Prior Analyt\r ii. 1) is [Greek: eis on dialuetai hae protasis], but both in the\r account of [Greek: nous] and here it seems that the proposition itself\r is really indicated by it.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1373},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-10","text":"[10] The Greek would give “avoids excessive pain,” but this is not\r true, for the excess of pain would be ground for excuse the warrant for\r translating as in the text, is the passage occurring just below [Greek:\r diokei tas uperbolas kai pheugei metrias lupas].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1374},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-11","text":"[11] Compare Bishop Butler on Particular Propensions, Analogy, Part I\r chap v sect. iv.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1375},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-12","text":"[14] Consult in connection with this Chapter the Chapter on [Greek:\r orgae] in the Rhetoric, II. 2, and Bishop Butler’s Sermon on\r Resentment.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1376},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-13","text":"[15] The reasoning here being somewhat obscure from the concisement of\r expression, the following exposition of it is subjoined.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1377},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-14","text":"Actions of Lust are wrong actions done with pleasure,\r      Wrong actions done with pleasure are more justly objects of wrath,[*]\r      Such as are more justly objects of wrath are more unjust,\r      Actions of Lust are more unjust","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1378},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-15","text":"[*] [Greek: hubpis] is introduced as the single instance from\r      which this premiss is proved inductively. See the account of it in\r      the Chapter of the Rhetoric referred to in the preceding note.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1379},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-16","text":"[16][Greek: ton dae lechthenton]. Considerable difference of opinion\r exists as to the proper meaning of these words. The emendation which\r substitutes [Greek: akrataes] for [Greek: akolastos] removes all\r difficulty, as the clause would then naturally refer to [Greek: ton mae\r proairoumenon] but Zell adheres to the reading in the text of Bekker,\r because the authority of MSS and old editions is all on this side.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1380},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-17","text":"I understand [Greek: mallon] as meant to modify the word [Greek:\r malakias], which properly denotes that phase of [Greek: akrasia] (not\r [Greek: akolasia]) which is caused by pain.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1381},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-18","text":"The [Greek: akolastos] _deliberately_ pursues pleasure and declines\r pain if there is to be a distinct name for the latter phase, it comes\r under [Greek: malakia] more nearly than any other term, though perhaps\r not quite properly.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1382},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-19","text":"Or the words may be understood as referring to the class of wrong acts\r caused by avoidance of pain, whether deliberate or otherwise, and then\r of course the names of [Greek: malakia] and [Greek: akolasia] may be\r fitly given respectively.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1383},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-20","text":"[17] “If we went into a hospital where all were sick or dying, we\r should think those least ill who were insensible to pain; a physician\r who knew the whole, would behold them with despair. And there is a\r mortification of the soul as well as of the body, in which the first\r symptoms of returning hope are pain and anguish” Sewell, Sermons to\r Young Men (Sermon xii.)","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1384},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-21","text":"[18] Before the time of trial comes the man deliberately makes his\r Moral Choice to act rightly, but, at the moment of acting, the powerful\r strain of desire makes him contravene this choice his Will does not act\r in accordance with the affirmation or negation of his Reason. His\r actions are therefore of the mixed kind. See Book III. chap. i, and\r note on page 128.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1385},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-22","text":"[19] Let a man be punctual _on principle_ to any one engagement in the\r day, and he must, as a matter of course, keep all his others in their\r due places relatively to this one; and so will often wear an appearance\r of being needlessly punctilious in trifles.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1386},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-23","text":"[20] Because he is destitute of these minor springs of action, which\r are intended to supply the defects of the higher principle.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1387},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-17-24","text":"See Bishop Butler’s first Sermon on Compassion, and the conclusion of\r note on p. 129.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 17","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"17"},"sequenceIndex":1388},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-18-1","text":"[1] “Owe no man anything, but to _love_ one another for he that loveth\r another _hath fulfilled the Law_.” Romans XIII. 8.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 18","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"18"},"sequenceIndex":1389},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-18-2","text":"[2] [Greek: kerameis]. The Proverb in full is a line from Hesiod,\r [Greek: kahi keramehus keramei koteei kai tektoni tekton].","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 18","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"18"},"sequenceIndex":1390},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-18-3","text":"“two stone bottles found,\r      To hold the liquor that she _loved_,\r      And keep it safe and sound.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 18","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"18"},"sequenceIndex":1391},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-18-4","text":"[4] Cardwell’s reading, [Greek: tautae gar omoioi, kai ta loipa] is\r here adopted, as yielding a better sense than Bekker’s.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 18","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"18"},"sequenceIndex":1392},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-18-5","text":"[5]The Great man will have a right to look for more Friendship than he\r bestows, but the Good man _can_ feel Friendship only for, and in\r proportion to, the goodness of the other.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 18","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"18"},"sequenceIndex":1393},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-18-6","text":"[8] “For the mutual society, help, and comfort that the one ought to\r have of the other, both in prosperity and adversity.”","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 18","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"18"},"sequenceIndex":1394},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-18-7","text":"[9] Which one would be assuming he was, if one declined to recognise\r the obligation to requite the favour or kindness.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 18","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"18"},"sequenceIndex":1395},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-19-1","text":"“In a few instances the Second Intention, or Philosophical employment\r of a Term, is more extensive than the First Intention, or popular use.”\r Whately, Logic, iii. 10.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 19","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"19"},"sequenceIndex":1396},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-19-2","text":"[2] “I have sometimes considered in what troublesome case is that\r Chamberlain in an Inn who being but one is to give attendance to many\r guests. For suppose them all in one chamber, yet, if one shall command\r him to come to the window, and the other to the table, and another to\r the bed, and another to the chimney, and another to come upstairs, and\r another to go downstairs, and all in the same instant, how would he be\r distracted to please them all? And yet such is the sad condition of nay\r soul by nature, not only a servant but a slave unto sin. Pride calls me\r to the window, gluttony to th","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 19","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"19"},"sequenceIndex":1397},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-20-1","text":"[4] The notion alluded to is that of the [greek: idea]: that there is\r no real substantial good except the [greek: auto agathon], and\r therefore whatever is so called is so named in right of its\r participation in that.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 20","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"20"},"sequenceIndex":1398},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-20-2","text":"P. 238, 1. 24. Movement is, according to Aristotle, of six kinds:\r    From not being to being    .  .  .  .    Generation\r    From being to not being    .  .  .  .    Destruction\r    From being to being more   .  .  .  .    Increase\r    From being to being less   .  .  .  .    Diminution\r    From being here to being there   .  .    Change of Place\r    From being in this way to being in that  Alteration","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 20","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"20"},"sequenceIndex":1399},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-20-3","text":"[7] _A_ may go to sleep quicker than _B_, but cannot _do more sleep_ in\r a given time.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 20","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"20"},"sequenceIndex":1400},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-20-4","text":"[11] Pleasure is so instantaneous a sensation, that it cannot be\r conceived divisible or incomplete; the longest continued Pleasure is\r only a succession of single sparks, so rapid as to give the appearance\r of a stream, of light.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 20","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"20"},"sequenceIndex":1401},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-20-5","text":"[12] A man is as effectually hindered from taking a walk by the [Greek:\r allotria haedouae] of reading a novel, as by the [Greek: oikeia lupae]\r of gout in the feet.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 20","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"20"},"sequenceIndex":1402},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-20-6","text":"[13] I have thus rendered [Greek: spoudae (ouk agnoon to\r hamartanomenon)]; but, though the English term does not represent the\r depth of the Greek one, it is some approximation to the truth to\r connect an earnest serious purpose with Happiness.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 20","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"20"},"sequenceIndex":1403},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-20-7","text":"“Knowledge is not our proper Happiness. Whoever will in the least\r attend to the thing will see that it is the gaining, not the having, of\r it, which is the entertainment of the mind.” The two statements may\r however be reconciled. Aristotle may be well understood only to mean,\r that the pursuit of knowledge will be the pleasanter, the freer it is\r from the minor hindrances which attend on _learning_.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 20","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"20"},"sequenceIndex":1404},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-20-8","text":"[15] The clause immediately following indicates that Aristotle felt\r this statement to be at first sight startling, Happiness having been\r all the way through connected with [Greek: energeia], but the statement\r illustrates and confirms what was said in note on page 6, 1. 15.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 20","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"20"},"sequenceIndex":1405},{"id":"aristotle-nicomach-20-9","text":"[16] That is to say, he aims at producing not merely a happy aggregate,\r but an aggregate of happy individuals. Compare what is said of\r Legislators in the last chapter of Book I and the first of Book II.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Nicomachean Ethics, Book 20","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Nicomachean Ethics","book":"20"},"sequenceIndex":1406},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-1","text":"As we see that every city is a society, and every society Ed. is\r established for some good purpose; for an apparent [Bekker 1252a] good\r is the spring of all human actions; it is evident that this is the\r principle upon which they are every one founded, and this is more\r especially true of that which has for its object the best possible, and\r is itself the most excellent, and comprehends all the rest. Now this is\r called a city, and the society thereof a political society; for those\r who think that the principles of a political, a regal, a family, and\r a herile government are the same are mis","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1407},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-2","text":"Now if in this particular science any one would attend to its original\r seeds, and their first shoot, he would then as in others have the\r subject perfectly before him; and perceive, in the first place, that it\r is requisite that those should be joined together whose species cannot\r exist without each other, as the male and the female, for the business\r of propagation; and this not through choice, but by that natural impulse\r which acts both upon plants and animals also, for the purpose of their\r leaving behind them others like themselves. It is also from natural\r causes that some beings comma","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1408},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-3","text":"SINCE it is now evident of what parts a city is composed, it will be\r necessary to treat first of family government, for every city is made\r up of families, and every family [1253b] has again its separate parts of\r which it is composed. When a family is complete, it consists of freemen\r and slaves; but as in every subject we should begin with examining into\r the smallest parts of which it consists, and as the first and smallest\r parts of a family are the master and slave, the husband and wife, the\r father and child, let us first inquire into these three, what each of\r them may be, and what the","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1409},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-4","text":"Since then a subsistence is necessary in every family, the means of\r procuring it certainly makes up part of the management of a family, for\r without necessaries it is impossible to live, and to live well. As\r in all arts which are brought to perfection it is necessary that they\r should have their proper instruments if they would complete their works,\r so is it in the art of managing a family: now of instruments some of\r them are alive, others inanimate; thus with respect to the pilot of the\r ship, the tiller is without life, the sailor is alive; for a servant\r is as an instrument in many arts","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1410},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-5","text":"But whether any person is such by nature, and whether it is advantageous\r and just for any one to be a slave or no, or whether all slavery is\r contrary to nature, shall be considered hereafter; not that it is\r difficult to determine it upon general principles, or to understand\r it from matters of fact; for that some should govern, and others be\r governed, is not only necessary but useful, and from the hour of their\r birth some are marked out for those purposes, and others for the other,\r and there are many species of both sorts. And the better those are who\r are governed the better also is the","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1411},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-6","text":"But it is not difficult to perceive that those who maintain the contrary\r opinion have some reason on their side; for a man may become a slave two\r different ways; for he may be so by law also, and this law is a certain\r compact, by which whatsoever is taken in battle is adjudged to be the\r property of the conquerors: but many persons who are conversant in law\r call in question this pretended right, and say that it would be hard\r that a man should be compelled by violence to be the slave and subject\r of another who had the power to compel him, and was his superior in\r strength; and upon this s","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1412},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-7","text":"\"Who dares reproach me with the name of slave? When from the\r immortal gods, on either side, I draw my lineage.\"","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1413},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-8","text":"Those who express sentiments like these, shew only that they distinguish\r the slave and the freeman, the noble and the ignoble from each other\r by their virtues and their [1255b] vices; for they think it reasonable,\r that as a man begets a man, and a beast a beast, so from a good man, a\r good man should be descended; and this is what nature desires to do, but\r frequently cannot accomplish it. It is evident then that this doubt\r has some reason in it, and that these persons are not slaves, and those\r freemen, by the appointment of nature; and also that in some instances\r it is sufficiently clea","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1414},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-9","text":"It is evident from what has been said, that a herile and a political\r government are not the same, or that all governments are alike to each\r other, as some affirm; for one is adapted to the nature of freemen, the\r other to that of slaves. Domestic government is a monarchy, for that is\r what prevails in every house; but a political state is the government of\r free men and equals. The master is not so called from his knowing how to\r manage his slave, but because he is so; for the same reason a slave and\r a freeman have their respective appellations. There is also one sort of\r knowledge proper f","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1415},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-10","text":"[1256a] As a slave is a particular species of property, let us by\r all means inquire into the nature of property in general, and the\r acquisition of money, according to the manner we have proposed. In the\r first place then, some one may doubt whether the getting of money is\r the same thing as economy, or whether it is a part of it, or something\r subservient to it; and if so, whether it is as the art of making\r shuttles is to the art of weaving, or the art of making brass to that\r of statue founding, for they are not of the same service; for the one\r supplies the tools, the other the matter: by","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1416},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-11","text":"for they may be fixed as in other arts; for the instruments of no art\r whatsoever are infinite, either in their number or their magnitude; but\r riches are a number of instruments in domestic and civil economy; it is\r therefore evident that the acquisition of certain things according\r to nature is a part both of domestic and civil economy, and for what\r reason.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1417},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-12","text":"There is also another species of acquisition which they [1257a]\r particularly call pecuniary, and with great propriety; and by this\r indeed it seems that there are no bounds to riches and wealth. Now many\r persons suppose, from their near relation to each other, that this is\r one and the same with that we have just mentioned, but it is not the\r same as that, though not very different; one of these is natural, the\r other is not, but rather owing to some art and skill; we will enter into\r a particular examination of this subject. The uses of every possession\r are two, both dependent upon the thi","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1418},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-13","text":"Money then being established as the necessary medium of exchange,\r another species of money-getting soon took place, namely, by buying\r and selling, at probably first in a simple manner, afterwards with more\r skill and experience, where and how the greatest profits might be made.\r For which reason the art of money-getting seems to be chiefly conversant\r about trade, and the business of it to be able to tell where the\r greatest profits can be made, being the means of procuring abundance\r of wealth and possessions: and thus wealth is very often supposed to\r consist in the quantity of money which","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1419},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-14","text":"Like Midas in the fable, who from his insatiable wish had everything he\r touched turned into gold. For which reason others endeavour to procure\r other riches and other property, and rightly, for there are other riches\r and property in nature; and these are the proper objects of economy:\r while trade only procures money, not by all means, but by the exchange\r of it, and for that purpose it is this which it is chiefly employed\r about, for money is the first principle and the end of trade; nor are\r there any bounds to be set to what is thereby acquired. Thus also there\r are no limits to the art o","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1420},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-15","text":"We have now considered that art of money-getting which is not necessary,\r and have seen in what manner we became in want of it; and also that\r which is necessary, which is different from it; for that economy which\r is natural, and whose object is to provide food, is not like this\r unlimited in its extent, but has its bounds.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1421},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-16","text":"We have now determined what was before doubtful, whether or no the art\r of getting money is his business who is at the head of a family or a\r state, and though not strictly so, it is however very necessary; for\r as a politician does not make men, but receiving them from the hand of\r nature employs them to proper purposes; thus the earth, or the sea, or\r something else ought to supply them with provisions, and this it is the\r business of the master of the family to manage properly; for it is not\r the weaver's business to make yarn, but to use it, and to distinguish\r what is good and useful from","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1422},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-17","text":"And this is the explanation of the name (TOKOS), which means the\r breeding of money. For as offspring resemble their parents, so usury\r is money bred of money. Whence of all forms of money-making it is most\r against nature.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1423},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-18","text":"Having already sufficiently considered the general principles of this\r subject, let us now go into the practical part thereof; the one is a\r liberal employment for the mind, the other necessary. These things are\r useful in the management of one's affairs; to be skilful in the nature\r of cattle, which are most profitable, and where, and how; as for\r instance, what advantage will arise from keeping horses, or oxen, or\r sheep, or any other live stock; it is also necessary to be acquainted\r with the comparative value of these things, and which of them in\r particular places are worth most; for some","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1424},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-19","text":"With respect to gaining money by exchange, the principal method of doing\r this is by merchandise, which is carried on in three different ways,\r either by sending the commodity for sale by sea or by land, or else\r selling it on the place where it grows; and these differ from each other\r in this, that the one is more profitable, the other safer. The second\r method is by usury. The third by receiving wages for work done, and\r this either by being employed in some mean art, or else in mere bodily\r labour. There is also a third species of improving a fortune, that is\r something between this and the","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1425},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-20","text":"These we have now mentioned in general, but to enter into particulars\r concerning each of them, though it might be useful to the artist, would\r be tiresome to dwell on. Now of all the works of art, those are the most\r excellent wherein chance has the least to do, and those are the meanest\r which deprave the body, those the most servile in which bodily strength\r alone is chiefly wanted, those most illiberal which require least skill;\r but as there are books written on these subjects by some persons, as\r by Chares the Panian, and Apollodorus the Lemnian, upon husbandry and\r planting; and by othe","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1426},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-21","text":"There are then three parts of domestic government, the masters, of\r which we have already treated, the fathers, and the husbands; now the\r government of the wife and children should both be that of free persons,\r but not the [I259b] same; for the wife should be treated as a citizen of\r a free state, the children should be under kingly power; for the male is\r by nature superior to the female, except when something happens contrary\r to the usual course of nature, as is the elder and perfect to the\r younger and imperfect. Now in the generality of free states, the\r governors and the governed alter","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1427},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-22","text":"It is evident then that in the due government of a family, greater\r attention should be paid to the several members of it and their virtues\r than to the possessions or riches of it; and greater to the freemen\r than the slaves: but here some one may doubt whether there is any other\r virtue in a slave than his organic services, and of higher estimation\r than these, as temperance, fortitude, justice, and such-like habits, or\r whether they possess only bodily qualities: each side of the question\r has its difficulties; for if they possess these virtues, wherein do\r they differ from freemen? and tha","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1428},{"id":"aristotle-politics-1-23","text":"but it is not a man's; and as a child is incomplete, it is evident that\r his virtue is not to be referred to himself in his present situation,\r but to that in which he will be complete, and his preceptor. In like\r manner the virtue of a slave is to be referred to his master; for we\r laid it down as a maxim, that the use of a slave was to employ him in\r what you wanted; so that it is clear enough that few virtues are wanted\r in his station, only that he may not neglect his work through idleness\r or fear: some person may question if what I have said is true, whether\r virtue is not necessary for ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 1","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"1"},"sequenceIndex":1429},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-1","text":"Since then we propose to inquire what civil society is of all others\r best for those who have it in their power to live entirely as they wish,\r it is necessary to examine into the polity of those states which are\r allowed to be well governed; and if there should be any others which\r some persons have described, and which appear properly regulated, to\r note what is right and useful in them; and when we point out wherein\r they have failed, let not this be imputed to an affectation of wisdom,\r for it is because there are great defects in all those which are already\r established, that I have been ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1430},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-2","text":"Now as a community of wives is attended with many other difficulties, so\r neither does the cause for which he would frame his government in this\r manner seem agreeable to reason, nor is it capable of producing that end\r which he has proposed, and for which he says it ought to take place; nor\r has he given any particular directions for putting it in practice. Now\r I also am willing to agree with Socrates in the principle which he\r proceeds upon, and admit that the city ought to be one as much as\r possible; and yet it is evident that if it is contracted too much, it\r will be no longer a city, fo","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1431},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-3","text":"But admitting that it is most advantageous for a city to be one as much\r as possible, it does not seem to follow that this will take place by\r permitting all at once to say this is mine, and this is not mine (though\r this is what Socrates regards as a proof that a city is entirely one),\r for the word All is used in two senses; if it means each individual,\r what Socrates proposes will nearly take place; for each person will\r say, this is his own son, and his own wife, and his own property, and\r of everything else that may happen to belong to him, that it is his own.\r But those who have their wi","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1432},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-4","text":"Besides, those who contrive this plan of community cannot easily avoid\r the following evils; namely, blows, murders involuntary or voluntary,\r quarrels, and reproaches, all which it would be impious indeed to be\r guilty of towards our fathers and mothers, or those who are nearly\r related to us; though not to those who are not connected to us by any\r tie of affinity: and certainly these mischiefs must necessarily happen\r oftener amongst those who do not know how they are connected to each\r other than those who do; and when they do happen, if it is among the\r first of these, they admit of a lega","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1433},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-5","text":"We proceed next to consider in what manner property should be regulated\r in a state which is formed after the most perfect mode of government,\r whether it should be common or not; for this may be considered as a\r separate question from what had been determined concerning [1263a] wives\r and children; I mean, whether it is better that these should be held\r separate, as they now everywhere are, or that not only possessions but\r also the usufruct of them should be in common; or that the soil should\r have a particular owner, but that the produce should be brought together\r and used as one common st","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1434},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-6","text":"But the manner of life which is now established, more particularly when\r embellished with good morals and a system of equal laws, is far superior\r to it, for it will have the advantage of both; by both I mean properties\r being common, and divided also; for in some respects it ought to be in\r a manner common, but upon the whole private: for every man's attention\r being employed on his own particular concerns, will prevent mutual\r complaints against each other; nay, by this means industry will be\r increased, as each person will labour to improve his own private\r property; and it will then be, th","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1435},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-7","text":"It is evident then that it is best to have property private, but to make\r the use of it common; but how the citizens are to be brought to it is\r the particular [1263b] business of the legislator. And also with respect\r to pleasure, it is unspeakable how advantageous it is, that a man should\r think he has something which he may call his own; for it is by no means\r to no purpose, that each person should have an affection for himself,\r for that is natural, and yet to be a self-lover is justly censured; for\r we mean by that, not one that simply loves himself, but one that loves\r himself more than ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1436},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-8","text":"This system of polity does indeed recommend itself by its good\r appearance and specious pretences to humanity; and when first proposed\r to any one, must give him great pleasure, as he will conclude it to be\r a wonderful bond of friendship, connecting all to all; particularly\r when any one censures the evils which are now to be found in society,\r as arising from properties not being common, I mean the disputes which\r happen between man and man, upon their different contracts with each\r other; those judgments which are passed in court in consequence of\r fraud, and perjury, and flattering the ric","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1437},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-9","text":"We must suppose, then, that Socrates's mistake arose from the principle\r he set out with being false; we admit, indeed, that both a family and a\r city ought to be one in some particulars, but not entirely; for there\r is a point beyond which if a city proceeds in reducing itself to one, it\r will be no longer a city.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1438},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-10","text":"There is also another point at which it will still continue to be a\r city, but it will approach so near to not being one, that it will be\r worse than none; as if any one should reduce the voices of those who\r sing in concert to one, or a verse to a foot. But the people ought to\r be made one, and a community, as I have already said, by education;\r as property at Lacedaemon, and their public tables at Crete, were made\r common by their legislators. But yet, whosoever shall introduce any\r education, and think thereby to make his city excellent and respectable,\r will be absurd, while he expects to ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1439},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-11","text":"Nor has Socrates told us (nor is it easy to say) what plan of government\r should be pursued with respect to the individuals in the state where\r there is a community of goods established; for though the majority\r of his citizens will in general consist of a multitude of persons of\r different occupations, of those he has determined nothing; whether the\r property of the husbandman ought to be in common, or whether each person\r should have his share to himself; and also, whether their wives and\r children ought to be in common: for if all things are to be alike common\r to all, where will be the dif","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1440},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-12","text":"Besides, if he makes the wives common, while the property [1264b]\r continues separate, who shall manage the domestic concerns with the same\r care which the man bestows upon his fields? nor will the inconvenience\r be remedied by making property as well as wives common; and it is absurd\r to draw a comparison from the brute creation, and say, that the same\r principle should regulate the connection of a man and a woman which\r regulates theirs amongst whom there is no family association.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1441},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-13","text":"It is also very hazardous to settle the magistracy as Socrates has\r done; for he would have persons of the same rank always in office, which\r becomes the cause of sedition even amongst those who are of no account,\r but more particularly amongst those who are of a courageous and warlike\r disposition; it is indeed evidently necessary that he should frame his\r community in this manner; for that golden particle which God has mixed\r up in the soul of man flies not from one to the other, but always\r continues with the same; for he says, that some of our species have\r gold, and others silver, blended","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1442},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-14","text":"It is also nearly the same in the treatise upon Laws which was writ\r afterwards, for which reason it will be proper in this place to consider\r briefly what he has there said upon government, for Socrates has\r thoroughly settled but very few parts of it; as for instance, in what\r manner the community of wives and children ought to be regulated, how\r property should be established, and government conducted.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1443},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-15","text":"Now he divides the inhabitants into two parts, husbandmen and soldiers,\r and from these he select a third part who are to be senators and govern\r the city; but he has not said whether or no the husbandman and artificer\r shall have any or what share in the government, or whether they shall\r have arms, and join with the others in war, or not. He thinks also\r that the women ought to go to war, and have the same education as the\r soldiers; as to other particulars, he has filled his treatise with\r matter foreign to the purpose; and with respect to education, he has\r only said what that of the guard","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1444},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-16","text":"[1265a] As to his book of Laws, laws are the principal thing which that\r contains, for he has there said but little concerning government; and\r this government, which he was so desirous of framing in such a manner as\r to impart to its members a more entire community of goods than is to be\r found in other cities, he almost brings round again to be the same\r as that other government which he had first proposed; for except the\r community of wives and goods, he has framed both his governments alike,\r for the education of the citizens is to be the same in both; they are in\r both to live without any","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1445},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-17","text":"All the discourses of Socrates are masterly, noble, new, and\r inquisitive; but that they are all true it may probably be too much\r to say. For now with respect to the number just spoken of, it must be\r acknowledged that he would want the country of Babylonia for them, or\r some one like it, of an immeasurable extent, to support five thousand\r idle persons, besides a much greater number of women and servants. Every\r one, it is true, may frame an hypothesis as he pleases, but yet it ought\r to be possible. It has been said, that a legislator should have two\r things in view when he frames his laws,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1446},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-18","text":"It may also be considered whether the quantity of each person's property\r may not be settled in a different manner from what he has done it in,\r by making it more determinate; for he says, that every one ought to have\r enough whereon to live moderately, as if any one had said to live well,\r which is the most comprehensive expression. Besides, a man may live\r moderately and miserably at the same time; he had therefore better\r have proposed, that they should live both moderately and liberally;\r for unless these two conspire, luxury will come in on the one hand, or\r wretchedness on the other, sin","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1447},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-19","text":"It is also absurd to render property equal, and not to provide for\r the increasing number of the citizens; but to leave that circumstance\r uncertain, as if it would regulate itself according to the number of\r women who [1265b] should happen to be childless, let that be what it\r would because this seems to take place in other cities; but the case\r would not be the same in such a state which he proposes and those which\r now actually unite; for in these no one actually wants, as the property\r is divided amongst the whole community, be their numbers what they will;\r but as it could not then be div","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1448},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-20","text":"In Plato's Laws it is however different; we shall mention hereafter what\r we think would be best in these particulars. He has also neglected in\r that treatise to point out how the governors are to be distinguished\r from the governed; for he says, that as of one sort of wool the warp\r ought to be made, and of another the woof, so ought some to govern, and\r others to be governed. But since he admits, that all their property may\r be increased fivefold, why should he not allow the same increase to the\r country? he ought also to consider whether his allotment of the houses\r will be useful to the co","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1449},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-21","text":"Some persons say, that the most perfect government should be composed\r of all others blended together, for which reason they commend that\r of Lacedaemon; for they say, that this is composed of an oligarchy,\r a monarchy, and a democracy, their kings representing the monarchical\r part, the senate the oligarchical; and, that in the ephori may be found\r the democratical, as these are taken from the people. But some say, that\r in the ephori is absolute power, and that it is their common meal and\r daily course of life, in which the democratical form is represented.\r It is also said in this treatise ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1450},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-22","text":"The same principle prevails also in the choice of their senate; the\r manner of electing which is favourable also to an oligarchy; for all\r are obliged to vote for those who are senators of the first class,\r afterwards they vote for the same number out of the second, and then out\r of the third; but this compulsion to vote at the election of senators\r does not extend to the third and fourth classes and the first and second\r class only are obliged to vote for the fourth. By this means he says\r he shall necessarily have an equal number of each rank, but he is\r mistaken--for the majority will alway","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1451},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-23","text":"There will also great danger arise from the manner of electing the\r senate, when those who are elected themselves are afterwards to elect\r others; for by this means, if a certain number choose to combine\r together, though not very considerable, the election will always fall\r according to their pleasure. Such are the things which Plato proposes\r concerning government in his book of Laws.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1452},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-24","text":"There are also some other forms of government, which have been proposed\r either by private persons, or philosophers, or politicians, all of which\r come much nearer to those which have been really established, or now\r exist, than these two of Plato's; for neither have they introduced the\r innovation of a community of wives and children, and public tables for\r the women, but have been contented to set out with establishing such\r rules as are absolutely necessary.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1453},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-25","text":"There are some persons who think, that the first object of government\r should be to regulate well everything relating to private property;\r for they say, that a neglect herein is the source of all seditions\r whatsoever. For this reason, Phaleas the Chalcedonian first proposed,\r that the fortunes of the citizens should be equal, which he thought was\r not difficult to accomplish when a community was first settled, but\r that it was a work of greater difficulty in one that had been long\r established; but yet that it might be effected, and an equality of\r circumstances introduced by these means, th","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1454},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-26","text":"But Plato, in his treatise of Laws, thinks that a difference in\r circumstances should be permitted to a certain degree; but that no\r citizen should be allowed to possess more than five times as much as the\r lowest census, as we have already mentioned. But legislators who\r would establish this principle are apt to overlook what they ought to\r consider; that while they regulate the quantity of provisions which each\r individual shall possess, they ought also to regulate the number of his\r children; for if these exceed the allotted quantity of provision, the\r law must necessarily be repealed; and ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1455},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-27","text":"For men are not guilty of crimes for necessaries only (for which he\r thinks an equality of goods would be a sufficient remedy, as they would\r then have no occasion to steal cold or hunger), but that they may enjoy\r what they desire, and not wish for it in vain; for if their desire extend\r beyond the common necessaries of life, they were be wicked to gratify\r them; and not only so, but if their wishes point that way, they will do\r the same to enjoy those pleasures which are free from the alloy of pain.\r What remedy then shall we find for these three disorders? And first,\r to prevent stealing fr","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1456},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-28","text":"Since then men are guilty of the greatest crimes from ambition, and not\r from necessity, no one, for instance aims at being a tyrant to keep him\r from the cold, hence great honour is due to him who kills not a thief,\r but tyrant; so that polity which Phaleas establishes would only be\r salutary to prevent little crimes. He has also been very desirous to\r establish such rules as will conduce to perfect the internal policy of\r his state, and he ought also to have done the same with respect to\r its neighbours and all foreign nations; for the considerations of the\r military establishment should tak","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1457},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-29","text":"Thus it should not be so much as to tempt those who are near, and more\r powerful to invade it, while those who possess it are not able to drive\r out the invaders, nor so little as that the state should not be able to\r go to war with those who are quite equal to itself, and of this he has\r determined nothing; it must indeed be allowed that it is advantageous to\r a community to be rather rich than poor; probably the proper boundary is\r this, not to possess enough to make it worth while for a more powerful\r neighbour to attack you, any more than he would those who had not so\r much as yourself; th","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1458},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-30","text":"Hippodamus, the son of Euruphon a Milesian, contrived the art of laying\r out towns, and separated the Pireus. This man was in other respects\r too eager after notice, and seemed to many to live in a very affected\r manner, with his flowing locks and his expensive ornaments, and a coarse\r warm vest which he wore, not only in the winter, but also in the\r hot weather. As he was very desirous of the character of a universal\r scholar, he was the first who, not being actually engaged in the\r management of public affairs, sat himself to inquire what sort of\r government was best; and he planned a state,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1459},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-31","text":"These are the principal parts and most worthy of notice in Hippodamus's\r plan. But some persons might doubt the propriety of his division of the\r citizens into three parts; for the artisans, the husbandmen, and the\r soldiers are to compose one community, where the husbandmen are to have\r no arms, and the artisans neither arms nor land, which would in a manner\r render them slaves to the soldiery. It is also impossible that the whole\r community should partake of all the honourable employments in it--for\r the generals and the guardians of the state must necessarily be\r appointed out of the soldie","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1460},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-32","text":"Nor do I approve of his method of determining causes, when he would\r have the judge split the case which comes simply before him; and thus,\r instead of being a judge, become an arbitrator. Now when any matter\r is brought to arbitration, it is customary for many persons to confer\r together upon the business that is before them; but when a cause is\r brought before judges it is not so; and many legislators take care\r that the judges shall not have it in their power to communicate their\r sentiments to each other. Besides, what can prevent confusion on the\r bench when one judge thinks a fine should","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1461},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-33","text":"Now with respect to these honours which he proposes to bestow on those\r who can give any information useful to the community, this, though very\r pleasing in speculation, is what the legislator should not settle, for\r it would encourage informers, and probably occasion commotions in the\r state. And this proposal of his gives rise also to further conjectures\r and inquiries; for some persons have doubted whether it is useful or\r hurtful to alter the established law of any country, if even for the\r better; for which reason one cannot immediately determine upon what he\r here says, whether it is adv","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1462},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-34","text":"Thus the science of physic is extended beyond its ancient bounds; so is\r the gymnastic, and indeed all other arts and powers; so that one may lay\r it down for certain that the same thing will necessarily hold good in\r the art of government. And it may also be affirmed, that experience\r itself gives a proof of this; for the ancient laws are too simple and\r barbarous; which allowed the Greeks to wear swords in the city, and to\r buy their wives of each [1269a]. other. And indeed all the remains of\r old laws which we have are very simple; for instance, a law in Cuma\r relative to murder. If any per","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1463},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-35","text":"There are two considerations which offer themselves with respect to the\r government established at Lacedaemon and Crete, and indeed in almost all\r other states whatsoever; one is whether their laws do or do not promote\r the best establishment possible? the other is whether there is anything,\r if we consider either the principles upon which it is founded or the\r executive part of it, which prevents the form of government that they\r had proposed to follow from being observed; now it is allowed that in\r every well-regulated state the members of it should be free from servile\r labour; but in what ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1464},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-36","text":"As to the indulging of women in any particular liberties, it is hurtful\r to the end of government and the prosperity of the city; for as a man\r and his wife are the two parts of a family, if we suppose a city to be\r divided into two parts, we must allow that the number of men and women\r will be equal.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1465},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-37","text":"In whatever city then the women are not under good regulations, we must\r look upon one half of it as not under the restraint of law, as it\r there happened; for the legislator, desiring to make his whole city\r a collection of warriors with respect to the men, he most evidently\r accomplished his design; but in the meantime the women were quite\r neglected, for they live without restraint in every improper indulgence\r and luxury. So that in such a state riches will necessarily be in\r general esteem, particularly if the men are governed by their wives,\r which has been the case with many a brave and","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1466},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-38","text":"The origin of this indulgence which the Lacedaemonian women enjoy is\r easily accounted for, from the long time the men were absent from home\r upon foreign expeditions [1270a] against the Argives, and afterwards the\r Arcadians and Messenians, so that, when these wars were at an end, their\r military life, in which there is no little virtue, prepared them to obey\r the precepts of their law-giver; but we are told, that when Lycurgus\r endeavoured also to reduce the women to an obedience to his laws, upon\r their refusal he declined it. It may indeed be said that the women were\r the causes of these t","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1467},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-39","text":"And from these facts it is evident, that this particular is badly\r regulated; for the city could not support one shock, but was ruined for\r want of men. They say, that during the reigns of their ancient kings\r they used to present foreigners with the freedom of their city, to\r prevent there being a want of men while they carried on long wars; it is\r also affirmed that the number of Spartans was formerly ten thousand; but\r be that as it will, an equality of property conduces much to increase\r the number of the people. The law, too, which he made to encourage\r population was by no means calculat","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1468},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-40","text":"Nor was he less blamable for the manner in which he constituted the\r ephori; for these magistrates take cognisance of things of the last\r importance, and yet they are chosen out of the people in general; so\r that it often happens that a very poor person is elected to that office,\r who, from that circumstance, is easily bought. There have been many\r instances of this formerly, as well as in the late affair at Andros. And\r these men, being corrupted with money, went as far as they could to ruin\r the city: and, because their power was too great and nearly tyrannical,\r their kings were obliged to ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1469},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-41","text":"We will inquire at another time whether the office of a king is useful\r to the state: thus much is certain, that they should be chosen from a\r consideration of their conduct and not as they are now. But that the\r legislator himself did not expect to make all his citizens honourable\r and completely virtuous is evident from this, that he distrusts them as\r not being good men; for he sent those upon the same embassy that were at\r variance with each other; and thought, that in the dispute of the kings\r the safety of the state consisted. Neither were their common meals at\r first well established: f","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1470},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-42","text":"[1271b] There is also another defect in his laws worthy of censure,\r which Plato has given in his book of Laws; that the whole constitution\r was calculated only for the business of war: it is indeed excellent to\r make them conquerors; for which reason the preservation of the state\r depended thereon. The destruction of it commenced with their victories:\r for they knew not how to be idle, or engage in any other employment\r than war. In this particular also they were mistaken, that though they\r rightly thought, that those things which are the objects of contention\r amongst mankind are better proc","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1471},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-43","text":"The government of Crete bears a near resemblance to this, in some few\r particulars it is not worse, but in general it is far inferior in its\r contrivance. For it appears and is allowed in many particulars the\r constitution of Lacedaemon was formed in imitation of that of Crete;\r and in general most new things are an improvement upon the old. For they\r say, that when Lycurgus ceased to be guardian to King Charilles he\r went abroad and spent a long time with his relations in Crete, for the\r Lycians are a colony of the Lacedaemonians; and those who first settled\r there adopted that body of laws w","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1472},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-44","text":"This island seems formed by nature to be the mistress of Greece, for it\r is entirely surrounded by a navigable ocean which washes almost all the\r maritime parts of that country, and is not far distant on the one side\r from Peloponnesus, on the other, which looks towards Asia, from Triopium\r and Rhodes. By means of this situation Minos acquired the empire of\r the sea and the islands; some of which he subdued, in others planted\r colonies: at last he died at Camicus while he was attacking Sicily.\r There is this analogy between the customs of the Lacedaemonians and\r the Cretans, the Helots cultiva","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1473},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-45","text":"The Cretans conducted their public meals better than the Lacedaemonians,\r for at Lacedaemon each individual was obliged to furnish what was\r assessed upon him; which if he could not do, there was a law which\r deprived him of the rights of a citizen, as has been already mentioned:\r but in Crete they were furnished by the community; for all the corn and\r cattle, taxes and contributions, which the domestic slaves were obliged\r to furnish, were divided into parts and allotted to the gods, the\r exigencies of the state, and these public meals; so that all the men,\r women, and children were maintaine","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1474},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-46","text":"The institution of the _kosmoi_, was still worse than that of the\r ephori: for it contained all the faults incident to that magistracy and\r some peculiar to itself; for in both cases it is uncertain who will be\r elected: but the Lacedaemonians have this advantage which the others\r have not, that as all are eligible, the whole community have a share\r in the highest honours, and therefore all desire to preserve the state:\r whereas among the Cretans the _kosmoi_ are not chosen out of the people\r in general, but out of some certain families, and the senate out of the\r _kosmoi_. And the same observ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1475},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-47","text":"The government of Carthage seems well established, and in many respects\r superior to others; in some particulars it bears a near resemblance\r to the Lacedaemonians; and indeed these three states, the Cretans, the\r Lacedaemonians and the Carthaginians are in some things very like\r each other, in others they differ greatly. Amongst many excellent\r constitutions this may show how well their government is framed, that\r although the people are admitted to a share in the administration, the\r form of it remains unaltered, without any popular insurrections, worth\r notice, on the one hand, or degenerat","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1476},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-48","text":"Now of those principles on which the Carthaginians have established\r their mixed form of government, composed of an aristocracy and\r democracy, some incline to produce a democracy, others an oligarchy: for\r instance, if the kings and the senate are unanimous upon any point in\r debate, they can choose whether they will bring it before the people or\r no; but if they disagree, it is to these they must appeal, who are not\r only to hear what has been approved of by the senate, but are finally\r to determine upon it; and whosoever chooses it, has a right to speak\r against any matter whatsoever that m","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1477},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-49","text":"The determining all causes by the same magistrates, and not orae in one\r court and another in another, as at Lacedaemon, has the same influence.\r The constitution of Carthage is now shifting from an aristocracy to an\r oligarchy, in consequence of an opinion which is favourably entertained\r by many, who think that the magistrates in the community ought not to\r be persons of family only, but of fortune also; as it is impossible\r for those who are in bad circumstances to support the dignity of their\r office, or to be at leisure to apply to public business. As choosing men\r of fortune to be magist","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1478},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-50","text":"It seems also improper, that one person should execute several offices,\r which was approved of at Carthage; for one business is best done by one\r person; and it is the duty of the legislator to look to this, and not\r make the same person a musician and a shoemaker: so that where the state\r is not small it is more politic and more popular to admit many persons\r to have a share in the government; for, as I just now said, it is not\r only more usual, but everything is better and sooner done, when one\r thing only is allotted to one person: and this is evident both in the\r army and navy, where almos","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1479},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-51","text":"Some of those persons who have written upon government had never any\r share in public affairs, but always led a private life. Everything\r worthy of notice in their works we have already spoke to. Others\r were legislators, some in their own cities, others were employed in\r regulating the governments of foreign states. Some of them only composed\r a body of laws; others formed the constitution also, as Lycurgus; and\r Solon, who did both. The Lacedaemonians have been already mentioned.\r Some persons think that Solon was an excellent legislator, who could\r dissolve a pure oligarchy, and save the pe","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1480},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-52","text":"Solon seems not to have altered the established form of government,\r either with respect to the senate or the mode of electing their\r magistrates; but to have raised the people to great consideration in the\r state by allotting the supreme judicial department to them; and for this\r some persons blame him, as having done what would soon overturn that\r balance of power he intended to establish; for by trying all causes\r whatsoever before the people, who were chosen by lot to determine them,\r it was necessary to flatter a tyrannical populace who had got this\r power; which contributed to bring the ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1481},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-53","text":"Both Ephialtes and Pericles abridged the power of the Areopagites, the\r latter of whom introduced the method of paying those who attended\r the courts of justice: and thus every one who aimed at being popular\r proceeded increasing the power of the people to what we now see it. But\r it is evident that this was not Solon's intention, but that it arose\r from accident; for the people being the cause of the naval victory\r over the Medes, assumed greatly upon it, and enlisted themselves\r under factious demagogues, although opposed by the better part of the\r citizens. He thought it indeed most necessa","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1482},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-54","text":"As for those of the fourth, which consisted of mechanics, they were\r incapable of any office. Zaleucus was the legislator of the Western\r Locrians, as was Charondas, the Catanean, of his own cities, and those\r also in Italy and Sicily which belonged to the Calcidians. Some persons\r endeavour to prove that Onomacritus, the Locrian, was the first person\r of note who drew up laws; and that he employed himself in that business\r while he was at Crete, where he continued some time to learn the\r prophetic art: and they say, that Thales was his companion; and that\r Lycurgus and Zaleucus were the schol","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1483},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-55","text":"As Philolaus gave them laws concerning many other things, so did he upon\r adoption, which they call adoptive laws; and this he in particular did\r to preserve the number of families. Charondas did nothing new, except\r in actions for perjury, which he was the first person who took into\r particular consideration. He also drew up his laws with greater elegance\r and accuracy than even any of our present legislators. Philolaus\r introduced the law for the equal distribution of goods; Plato that for\r the community of women, children, and goods, and also for public tables\r for the women; and one concer","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1484},{"id":"aristotle-politics-2-56","text":"As for Draco's laws, they were published when the government was already\r established, and they have nothing particular in them worth mentioning,\r except their severity on account of the enormity of their punishments.\r Pittacus was the author of some laws, but never drew up any form of\r government; one of which was this, that if a drunken man beat any person\r he should be punished more than if he did it when sober; for as\r people are more apt to be abusive when drunk than sober, he paid no\r consideration to the excuse which drunkenness might claim, but regarded\r only the common benefit. Androm","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 2","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1485},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-1","text":"Every one who inquires into the nature of government, and what are its\r different forms, should make this almost his first question, What is a\r city? For upon this there is a dispute: for some persons say the city\r did this or that, while others say, not the city, but the oligarchy,\r or the tyranny. We see that the city is the only object which both the\r politician and legislator have in view in all they do: but government\r is a certain ordering of those who inhabit a city. As a city is a\r collective body, and, like other wholes, composed of many parts, it is\r evident our first inquiry must be","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1486},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-2","text":"Now it is not residence which constitutes a man a citizen; for in this\r sojourners and slaves are upon an equality with him; nor will it be\r sufficient for this purpose, that you have the privilege of the laws,\r and may plead or be impleaded, for this all those of different nations,\r between whom there is a mutual agreement for that purpose, are allowed;\r although it very often happens, that sojourners have not a perfect right\r therein without the protection of a patron, to whom they are obliged to\r apply, which shows that their share in the community is incomplete. In\r like manner, with respe","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1487},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-3","text":"With respect to offices, some are fixed to a particular time, so that\r no person is, on any account, permitted to fill them twice; or else\r not till some certain period has intervened; others are not fixed, as a\r juryman's, and a member of the general assembly: but probably some one\r may say these are not offices, nor have the citizens in these capacities\r any share in the government; though surely it is ridiculous to say that\r those who have the principal power in the state bear no office in it.\r But this objection is of no weight, for it is only a dispute about\r words; as there is no general","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1488},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-4","text":"Now we see that governments differ from each other in their form,\r and that some of them are defective, others [1275b] as excellent as\r possible: for it is evident, that those which have many deficiencies\r and degeneracies in them must be far inferior to those which are without\r such faults. What I mean by degeneracies will be hereafter explained.\r Hence it is clear that the office of a citizen must differ as\r governments do from each other: for which reason he who is called\r a citizen has, in a democracy, every privilege which that station\r supposes. In other forms of government he may enjoy ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1489},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-5","text":"The trial also of different causes is allotted to different persons; as\r at Lacedaemon all disputes concerning contracts are brought before some\r of the ephori: the senate are the judges in cases of murder, and so on;\r some being to be heard by one magistrate, others by another: and thus\r at Carthage certain magistrates determine all causes. But our former\r description of a citizen will admit of correction; for in some\r governments the office of a juryman and a member of the general assembly\r is not an indeterminate one; but there are particular persons appointed\r for these purposes, some or a","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1490},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-6","text":"In common use they define a citizen to be one who is sprung from\r citizens on both sides, not on the father's or the mother's only. Others\r carry the matter still further, and inquire how many of his ancestors\r have been citizens, as his grandfather, great-grandfather, etc., but\r some persons have questioned how the first of the family could prove\r themselves citizens, according to this popular and careless definition.\r Gorgias of Leontium, partly entertaining the same doubt, and partly in\r jest, says, that as a mortar is made by a mortar-maker, so a citizen is\r made by a citizen-maker, and a ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1491},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-7","text":"It has also been doubted what was and what was not the act of the city;\r as, for instance, when a democracy arises out of an aristocracy or a\r tyranny; for some persons then refuse to fulfil their contracts; as if\r the right to receive the money was in the tyrant and not in the state,\r and many other things of the same nature; as if any covenant was founded\r for violence and not for the common good. So in like manner, if anything\r is done by those who have the management of public affairs where a\r democracy is established, their actions are to be considered as the\r actions of the state, as wel","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1492},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-8","text":"And here it seems very proper to consider this question, When shall we\r say that a city is the same, and when shall we say that it is different?","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1493},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-9","text":"It is but a superficial mode of examining into this question to begin\r with the place and the people; for it may happen that these may be\r divided from that, or that some one of them may live in one place, and\r some in another (but this question may be regarded as no very knotty\r one; for, as a city may acquire that appellation on many accounts,\r it may be solved many ways); and in like manner, when men inhabit one\r common place, when shall we say that they inhabit the same city, or that\r the city is the same? for it does not depend upon the walls; for I can\r suppose Peloponnesus itself surrou","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1494},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-10","text":"What has been said, it follows that we should consider whether the\r same virtues which constitute a good man make a valuable citizen, or\r different; and if a particular inquiry is necessary for this matter we\r must first give a general description of the virtues of a good citizen;\r for as a sailor is one of those who make up a community, so is a\r citizen, although the province of one sailor may be different from\r another's (for one is a rower, another a steersman, a third a boatswain,\r and so on, each having their several appointments), it is evident that\r the most accurate description of any ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1495},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-11","text":"As if those who are to rule were to have an education peculiar to\r themselves. But if we allow, that the virtues of a good man and a\r good magistrate may be the same, and a citizen is one who obeys the\r magistrate, it follows that the virtue of the one cannot in general be\r the same as the virtue of the other, although it may be true of some\r particular citizen; for the virtue of the magistrate must be different\r from the virtue of the citizen. For which reason Jason declared that\r was he deprived of his kingdom he should pine away with regret, as not\r knowing how to live a private man. But it","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1496},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-12","text":"There are many sorts of slaves; for their employments are various: of\r these the handicraftsmen are one, who, as their name imports, get their\r living by the labour of their hands, and amongst these all mechanics are\r included; [1277b] for which reasons such workmen, in some states, were\r not formerly admitted into any share in the government; till at length\r democracies were established: it is not therefore proper for any man\r of honour, or any citizen, or any one who engages in public affairs, to\r learn these servile employments without they have occasion for them for\r their own use; for wit","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1497},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-13","text":"The domestic employments of each of them are also different; it is the\r man's business to acquire subsistence, the woman's to take care of it.\r But direction and knowledge of public affairs is a virtue peculiar to\r those who govern, while all others seem to be equally requisite for both\r parties; but with this the governed have no concern, it is theirs to\r entertain just notions: they indeed are like flute-makers, while those\r who govern are the musicians who play on them. And thus much to show\r whether the virtue of a good man and an excellent citizen is the same,\r or if it is different, and ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1498},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-14","text":"But with respect to citizens there is a doubt remaining, whether those\r only are truly so who are allowed to share in the government, or whether\r the mechanics also are to be considered as such? for if those who are\r not permitted to rule are to be reckoned among them, it is impossible\r that the virtue of all the citizens should be the same, for these also\r are citizens; and if none of them are admitted to be citizens, where\r shall they be ranked? for they are neither [1278a] sojourners nor\r foreigners? or shall we say that there will no inconvenience arise from\r their not being citizens, as t","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1499},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-15","text":"There was a law at Thebes that no one could have a share in the\r government till he had been ten years out of trade. In many states the\r law invites strangers to accept the freedom of the city; and in some\r democracies the son of a free-woman is himself free. The same is also\r observed in many others with respect to natural children; but it is\r through want of citizens regularly born that they admit such: for these\r laws are always made in consequence of a scarcity of inhabitants; so,\r as their numbers increase, they first deprive the children of a male or\r female slave of this privilege, next","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1500},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-16","text":"That there are many sorts of citizens, and that he may be said to be as\r completely who shares the honours of the state, is evident from what\r has been already said. Thus Achilles, in Homer, complains of Agamemnon's\r treating him like an unhonoured stranger; for a stranger or sojourner is\r one who does not partake of the honours of the state: and whenever the\r right to the freedom of the city is kept obscure, it is for the sake of\r the inhabitants. [1278b] From what has been said it is plain whether the\r virtue of a good man and an excellent citizen is the same or different:\r and we find that ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1501},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-17","text":"Having established these points, we proceed next to consider whether one\r form of government only should be established, or more than one; and if\r more, how many, and of what sort, and what are the differences between\r them. The form of government is the ordering and regulating of the city,\r and all the offices in it, particularly those wherein the supreme power\r is lodged; and this power is always possessed by the administration; but\r the administration itself is that particular form of government which\r is established in any state: thus in a democracy the supreme power is\r lodged in the whol","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1502},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-18","text":"I have already mentioned in my treatise on the management of a family,\r and the power of the master, that man is an animal naturally formed\r for society, and that therefore, when he does not want any foreign\r assistance, he will of his own accord desire to live with others; not\r but that mutual advantage induces them to it, as far as it enables each\r person to live more agreeably; and this is indeed the great object\r not only to all in general, but also to each individual: but it is not\r merely matter of choice, but they join in society also, even that they\r may be able to live, which probably","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1503},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-19","text":"It is evident, then, that all those governments which have a common good\r in view are rightly established and strictly just, but those who have\r in view only the good of the rulers are all founded on wrong principles,\r and are widely different from what a government ought to be, for they\r are tyranny over slaves, whereas a city is a community of freemen.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1504},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-20","text":"Having established these particulars, we come to consider next the\r different number of governments which there are, and what they are; and\r first, what are their excellencies: for when we have determined this,\r their defects will be evident enough.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1505},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-21","text":"It is evident that every form of government or administration, for the\r words are of the same import, must contain a supreme power over the\r whole state, and this supreme power must necessarily be in the hands\r of one person, or a few, or many; and when either of these apply their\r power for the common good, such states are well governed; but when the\r interest of the one, the few, or the many who enjoy this power is alone\r consulted, then ill; for you must either affirm that those who make\r up the community are not citizens, or else let these share in the\r advantages of government. We usually","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1506},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-22","text":"Now the corruptions attending each of these governments are these; a\r kingdom may degenerate into a tyranny, an aristocracy into an oligarchy,\r and a state into a democracy. Now a tyranny is a monarchy where the good\r of one man only is the object of government, an oligarchy considers\r only the rich, and a democracy only the poor; but neither of them have a\r common good in view.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1507},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-23","text":"It will be necessary to enlarge a little more upon the nature of each\r of these states, which is not without some difficulty, for he who would\r enter into a philosophical inquiry into the principles of them, and not\r content himself with a superficial view of their outward conduct, must\r pass over and omit nothing, but explain the true spirit of each of them.\r A tyranny then is, as has been said, a monarchy, where one person has\r an absolute and despotic power over the whole community and every member\r therein: an oligarchy, where the supreme power of the state is lodged\r with the rich: a demo","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1508},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-24","text":"Let us first determine what are the proper limits of an oligarchy and\r a democracy, and what is just in each of these states; for all men have\r some natural inclination to justice; but they proceed therein only to\r a certain degree; nor can they universally point out what is absolutely\r just; as, for instance, what is equal appears just, and is so; but not\r to all; only among those who are equals: and what is unequal appears\r just, and is so; but not to all, only amongst those who are unequals;\r which circumstance some people neglect, and therefore judge ill; the\r reason for which is, they jud","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1509},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-25","text":"As to the equality of the things, these they agree in; but their dispute\r is concerning the equality of the persons, and chiefly for the reason\r above assigned; because they judge ill in their own cause; and also\r because each party thinks, that if they admit what is right in some\r particulars, they have done justice on the whole: thus, for instance,\r if some persons are unequal in riches, they suppose them unequal in the\r whole; or, on the contrary, if they are equal in liberty, they suppose\r them equal in the whole: but what is absolutely just they omit; for\r if civil society was founded for","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1510},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-26","text":"Nor was civil society founded merely to preserve the lives of its\r members; but that they might live well: for otherwise a state might\r be composed of slaves, or the animal creation: but this is not so; for\r these have no share in the happiness of it; nor do they live after their\r own choice; nor is it an alliance mutually to defend each other from\r injuries, or for a commercial intercourse: for then the Tyrrhenians and\r Carthaginians, and all other nations between whom treaties of commerce\r subsist, would be citizens of one city; for they have articles\r to regulate their exports and imports, ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1511},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-27","text":"It is evident, then, that a city is not a community of place; nor\r established for the sake of mutual safety or traffic with each other;\r but that these things are the necessary consequences of a city, although\r they may all exist where there is no city: but a city is a society of\r people joining together with their families and their children to live\r agreeably for the sake of having their lives as happy and as independent\r as possible: and for this purpose it is necessary that they should live\r in one place and intermarry with each other: hence in all cities there\r are family-meetings, clubs","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1512},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-28","text":"It may also be a doubt where the supreme power ought to be lodged.\r Shall it be with the majority, or the wealthy, with a number of proper\r persons, or one better than the rest, or with a tyrant? But whichever\r of these we prefer some difficulty will arise. For what? shall the\r poor have it because they are the majority? they may then divide among\r themselves, what belongs to the rich: nor is this unjust; because truly\r it has been so judged by the supreme power. But what avails it to point\r out what is the height of injustice if this is not? Again, if the many\r seize into their own hands ever","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1513},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-29","text":"Other particulars we will consider separately; but it seems proper to\r prove, that the supreme power ought to be lodged with the many, rather\r than with those of the better sort, who are few; and also to explain\r what doubts (and probably just ones) may arise: now, though not one\r individual of the many may himself be fit for the supreme power, yet\r when these many are joined together, it does not follow but they may be\r better qualified for it than those; and this not separately, but as a\r collective body; as the public suppers exceed those which are given at\r one person's private expense: fo","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1514},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-30","text":"But if this distinction is to be made between every people and every\r general assembly, and some few men of consequence, it may be doubtful\r whether it is true; nay, it is clear enough that, with respect to a few,\r it is not; since the same conclusion might be applied even to brutes:\r and indeed wherein do some men differ from brutes? Not but that nothing\r prevents what I have said being true of the people in some states. The\r doubt then which we have lately proposed, with all its consequences, may\r be settled in this manner; it is necessary that the freemen who compose\r the bulk of the people","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1515},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-31","text":"But there is a difficulty attending this form of government, for it\r seems, that the person who himself was capable of curing any one who\r was then sick, must be the best judge whom to employ as a physician; but\r such a one must be himself a physician; and the same holds true in every\r other practice and art: and as a physician ought [1282a] to give an\r account of his practice to a physician, so ought it to be in other arts:\r those whose business is physic may be divided into three sorts, the\r first of these is he who makes up the medicines; the second prescribes,\r and is to the other as the a","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1516},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-32","text":"But probably all that has been here said may not be right; for, to\r resume the argument I lately used, if the people are not very brutal\r indeed, although we allow that each individual knows less of these\r affairs than those who have given particular attention to them, yet when\r they come together they will know them better, or at least not worse;\r besides, in some particular arts it is not the workman only who is the\r best judge; namely, in those the works of which are understood by those\r who do not profess them: thus he who builds a house is not the only\r judge of it, for the master of the ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1517},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-33","text":"The first question that we stated shows plainly, that the supreme\r power should be lodged in laws duly made and that the magistrate or\r magistrates, either one or more, should be authorised to determine those\r cases which the laws cannot particularly speak to, as it is impossible\r for them, in general language, to explain themselves upon everything\r that may arise: but what these laws are which are established upon the\r best foundations has not been yet explained, but still remains a matter\r of some question: but the laws of every state will necessarily be like\r every state, either trifling or","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1518},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-34","text":"Since in every art and science the end aimed at is always good, so\r particularly in this, which is the most excellent of all, the founding\r of civil society, the good wherein aimed at is justice; for it is this\r which is for the benefit of all. Now, it is the common opinion, that\r justice is a certain equality; and in this point all the philosophers\r are agreed when they treat of morals: for they say what is just, and to\r whom; and that equals ought to receive equal: but we should know how\r we are to determine what things are equal and what unequal; and in\r this there is some difficulty, which","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1519},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-35","text":"If what is now said does not make this clear, we will explain it still\r further: if there should be any one, a very excellent player on the\r flute, but very deficient in family and beauty, though each of them are\r more valuable endowments than a skill in music, and excel this art in a\r higher degree than that player excels others, yet the best flutes ought\r to be given to him; for the superiority [1283a] in beauty and fortune\r should have a reference to the business in hand; but these have none.\r Moreover, according to this reasoning, every possible excellence might\r come in comparison with ev","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1520},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-36","text":"It seems, then, requisite for the establishment of a state, that all, or\r at least many of these particulars should be well canvassed and inquired\r into; and that virtue and education may most justly claim the right of\r being considered as the necessary means of making the citizens happy, as\r we have already said. As those who are equal in one particular are not\r therefore equal in all, and those who are unequal in one particular\r are not therefore unequal in all, it follows that all those governments\r which are established upon a principle which supposes they are, are\r erroneous.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1521},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-37","text":"We have already said, that all the members of the community will dispute\r with each other for the offices of the state; and in some particulars\r justly, but not so in general; the rich, for instance, because they\r have the greatest landed property, and the ultimate right to the soil is\r vested in the community; and also because their fidelity is in general\r most to be depended on. The freemen and men of family will dispute the\r point with each other, as nearly on an equality; for these latter have\r a right to a higher regard as citizens than obscure persons, for\r honourable descent is everywhe","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1522},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-38","text":"Let us now see what the many have to urge on their side against the few;\r and they may say, that if, when collectively taken, they are compared\r with them, they are stronger, richer, and better than they are. But\r should it ever happen that all these should inhabit the [1283b] same\r city, I mean the good, the rich, the noble, as well as the many, such as\r usually make up the community, I ask, will there then be any reason to\r dispute concerning who shall govern, or will there not? for in every\r community which we have mentioned there is no dispute where the supreme\r power should be placed; for","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1523},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-39","text":"There is also a doubt concerning the pretensions of all those who claim\r the honours of government: for those who found them either on fortune or\r family have nothing which they can justly say in their defence; since\r it is evident upon their principle, that if any one person can be found\r richer than all the rest, the right of governing all these will be\r justly vested in this one person. In the same manner, one man who is\r of the best family will claim it from those who dispute the point upon\r family merit: and probably in an aristocracy the same dispute might\r arise on the score of virtue, ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1524},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-40","text":"All these things seem to make it plain, that none of these principles\r are justly founded on which these persons would establish their right to\r the supreme power; and that all men whatsoever ought to obey them:\r for with respect to those who claim it as due to their virtue or their\r fortune, they might have justly some objection to make; for nothing\r hinders but that it may sometimes happen, that the many may be better\r or richer than the few, not as individuals, but in their collective\r capacity.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1525},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-41","text":"As to the doubt which some persons have proposed and objected, we may\r answer it in this manner; it is this, whether a legislator, who would\r establish the most perfect system of laws, should calculate them for\r the use of the better part of the citizens, or the many, in the\r circumstances we have already mentioned? The rectitude of anything\r consists in its equality; that therefore which is equally right will be\r advantageous to the whole state, and to every member of it in common.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1526},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-42","text":"Now, in general, a citizen is one who both shares in the government and\r also in his turn submits to be governed; [1284a] their condition, it is\r true, is different in different states: the best is that in which a man\r is enabled to choose and to persevere in a course of virtue during his\r whole life, both in his public and private state. But should there be\r one person, or a very few, eminent for an uncommon degree of virtue,\r though not enough to make up a civil state, so that the virtue of the\r many, or their political abilities, should be too inferior to come in\r comparison with theirs, if","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1527},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-43","text":"The same thing is to be perceived in the other arts and sciences; for\r a painter would not represent an animal with a foot disproportionally\r large, though he had drawn it remarkably beautiful; nor would the\r shipwright make the prow or any other part of the vessel larger than it\r ought to be; nor will the master of the band permit any who sings\r louder and better than the rest to sing in concert with them. There is\r therefore no reason that a monarch should not act in agreement with\r free states, to support his own power, if they do the same thing for the\r benefit of their respective communit","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1528},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-44","text":"It is evident, then, that in corrupt governments it is partly just and\r useful to the individual, though probably it is as clear that it is not\r entirely just: for in a well-governed state there may be great doubts\r about the use of it, not on account of the pre-eminence which one may\r have in strength, riches, or connection: but when the pre-eminence is\r virtue, what then is to be done? for it seems not right to turn out and\r banish such a one; neither does it seem right to govern him, for that\r would be like desiring to share the power with Jupiter and to govern\r him: nothing then remains bu","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1529},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-45","text":"What has been now said, it seems proper to change our subject and to\r inquire into the nature of monarchies; for we have already admitted them\r to be one of those species of government which are properly founded. And\r here let us consider whether a kingly government is proper for a city or\r a country whose principal object is the happiness of the inhabitants,\r or rather some other. But let us first determine whether this is of one\r kind only, or more; [1285a] and it is easy to know that it consists of\r many different species, and that the forms of government are not the\r same in all: for at Sp","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1530},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-46","text":"\"Whoe'er I know shall shun th' impending fight,\r    To dogs and vultures soon shall be a prey; For death is mine....\"","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1531},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-47","text":"This, then, is one species of monarchical government in which the kingly\r power is in a general for life; and is sometimes hereditary, sometimes\r elective: besides, there is also another, which is to be met with among\r some of the barbarians, in which the kings are invested with powers\r nearly equal to a tyranny, yet are, in some respects, bound by the laws\r and the customs of their country; for as the barbarians are by nature\r more prone to slavery than the Greeks, and those in Asia more than those\r in Europe, they endure without murmuring a despotic government; for\r this reason their governm","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1532},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-48","text":"These, then, are the two different sorts of these monarchies, and\r another is that which in ancient Greece they called _aesumnetes_; which\r is nothing more than an elective tyranny; and its difference from that\r which is to be found amongst the barbarians consists not in its not\r being according to law, but only in its not being according to the\r ancient customs of the country. Some persons possessed this power for\r life, others only for a particular time or particular purpose, as the\r people of Mitylene elected Pittacus to oppose the exiles, who were\r headed by Antimenides and Alcaeus the poe","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1533},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-49","text":"A fourth species of kingly government is that which was in use in the\r heroic times, when a free people submitted to a kingly government,\r according to the laws and customs of their country. For those who were\r at first of benefit to mankind, either in arts or arms, or by collecting\r them into civil society, or procuring them an establishment, became the\r kings of a willing people, and established an hereditary monarchy.\r They were particularly their generals in war, and presided over their\r sacrifices, excepting such only as belonged to the priests: they were\r also the supreme judges over the","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1534},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-50","text":"In ancient times the power of the kings extended to everything\r whatsoever, both civil, domestic, and foreign; but in after-times they\r relinquished some of their privileges, and others the people assumed, so\r that, in some states, they left their kings only the right of presiding\r over the sacrifices; and even those whom it were worth while to call\r by that name had only the right of being commander-in-chief in their\r foreign wars.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1535},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-51","text":"These, then, are the four sorts of kingdoms: the first is that of the\r heroic times; which was a government over a free people, with its rights\r in some particulars marked out; for the king was their general, their\r judge, and their high priest. The second, that of the barbarians; which\r is an hereditary despotic government regulated by laws: the third is\r that which they call aesumnetic, which is an elective tyranny. The\r fourth is the Lacedaemonian; and this, in few words, is nothing more\r than an hereditary generalship: and in these particulars they differ\r from each other. There is a fifth","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1536},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-52","text":"But the different sorts of kingly governments may, if I may so say,\r be reduced to two; which we will consider more particularly. The last\r spoken of, and the Lacedaemonian, for the chief of the others are placed\r between these, which are as it were at the extremities, they having less\r power than an absolute government, and yet more than the Lacedaemonians;\r so that the whole matter in question may be reduced to these two points;\r the one is, whether it is advantageous to the citizens to have the\r office of general continue in one person for life, and whether it should\r be confined to any par","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1537},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-53","text":"Now the first thing which presents itself to our consideration is this,\r whether it is best to be governed by a good man, or by good laws? Those\r who prefer a kingly government think that laws can only speak a general\r language, but cannot adapt themselves to particular circumstances; for\r which reason it is absurd in any science to follow written rule; and\r even in Egypt the physician was allowed to alter the mode of cure which\r the law prescribed to him, after the fourth day; but if he did it sooner\r it was at his own peril: from whence it is evident, on the very same\r account, that a govern","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1538},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-54","text":"If then a government of many, and all of them good men, compose an\r aristocracy, and the government of one a kingly power, it is evident\r that the people should rather choose the first than the last; and this\r whether the state is powerful or not, if many such persons so alike\r can be met with: and for this reason probable it was, that the first\r governments were generally monarchies; because it was difficult to find\r a number of persons eminently virtuous, more particularly as the world\r was then divided into small communities; besides, kings were appointed\r in return for the benefits they ha","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1539},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-55","text":"[1287a] We will next consider the absolute monarch that we have just\r mentioned, who does everything according to his own will: for a king\r governing under the direction of laws which he is obliged to follow does\r not of himself create any particular species of government, as we have\r already said: for in every state whatsoever, either aristocracy or\r democracy, it is easy to appoint a general for life; and there are many\r who entrust the administration of affairs to one person only; such is\r the government at Dyrrachium, and nearly the same at Opus. As for an\r absolute monarchy as it is calle","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1540},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-56","text":"The instance taken from the arts seems fallacious: wherein it is said to\r be wrong for a sick person to apply for a remedy to books, but that it\r would be far more eligible to employ those who are skilful in physic;\r for these do nothing contrary to reason from motives of friendship\r but earn their money by curing the sick, whereas those who have the\r management of public affairs do many things through hatred or favour.\r And, as a proof of what we have advanced, it may be observed, that\r whenever a sick person suspects that his physician has been persuaded by\r his enemies to be guilty of any f","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1541},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-57","text":"No one then denies, that it is necessary that there should be some\r person to decide those cases which cannot come under the cognisance of\r a written law: but we say, that it is better to have many than one;\r for though every one who decides according to the principles of the law\r decides justly; yet surely it seems absurd to suppose, that one person\r can see better with two eyes, and hear better with two ears, or do\r better with two hands and two feet, than many can do with many: for we\r see that absolute monarchs now furnish themselves with many eyes and\r ears and hands and feet; for they en","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1542},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-58","text":"Probably what we have said may be true of some persons, but not of\r others; for some men are by nature formed to be under the government of\r a master; others, of a king; others, to be the citizens of a free state,\r just and useful; but a tyranny is not according to nature, nor the other\r perverted forms of government; for they are contrary to it. But it\r is evident from what has been said, that among equals it is neither\r advantageous nor [1288a] right that one person should be lord over all\r where there are no established laws, but his will is the law; or where\r there are; nor is it right tha","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1543},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-59","text":"Since then we have said that there are three sorts of regular\r governments, and of these the best must necessarily be that which is\r administered by the best men (and this must be that which happens to\r have one man, or one family, or a number of persons excelling all the\r rest in virtue, who are able to govern and be governed in such a manner\r as will make life most agreeable, and we have already shown that the\r virtue of a good man and of a citizen in the most perfect government\r will be the same), it is evident, that in the same manner, and for those\r very qualities which would procure a ma","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1544},{"id":"aristotle-politics-3-60","text":"These particulars being treated of, we will now proceed to consider\r what sort of government is best, how it naturally arises, and how it\r is established; for it is necessary to make a proper inquiry concerning\r this.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 3","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"3"},"sequenceIndex":1545},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-1","text":"In every art and science which is not conversant in parts but in some\r one genus in which it is complete, it is the business of that art alone\r to determine what is fitted to its particular genus; as what particular\r exercise is fitted to a certain particular body, and suits it best: for\r that body which is formed by nature the most perfect and superior to\r others necessarily requires the best exercise-and also of what one kind\r that must be which will suit the generality; and this is the business of\r the gymnastic arts: and although any one should not desire to acquire\r an exact knowledge and","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1546},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-2","text":"Since, then, according to our first method in treating of the different\r forms of government, we have divided those which are regular into three\r sorts, the kingly, the aristocratical, the free states, and shown\r the three excesses which these are liable to: the kingly, of becoming\r tyrannical; the aristocratical, oligarchical; and the free state,\r democratical: and as we have already treated of the aristocratical and\r kingly; for to enter into an inquiry what sort of government is best\r is the same thing as to treat of these two expressly; for each of\r them desires to be established upon the ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1547},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-3","text":"Now I affirm, that all these states have, without exception, fallen into\r excess; and also that he should not have said that one oligarchy was\r better than another, but that it was not quite so bad. But this question\r we shall not enter into at present. We shall first inquire how many\r different sorts of free states there are; since there are many\r species of democracies and oligarchies; and which of them is the most\r comprehensive, and most desirable after the best form of government; or\r if there is any other like an aristocracy, well established; and also\r which of these is best adapted to ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1548},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-4","text":"The reason for there being many different sorts of governments is this,\r that each state consists of a great number of parts; for, in the first\r place, we see that all cities are made up of families: and again, of\r the multitude of these some must be rich, some poor, and others in the\r middle station; and that, both of the rich and poor, some will be used\r to arms, others not. We see also, that some of the common people are\r husbandmen, others attend the market, and others are artificers. There\r is also a difference between the nobles in their wealth, and the dignity\r in which they live: for i","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1549},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-5","text":"It is evident then, that there must be many forms of government,\r differing from each other in their particular constitution: for the\r parts of which they are composed each differ from the other. For\r government is the ordering of the magistracies of the state; and these\r the community share between themselves, either as they can attain them\r by force, or according to some common equality which there is amongst\r them, as poverty, wealth, or something which they both partake of. There\r must therefore necessarily be as many different forms of governments as\r there are different ranks in the soci","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1550},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-6","text":"We ought not to define a democracy as some do, who say simply, that it\r is a government where the supreme power is lodged in the people; for\r even in oligarchies the supreme power is in the majority. Nor should\r they define an oligarchy a government where the supreme power is in the\r hands of a few: for let us suppose the number of a people to be thirteen\r hundred, and that of these one thousand were rich, who would not permit\r the three hundred poor to have any share in the government, although\r they were free, and their equal in everything else; no one would say,\r that this government was a ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1551},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-7","text":"Nor are those things which we have already mentioned alone sufficient\r to describe these states; for since there are many species both of a\r democracy and an oligarchy, the matter requires further consideration;\r as we cannot admit, that if a few persons who are free possess the\r supreme power over the many who are not free, that this government is a\r democracy: as in Apollonia, in Ionia, and in Thera: for in each of these\r cities the honours of the state belong to some few particular families,\r who first founded the colonies. Nor would the rich, because they are\r superior in numbers, form a d","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1552},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-8","text":"We have now proved that there are various forms of government and have\r assigned a reason for it; and shall proceed to show that there are\r even more than these, and what they are, and why; setting out with the\r principle we have already laid down. We admit that every city consists\r not of one, but many parts: thus, if we should endeavour to comprehend\r the different species of animals we should first of all note those parts\r which every animal must have, as a certain sensorium, and also what is\r necessary to acquire and retain food, as a mouth and a belly; besides\r certain parts to enable it ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1553},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-9","text":"The same thing is true of what are called states; for a city is not made\r of one but many parts, as has already been often said; one of which is\r those who supply it with provisions, called husbandmen, another called\r mechanics, [1291a] whose employment is in the manual arts, without which\r the city could not be inhabited; of these some are busied about what is\r absolutely necessary, others in what contribute to the elegancies and\r pleasures of life; the third sort are your exchange-men, I mean by these\r your buyers, sellers, merchants, and victuallers; the fourth are your\r hired labourers or ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1554},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-10","text":"Besides, every one supposes himself a man of political abilities, and\r that he is qualified for almost every department in the state. But the\r same person cannot at once be poor and rich: for which reason the most\r obvious division of the city is into two parts, the poor and rich;\r moreover, since for the generality the one are few, the other many, they\r seem of all the parts of a city most contrary to each other; so that as\r the one or the other prevail they form different states; and these are\r the democracy and the oligarchy.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1555},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-11","text":"But that there are many different states, and from what causes they\r arise, has been already mentioned: and that there are also different\r species both of democracies and oligarchies we will now show. Though\r this indeed is evident from what we have already said: there are also\r many different sorts of common people, and also of those who are\r called gentlemen. Of the different sorts of the first are husbandmen,\r artificers, exchange-men, who are employed in buying and selling,\r seamen, of which some are engaged in war, some in traffic, some in\r carrying goods and passengers from place to plac","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1556},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-12","text":"The most pure democracy is that which is so called principally from that\r equality which prevails in it: for this is what the law in that state\r directs; that the poor shall be in no greater subjection than the rich;\r nor that the supreme power shall be lodged with either of these, but\r that both shall share it. For if liberty and equality, as some persons\r suppose, are chiefly to be found in a democracy, it must be most so\r by every department of government being alike open to all; but as the\r people are the majority, and what they vote is law, it follows that such\r a state must be a democrac","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1557},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-13","text":"Homer also discommends the government of many; but whether he means this\r we are speaking of, or where each person exercises his power separately,\r is uncertain. When the people possess this power they desire to be\r altogether absolute, that they may not be under the control of the law,\r and this is the time when flatterers are held in repute. Nor is there\r any difference between such a people and monarchs in a tyranny: for\r their manners are the same, and they both hold a despotic power over\r better persons than themselves. For their decrees are like the others'\r edicts; their demagogues like","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1558},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-14","text":"Any one, therefore, may with great justice blame such a government as\r being a democracy, and not a free state; for where the government is\r not in the laws, then there is no free state, for the law ought to be\r supreme over all things; and particular incidents which arise should be\r determined by the magistrates or the state. If, therefore, a\r democracy is to be reckoned a free state, it is evident that any such\r establishment which centres all power in the votes of the people cannot,\r properly speaking, be a democracy: for their decrees cannot be general\r in their extent. Thus, then, we may ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1559},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-15","text":"Of the different species of oligarchies one is, when the right to the\r offices is regulated by a certain census; so that the poor, although the\r majority, have no share in it; while all those who are included therein\r take part in the management of public affairs. Another sort is, when\r [1292b] the magistrates are men of very small fortune, who upon any\r vacancy do themselves fill it up: and if they do this out of the\r community at large, the state approaches to an aristocracy; if out of\r any particular class of people, it will be an oligarchy. Another sort of\r oligarchy is, when the power is ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1560},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-16","text":"It should also be known, that it often happens that a free state, where\r the supreme power is in the laws, may not be democratic, and yet in\r consequence of the established manners and customs of the people, may\r be governed as if it was; so, on the other hand, where the laws may\r countenance a more democratic form of government, these may make the\r state inclining to an oligarchy; and this chiefly happens when there\r has been any alteration in the government; for the people do not easily\r change, but love their own ancient customs; and it is by small degrees\r only that one thing takes place o","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1561},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-17","text":"It is evident from what has been said, that there are as many different\r sorts of democracies and oligarchies as I have reckoned up: for, of\r necessity, either all ranks of the people which I have enumerated must\r have a share in the government, or some only, and others not; for when\r the husbandmen, and those only who possess moderate fortunes, have the\r supreme power, they will govern according to law; for as they must get\r their livings by their employs, they have but little leisure for public\r business: they will therefore establish proper laws, and never call\r public assemblies but when t","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1562},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-18","text":"The first species of oligarchy is, when the generality of the state are\r men of moderate and not too large property; for this gives them leisure\r for the management of public affairs: and, as they are a numerous body,\r it necessarily follows that the supreme power must be in the laws, and\r not in men; for as they are far removed from a monarchical government,\r and have not sufficient fortune to neglect their private affairs, while\r they are too many to be supported by the public, they will of course\r determine to be governed by the laws, and not by each other. But if the\r men of property in th","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1563},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-19","text":"There are besides two other states, a democracy and an oligarchy, one\r of which all speak of, and it is always esteemed a species of the\r four sorts; and thus they reckon them up; a monarchy, an oligarchy, a\r democracy, and this fourth which they call an aristocracy. There is\r also a fifth, which bears a name that is also common to the other four,\r namely, a state: but as this is seldom to be met with, it has escaped\r those who have endeavoured to enumerate the different sorts of\r governments, which [1293b] they fix at four only, as does Plato in his\r Republic.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1564},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-20","text":"An aristocracy, of which I have already treated in the first book, is\r rightly called so; for a state governed by the best men, upon the most\r virtuous principles, and not upon any hypothesis, which even good men\r may propose, has alone a right to be called an aristocracy, for it is\r there only that a man is at once a good man and a good citizen; while in\r other states men are good only relative to those states. Moreover, there\r are some other states which are called by the same name, that differ\r both from oligarchies and free states, wherein not only the rich but\r also the virtuous have a sh","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1565},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-21","text":"It now remains for us to treat of that government which is particularly\r called a free state, and also of a tyranny; and the reason for my\r choosing to place that free state here is, because this, as well\r as those aristocracies already mentioned, although they do not seem\r excesses, yet, to speak true, they have all departed from what a perfect\r government is. Nay, they are deviations both of them equally from other\r forms, as I said at the beginning. It is proper to mention a tyranny the\r last of all governments, for it is of all others the least like one:\r but as my intention is to treat of","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1566},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-22","text":"I shall now inquire into a free state and show what it is; and we shall\r the better understand its positive nature as we have already described\r an oligarchy and a democracy; for a free state is indeed nothing more\r than a mixture of them, and it has been usual to call those which\r incline most to a democracy, a free state; those which incline most to\r an oligarchy, an aristocracy, because those who are rich are generally\r men of family and education; besides, they enjoy those things which\r others are often guilty of crimes to procure: for which reason they are\r regarded as men of worth and ho","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1567},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-23","text":"Since, then, it is the genius of an aristocracy to allot the larger\r part of the government to the best citizens, they therefore say, that\r an oligarchy is chiefly composed of those men who are worthy and\r honourable: now it [1294a] seems impossible that where the government\r is in the hands of the good, there the laws should not be good, but bad;\r or, on the contrary, that where the government is in the hands of the\r bad, there the laws should be good; nor is a government well constituted\r because the laws are, without at the same time care is taken that they\r are observed; for to enforce obe","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1568},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-24","text":"We have already seen that there are governments different from a\r monarchy, a democracy, and an oligarchy; and what they are, and wherein\r they differ from each other; and also aristocracies and states properly\r so called, which are derived from them; and it is evident that these are\r not much unlike each other.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1569},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-25","text":"We shall next proceed to show how that government which is peculiarly\r called a state arises alongside of democracy and oligarchy, and how it\r ought to be established; and this will at the same time show what are\r the proper boundaries of both these governments, for we must mark out\r wherein they differ from one another, and then from both these compose\r a state of such parts of each of them as will show from whence they were\r taken.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1570},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-26","text":"There are three different ways in which two states may be blended and\r joined together; for, in the first place, all those rules may be adopted\r which the laws of each of them have ordered; as for instance in the\r judicial department, for in an oligarchy the rich are fined if they do\r not come to the court as jurymen, but the poor are not paid for their\r attendance; but in democracies they are, while the rich are not fined\r for their neglect. Now these things, as being common to both, are fit\r to be observed in a free [1294b] state which is composed of both. This,\r then, is one way in which th","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1571},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-27","text":"It now remains to treat of a tyranny; not that there is [1295a] much\r to be said on that subject, but as it makes part of our plan, since\r we enumerated it amongst our different sorts of governments. In the\r beginning of this work we inquired into the nature of kingly government,\r and entered into a particular examination of what was most properly\r called so, and whether it was advantageous to a state or not, and what\r it should be, and how established; and we divided a tyranny into two\r pieces when we were upon this subject, because there is something\r analogous between this and a kingly gove","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1572},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-28","text":"We proceed now to inquire what form of government and what manner\r of life is best for communities in general, not adapting it to that\r superior virtue which is above the reach of the vulgar, or that\r education which every advantage of nature and fortune only can furnish,\r nor to those imaginary plans which may be formed at pleasure; but to\r that mode of life which the greater part of mankind can attain to,\r and that government which most cities may establish: for as to those\r aristocracies which we have now mentioned, they are either too perfect\r for a state to support, or one so nearly alike","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1573},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-29","text":"The opinions which we form upon these subjects must depend upon one\r common principle: for if what I have said in my treatise on Morals is\r true, a happy life must arise from an uninterrupted course of virtue;\r and if virtue consists in a certain medium, the middle life must\r certainly be the happiest; which medium is attainable [1295b] by\r every one. The boundaries of virtue and vice in the state must also\r necessarily be the same as in a private person; for the form of\r government is the life of the city. In every city the people are divided\r into three sorts; the very rich, the very poor, a","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1574},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-30","text":"A city composed of such men must therefore consist of slaves and\r masters, not freemen; where one party must hate, and the other\r despise, where there could be no possibility of friendship or political\r community: for community supposes affection; for we do not even on the\r road associate with our enemies. It is also the genius of a city to be\r composed as much as possible of equals; which will be most so when the\r inhabitants are in the middle state: from whence it follows, that that\r city must be best framed which is composed of those whom we say are\r naturally its proper members. It is men ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1575},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-31","text":"It is therefore the greatest happiness which the citizens can enjoy to\r possess a moderate and convenient fortune; for when some possess too\r much, and others nothing at [1296a] all, the government must either be\r in the hands of the meanest rabble or else a pure oligarchy; or, from\r the excesses of both, a tyranny; for this arises from a headstrong\r democracy or an oligarchy, but very seldom when the members of the\r community are nearly on an equality with each other. We will assign a\r reason for this when we come to treat of the alterations which different\r states are likely to undergo. The ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1576},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-32","text":"We ought to consider as a proof of what I now advance, that the best\r lawgivers themselves were those in the middle rank of life, amongst whom\r was Solon, as is evident from his poems, and Lycurgus, for he was not\r a king, and Charondas, and indeed most others. What has been said will\r show us why of so many free states some have changed to democracies,\r others to oligarchies: for whenever the number of those in the middle\r state has been too small, those who were the more numerous, whether the\r rich or the poor, always overpowered them and assumed to themselves the\r administration of public a","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1577},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-33","text":"Those who made conquests in Greece, having all of them an eye to the\r respective forms of government in their own cities, established either\r democracies or oligarchies, not considering what was serviceable to the\r state, but what was similar to their own; for which reason a government\r has never been established where the supreme power has been placed\r amongst those of the middling rank, or very seldom; and, amongst a few,\r one man only of those who have yet been conquerors has been persuaded\r to give the preference to this order of [1296b] men: it is indeed an\r established custom with the in","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1578},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-34","text":"Thus we have shown what the best state is, and why. It will not be\r difficult to perceive of the many states which there are, for we have\r seen that there are various forms both of democracies and oligarchies,\r to which we should give the first place, to which the second, and in\r the same manner the next also; and to observe what are the particular\r excellences and defects of each, after we have first described the best\r possible; for that must be the best which is nearest to this, that worst\r which is most distant from the medium, without any one has a particular\r plan of his own which he jud","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1579},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-35","text":"After what has been said, it follows that we should now show what\r particular form of government is most suitable for particular persons;\r first laying this down as a general maxim, that that party which desires\r to support the actual administration of the state ought always to be\r superior to that which would alter it. Every city is made up of quality\r and quantity: by quality I mean liberty, riches, education, and family,\r and by quantity its relative populousness: now it may happen that\r quality may exist in one of those parts of which the city is composed,\r and quantity in another; thus th","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1580},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-36","text":"Those who would establish aristocratical governments are mistaken not\r only in giving too much power to the rich, but also in deceiving the\r common people; for at last, instead of an imaginary good, they must feel\r a real evil, for the encroachments of the rich are more destructive to\r the state than those of the poor.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1581},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-37","text":"There are five particulars in which, under fair pretences, the rich\r craftily endeavour to undermine the rights of the people, these are\r their public assemblies, their offices of state, their courts of\r justice, their military power, and their gymnastic exercises. With\r respect to their public assemblies, in having them open to all, but in\r fining the rich only, or others very little, for not attending; with\r respect to offices, in permitting the poor to swear off, but not\r granting this indulgence to those who are within the census;\r with respect to their courts of justice, in fining the ric","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1582},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-38","text":"The contrary prevails in a democracy; for there they make the poor a\r proper allowance for attending the assemblies and the courts, but give\r the rich nothing for doing it: whence it is evident, that if any one\r would properly blend these customs together, they must extend both the\r pay and the fine to every member of the community, and then every one\r would share in it, whereas part only now do. The citizens of a free\r state ought to [1297b] consist of those only who bear arms: with respect\r to their census it is not easy to determine exactly what it ought to be,\r but the rule that should dir","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1583},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-39","text":"In some governments the power is vested not only in those who bear arms,\r but also in those who have borne them. Among the Malienses the state was\r composed of these latter only, for all the officers were soldiers who\r had served their time. And the first states in Greece which succeeded\r those where kingly power was established, were governed by the military.\r First of all the horse, for at that time the strength and excellence of\r the army depended on the horse, for as to the heavy-armed foot they were\r useless without proper discipline; but the art of tactics was not known\r to the ancients,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1584},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-40","text":"We have now shown why there are many sorts of governments, and others\r different from those we have treated of: for there are more species of\r democracies than one, and the like is true of other forms, and what are\r their differences, and whence they arise; and also of all others\r which is the best, at least in general; and which is best suited for\r particular people.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1585},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-41","text":"We will now proceed to make some general reflections upon the\r governments next in order, and also to consider each of them in\r particular; beginning with those principles which appertain to each: now\r there are three things in all states which a careful legislator ought\r well to consider, which are of great consequence to all, and which\r properly attended to the state must necessarily be happy; and according\r to the variation of which the one will differ from the other. The first\r of these is the [1298a] public assembly; the second the officers of the\r state, that is, who they ought to be, an","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1586},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-42","text":"Now it is the proper business of the public assembly to determine\r concerning war and peace, making or breaking off alliances, to enact\r laws, to sentence to death, banishment, or confiscation of goods, and to\r call the magistrates to account for their behaviour when in office. Now\r these powers must necessarily be entrusted to the citizens in general,\r or all of them to some; either to one magistrate or more; or some to\r one, and some to another, or some to all, but others to some: to entrust\r all to all is in the spirit of a democracy, for the people aim at\r equality. There are many methods ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1587},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-43","text":"These, then, are the methods in which public business is conducted in a\r democracy. When the power is in the hands of part of the community\r only, it is an oligarchy and this also admits of different customs; for\r whenever the officers of the state are chosen out of those who have a\r moderate fortune, and these from that circumstance are many, and\r when they depart not from that line which the law has laid down, but\r carefully follow it, and when all within the census are eligible,\r certainly it is then an oligarchy, but founded on true principles of\r government [1298b] from its moderation. Wh","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1588},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-44","text":"In an oligarchy they should either call up some of the common people to\r the council, or else establish a court, as is done in some other states,\r whom they call pre-advisers or guardians of the laws, whose business\r should be to propose first what they should afterwards enact. By this\r means the people would have a place in the administration of public\r affairs, without having it in their power to occasion any disorder in\r the government. Moreover, the people may be allowed to have a vote\r in whatever bill is proposed, but may not themselves propose anything\r contrary thereto; or they may giv","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1589},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-45","text":"We now proceed to consider the choice of magistrates; for this branch of\r public business contains many different Parts, as how many there shall\r be, what shall be their particular office, and with respect to time how\r long each of them shall continue in place; for some make it six months,\r others shorter, others for a year, others for a much longer time; or\r whether they should be perpetual or for a long time, or neither; for\r the same person may fill the same office several times, or he may not be\r allowed to enjoy it even twice, but only once: and also with respect to\r the appointment of ma","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1590},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-46","text":"Now it is not easy to determine to whom we ought properly to give the\r name of magistrate, for a government requires many persons in office;\r but every one of those who is either chosen by vote or lot is not to be\r reckoned a magistrate. The priests, for instance, in the first place;\r for these are to be considered as very different from civil magistrates:\r to these we may add the choregi and heralds; nay, even ambassadors are\r elected: there are some civil employments which belong to the citizens;\r and these are either when they are all engaged in one thing, as when as\r soldiers they obey the","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1591},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-47","text":"In extensive governments it is proper to allot one employment to one\r person, as there are many to serve the public in so numerous a society,\r where some may be passed over for a long time, and others never be in\r office but once; and indeed everything is better done which has the\r whole attention of one person, than when that [1299b] attention is\r divided amongst many; but in small states it is necessary that a few of\r the citizens should execute many employments; for their numbers are so\r small it will not be convenient to have many of them in office at the\r same time; for where shall we fin","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1592},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-48","text":"In different states shall the magistrates be different or the same?\r I mean, whether in a democracy, an oligarchy, an aristocracy, and a\r monarchy, the same persons shall have the same power? or shall it\r vary according to the different formation of the government? as in an\r aristocracy the offices of the state are allotted to those who are well\r educated; in an oligarchy to those who are rich; in a democracy to the\r freemen? Or shall the magistrates differ as the communities differ?\r For it may happen that the very same may be sometimes proper, sometimes\r otherwise: in this state it may be ne","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1593},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-49","text":"Of the three parts of which a government is formed, we now come to\r consider the judicial; and this also we shall divide in the same manner\r as we did the magisterial, into three parts. Of whom the judges shall\r consist, and for what causes, and how. When I say of whom, I mean\r whether they shall be the whole people, or some particulars; by for what\r causes I mean, how many different courts shall be appointed; by how,\r whether they shall be elected by vote or lot. Let us first determine how\r many different courts there ought to be. Now these are eight. The\r first of these is the court of inspe","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1594},{"id":"aristotle-politics-4-50","text":"There is also another court called at Athens the Court of Phreattae,\r which determines points relating to a murder committed by one who has\r run away, to decide whether he shall return; though such an affair\r happens but seldom, and in very large cities; the seventh, to determine\r causes wherein strangers are concerned, and this whether they are\r between stranger and stranger or between a stranger and a citizen. The\r eighth and last is for small actions, from one to five drachma's, or a\r little more; for these ought also to be legally determined, but not to\r be brought before the whole body of","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 4","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"4"},"sequenceIndex":1595},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-1","text":"We have now gone through those particulars we proposed to speak of; it\r remains that we next consider from what causes and how alterations\r in government arise, and of what nature they are, and to what the\r destruction of each state is owing; and also to what form any form of\r polity is most likely to shift into, and what are the means to be\r used for the general preservation of governments, as well as what are\r applicable to any particular state; and also of the remedies which\r are to be applied either to all in general, or to any one considered\r separately, when they are in a state of corrup","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1596},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-2","text":"Since we are inquiring into the causes of seditions and revolutions\r in governments, we must begin entirely with the first principles from\r whence they arise. Now these, so to speak, are nearly three in number;\r which we must first distinguish in general from each other, and\r endeavour to show in what situation people are who begin a sedition;\r and for what causes; and thirdly, what are the beginnings of political\r troubles and mutual quarrels with each other. Now that cause which of\r all others most universally inclines men to desire to bring about a\r change in government is that which I have","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1597},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-3","text":"What influence ill-treatment and profit have for this purpose, and how\r they may be the causes of sedition, is almost self-evident; for when the\r magistrates are haughty and endeavour to make greater profits than their\r office gives them, they not only occasion seditions amongst each other,\r but against the state also who gave them their power; and this their\r avarice has two objects, either private property or the property of the\r state. What influence honours have, and how they may occasion sedition,\r is evident enough; for those who are themselves unhonoured while they\r see others honoured,","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1598},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-4","text":"But seditions in government do not arise for little things, but from\r them; for their immediate cause is something of moment. Now, trifling\r quarrels are attended with the greatest consequences when they arise\r between persons of the first distinction in the state, as was the\r case with the Syracusians in a remote period; for a revolution in the\r government was brought about by a quarrel between two young men who were\r in office, upon a love affair; for one of them being absent, the other\r seduced his mistress; he in his turn, offended with this, persuaded his\r friend's wife to come and live w","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1599},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-5","text":"We ought now to inquire into those events which will arise from these\r causes in every species of government. Democracies will be most subject\r to revolutions from the dishonesty of their demagogues; for partly, by\r informing against men of property, they induce them to join together\r through self-defence, for a common fear will make the greatest enemies\r unite; and partly by setting the common people against them: and this is\r what any one may continually see practised in many states. In the island\r of Cos, for instance, the democracy was subverted by the wickedness\r of the demagogues, for th","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1600},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-6","text":"There are two things which of all others most evidently occasion a\r revolution in an oligarchy; one is, when the people are ill used, for\r then every individual is ripe for [1305b] sedition; more particularly if\r one of the oligarchy should happen to be their leader; as Lygdamis, at\r Naxus, who was afterwards tyrant of that island. Seditions also which\r arise from different causes will differ from each other; for sometimes\r a revolution is brought about by the rich who have no share in the\r administration, which is in the hands of a very few indeed: and this\r happened at Massilia, Ister, Herac","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1601},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-7","text":"Commotions also arise in aristocracies, from there being so few persons\r in power (as we have already observed they do in oligarchies, for in\r this particular an aristocracy is most near an oligarchy, for in both\r these states the administration of public affairs is in the hands of\r a few; not that this arises from the same cause in both, though herein\r they chiefly seem alike): and these will necessarily be most likely to\r happen when the generality of the people are high-spirited and think\r themselves equal to each other in merit; such were those at Lacedasmon,\r called the Partheniae (for th","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1602},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-8","text":"We are now to consider upon what the preservation of governments in\r general and of each state in particular depends; and, in the first\r place, it is evident that if we are right in the causes we have assigned\r for their destruction, we know also the means of their preservation; for\r things contrary produce contraries: but destruction and preservation are\r contrary to each other. In well-tempered governments it requires as much\r care as anything whatsoever, that nothing be done contrary to law: and\r this ought chiefly to be attended to in matters of small consequence;\r for an illegality that a","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1603},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-9","text":"There are three qualifications necessary for those who fill the\r first departments in government; first of all, an affection for the\r established constitution; second place, abilities every way completely\r equal to the business of their office; in the third, virtue and justice\r correspondent to the nature of that particular state they are placed in;\r for if justice is not the same in all states, it is evident that there\r must be different species thereof. There may be some doubt, when all\r these qualifications do not in the same persons, in what manner the\r choice shall be made; as for instanc","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1604},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-10","text":"It now remains that we speak of monarchies, their causes of corruption,\r and means of preservation; and indeed almost the same things which have\r been said of other governments happen to kingdoms and tyrannies; for a\r kingdom partakes of an aristocracy, a tyranny of the worst species of an\r oligarchy and democracy; for which reason it is the worst that man\r can submit to, as being composed of two, both of which are bad, and\r collectively retains all the corruptions and all the defects of both\r these states. These two species of monarchies arise from principles\r contrary to each other: a kingdo","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1605},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-11","text":"That a tyranny contains all that is bad both in a democracy and an\r oligarchy is evident; with an oligarchy it has for its end gain, as the\r only means of providing the tyrant with guards and the luxuries of life;\r like that it places no confidence in the people; and therefore deprives\r them of the use of arms: it is also common to them both to persecute the\r populace, to drive them out of the city and their own habitations. With\r a democracy it quarrels with the nobles, and destroys them both\r publicly and privately, or drives them into banishment, as rivals and\r an impediment to the governme","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1606},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-12","text":"Many also who have had their bodies scourged with stripes have, through\r resentment, either killed those who caused them to be inflicted or\r conspired against them, even when they had kingly power, as at Mitylene\r Megacles, joining with his friends, killed the Penthelidee, who used\r to go about striking those they met with clubs. Thus, in later times,\r Smendes killed Penthilus for whipping him and dragging him away from\r his wife. Decamnichus also was the chief cause of the conspiracy against\r Archelaus, for he urged others on: the occasion of his resentment was\r his having delivered him to Eu","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1607},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-13","text":"Kingdoms are seldom destroyed by any outward attack; for which reason\r they are generally very stable; but they have many causes of subversion\r within; of which two are the principal; one is when those who are\r in power [1313a] excite a sedition, the other when they endeavour to\r establish a tyranny by assuming greater power than the law gives them.\r A kingdom, indeed, is not what we ever see erected in our times, but\r rather monarchies and tyrannies; for a kingly government is one that\r is voluntarily submitted to, and its supreme power admitted upon great\r occasions: but where many are equal","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1608},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-14","text":"Monarchies, in a word, are preserved by means contrary to what I have\r already mentioned as the cause of their destruction; but to speak to\r each separately: the stability of a kingdom will depend upon the power\r of the king's being kept within moderate bounds; for by how much the\r less extensive his power is, by so much the longer will his government\r continue; for he will be less despotic and more upon an equality of\r condition with those he governs; who, on that account, will envy him the\r less.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1609},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-15","text":"It was on this account that the kingdom of the Molossi continued so\r long; and the Lacedaemonians from their government's being from the\r beginning divided into two parts, and also by the moderation introduced\r into the other parts of it by Theopompus, and his establishment of the\r ephori; for by taking something from the power he increased the duration\r of the kingdom, so that in some measure he made it not less, but bigger;\r as they say he replied to his wife, who asked him if he was not ashamed\r to deliver down his kingdom to his children reduced from what he\r received it from his ancestors","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1610},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-16","text":"Indeed an oligarchy and a tyranny are of all governments of the shortest\r duration. The tyranny of Orthagoras and his family at Sicyon, it is\r true, continued longer than any other: the reason for which was, that\r they used their power with moderation, and were in many particulars\r obedient to the laws; and, as Clisthenes was an able general, he never\r fell into contempt, and by the care he took that in many particulars his\r government should be popular. He is reported also to have presented a\r person with a crown who adjudged the victory to another; and some say\r that it is the statue of that","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1611},{"id":"aristotle-politics-5-17","text":"They say also, that Pisistratus submitted to be summoned into the court\r of the Areopagites. The second that we shall mention is the tyranny of\r the Cypselidse, at Corinth, which continued seventy-seven years and\r six months; for Cypselus was tyrant there thirty years, Periander\r forty-four, and Psammetichus, the son of Georgias, three years; the\r reason for which was, that Cypselus was a popular man, and governed\r without guards. Periander indeed ruled like a tyrant, but then he was an\r able general. The third was that of the Pisistradidae at Athens; but it\r was not continual: for Pisistratus","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 5","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"5"},"sequenceIndex":1612},{"id":"aristotle-politics-6-1","text":"We have already shown what is the nature of the supreme council in the\r state, and wherein one may differ from another, and how the different\r magistrates should be regulated; and also the judicial department, and\r what is best suited to what state; and also to what causes both the\r destruction and preservation of governments are owing.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":1613},{"id":"aristotle-politics-6-2","text":"As there are very many species of democracies, as well as of other\r states, it will not be amiss to consider at the same time anything which\r we may have omitted to mention concerning either of them, and to allot\r to each that mode of conduct which is peculiar to and advantageous for\r them; and also to inquire into the combinations of all these different\r modes of government which we [1317a] have mentioned; for as these are\r blended together the government is altered, as from an aristocracy to\r be an oligarchy, and from a free state to be a democracy. Now, I mean\r by those combinations of gove","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":1614},{"id":"aristotle-politics-6-3","text":"And first, we will speak of a democracy; and this will at the same\r time show clearly the nature of its opposite which some persons call\r an oligarchy; and in doing this we must examine into all the parts of\r a democracy, and everything that is connected therewith; for from the\r manner in which these are compounded together different species of\r democracies arise: and hence it is that they are more than one, and of\r various natures. Now, there are two causes which occasion there being so\r many democracies; one of which is that which we have already mentioned;\r namely, there being different sor","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":1615},{"id":"aristotle-politics-6-4","text":"Now the foundation of a democratical state is liberty, and people have\r been accustomed to say this as if here only liberty was to be found; for\r they affirm that this is the end proposed by every democracy. But one\r part of liberty is to govern and be governed alternately; for, according\r to democratical justice, equality is measured by numbers, and not by\r worth: and this being just, it is necessary that the supreme power\r should be vested in the people at large; and that what the majority\r determine should be final: so that in a democracy the poor ought to have\r more power than the rich, as","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":1616},{"id":"aristotle-politics-6-5","text":"In the next place we must inquire how this equality is to be procured.\r Shall the qualifications be divided so that five hundred rich should be\r equal to a thousand poor, or shall the thousand have equal power with\r the five hundred? or shall we not establish our equality in this manner?\r but divide indeed thus, and afterwards taking an equal number both out\r of the five hundred and the thousand, invest them with the power of\r creating the magistrates and judges. Is this state then established\r according to perfect democratical justice, or rather that which is\r guided by numbers only? For the ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":1617},{"id":"aristotle-politics-6-6","text":"There are four kinds of democracies. The best is that which is composed\r of those first in order, as we have already said, and this also is the\r most ancient of any. I call that the first which every one would place\r so, was he to divide the people; for the best part of these are the\r husbandmen. We see, then, that a democracy may be framed where the\r majority live by tillage or pasturage; for, as their property is\r but small, they will not be at leisure perpetually to hold public\r assemblies, but will be continually employed in following their own\r business, not having otherwise the means of ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":1618},{"id":"aristotle-politics-6-7","text":"It is also the business of the legislator and all those who would\r support a government of this sort not to make it too great a work, or\r too perfect; but to aim only to render it stable: for, let a state be\r constituted ever so badly, there is no difficulty in its continuing a\r few days: they should therefore endeavour to procure its safety by\r all those ways which we have described in assigning the causes of the\r preservation and destruction of governments; avoiding what is hurtful,\r and by framing such laws, written and unwritten, as contain those things\r which chiefly tend to the preservat","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":1619},{"id":"aristotle-politics-6-8","text":"What has been already said will almost of itself sufficiently show how\r an oligarchy ought to be founded; for he who would frame such a state\r should have in his view a democracy to oppose it; for every species of\r oligarchy should be founded on principles diametrically opposite to some\r species of democracy.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":1620},{"id":"aristotle-politics-6-9","text":"The first and best-framed oligarchy is that which approaches near to\r what we call a free state; in which there ought to be two different\r census, the one high, the other low: from those who are within the\r latter the ordinary officers of the state ought to be chosen; from the\r former the supreme magistrates: nor should any one be excluded from a\r part of the administration who was within the census; which should be\r so regulated that the commonalty who are included in it should by means\r thereof be superior to those who have no share in the government; for\r those who are to have the managemen","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":1621},{"id":"aristotle-politics-6-10","text":"As the greater part of the community are divided into four sorts of\r people; husbandmen, mechanics, traders, and hired servants; and as those\r who are employed in war may likewise be divided into four; the horsemen,\r the heavy-armed soldier, the light-armed, and the sailor, where the\r nature of the country can admit a great number of horse; there a\r powerful oligarchy may be easily established: for the safety of the\r inhabitants depends upon a force of that sort; but those who can support\r the expense of horsemen must be persons of some considerable fortune.\r Where the troops are chiefly heavy","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":1622},{"id":"aristotle-politics-6-11","text":"After what has been said I proceed next to treat particularly of the\r magistrates; of what nature they should be, how many, and for what\r purpose, as I have already mentioned: for without necessary magistrates\r no state can exist, nor without those which contribute to its dignity\r and good order can exist happily: now it is necessary that in small\r states the magistrates should be few; in a large one, many: also to\r know well what offices may be joined together, and what ought to be\r separated. The first thing necessary is to establish proper regulators\r in the markets; for which purpose a cer","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 6","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"6"},"sequenceIndex":1623},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-1","text":"He who proposes to make that inquiry which is necessary concerning what\r government is best, ought first to determine what manner of living is\r most eligible; for while this remains uncertain it will also be equally\r uncertain what government is best: for, provided no unexpected accidents\r interfere, it is highly probable, that those who enjoy the best\r government will live the most happily according to their circumstances;\r he ought, therefore, first to know what manner of life is most desirable\r for all; and afterwards whether this life is the same to the man and\r the citizen, or different. ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1624},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-2","text":"Thus much by way of introduction; for I could not but just touch upon\r this subject, though I could not go through a complete investigation\r of it, as it properly belongs to another question: let us at present\r suppose so much, that a man's happiest life, both as an individual and\r as a citizen, is a life of virtue, accompanied with those enjoyments\r which virtue usually procures. If [1324a] there are any who are not\r convinced by what I have said, their doubts shall be answered hereafter,\r at present we shall proceed according to our intended method.","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1625},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-3","text":"It now remains for us to say whether the happiness of any individual\r man and the city is the same or different: but this also is evident; for\r whosoever supposes that riches will make a person happy, must place the\r happiness of the city in riches if it possesses them; those who prefer a\r life which enjoys a tyrannic power over others will also think, that the\r city which has many others under its command is most happy: thus also\r if any one approves a man for his virtue, he will think the most worthy\r city the happiest: but here there are two particulars which require\r consideration, one of ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1626},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-4","text":"Now a city which is well governed might be very [1325a] happy in itself\r while it enjoyed a good system of laws, although it should happen to be\r so situated as to have no connection with any other state, though its\r constitution should not be framed for war or conquest; for it would then\r have no occasion for these. It is evident therefore that the business of\r war is to be considered as commendable, not as a final end, but as the\r means of procuring it. It is the duty of a good legislator to examine\r carefully into his state; and the nature of the people, and how they may\r partake of every i","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1627},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-5","text":"We will now speak to those who, while they agree that a life of virtue\r is most eligible, yet differ in the use of it addressing ourselves to\r both these parties; for there are some who disapprove of all political\r governments, and think that the life of one who is really free is\r different from the life of a citizen, and of all others most eligible:\r others again think that the citizen is the best; and that it is\r impossible for him who does nothing to be well employed; but that\r virtuous activity and happiness are the same thing. Now both parties in\r some particulars say what is right, in ot","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1628},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-6","text":"As I have now finished what was introductory to this subject, and\r considered at large the nature of other states, it now remains that I\r should first say what ought to be the establishment of a city which one\r should form according to one's wish; for no good state can exist without\r a moderate proportion of what is necessary. Many things therefore\r ought to be forethought of as desirable, but none of them such as are\r impossible: I mean relative to the number of citizens and the extent\r of the territory: for as other artificers, such as the weaver and the\r shipwright, ought to have such mater","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1629},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-7","text":"What we have said concerning a city may nearly be applied to a country;\r for as to what soil it should be, every one evidently will commend it\r if it is such as is sufficient in itself to furnish what will make the\r inhabitants happy; for which purpose it must be able to supply them\r with all the necessaries of life; for it is the having these in plenty,\r without any want, which makes them content. As to its extent, it should\r be such as may enable the inhabitants to live at their ease with freedom\r and temperance. Whether we have done right or wrong in fixing this limit\r to the territory shal","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1630},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-8","text":"But with respect to placing a city in the neighbourhood of the sea,\r there are some who have many doubts whether it is serviceable or hurtful\r to a well-regulated state; for they say, that the resort of persons\r brought up under a different system of government is disserviceable\r to the state, as well by impeding the laws as by their numbers; for a\r multitude of merchants must necessarily arise from their trafficking\r backward and forward upon the seas, which will hinder the well-governing\r of the city: but if this inconvenience should not arise, it is evident\r that it is better, both on accou","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1631},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-9","text":"We now proceed to point out what natural disposition the members of the\r community ought to be of: but this any one will easily perceive who\r will cast his eye over the states of Greece, of all others the most\r celebrated, and also the other different nations of this habitable\r world. Those who live in cold countries, as the north of Europe, are\r full of courage, but wanting in understanding and the arts: therefore\r they are very tenacious of their liberty; but, not being politicians,\r they cannot reduce their neighbours under their power: but the Asiatics,\r whose understandings are quick, and","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1632},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-10","text":"As in natural bodies those things are not admitted to be parts of them\r without which the whole would not exist, so also it is evident that in\r a political state everything that is necessary thereunto is not to be\r considered as a part of it, nor any other community from whence one\r whole is made; for one thing ought to be common and the same to the\r community, whether they partake of it equally or unequally, as, for\r instance, food, land, or the like; but when one thing is for the benefit\r of one person, and another for the benefit of another, in this there is\r nothing like a community, excep","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1633},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-11","text":"Having determined thus far, it remains that we consider whether all\r these different employments shall be open to all; for it is possible\r to continue the same persons always husbandmen, artificers, judges,\r or counsellors; or shall we appoint different persons to each of those\r employments which we have already mentioned; or shall some of them be\r appropriated to particulars, and others of course common to all? but\r this does not take place in every state, for, as we have already said,\r it is possible that all may be common to all, or not, but only common to\r some; and this is the difference ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1634},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-12","text":"Since we are inquiring what is the best government possible, and it is\r admitted to be that in which the citizens are happy; and that, as we\r have already said, it is impossible to obtain happiness without virtue;\r it follows, that in the best-governed states, where the citizens are\r really men of intrinsic and not relative goodness, none of them should\r be permitted to exercise any mechanic employment or follow merchandise,\r as being ignoble and destructive to virtue; neither should they be\r husband-[1329a] men, that they may be at leisure to improve in virtue\r and perform the duty they owe t","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1635},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-13","text":"It seems neither now nor very lately to have been known [1329b] to those\r philosophers who have made politics their study, that a city ought to\r be divided by families into different orders of men; and that the\r husbandmen and soldiers should be kept separate from each other;\r which custom is even to this day preserved in Egypt and in Crete; also\r Sesostris having founded it in Egypt, Minos in Crete. Common meals seem\r also to have been an ancient regulation, and to have been established\r in Crete during the reign of Minos, and in a still more remote period\r in Italy; for those who are the bes","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1636},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-14","text":"We have already mentioned, that both the city and all the country should\r communicate both with the sea and the continent as much as possible.\r There are these four things which we should be particularly desirous of\r in the position of the city with respect to itself: in the first place,\r health is to be consulted as the first thing necessary: now a city\r which fronts the east and receives the winds which blow from thence is\r esteemed most healthful; next to this that which has a northern position\r is to be preferred, as best in winter. It should next be contrived that\r it may have a proper si","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1637},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-15","text":"As the citizens in general are to eat at public tables in certain\r companies, and it is necessary that the walls should have bulwarks and\r towers in proper places and at proper distances, it is evident that\r it will be very necessary to have some of these in the towers; let the\r buildings for this purpose be made the ornaments of the walls. As to\r temples for public worship, and the hall for the public tables of\r the chief magistrates, they ought to be built in proper places, and\r contiguous to each other, except those temples which the law or the\r oracle orders to be separate from all other b","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1638},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-16","text":"We will now show of what numbers and of what sort of people a government\r ought to consist, that the state may be happy and well administered.\r As there are two particulars on which the excellence and perfection of\r everything depend, one of these is, that the object and end proposed\r should be proper; the other, that the means to accomplish it should be\r adapted to that purpose; for it may happen that these may either agree\r or disagree with each other; for the end we propose may be good, but in\r taking the means to obtain it we may err; at other times we may have\r the right and proper means ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1639},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-17","text":"As every political community consists of those who govern and of those\r who are governed, let us consider whether during the continuance of\r their lives they ought to be the same persons or different; for it\r is evident that the mode of education should be adapted to this\r distinction. Now, if one man differed from another as much, as we\r believe, the gods and heroes differ from men: in the first place, being\r far their superiors in body; and, secondly, in the soul: so that the\r superiority of the governors over the governed might be evident beyond\r a doubt, it is certain that it would be bett","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1640},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-18","text":"They ought to be fitted both for labour and war, but rather [1333b] for\r rest and peace; and also to do what is necessary and useful, but rather\r what is fair and noble. It is to those objects that the education of the\r children ought to tend, and of all the youths who want instruction. All\r the Grecian states which now seem best governed, and the legislators who\r founded those states, appear not to have framed their polity with a view\r to the best end, or to every virtue, in their laws and education; but\r eagerly to have attended to what is useful and productive of gain: and\r nearly of the sa","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1641},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-19","text":"Such reasoning and such laws are neither political, useful nor true: but\r a legislator ought to instil those laws on the minds of men which are\r most useful for them, both in their public and private capacities. The\r rendering a people fit for war, that they may enslave their inferiors\r ought not to be the care of the legislator; but that they may not\r themselves be reduced to slavery by others. In [1334a] the next place,\r he should take care that the object of his government is the safety\r of those who are under it, and not a despotism over all: in the third\r place, that those only are slaves","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1642},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-20","text":"As there is one end common to a man both as an individual and a citizen,\r it is evident that a good man and a good citizen must have the same\r object in view; it is evident that all the virtues which lead to rest\r are necessary; for, as we have often said, the end of war is peace, of\r labour, rest; but those virtues whose object is rest, and those also\r whose object is labour, are necessary for a liberal life and rest; for\r we want a supply of many necessary things that we may be at rest. A city\r therefore ought to be temperate, brave, and patient; for, according to\r the proverb, \"Rest is not ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1643},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-21","text":"If then the legislator ought to take care that the bodies of the\r children are as perfect as possible, his first attention ought to be\r given to matrimony; at what time and in what situation it is proper that\r the citizens should engage in the nuptial contract. Now, with respect\r to this alliance, the legislator ought both to consider the parties and\r their time of life, that they may grow old at the same part of time, and\r that their bodily powers may not be different; that is to say, the man\r being able to have children, but the woman too old to bear them; or, on\r the contrary, the woman be ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1644},{"id":"aristotle-politics-7-22","text":"When a child is born it must be supposed that the strength of its body\r will depend greatly upon the quality of its food. Now whoever will\r examine into the nature of animals, and also observe those people who\r are very desirous their children should acquire a warlike habit, will\r find that they feed them chiefly with milk, as being best accommodated\r to their bodies, but without wine, to prevent any distempers: those\r motions also which are natural to their age are very serviceable; and\r to prevent any of their limbs from being crooked, on account of their\r extreme ductility, some people even","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 7","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"7"},"sequenceIndex":1645},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-1","text":"No one can doubt that the magistrate ought greatly to interest himself\r in the care of youth; for where it is neglected it is hurtful to the\r city, for every state ought to be governed according to its particular\r nature; for the form and manners of each government are peculiar to\r itself; and these, as they originally established it, so they usually\r still preserve it. For instance, democratic forms and manners a\r democracy; oligarchic, an oligarchy: but, universally, the best manners\r produce the best government. Besides, as in every business and art there\r are some things which men are to l","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1646},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-2","text":"What education is, and how children ought to be instructed, is what\r should be well known; for there are doubts concerning the business of\r it, as all people do not agree in those things they would have a child\r taught, both with respect to their improvement in virtue and a happy\r life: nor is it clear whether the object of it should be to improve\r the reason or rectify the morals. From the present mode of education\r we cannot determine with certainty to which men incline, whether to\r instruct a child in what will be useful to him in life; or what tends to\r virtue, and what is excellent: for a","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1647},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-3","text":"There are four things which it is usual to teach children--reading,\r gymnastic exercises, and music, to which (in the fourth place) some add\r painting. Reading and painting are both of them of singular use in life,\r and gymnastic exercises, as productive of courage. As to music, some\r persons may doubt, as most persons now use it for the sake of pleasure:\r but those who originally made it part of education did it because,\r as has been already said, nature requires that we should not only be\r properly employed, but to be able to enjoy leisure honourably: for this\r (to repeat what I have already","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1648},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-4","text":"It is evident, then, that there is a certain education in which a child\r may be instructed, not as useful nor as necessary, but as noble and\r liberal: but whether this is one or more than one, and of what sort they\r are, and how to be taught, shall be considered hereafter: we are now got\r so far on our way as to show that we have the testimony of the ancients\r in our favour, by what they have delivered down upon education--for\r music makes this plain. Moreover, it is necessary to instruct children\r in what is useful, not only on account of its being useful in itself,\r as, for instance, to lear","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1649},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-5","text":"Now those states which seem to take the greatest care of their\r children's education, bestow their chief attention on wrestling, though\r it both prevents the increase of the body and hurts the form of it. This\r fault the Lacedaemonians did not fall into, for they made their children\r fierce by painful labour, as chiefly useful to inspire them with\r courage: though, as we have already often said, this is neither the\r only thing nor the principal thing necessary to attend to; and even with\r respect to this they may not thus attain their end; for we do not find\r either in other animals, or other ","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1650},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-6","text":"With respect to music we have already spoken a little in a doubtful\r manner upon this subject. It will be proper to go over again more\r particularly what we then said, which may serve as an introduction to\r what any other person may choose to offer thereon; for it is no easy\r matter to distinctly point out what power it has, nor on what accounts\r one should apply it, whether as an amusement and refreshment, as sleep\r or wine; as these are nothing serious, but pleasing, and the killers of\r care, as Euripides says; for which reason they class in the same order\r and use for the same purpose all t","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1651},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-7","text":"We will now determine whether it is proper that children should be\r taught to sing, and play upon any instrument, which we have before made\r a matter of doubt. Now, it is well known that it makes a great deal of\r difference when you would qualify any one in any art, for the person\r himself to learn the practical part of it; for it is a thing very\r difficult, if not impossible, for a man to be a good judge of what he\r himself cannot do. It is also very necessary that children should have\r some employment which will amuse them; for which reason the rattle of\r Archytas seems well contrived, which","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1652},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-8","text":"We are now to enter into an inquiry concerning harmony and rhythm;\r whether all sorts of these are to be employed in education, or whether\r some peculiar ones are to be selected; and also whether we should\r give the same directions to those who are engaged in music as part of\r education, or whether there is something different from these two.\r Now, as all music consists in melody and rhythm, we ought not to be\r unacquainted with the power which each of these has in education; and\r whether we should rather choose music in which melody prevails, or\r rhythm: but when I consider how many things ha","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1653},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-9","text":"Animals, their different provisions by nature, 14;\r       intended by nature for the benefit of man, 14;\r       what constitutes their different species, 113","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1654},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-10","text":"Aristocracies, causes of commotions in them, 157;\r       chief cause of their alteration, 158;\r       may degenerate into an oligarchy, 79","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1655},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-11","text":"Census in a free state should be as extensive as possible, 131;\r       how to be altered, 162","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1656},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-12","text":"Child, how to be managed when first born, 235;\r       should be taught nothing till he is five years old, 235;\r       how then to be educated, 236","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1657},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-13","text":"Children, the proper government of, 22;\r       what their proper virtues, 23;\r       what they are usually taught, 240","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1658},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-14","text":"Cities, how governed at first, 3;\r       what, 3;\r       the work of nature, 3;\r       prior in contemplation to a family, or an individual, 4","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1659},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-15","text":"Citizen, who is one? 66, 68;\r       should know both how to command and obey, 73","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1660},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-16","text":"Citizens must have some things in common, 26;\r       should be exempted from servile labour, 51;\r       privileges different in different governments, 68;\r       if illegally made, whether illegal, 69;\r       who admitted to be, 75;\r       in the best states ought not to follow merchandise, 216","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1661},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-17","text":"City, may be too much one, 27, 35;\r       what, 66, 82;\r       when it continues the same, 70;\r       for whose sake established, 76;\r       its end, 83;\r       of what parts made up, 113;\r       best composed of equals, 126","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1662},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-18","text":"City of the best form, what its establishment ought to be, 149;\r       wherein its greatness consists, 149;\r       may be either too large or too small, 209;\r       what should be its situation, 211;\r       whether proper near the sea, 211;\r       ought to be divided by families into different sorts of men, 218","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1663},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-19","text":"Common meals not well established at Lacedaemon-well at Crete, 56;\r       the model from whence the Lacedaemonian was taken, 56;\r       inferior to it in some respects, 56","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1664},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-20","text":"Community, its recommendations deceitful, 34;\r       into what people it may be divided, 194","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1665},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-21","text":"Community of goods, its inconveniences, 28;\r       destructive of modesty and liberality, 34","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1666},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-22","text":"Cretan customs similar to the Lacedasmonian, 57;\r       assembly open to every citizen, 58","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1667},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-23","text":"Customs at Carthage, Lacedaemon, and amongst the Scythians and\r   Iberians, concerning those who had killed an enemy, 204, 205","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1668},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-24","text":"Democracies, arose out of tyrannies, 100;\r       whence they arose, 142;\r       when changed into tyrannies, 153;\r       their different sorts, 184, 188;\r       general rules for their establishment, 185;\r       should not be made too perfect, 191","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1669},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-25","text":"Democracy, what, 79, 80;\r       its definition, 112, 113;\r       different sorts of, 115, 118;\r       its object, 122;\r       how subverted in the Isle of Cos, 152","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1670},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-26","text":"Education necessary for the happiness of the city, 90;\r       of all things most necessary to preserve the state, 166;\r       what it ought to be, 166;\r       the objects of it, 228, 229;\r       should be taken care of by the magistrate, and correspond to\r           the nature of government, 238;\r       should be a common care, and regulated by laws, 238","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1671},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-27","text":"Employments in the state, how to be disposed of, 88-90;\r       whether all should be open to all, 216","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1672},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-28","text":"Ephori, at Sparta, their power too great, 54;\r       improperly chosen, 54;\r       flattered by their kings, 54;\r       the supreme judges, 55;\r       manner of life too indulgent, 55","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1673},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-29","text":"Females and slaves, wherein they differ, 2;\r       why upon a level amongst barbarians, 3","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1674},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-30","text":"Free state treated of, 121;\r       how it arises out of a democracy and oligarchy, 122, 123","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1675},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-31","text":"Government should continue as much as possible in the same hands, 28;\r       in what manner it should be in rotation, 28;\r       what, 66;\r       which best, of a good man or good laws, 98;\r       good, to what it should owe its preservation, 124;\r       what the best, 225","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1676},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-32","text":"Governments, how different from each other, 67;\r       whether more than one form should be established, 76;\r       should endeavour to prevent others from being too powerful--\r       instances of it, 93;\r       how compared to music, in;\r       in general, to what they owe their preservation, 160","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1677},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-33","text":"Governments, political, regal, family, and servile, their difference\r   from each other, i","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1678},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-34","text":"Governors and governed, whether their virtues are the same or different, 23;\r       whether they should be the same persons or different, 227","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1679},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-35","text":"Gymnastic exercises, when to be performed, 223;\r       how far they should be made a part of education, 242, 243","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1680},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-36","text":"Hippodamus, an account of, 46;\r       his plan of government, 46, 47:\r       objected to, 47, 48","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1681},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-37","text":"Husbandmen compose the best democracy, 189;\r       will choose to govern according to law, 118","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1682},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-38","text":"Instruments, their difference from each other, 6;\r       wherein they differ from possessions, 6","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1683},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-39","text":"Judge should not act as an arbitrator, 48, 49;\r       which is best for an individual, or the people in general, 98, 99","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1684},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-40","text":"Judges, many better than one, 102;\r       of whom to consist, 102;\r       how many different sorts are necessary, 141","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1685},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-41","text":"Justice, what, 88;\r       the course of, impeded in Crete, 59;\r       different in different situations, 74","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1686},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-42","text":"Kingdoms, their object, 167;\r       how bestowed, 168;\r       causes of their dissolution, 173;\r       how preserved, 173","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1687},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-43","text":"Kingly power regulated by the laws at Sparta in peace, 95;\r       absolute in war, 95","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1688},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-44","text":"Kings formerly in Crete, 58;\r       their power afterwards devolved to the kosmoi, 58;\r       method of electing them at Carthage, 60","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1689},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-45","text":"Kosmoi, the power of, 58;\r       their number, 58;\r       wherein inferior to the ephori, 58;\r       allowed to resign their office before their time is elapsed, 59","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1690},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-46","text":"Lacedaemonian government much esteemed, 41;\r       the faults of it, 53-56;\r       calculated only for war, 56;\r       how composed of a democracy and oligarchy, 124","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1691},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-47","text":"Law makes one man a slave, another free, 6;\r       whether just or not, 9;\r       at Thebes respecting tradesmen, 75;\r       nothing should be done contrary to it, 160","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1692},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-48","text":"Laws, when advantageous\r   to alter them, 49,50, 52;\r       of every state will be like the state, 88;\r       whom they should be calculated for, 92;\r       decide better than men, 101;\r       moral preferable to written, 102;\r       must sometimes bend to ancient customs, 117;\r       should be framed to the state, 107;\r       the same suit not all governments, 108","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1693},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-49","text":"Lycurgus gave over reducing the women to obedience, 53;\r       made it infamous for any one to sell his possessions, 53;\r       some of his laws censured, 54;\r       spent much time at Crete, 57;\r       supposed to be the scholar of Thales, 64","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1694},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-50","text":"Magistrates, when they make the state incline to an oligarchy, 61;\r       when to an aristocracy, 61;\r       at Athens, from whom to be chosen, 64;\r       to determine those causes which the law cannot be applied to, 88;\r       whether their power is to be the same, or different\r           in different communities, 137;\r       how they differ from each other, 138;\r           in those who appoint them, 138;\r       should be continued but a short time in democracies, 161;\r       how to be chosen in a democracy, 185;\r       different sorts and employments, 196","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1695},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-51","text":"Man proved to be a political animal, 4;\r       has alone a perception of good and evil, 4;\r       without law and justice the worst of beings, 5","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1696},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-52","text":"Meals, common, established in Crete and Italy, 218;\r       expense of, should be defrayed by the whole state, 219","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1697},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-53","text":"Mechanics, whether they should be allowed to be citizens, 74, 75;\r       cannot acquire the practice of virtue, 75;\r       admitted to be citizens in an oligarchy, 75","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1698},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-54","text":"Members of the community, their different pretences to the employments\r   of the state, 90;\r       what natural dispositions they ought to be of, 213","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1699},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-55","text":"Men, some distinguished by nature for governors, others to be governed, 7;\r       their different modes of living, 13;\r       worthy three ways, 226","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1700},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-56","text":"Middle rank of men make the best citizens, 127;\r       most conducive to the preservation of the state, 128;\r       should be particularly attended to by the legislators, 130","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1701},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-57","text":"Monarchies, their nature, 95, 96;\r       sometimes elective, 95;\r       sometimes hereditary, 95;\r       whence they sometimes arise, 146;\r       causes of corruption in them, 167;\r       how preserved, 173","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1702},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-58","text":"Money, how it made its way into commerce, 16;\r       first weighed, 16;\r       afterwards stamped, 16;\r       its value dependent on agreement, 16;\r       how gained by exchange, 19","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1703},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-59","text":"Music, how many species of it, in;\r       why a part of education, 240;\r       how far it should be taught, 242, 243;\r       professors of it considered as mean people, 244;\r       imitates the disposition of the mind, 246;\r       improves our manners, 246;\r       Lydian, softens the mind, 247;\r       pieces of, difficult in their execution, not to be taught to children, 249","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1704},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-60","text":"Nobles, the difference between them, no;\r       should take care of the poor, 193","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1705},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-61","text":"Officers of state, who they ought to be, 135;\r       how long to continue, 135;\r       who to choose them, 136","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1706},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-62","text":"Offices, distinction between them, 67;\r       when subversive of the rights of the people, 130","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1707},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-63","text":"Oligarchies arise where the strength of the state consists in horse, no;\r       whence they arose, 142","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1708},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-64","text":"Oligarchy admits not hired servants to be citizens, 75;\r       its object, 79;\r       what, 79, 81;\r       its definition, 112;\r       different sorts of, 117, 119;\r       its object, 122;\r       how it ought to be founded, 195","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1709},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-65","text":"Ostracism, why established, 93, 146;\r       its power, 93;\r       a weapon in the hand of sedition, 94","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1710},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-66","text":"People, how they should be made one, 35;\r       of Athens assume upon their victory over the Medes, 64;\r       what best to submit to a kingly government, 104;\r       to an aristocratic, 104;\r       to a free state, 104;\r       should be allowed the power of pardoning, not of condemning, 135","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1711},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-67","text":"Physicians, their mode of practice in Egypt, 98;\r       when ill consult others, 102","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1712},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-68","text":"Poor excused from bearing arms and from gymnastic exercises in\r   an oligarchy, 131;\r       paid for attending the public assemblies in a democracy, 131","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1713},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-69","text":"Power, supreme, where it ought to be lodged, 84;\r       why with the many, 85, 87","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1714},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-70","text":"Powers of a state, different methods of delegating them to the citizens,\r   132-134","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1715},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-71","text":"Private property not regulated the source of sedition, 42;\r       Phaleas would have it equal, 42;\r       how Phaleas would correct the irregularities of it, 43;\r       Plato would allow a certain difference in it, 43","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1716},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-72","text":"Property, its nature, 12;\r       how it should be regulated, 32, 33;\r       the advantages of having it private, 34;\r       what quantity the public ought to have, 44;\r       ought not to be common, 219","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1717},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-73","text":"Qualifications necessary for those who are to fill the first departments\r   in government, 164","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1718},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-74","text":"Rich fined in an oligarchy for not bearing arms and attending the\r   gymnastic exercises, 131;\r       receive nothing for attending the public assemblies in a democracy, 131","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1719},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-75","text":"Seditions sometimes prevented by equality, 45;\r       their causes, 144-146;\r       how to be prevented, 163","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1720},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-76","text":"Slaves, an inquiry into the virtues they are capable of, 23;\r       difficult to manage properly, 51;\r       their different sorts, 73","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1721},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-77","text":"Society, civil, the greatest blessing to man, 4;\r       different from a commercial intercourse, 82","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1722},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-78","text":"Socrates, his mistakes on government, Book II. passim;\r       his division of the inhabitants, 38;\r       would have the women go to war, 38;\r       Aristotle's opinion of his discourses, 38;\r       his city would require a country of immeasurable extent, 39;\r       his comparison of the human species to different kinds of metals, 40;\r       his account of the different orders of men in a city imperfect, 3","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1723},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-79","text":"Solon's opinion of riches, 14;\r       law for restraining property, 43;\r       alters the Athenian government, 63","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1724},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-80","text":"Soul by nature the governor over the body, and in what manner, 8;\r       of man how divided, 228, 231","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1725},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-81","text":"State, each, consists of a great number of parts, 109;\r       its disproportionate increase the cause of revolutions, 147;\r       firm, what, 159","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1726},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-82","text":"Thales, his contrivance to get money, 21;\r       supposed to be the companion of Onomacritus, 64","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1727},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-83","text":"Things necessary to be known for the management of domestic affairs, 19, 20;\r       necessary in the position of a city, 220","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1728},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-84","text":"Tribunals, what different things they should have under their\r   jurisdictions, 137","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1729},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-85","text":"Tyrannies, how established, 168;\r       how preserved, 174, 176;\r       of short duration, 180;\r       instances thereof, 180","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1730},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-86","text":"Tyranny, what, 79;\r       not natural, 103;\r       whence it arises, 108;\r       treated of, 124;\r       contains all that is bad in all governments, 125","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1731},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-87","text":"Tyrant, from whom usually chosen, 167;\r       his object, 168;\r       his guards, 168","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1732},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-88","text":"Tyrants, many of them originally enjoyed only kingly power, 168;\r       the causes of their being conspired against, 169, 170;\r       always love the worst of men, 175","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1733},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-89","text":"Virtue of a citizen has reference to the state, 71;\r       different in different governments, 71","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1734},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-90","text":"Virtues different in different persons, 23, 24;\r       whether the same constitute a good man and a valuable citizen, 71","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1735},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-91","text":"War, what is gained by it in some degree a natural acquisition, 14;\r       not a final end, 205, 229","author":"Aristotle","source":"Aristotle — Politics, Book 8","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:aristotle"],"groups":{"work":"Politics","book":"8"},"sequenceIndex":1736},{"id":"aristotle-politics-8-92","text":"Women, what their proper virtue, 23;\r       not to be indulged in improper liberties, 52;\r       had great influence at Lacedaemon, 52;\r       of great disservice to the Lacedemonians, 52;\r       why indulged by them, 53;\r       their proper time of marrying, 233;\r       how to be managed when with child, 234","